the armed forces that keep gen. manuel antonio noriega in power went unpaid friday and the broke and beleaguered government ordered businesses closed in the general strike to reopen
in a decree issued under a week-old state of emergency, the civilian government that does noriega's bidding said it would take away the commercial licenses of any businesses ``offering goods and services to the public'' if they remained closed
the decree specifically mentioned grocery stores, pharmacies, transportation companies and gasoline stations
an estimated 90 percent of panama's industry and businesses have shut down in the strike that began monday in an effort to force noriega's removal as the head of the 15,000-member defense forces that includes the military and police
the government's inability to pay the defense forces kindled hopes in the opposition that loyalty for him will wane
several members of the defense forces, including a secretary at military headquarters, said army, navy, police and air force personnel did not receive their semi-monthly paychecks as scheduled friday
we did not receive our wages and we were not told when we would receive them,'' said the secretary, who declined to give her name. soldiers questioned by reporters also said they had not been paid
in mid-march, most of the 130,000 public employees were given partial payment of at least $75 on their salaries. those employees whose monthly salaries are $1,000 or more were not paid. social security checks have been postponed
demonstrators at the roman catholic cathedral protested the church's failure to issue a denunciation of noriega as expected
pilots who guide ships through the panama canal and claimed they had been harassed by soldiers in panama city demanded protection and met with the panama canal commission. some pilots had spoken of a strike, but commission spokesman frank castrellon said the situation was resolved at the meeting. he did not elaborate
john maher, president of the panama canal pilots association, said: ``there is no problem now.''
noriega remained obstinate
he was asked at a military ceremony about president reagan's renewed call for his departure and he replied:
my president is called (manuel) solis palma and my geographic space is called panama. i don't take orders from extra-terrestrials.''
solis palma was named chief executive by the legislature when president eric arturo delvalle was ousted on feb. 26, the day after he tried to fire noriega
two members of the house foreign affairs committee, reps. gary ackerman, d-n.y., and peter h. kostmayer, d-pa., ended a two-day visit friday and told a news conference they thought the reagan administration should increase economic pressure on noriega
noriega is under indictment in the united states on narcotics charges. the reagan administration has cut the flow of money to panama, which uses the u.s. dollar as its currency
the order for businesses to reopen was in decree no. 16 issued under the state of emergency that enables the government to act as it deems necessary ``to secure public order,'' including suspending civil liberties
the decree also said any establishment that had been closed for the past five days and sold food, meats or canned goods ``cannot reopen unless it is first inspected by the health ministry.''
it said store owners who do not comply face ``temporary suspension of their licenses or, in case of repeated violations, the cancellation of their commercial licenses.''
the strike began monday and was called by the national civic crusade, a broad alliance of noriega's opposition. crusade leaders said it would continue until noriega was ousted
panama canal employees have worked throughout protests and general strikes against noriega that began last june. the canal continues to operate normally while the nation around the waterway is at a virtual standstill
most of the canal's 230 pilots are american citizens
soldiers man roadblocks around the capital and they demand identification from drivers, search cars and rummage through personal belongings. some pilots complained about those actions
about 100 people stalked out of the cathedral after archbishop marcos g. mcgrath opened a special mass by telling worshipers and observers the church would not issue the anticipated anti-noriega statement
we don't know how this mistaken rumor originated,'' mcgrath said. ``we are sorry, but it is not our fault.''
civic crusade leaders and ackerman had said they had been assured the church would issue a strong condemnation of noriega
those who walked out stood on the steps of the gray stone cathedral chanting, ``justice! justice!'' and ``noriega must go!''
mcgrath told those remaining inside that he and noriega had a ``preparatory meeting'' thursday. he did not explain and said he could not discuss the conversation. interpretation</head>
democrats and republicans on the senate foreign relations committee are trying to settle the one major dispute left before the panel approves the u.s.-soviet treaty eliminating medium-range nuclear missiles
i think we'll be able to agree on something,'' said sen. richard lugar, r-ind., leader of a group of republicans who are seeking a compromise on the issue of how treaties are legally intepreted
that is the only major question left and i would expect that we can solve it by next week,'' sen. claiborne pell, d-r.i., chairman of the committee, said thursday
the panel spent three days this week rejecting a series of challenges by conservative republicans to the intermediate-range nuclear forces treaty and has set tuesday afternoon for a final vote on the pact
pell and other democratic leaders have predicted overwhelming approval, both in the committee next week and by the full senate next month when the democratic-controlled chamber returns from an easter recess. ratification requires the approval of 67 of the 100 senators
the remaining fight centers on the dispute between the legislative and executive branches over the authority to interpret treaties. the disagreement arises from president reagan's assertion that his administration can unilaterally change the intepretation of the 1972 anti-ballistic missile treaty, a contention the senate disputes
pell and other democrats want some type of condition on the inf treaty that would block a future administration from changing the u.s. interpretation of the pact
lugar said one compromise being considered is attaching an amendment to the ratification resolution which says the inf treaty cannot be reinterpreted by a future administration without prior consent of the senate
that is one ay to solve it and remove the fight from this treaty without coming to a final answer on the intepretation issue,'' said lugar
the treaty was signed dec. 8 by reagan and soviet leader mikhail s. gorbachev. it requires the elimination within three years of all missiles with a range of 300 to 3,400 miles. anti-cheating provisions _ the strictest in arms control history _ include provisions for on-site inspections by each superpower in the other country
in the senate, the treaty has been criticized chiefly by conservative republicans, including sens. jesse helms of north carolina and larry pressler of south dakota
senate officials are preparing for an unusual secret session of the senate early next week to examine sensitive intelligence information about the number of ss-20 medium-range missiles possessed by the soviet union
a total of 650 were declared by the soviets and those will be destroyed after the treaty takes effect. but helms claims there are conflicting estimates by u.s. intelligence agencies about the number of missiles, including one report by the defense intelligence agency that the soviets may have up to 300 more ss-20s than they have declared
the foreign relations panel voted 15-2 thursday to reject helms' amendment requiring new intelligence analyses of the ss-20 question. only helms and pressler supported his proposal which would have required reagan to certify the accuracy of the soviet claims that they only have 650 ss-20s
the closed-door session will take place in the capitol's old senate chamber, according to senate majority leader robert c. byrd, d-w.va
the small, historic room is normally maintained as a museum, but byrd said it is better for the meeting than the current senate chamber. the new senate is laced with a variety of cables that make it more difficult to protect security, byrd explained
later, the committee also rejected, 15-2, pressler's plan to block implementation of the treaty until reagan certifies that nato won't be jeopardized by the soviets' advantage in a variety of non-nuclear weapons
helms originally had 36 amendments, but dropped the majority of them after only pressler supported his proposals. pressler also dropped some of his challenges in the face of widespread rejection
the heaviest savings institution losses since the great depression underscore the need for federal regulators to begin cleaning up the mire of insolvent institutions in the southwest, savings and loan lobby groups say
the federal home loan bank board said thursday that the nation's 3,147 savings institutions lost $3.2 billion in the fourth quarter of 1987, pushing red ink for the year to $6.8 billion, the worst loss since the agency began keeping track in 1934
i hope it's the worst we'll ever see,'' said james w. christian, chief economist of the u.s. league of savings insitutions, the industry's largest trade group
the bank board said s&amp;l losses were heavily concentrated in states like texas, oklahoma and louisiana, which are dependent on the ailing oil and gas industry
the worst 20 institutions _ most of them in the southwest _ lost a total of $2.1 billion in the final quarter of last year, accounting for two-thirds of the overall industry loss
the no. 1 item on the agenda is to stop the bleeding in the southwest,'' christian said. ``that's in the bank board's lap. ... and we hope they do it sooner rather than later.''
until recently, the bank board has been forced to keep insolvent institutions open because it lacked the money to pay off depositors or entice a healthier s&amp;l into merging with the sick institution
the bank board said 345 s&amp;ls were insolvent at the end of the year, 109 in texas alone. an s&amp;l is considered insolvent when its loans and other assets are worth less than what it owes to depositors and other creditors
by the tougher accounting standards the bank board will be using next year, 510 would be considered insolvent
yet, regulators closed only 17 institutions in 1987 and provided assistance for the merger of 26 others
now that money has begun flowing from a three-year, $10.8 billion recapitalization enacted in august, bank board chairman m. danny wall has pledged to pick up the pace
last month, he announced a plan to spend $6 billion to $7 billion in texas over the next several years, but the bank board said wednesday it expected no announcements on specific institutions before early april
martin a. regalia, chief economist of the national council of savings institutions, warned that the bank board must move swiftly
on balance, next year will be not quite as bad, but that depends on how quickly you get rid of these institutions'' in the southwest, he said
james barth, chief economist of the bank board, said he believed the industry's problems have ``plateaued out'' and that ``there is some light at the end of the tunnel'' in the southwest
industry losses in 1987 were nearly 50 percent greater than the previous post-depression record of $4.6 billion, set in 1981, when the prime lending rate soared above 20 percent
insured s&amp;ls lost $1.8 billion in the third quarter of last year and $1.9 billion in the spring. they earned $100 million in the first three months of the year and had a modest $132 million profit for all of 1986
in contrast, the federal deposit insurance corp. said earlier this month that the nation's 13,700 federally insured commercial banks earned $3.7 billion in 1987. still, it was their lowest profit since 1933
despite the overall loss for the s&amp;l industry, 66 percent of the s&amp;ls earned money in the fourth quarter. the $1.3 billion earnings of 2,089 s&amp;ls partly offset the $4.5 billion losses of the remaining 1,058 institutions
the percentage of institutions earning a profit has declined steadily for two years, from 81 percent in the first quarter of 1986 to 66 percent at the end of last year
barth said part of the overall industry loss in 1987 can be attributed to a decrease in the corporate tax rate. he said some s&amp;ls decided to push profits into 1988, when the top tax rate is 34 percent, rather than take them in 1987, when the rate was 40 percent
israeli troops stormed a west bank hospital and a mosque and killed two palestinian demonstrators and wounding 18 in a new outbreak of clashes in the occupied lands. most media coverage was barred
prime minister yitzhak shamir met with u.s. ambassador thomas pickering to express his ``dissatisfaction'' about today's scheduled meeting in the united states between secretary of state george p. shultz and two members of the plo's legislative arm
also friday, an arab-american advocate of non-violent resistance to occupation called for the establishment of a ``parallel'' palestinian government in israel's occupied territories
the army closed key areas of the occupied gaza strip and west bank to the media, including the west bank's hebron area, where the most of friday's violent clashes occurred
in washington, meanwhile, the state department urged americans to stay away from the west bank and gaza. easter and passover are approaching, christian and jewish holidays that usually attract tourists to the holy land
about 50 israeli troops fired tear gas and rubber bullets into hebron's alia hospital compound friday to subdue about 100 protesters who were hurling stones and bottles, hospital officials and arab reports said
later, soldiers stormed the hospital to arrest six arab youths who barricaded themselves on the roof, the army said
reporters saw troops surround hebron's al haras mosque after friday's moslem prayers, firing live ammunition and tear gas from the rooftops of nearby houses at several dozen stone-throwing arab youths on the mosque's roof
four palestinians were wounded, hospital officials and israel radio reported
after a two-hour confrontation, soldiers stormed the mosque, yanked down palestinian flags raised by the protesters and lined up dozens of arab teenagers against a wall. the army said 50 arabs were arrested
the army said it was forced to break in when the stone-throwers refused to surrender. television said it was the first time soldiers had stormed a mosque since unrest began dec. 8 in the territories israel seized in the 1967 middle east war
another arab was wounded in the village of idna, israel radio said
in the village of tarqumia near hebron, troops killed two palestinians and wounded 13, witnesses and the radio said. the army said it was checking the reports but could not confirm them because relatives took the bodies
troops entered tarqumia at about 4 a.m. and took over the school, said naim odeh, a 52-year-old teacher. the army has converted a number of schools into military bases since the unrest began and is using about half a dozen as temporary detention centers
then about 500 youths marched out to the school and started throwing rocks and broken bottles,'' odeh said in an interview
khaled hassan ahmed murktan, 18, died of a gunshot wound to the stomach and walid abdul fatatta, 18, was shot in the heart, villagers and alia hospital officials said
friday's fatalities brought to 111 the number of palestinians killed by u.n. count in the anti-occupation unrest since dec. 8. one israeli soldier has been killed
meanwhile, 72 percent of the israelis questioned said they want harsher measures in the occupied territories. the dahaf nstitute poll published in the daily yediot ahronot said 7 percent of the 606 israelis questioned this week supported less severe measures while 21 percent did not want policy changes
also, 49 percent of those questioned said shultz' middle east peace plan _ essentially an exchange of land for piece with the arabs _ should be accepted. forty-three percent were against it and 8 percent had no opinion
israeli officials, however, reacted angrily to shultz' plans to discuss the peace initiative with two american citizens who belong to the palestine national council, the plo's parliament-in-exile
shamir expressed his ``dissatisfaction'' during friday's meeting with pickering, israel tv said
shamir's spokesman avi pazner said shultz's meeting with edward said, a professor at columbia university, and ibrahim abu-lughod, a northwestern university professor, violates a u.s. commitment not to talk to the palestine liberation organization
in another development, mubarak awad, an arab-american advocate of non-violent resistance to israeli occupation, called for forming a ``parallel'' government in the occupied territories
we should start thinking what kind of a palestinian state we are going to have, what to do with jerusalem, where are the borders,'' he told israel tv
israeli authorities confiscated awad's u.s. passport and israeli identity card last year and ordered him expelled last november when his tourist visa expired. awad stayed following strong u.s. pressure
if gen. manuel antonio noriega leaves, it could start a political free-for-all in panama, where 20 years of military rule with a civilian facade have given opposition parties little chance to mature
no dictatorship ever prepared a people for democracy,'' said editor winston robles of la prensa newspaper, which the noriega-controlled government shut down last month
many political observers, including opposition party leaders, predict a ``free-for-all, no holds barred'' if noriega goes
the general, who heads the 15,000-strong defense forces, says he isn't leaving. he has defied a huge opposition campaign and crippling u.s. economic pressure and even indicated he might run for president
the government-controlled news media have started referring to noriega as ``the undisputed leader of the political majorities'' of panama. his predecessor, gen. omar torrijos, abolished political parties in 1968 after taking power in a coup
in 1977, when he and then-president jimmy carter signed the canal treaties, torrijos founded his own party. he let other parties campaign in 1984, but his revolutionary democratic party won in what the opposition called robbery
most parties here revolve around a single personality _ like 87-year-old arnulfo arias madrid of the authentic panamanian party, deposed three times as president by the military, and the leader of the christian democratic party, ricardo arias calderon, who returned thursday from exile
others parties are what panamanians call ``stationery.'' they exist on paper, issuing statements and communiques, but have no popular following
political parties have not been in the forefront of the campaign against noriega. the drive has been led by the national civic crusade, a coalition of business, private organizations and professional groups and some labor unions
we do not have any political leadership. we are being led by businessmen,'' said a young man collecting food for residents of a panama city slum
while the civic crusade was organizing national strikes and issuing calls for noriega to resign, most politicians applauded from the sidelines. arias calderon and some other christian democratic officials have been an exception
last month, the civic crusade and most of the opposition parties formed an alliance and agreed that if noriega goes, they will work under a transitional government with deposed president eric arturo delvalle as its head. the next election is scheduled for may 1989
the authenic panamanian party, however, refused to join the alliance. party leaders say they will never recognize delvalle because the party he represents robbed them of victory in the 1984 election
arias madrid is a populist first elected in 1940 and first deposed late the following year. he was elected again in 1950 and deposed in 1951. he was elected president a third time in 1968 and deposed after 11 days in office
the authentic panamanians see arias calderon _ arias madrid's vice presidential running mate in 1984 _ as a threat
the christian democrats, the nation's largest opposition party, gave arias madrid the top spot on the 1984 coalition ticket because arias calderon was seen as something of an egghead with little popular appeal
but since then, arias calderon's close cooperation with the civic crusade has positioned him for a presidential bid in a post-noriega panama
when arias calderon returned thursday, aurelio barria, the head of the panamanian chamber of commerce, industry and agriculture and a founder of the civic crusade, stood next to him as he greeted cheering well wishers
arias calderon has also been busy building bridges with other political parties, particularly the liberal republican nationalist movement, in what is seen as an attempt to forge a new coalition
some politicians say they do not expect the crusade to survive long after noriega because its leaders are mostly business people without political affiliation
typical of the crusade leaders are ernesto gonzalez de la lastra, general manager of an insurance company, and barria. neither is affiliated with a political party
other politicians, however, say the strong role people like barria and gonzalez de la lastra have assumed in the crusade could make them forces to be reckoned with if they remain active in public life
pat robertson says his lagging campaign for the republican presidential nomination is being revived in caucus states that will strengthen conservatives' hand at the party convention in new orleans
beyond that goal, robertson said thursday night, he is looking not only to lay the groundwork for another presidential campaign in 1992, but to help build gop strength in state houses and congress for the 1990s
although robertson was beaten by george bush in his home state's non-binding primary on super tuesday, he told 700 supporters at falls church high school that they can still capture most of the state's delegates by turning out in force at local precinct meetings
a few days from now we're going to be celebrating the most important event in the entire christian calendar,'' said the former religious broadcaster, referring to easter, which falls on april 3
he said the press wrote his candidacy off as dead after super tuesday, ``but i don't think they're aware of the resurrection.''
he said his campaign swept county convention delegates in wake county, n.c. on tuesday, and had picked up other delegates in charleston, s.c., as well as georgia, washington, nevada, alaska, hawaii, texas and elsewhere
all over this country, when june comes around and it's all over ... our people should be in significant places of responsibility in something like 15 or 20 of the state republican parties,'' he said
we are going to put together a coalition that will go to new orleans strong, speaking with one voice, and having enough political weight to make sure that some of the things we hold very dear ... are embodied in the platform of the republican party,'' he said
in the next few weeks, as these caucuses unfold in virginia, we are going to win the majority in the republican party,'' he predicted
asked as he left the rally if he was giving up in colorado, a caucus state where his campaign pulled the plug on a bank of 32 phones, robertson said, ``we're going from paid phone banks to volunteer phone banks. the operation is still under way. i'm going out there for a series of meetings a week from saturday.''
in his speech, robertson attacked the civil rights restoration act that congress passed tuesday over president reagan's veto, as ``a horrible bill. it was a federal power grab ... a blot on the u.s. congress.''
many of america's worst problems, including crime and drugs, stem from erosion of morals, he said, adding, ``if we're going to restore the greatness of america, we've got to go back to a sense of personal, individual responsibility.''
we must be no. 1 in our ethics, no. 1 in our morals, no. 1 in our lifestyles, no. 1 in our adherence to freedom, no. 1 in our trust and faith in god almighty,'' he said
we cannot allow the radical democrats to institutionalize aberrant behavior which is part of the destruction of america,'' he said
a falls church high school freshman, debbie weisshaar, 14, of annandale, va., said afterwards that she was discomfited by robertson's repeated references to god and christianity
i wasn't sure if he meant freedom for everyone, or freedom for the people who believed in what he believed in,'' said the teen-ager, who is jewish
robertson has just 17 delegates in the latest associated press count to 788 for bush and 178 for dole
in the chaos and intolerance that is lebanon, rmeileh is an oasis of liberty, a haven for people fleeing political and social persecution and assassination
this coastal town, 19 miles south of beirut, is what lebanon used to be before 13 years of civil war, sectarian hatreds and religious fanatacism turned it into a wilderness
leftists and other refugees from beirut and the south have fled to rmeileh following a campaign of assassinations by shiite moslem fundamentalists against communists, pro-iraqi baath socialists and other leftists
one of the things that makes rmeileh different from just about everywhere else in south lebanon is that alcohol is sold openly at the side of the road
alcohol is banned in most areas of the region, dominated by shiite moslem factions, and in beirut's southern slums, the shiite stronghold in the capital
islamic religious laws also ban mixed parties, mixed bathing and the consumption of pork
but in the summer, rmeileh's eight restaurants and three miles of mediterranean beaches and hillside picnic areas are packed with males and females having a good time. pork also is sold
hamza, 35, comes from the staunchly shiite town of nabatiyeh in the south
we can't buy drinks in nabatiyeh any more, so we come to rmeileh,'' he said. ``in summer women have to come here to swim because it's the one of the very few places they can do that.''
because he lives in a shiite area, where such activities are forbidden, hamza declined to disclose his full name
rmeileh was a mainly christian town, with about 5,000 maronite catholics, until 1985, when moslem forces overran the coastal plain. now only about 60 maronite families are left
but rmeileh now is protected by communist party militiamen, most of them christians, who are allied to neighboring druse and sunni moslem forces who help keep the shiites out
the syrian army also has a checkpoint just south of rmeileh on the awali river which also acts as a deterrent for shiite gunmen
abu rim, a leftist official in the town, said 500 refugee families _ moslems, christians and palestinians _ live in rmeileh with the local christians
our aim is to get rid of the sectarian atmosphere and implement co-existence,'' he said
elias tabet, director of the town's government school, said ethnic mix gives rmeileh a non-sectarian nature, where people from different areas and religions ``feel safe and free.''
samih germanos, 57, a christian who fled beirut's shiite-controlled southern slums, said: ``we're very happy and hope things will stay this way.''
acting mayor halim kleib, said the tourist influx last summer was even better than pre-war times
people in the south prefer rmeileh to other places because it's the closest resort to them that provides restaurants and private beaches as well as drinks,'' kleib added
ali hujeiri, 40, a father of nine, who works at a pepsi cola plant in a nearby town, said he sells alcohol on the street to earn extra money and that most of his customers are from the shiite south
i'm the only one to sell pork in this area,'' said abu elie, a 32-year-old shopowner.``i started bringing it from mount lebanon last week and in four days, i sold around 40 kilograms (88 pounds).''
justice minister nabih berri's amal movement and the iranian-backed hezbollah (party of god) have been blamed for many of the assasinations of leftists in south lebanon
but since many of those who have fled to rmeileh _ ``self-deportees,'' amal calls them _ are skilled or professional people, the amal recently asked them to return to their villages
wafiq rihan, a 33-year-old shiite school teacher, didn't sound as though he is ready to return. he said that after he fled nabatiyeh last year the communists and the leftist druse ``helped us find places to stay and in the beginning we relied on red cross supplies.''
i'm teaching at the school now,'' he added. ``i was originally a teacher. but most of the other deportees here are also working in their particular fields, medicine, the law, and so on
one doctor who fled nabatiyeh even has some of his old patients come here to see him for treatment.''
rihan said he wants to go back to his own village but only when it's safe
two palestinians on night guard duty, masked and armed with clubs, sprinted down the main village road passing the word: ``israeli soldiers are coming!''
behind them, about 20 more moved in the dark with the speed of practice to block the road in a half-dozen places. they dragged stockpiled boulders and twisted metal onto the pavement to slow the 12 jeeps in the israeli patrol
palestinians whose faces were hidden by checkered keffiyeh headdresses whistled shrilly to each other across the rocky hills, tracking the army's progress on the narrow road
the overnight citizen patrol was in action, witnessed in this case by a journalist. the patrol at arura was one of dozens organized after the army started nighttime raids, arresting hundreds of alleged agitators in an effort to quell nearly four months of violent anti-israeli protests
jamal, 30, stood watch atop a ridge on the outskirts of arura, a village of 2,200 palestinians that sprawls over hills of the occupied west bank about 20 miles north of jerusalem
because of these patrols, we are ready for an attack from anywhere,'' he said. ``but there is more than that. the guard duty makes us unified as a people. everyone feels he has a part in the uprising.''
arab patrols are clandestine and all those interviewed would agree only to the use of their first names
riots began dec. 8 in the west bank and gaza strip, which israel has occupied since capturing them from jordan and egypt in the 1967 middle east war. more than 100 palestinians and an israeli soldier have been killed
the patrols are a sign of the changing nature and steady escalation of the ``intefadeh,'' arabic for uprising. they illustrate growing sophistication in a rebellion that began spontaneously and, for that reason, worry israeli officials
illegal local organization could lead to illegal regional organization, all of it directed against us,'' a military man said privately
on this night the army jeeps stopped short of arura, parked for about half an hour, then drove away
why the soldiers approached and left in the latest cat-and-mouse game was not clear, but the villagers viewed called it a retreat by the enemy and a victory for themselves
residents said soldiers had approached arura on three occasions since the patrols began, but stopped each time when guards alerted villagers and about 1,000 people gathered in the streets, chanting and throwing stones
patrolling in arura, as witnessed on two evenings, is a methodical and sometimes tense business
men carrying clubs and rocks, their faces covered, stop each passing car. strangers are ordered out of their vehicles until they are determined to be friends and not israeli soldiers in plainclothes or jews from the nearby ateret settlement
between cars and sightings of soldiers, the sentinels often engage in mutual pep-talk. they encourage each other to continue the fight against israel, make optimistic predictions about the uprising and sometimes ward off the night cold with a shared glass of sweet herb tea
tahir, 23, said he would stand guard until 5 a.m. then leave for his job in an israeli factory, where he packs oranges
i'm one person at night and another in the day,'' he said. ``in israel, they have no idea that i am taking my turn, once a week, on patrol.''
nightly patrols were organized in arura about a month ago after the army had made four raids in a six-week period, arresting 21 young men
israeli soldiers have rounded up more than 700 palestinians in the past week in an effort to end the rebellion, and about 3,000 have been detained since the violence began
soldiers are ordered to make arrests overnight, when most people are sleeping, to avoid causing violent protests
they won't catch us sleeping here and they won't be able to arrest us. we are watching for them every night,'' said salah, 22, one of 250 men of arura aged 16 to 45 who take turns on guard duty from about 8 p.m. until dawn
boys under 16 are not taken for the patrols, but many children are eager to do their part
four boys huddled for warmth over smoldering embers in a small, smoky cave beside the road to the village
they said they would remain until 2 a.m., and if a man came running with word of approaching soldiers they would race through the rocky hills helping wake the villagers
i feel like a man because i am doing something to resist the israelis,'' yassin told a reporter with a solemnity far beyond his 11 years. ``this is in the interest of our homeland. it is the duty of everyone to help.'' crisis</head>
fund-raisers for lyndon larouche were ordered to tell people they owed the political extremist money because he was preventing soviet aggression and global economic collapse, a former larouche aide testified
the fund-raisers also were told that larouche needed the money to pay for security to protect him from assassins, former aide charles tate testified thursday at the federal trial of larouche, six aides and five larouche political groups
tate said larouche followers were treated as soliders and warned repeatedly that falling short of daily quotas was ``the moral equivalent of treason'' and would result in the immediate collapse of western civilization
tate testified that larouche's top fund-raising operative, will wirtz, said prospective donors should be told larouche prevented a soviet takeover, was the only democratic presidential candidate not under kgb influence and the only man on earth who could prevent global economic disaster
the warnings were given in late 1983 and 1984, when larouche followers were under stringent fund-raising quotas because of his campaign and the pending move of organization headquarters from new york to leesburg, va., tate said
larouche, a candidate for the 1988 democratic presidential nomination, is charged with conspiring to obstruct a federal grand jury investigation into allegations that his followers raised more than $2 million through credit card and loan fraud
four larouche organizations, including his two 1984 campaign committees, are charged with fraud. those organizations and a fifth larouche group are charged in the alleged obstruction, as are the six aides
prosecutors, through tate, are attempting to show that intense pressure from larouche led followers to solicit loans by falsely promising they would be repaid and by submitting unauthorized charges to the credit card accounts of past donors to larouche causes
larouche and defense lawyers have conceded some boston fund-raisers might have committed credit card fraud but contend larouche and top aides relieved those fund-raisers of their duties when allegations of impropriety surfaced
larouche contends the allegations of nationwide fraud were concocted as part of a reagan administration plot to ruin him because he opposed contra aid and because his fund-raising competed with former white house aide oliver north's private effort to resupply the nicaraguan rebels at a time when congress had halted government aid
the 125-count indictment against larouche and the other defendants, however, charges that three boston fund-raisers were ordered by larouche to destroy records and flee the country to avoid being called before the grand jury. the three were indicted but are fugitives
the slaughter of kurdish civilians in iraqi poison gas attacks and iranian warnings of retaliation underscore the growth of the chemical warfare arsenals of major middle east powers
despite efforts to curb such weapons, their spread has added a dangerous new dimension to conflicts in the volatile middle east. their use, but not their production, is banned under a 1925 geneva agreement
the london-based jane's defense weekly noted in a recent study that the use of poison and nerve gases since 1984 in the 7{-year-old iran-iraq war has ``changed the rules of war in the middle east.''
tehran charges that iraqi warplanes have dropped chemical bombs on several villages in northwestern iraq after iranian forces overran the kurdish area in a round offensive
western correspondents in iran have reported evidence to substantiate iranian claims that 5,000 iraqi kurds were killed and another 5,000 injured when iraqi warplanes dropped chemical bombs on towns captured by the iranians in northeast iraq last week
nicholas beeston of the times of london reported from halabja, one of the towns, that ``hundreds and possibly thousands'' of the kurds, who have been rebelling against baghdad for years, were killed
hashemi rafsanjani, speaker of iran's parliament and ayatollah ruhollah khomeini's representative on the supreme defense council, warned thursday that iran will be forced to use chemical weapons in retaliation if the iraqi attacks continue
the intensity of tehran's accusations against iraq in recent days has heightened fears that the iranians may be seeking to justify using chemical weapons of their own
u.s. state department spokesman charles redman said wednesday there was evidence iran may already have fired chemical artillery shells into iraq. he declined to elaborate
it's entirely likely that the iranians could do so,'' said don kerr of the international institute for strategic studies in london in a telephone interview
they've had these weapons used against them for a long time.''
iraq, a signatory to the 1925 agreement, has been condemned by the united nation four times since 1984 for using chemical weapons
the iranians claim the iraqis have launched around 100 chemical attacks in that period, mainly against iranian troops
iranian-backed kurdish guerrillas fighting the baghdad regime for autonomy have claimed scores of such attacks on their villages in the last year. but last week's bombing appears to have been the worst chemical attack in the persian gulf conflict
germ warfare dates back to the 14th century, when the tartars catapulted the rotting corpses of plague victims into the besieged crimean city of kaffa in a bid to spread disease
modern chemical warfare began at on april 22, 1915, at 5 p.m. when the germans released 180 tons of chlorine gas at ypres on the western front in world war i
within an hour, 5,000 french soldiers were dead or dying from the wind-blown gas rolling a few fet above their trenches
by the end of the war, gas had killed 100,000 men and affected more than 900,000 others. modern nerve gases are far more lethal
iraq has the biggest chemical weapons armory in the region, with sizable stocks of poison and nerve gases produced at three top-secret plants, western military analysts told the associated press
the sources, speaking on condition of anonymnity, said iraq is now producing sarin, a highly lethal nerve gas that can kill in less than 10 minutes
they said there are indications that the iraqis are also working on germ warfare weapons
the sources estimated that iraq can now produce 60 tons of mustard gas a month and four tons each of sarin and tabun, another highly lethal nerve agent
tabun, first developed by nazi germany before world war ii but never used, is a colorless gas that attacks the body's muscular centers and causes asphyxiation within 15 minutes
the sources said the iraqis' main production plant is at samarra, a heavily guarded 10-square-mile complex ringed by soviet-supplied sa-2 anti-aircraft missiles 70 miles north of baghdad
on the other side, iran's chief military spokesman, kamal kharrazi, has said his country is producing chemical weapons
the analysts and diplomatic sources, who spoke on condition of anonymity, said iranian chemical weapons are believed to be mainly mustard and phosgene gases
kerr noted: ``these are relatively simple to manufacture from readily available industrial components, as is hydrogen cyanide. only the more complex nerve gases are likely to pose a chemical challenge to the iranians.''
the syrians, moscow's main arab ally, also have developed their own chemical weapons industry over the last few years, intelligence and diplomatic sources said
the israelis allege the syrian chemical warfare capability is a serious threat and say syria has the means to deliver nerve agents with soviet-supplied ss-1 scud-b missiles and combat aircraft
in the uphill climb to the moscow summit, the united states this week made a couple of proposals to the soviet union on a new treaty to sharply reduce long-range nuclear weapons
one was the exemption of spy satellites from treaty restrictions. the other was that u.s. and soviet negotiators make a supreme effort to define space-based testing and deployment
the soviets seemed taken with the satellite proposal, but sharpening definitions of space tests and space deployments could be very difficult. there's always been a question whether technology sent into space is part of a permissible test or is a tricky step toward an illicit anti-missile deployment
in any event, with the moscow summit meeting only nine weeks away, the outlook for completing the new u.s.-soviet treaty is not bright
the biggest problem is verification _ making sure cutbacks are carried out
two types of long-range weapons are especially hard to monitor. one is the land-based mobile missile. the other is the sea-launched cruise
experts assisting secretary of state george p. shultz and soviet foreign minister eduard a. shevardnadze were unable to resolve the problem during three days of talks here
and yet, the two sides apparently still intend to try to include the weapons in the accord with all bombers, submarines and missiles having a range in excess of 3,000 miles
the soviets proposed a joint experiment next month to see whether monitors could determine if an american ship was carrying nuclear-tipped cruise missiles
the united states rejected the proposal as unlikely to solve the detection problem
on another front, a little headway was made
the u.s. strategic defense initiative, probably the biggest obstacle to the treaty, and the soviet space defense program will be dealt with separately by the negotiators
the soviets claim the u.s. program, known popularly as star wars, violates the 1972 anti-ballistic missile treaty. they have threatened at various times to hold up a new accord to reduce strategic nuclear weapons unless the u.s. program to develop a defense against ballistic missile were curbed
that ``linkage'' has not been removed
shultz told reporters wednesday night ``the two things move in parallel.'' in other words, the soviets are retaining the right suddenly to halt progress on arms reductions unless the united states slows down sdi
both sides have worked hard and some progress has been realized in a number of areas, but much more needs to be done,'' the two sides said in a communique winding up three days of talks
shultz and shevardnadze will meet again in moscow on april 21. meanwhile, u.s. and soviet negotiators will keep trying to agree on three drafts for the treaty. one deals with the elimination of weapons, another with verifying the cutbacks and the third with the size and location of u.s. and soviet strategic arsenals
before flying home, shevardnadze called the rejected soviet proposal to verify sea-launched cruise missiles a breakthrough in verification. he said the soviets had similar ideas for monitoring mobile intercontinental ballistic missiles and air-launched cruises
i hope that at the april round we will find solutions for a number of these problems,'' the soviet foreign minister said
but he was not all that optimistic about concluding a treaty before the june 29 summit meeting
i can't guarantee that a treaty will be signed in moscow, but it is a possibility, given enough effort,'' he said
barry schweid has covered six u.s.-soviet summits for the associated press
for 58 hours after a toddler tumbled into an abandoned well, hundreds of rescuers worked together to free her, but now an effort to bring their heroism to television has divided them
two groups _ one mostly volunteer rescuers and the other city officials _ are negotiating separately with different tv producers for a movie of the story that captured the nation's attention as it unfolded live on television
both groups are awaiting the endorsement of chip and cissy mcclure, whose 23-month-old daughter jessica became stuck in a 22-foot-deep well for 58 hours in october
one volunteer rescuer, bruce peeler, said he is remaining neutral in the dispute. but he said he wonders whether the story could be told properly in any case
i am wondering if a unified group got together ... if a really true, accurate picture of what took place could ever be put on the screen,'' said peeler, president of midland's airmaster equipment corp., which contributed drilling materials for the rescue
the effort brought praise and a spotlight to midland, an oil town of 97,400 people in western texas
it was a special event. there was so much effort, and everyone had their own story. maybe it should be kept special like that,'' he said thursday
the jessica mcclure rescuer's association, a group of about 30 volunteers, is committed to a movie deal with los angeles producer larry spivey, president of highland communications group inc. the group has asked all rescuers to join them
the association's president, kragg robinson, said 33 members have signed a contract that includes an initial $200,000, plus future payments, to be divided among the membership
the other group, the mcclure rescue association, has narrowed its selection to an unidentified producer but has not signed any commitments. the association, comprising 11 municipal officials including police chief richard czech, fire chief james roberts and paramedic robert o'donnell, wants nothing to do with spivey
we found that he was going around to individual members of our association offering each member side deals that the others didn't know about,'' said martin allday, a lawyer representing the group
spivey says everyone was offered the same deal _ a chance to consult in the production or to act in it
either group or neither group could end up actually making a film. spivey still needs a commitment from a network for his project
my advice to anyone is if they have not signed with the producer to not do so until the mcclures say who they want the movie to be made by,'' said allday
the mcclures have said they don't want to profit by their daughter's story, but do not want to stand in the way of the story being told
peeler said thursday he is concerned that the group of municipal workers will not allow others to help negotiate a movie deal
he said he and other neutral volunteers are working to bring the groups together ``so that the same type of unity and spirit as depicted last october can return.''
i'm sad about this problem,'' he said. ``my concern is that there were several hundred people out there and it is not right that maybe the lady that brought us hamburgers at three in the morning, or the guy who brought the sanitary privvies down _ how do you say they should not be in the movie, too?''
the department of health and human services is trying to determine whether a couple employed by the agency and earning more than $100,000 a year improperly billed it for more than $3,600 in personal expenses
hhs spokesman chuck kline said thursday that department general counsel ron robertson is heading the ethics board inquiry, which is not expected to take more than a few days
the review was started after a washington newsletter _ the child protection report _ obtained copies of travel vouchers for paget w. and terry a. hinch under a freedom of information act request
paget hinch is associate commissioner of the family youth services bureau of hhs. her husband, terry, is director of the social security office of communications technology. both are political appointees who began working at hhs in 1985
the newsletter said the couple flew to the san francisco area, near the hayward, calif., home of terry hinch's family for a one-week stay over thanksgiving 1985, apparently taking their child with them
they billed the government a total of $2,224 for that trip. paget hinch's voucher said her purpose was to visit shelters for runaway youth in the area. terry hinch said he attended a conference and met with a video company in connection with a film on the government's disability insurance program
the newsletter said paget hinch charged the government $1,410 for a 1987 thanksgiving trip to the same area
neither of the two people under investigation could be reached. officials in the branches where they work said it would be inappropriate for them to comment while the matter was under review
paget hinch is paid about $57,000 a year and her husband about $55,000
brochures besmirching the legend of robin hood were ordered publicly burned by an unlikely defender of the medieval hero, the sheriff of nottingham
