the mother of two soldiers was relieved, a shoe store owner was hopeful and opposition leaders welcomed the contra-sandinista cease-fire agreement, but all were skeptical about whether it will bring peace
every mother, even though she doesn't have sons in service, should be happy about peace,'' said auxiliadora del carmen acevedo, whose two sons had been drafted into the army. ``nicaraguans must not continue dying.''
we urgently need peace in nicaragua,'' said mrs. del carmen acevedo, who sells cosmetics in the roberto huembes market. ``all these eight years have been ones of horror.''
more than 40,000 people have died since the fighting began in november 1981, two years after the sandinistas overthrew the rightist regime of the late president anastasio somoza. the economy is a shambles
representatives of the leftist sandinista government and contra rebels signed a 60-day cease-fire agreement wednesday night that promises the contras a role in nicaragua's political process
talks beginning april 6 in managua will seek a permanent peace
alonso moreno, a 57-year-old shoe store owner, said he hoped the accord ``improves the economy and business and that everyone dedicates themselves to producing to put this country back on its feet.''
this is the most important thing that has happened since 1979 when the somoza dictatorship was overthrown,'' said moreno, who has three nephews in military service
i believe that those who are most happy with these announced measures are the thousands of mothers who have sons in the war, the thousands of prisoners in the country and thousands of exiled nicaraguans,'' said ramiro gurdian, an opposition leader and president of the nicaraguan agricultural and livestock producers' union
but gurdian said it should not create false hopes
the people should not believe that the problem is totally resolved,'' he said. ``it's not that way. i would like to see in the short term an adequate solution to the political-military problem to bring the economy out of bankruptcy.''
one hopes this will occur before may, when land is prepared for next year's crops _ 87 percent of the country's exports come from agriculture,'' he added
the war and a u.s. trade embargo have cost the country $3.8 billion in lost income, according to government figures
the last surviving commander of the warsaw ghetto uprising said he was not invited and had no plans to take part in government observances marking the 45th anniversary of the jewish anti-nazi revolt
dr. marek edelman, 66, a former commander of the jewish fighters, said thursday he will organize a ceremony at warsaw's jewish cemetery april 17 to dedicate a monument to two polish jewish socialist leaders executed by the soviets during world war ii
edelman, a staunch supporter of the outlawed solidarity free trade union, said he has invited lane kirkland, chairman of the afl-cio, and western europe leaders
several thousand jews from the united states, israel and other countries are expected to come for the weeklong official observances that culminate april 19 with a ceremony at the warsaw monument to heroes of the uprising
edelman said he was not invited to attend the official celebrations
they didn't invite me, but i wouldn't have taken part in it anyway,'' said edelman, a cardiologist in the central city of lodz
i have never taken part in it because i think this government, which is a totalitarian government, has no right to act in such matters,'' edelman said in a telephone interview
he had refused an invitation from authorities to participate in the april 1983 observances of the 40th anniversary of the uprising
in the uprising, several hundred poorly armed jewish fighters fought a desperate battle resisting the final nazi drive to liquidate the ghetto's 60,000 remaining jews. about 360,000 jews had already been deported from the ghetto to nazi death camps
this year, edelman has invited poles and foreign guests to join him at the ceremony at the jewish cemetery. he said solidarity leader lech walesa was expected to attend
edelman plans to unveil a stone monument honoring henryk erlich and wiktor alter, two leaders of the bund, a jewish socialist labor organization in poland, who were sentenced to death and executed in the soviet union in december 1941
it is important for me personally because i was connected with those people,'' said edelman, who as a leader of the bund's youth organization in the warsaw ghetto was given a command post in the uprising led by mordechai anielewicz
edelman escaped through the sewers when the nazis finally crushed the uprising
in addition to kirkland, edelman says he has invited members of the socialist international including its chairman, former west german chancellor willy brandt, and officials of the european parliament
edelman said the invitations were sent a week ago and he had not yet received any responses
in his letter to kirkland, edelman recalled that u.s. labor leaders had unsuccessfully intervened with soviet authorities to seek the release of the two bund leaders
your presence shall be an expression of solidarity with all unionists and workers fighting for their rights and freedom,'' edelman wrote to kirkland
edelman invited the socialist international members to show by their presence that ``the struggle for freedom, equality and brotherhood has not ceased, that you solidarize with all those who are repressed, and that this remains the superior ideal of socialism.'' up 4th graf pvs, `the dollar ...</note>
