a potent anti-rejection drug can safely be administered orally to severe burn patients, and appears to help skin grafts from cadavers last longer, says a leading burn specialist
i think it's a good first step, but it needs a lot more work,'' dr. a. richard grossman, who used the immunosuppressant drug cyclosporine on 13 patients, said in an interview thursday
grossman, a plastic surgeon and director of the southern california burn center at sherman oaks community hospital in los angeles, was to report his findings today at the american burn association's annual meeting here
cyclosporine has been used in injection and oral form to prevent rejection by the body's immune system of newly transplanted hearts and other organs
grossman said his work over the past year and a half showed that oral doses of the drug are also safe for skin transplants
he said it also appears that cyclosporine enables cadaver skin to ``take'' to the body's skin longer, reducing the need for several expensive cadaver skin grafts and providing a more attractive appearance than laboratory-grown skin
without cyclosporine, cadaver skin is rejected within a week to 10 days, he said. cadaver skin is mainly used to buy time for a few weeks until the patient has enough skin of his or her own to be transplanted. repeated cadaver skin grafts are made until that time
dr. david herndon, chief of staff at the shriners burn institute in galveston, texas, has not seen grossman's study, but said the prolongation effect appears to represent ``tremendous potential.''
grossman said more studies comparing cadaver skin transplants with and without the drug need to be done
grossman is not the first burn specialist to use cyclosporine on severe burn patients. dr. bruce achauer of the university of california at irvine used injections of the drug with poor results, and later used an oral dose on one patient, who survived, grossman said
grossman said he decided to try lower, oral doses
because of concern over kidney failure in burn patients, the grossman study on nine patients referred to in his paper and on four subsequent patients used increasingly lower doses
our original purpose was to let the cadaver skin stay on a while until we could reharvest the patient's own skin,'' grossman said. ``but we found after about three or four weeks that it was staying on for good.''
the first patient in the study was kept on cyclosporine for two months after his discharge from the hospital, grossman said. ``but with each successive patient we found they needed less and less'' cyclosporine
with the last patients in the study, the medication was discontinued before discharge, within six weeks of the injury
i don't believe that using cadaver skin with a possibly dangerous drug is the be-all and end-all,'' grossman said. ``i think we're plugging a dike until the right thing comes along.'' that, he said, would be improvements in the use of laboratory-grown skin
corrupt city health inspectors doubled and tripled their annual salaries by extorting hundreds of thousands of dollars from restaurants, federal officials said after the arrest of more than two dozen employees
the restaurant owners would dread seeing these inspectors pull up in their cadillacs and rolex watches,'' said james fox, assistant director in charge of the fbi's new york office. ``they turned the department of health into their own department of wealth.''
city health-code inspections of restaurants will be temporarily suspended while the department of health reorganizes
the revelations of widespread and longstanding corruption among restaurant inspectors are particularly repellent and painful because of the importance'' of public health, health commissioner stephen joseph said
twenty-eight people, including health inspectors, their supervisors and former health department employees who acted as middlemen, were charged thursday with extorting money from restaurateurs. the health department employees earned annual salaries of $25,000 to $30,000
if convicted, each could face a maximum penalty of 20 years in jail and a fine of $250,000
the charges contained in the complaint represent about one-third of the employees responsible for enforcing the city's health code, u.s. attorney andrew maloney said
inspectors allegedly secured the extortion money by threatening to cite restaurants for health-code violations
about 300 of the city's 15,000 restaurants were victimized, ranging from fast-food establishments to little ethnic places to some tony manhattan spots. a chart released by the fbi showed that the restaurants were in all five boroughs, with the largest concentration on manhattan's upper east side
the names of the restaurants were withheld because the owners are considered victims and because the information could hinder a grand jury investigation, maloney said
the city's department of investigations and the fbi combined separate investigations, dubbed ``kitchen net'' and ``operation sanisweep'' respectively, in 1986. they used a combination of confidential informants, undercover agents and physical and electronic surveillance
fox said if a restaurant owner refused to give an inspector a payoff during a regular inspection, the inspector would claim to find mouse droppings or dead flies in the restaurant and threaten to issue violations or, in some cases, close the restaurant
in one case, on-site inspectors demanded $1,400 from a restaurant owner to prevent the establishment from being closed for serious health violations, authorities said. in another, inspectors charged a queens restaurant $1,200 to allow it to reopen despite serious code violations
a confidential informant told authorities that he and another inspector made up to six stops a day and collected $500 to $1,000 in payoffs from owners at each restaurant, according to fox
the extortion payoffs were shared with inspectors' supervisors, authorities said. one senior inspector was called ``hungry joe'' by his fellow inspectors because he made so many demands
in addition, he said, former health department inspectors and others established ``consulting'' companies that would advise restaurants on how to pass inspections and would act as middlemen for the extortions
supervisors allegedly would recommend these consulting services to restaurants and then take a percentage of the consultation fee, authorities said
before his arrest on fraud charges, a high-living 23-year-old investment adviser lured customers by falsely telling them that his other clients included the rockefeller family and bill cosby, authorities say
those allegations were contained in criminal charges against david bloom filed thursday in u.s. district court. bloom is expected to plead guilty at a court appearance next week, according to his lawyer, peter morrison
bloom, who was not licensed as an investment adviser, allegedly lied to clients by telling them their funds were invested in the stock market when he was actually pouring the money _ more than $10 million worth _ into private purchases
among his purchases were works of art totaling $5.5 million; an $830,000 manhattan apartment; a beach house in east hampton worth $1.9 million; two cars _ an aston-martin convertible and a mercedes-benz _ worth $200,000; and home furnishings that cost $800,000
bloom also bought ``numerous items of expensive jewelry; and deluxe trips to europe and the caribbean for himself, his family and friends,'' according to the federal charges of mail fraud and securities fraud
the charges say that bloom ``falsely told investors that he managed money for prominent individuals and investors, including the rockefeller family, the sultan of brunei (and) bill cosby.''
in a brief appearance before u.s. magistrate barbara lee, bloom waived his right to have his case heard by a grand jury. after he entered a plea of innocent, ms. lee assigned the case to u.s. district judge david edelstein
bloom apparently was ready to plead guilty before edelstein, but the judge was unavailable and the case was scheduled for next thursday
if found guilty of the two charges against him, bloom faces a maximum sentence of five years in prison on each count and a maximum fine of twice the amount lost by investors
bloom was arrested jan. 14 on a federal complaint charging him with fraud. he had begun investing money for friends while at duke university and had 130 clients at his greater sutton investors group inc. in manhattan at the time of his arrest
morrison has said many of the items bloom purchased would be sold and his clients could recover their money and a profit. the assets were turned over to a court-appointed receiver
a former wedtech corp. executive says the scandal-plagued defense contractor contributed to numerous political campaigns, not because of ideology but ``for favors we expected to get.''
former wedtech vice chairman mario moreno also testified thursday that he gave under different names, about $30,000 to sen. alfonse d'amato, r-n.y., to evade election law contribution limits
federal election law limits individual campaign contributions to $1,000 per election and bars corporate contributions
a d'amato spokesman branded moreno's testimony ``ridiculous.''
moreno's claims came during defense cross-examination at the racketeering trial of rep. mario biaggi, d-n.y., and six others
prosecutors have said d'amato will testify for the government
the prosecution contends biaggi enlisted the help of d'amato and other politicians to help secure no-bid contracts for wedtech, then extorted millions of dollars in wedtech stock as a payoff
he and his co-defendants are accused of turning wedtech into a racketeering enterprise that paid out millions of dollars in bribes for government contracts and other favors
moreno is among four former wedtech executives cooperating with the government in return for leniency on state and federal charges to which they pleaded guilty
defense attorney maurice nessen got moreno, who was on the witness stand for the eighth day thursday, to admit he and other wedtech executives contributed to d'amato and other public officials who have not been charged with wrongdoing
now d'amato, sen. d'amato. there were contributions to his campaign that you in fact hid and put under different names so you could violate the limits on campaign contributions. isn't that correct,'' nessen asked
`yes,'' said moreno
when nessen asked moreno if he had given d'amato close to $30,000, the witness said it might have been more than that
and all the while, the senator from new york was helping you get contracts with the government?'' nessen asked later
yes,'' said moreno, later saying that d'amato ``was one of the most important people'' in helping wedtech secure a multimillion-dollar navy contract without competitive bidding
ed martin, the d'amato spokesman in washington, said, ``we have no knowledge of any secret contributions.''
he said prosecutors told d'amato staffers there was ``a lot of false name-dropping going on'' at the trial. ``this is an example.''
moreno said he and wedtech officials contributed to the campaigns of mayor edward i. koch, gov. mario cuomo, city comptroller harrison j. goldin and state sen. john marchi, none of whom has been charged with wrongdoing
he said contributions were made to the democratic, republican and conservative parties, not because of political ideology but ``in exchange for favors we expected to get.''
asked what favors wedtech expected from the republican state committee, moreno said, ``we expected to get the republican party in our pocket.''
by giving a check for $2,500?'' nessen asked incredulously
by giving a lot of checks,'' moreno said without elaborating
what he refers to, i have no idea,'' ed lurie, executive director of the gop state committee, said in a telephone interview from his albany office
if their (wedtech officials') purpose was to get some sort of hook into us, god, we didn't know it,'' lurie said. ``i didn't know certain people gave to us until i saw it in the newspapers.''
general motors corp. is being ordered to recall nearly 500,000 1985 vehicles for failure to meet federal air pollution standards, but the automaker and the government are at odds over how to fix the problem
the environmental protection agency, which announced the recall order thursday, said a faulty thermal vacuum switch was part of the reason the vehicles' exhaust contains excess carbon monoxide and evaporated gasoline
gm spokeswoman jane mott said the automaker told the epa it believed replacing the switch on the vehicles would be sufficient to bring emissions into compliance with federal standards
the epa, however, said its tests showed that ``replacement of the (switch) alone will not completely remedy the problem and that additional repairs may be necessary.''
gm has 45 days either to request a public hearing to contest the order, or to submit a repair plan for epa's approval before notices are mailed to owners
the vehicles affected by the recall are equipped with 5.0 liter (305 cubic inches) and 5.7 liter (350 cubic inches) engines, the epa said
they were sold as the chevrolet impala, caprice classic, camaro, monte carlo and el camino; the pontiac firebird, bonneville, grand prix and parisienne; and the gmc caballero, epa said. models sold in california, which are built to stricter standards, are also included
two education groups that say children are being subjected to tests too early in life are calling on schools not to subject kindergarten children to standardized exams that determine advancement to first grade
our children are being tested too early and failed too soon, and parents should ask for what purpose,'' said sue bredekamp, accreditation director of the national association for the education of young children
her group was joined thursday by the national association of early childhood specialists in state departments of education calling for an end to mass standardized testing of children before the third grade
the groups said the same tests are being used to determine whether a youngster is admitted to kindergarten or advised to spend another year in preschool
advocates for people who are hearing impaired say a federal communications commission proposal to require that more telephones be hearing-aid compatible does not go far enough
the fcc on thursday proposed to extend compatibility requirements to all credit-card operated phones and phones in common areas of a hearing-impaired employee's workplace. the agency said extending the requirement to all phones with existing technology would be unwise
karen peltz strauss, an attorney for the national center for law and the deaf at gallaudet university in washington said the fcc action was not tough enough and that legislation still is needed to extend compatibility to all phones
i just don't see those two areas (where the fcc extended compatibility requirements) as nearly sufficient to meet the needs of equal access for the hearing impaired,'' she said
an estimated 400,000 americans are expected to participate in a may 4 national program offering blood cholesterol tests
hundreds of hospitals will offer free tests, while a few will charge $3
the program, organized by the voluntary hospitals of america, was outlined thursday at a news conference. officials said they were announcing the national program well in advance to give people plenty of time to learn where they can go for testing for the fatty substance that is a leading contributor to heart disease and strokes
about 400 not-for-profit hospitals that are members of the association have agreed to participate. a public service television spot promoting the program, called ``countdown usa,'' will begin airing next week
it includes a toll-free telephone number _ 800-634-9541 _ for people to call weekdays from 9 a.m. to 6 p.m. (est) to find out which hospitals in their areas will offer the testing. victory</head>
thousands of people marched in memory of a slain archbishop while the man accused of ordering the clergyman's assassination defended his far-rightist party's nationwide election victory
about 10,000 people joined in thursday's march, which was called by student, labor, rights and church groups on the eighth anniversary of monsignor oscar romero's death. the bishop was shot through the heart by a sniper as he celebrated mass at a chapel in san salvador
the marchers carried flowers, large portraits of the bespectacled bishop and banners saying ``monsignor romero did not die in vain.'' they chanted calls for the prosecution an punishment of those responsible
in the weeks prior to his assassination, romero called on members of the security forces to disobey orders to torture, kidnap and murder their countrymen
the late 1970s and early 1980s were a time of intense activity of salvadoran death squads. in 1980, when romero was killed, the squads of soldiers, police and extremist anti-leftist civilians were blamed for killing more than 500 suspected leftists a month
no one was indicted in romero's slaying, but president jose napoleon duarte late last year publicly accused roberto d'aubuisson, a right-wing legislator and former army major, of masterminding the slaying
the case is solved. we know who did it, who ordered it, who drove the getaway car,'' duarte told the country on nationwide television in november
he accused d'aubuisson of issuing the order, and said testimony from the driver of the killer's car backed up his claim
d'aubuisson, the founder and a legislator for the far-rightist republican nationalist alliance, or arena, denies the charge. he says it is politically motivated slander
duarte's government has asked the united states for extradition of a salvadoran army captain, alvaro saravia, who allegedly hired the sniper. saravia, arrested for a traffic violation, is in jail in miami pending resolution of the extradition request
local authorities say it could be granted in the coming months
but whether the case will ever reach court is not clear. as a legislator, d'aubuisson enjoys broad immunity from prosecution. his party was the big victor in sunday's elections for all 60 members of the unicameral national assembly and municipal officials across this nation of 5 million
it is unlikely an assembly controlled by d'aubuisson's party would strip him of immunity to allow him to stand trial as an alleged conspiritor in romero's assassination
early returns indicated arena would hold an outright majority in the assembly and most town and city posts nationwide
but on wednesday, arena leaders charged the governing christian democrats with manipulating returns in an effort ``to steal'' the right's parliamentary majority. d'aubuisson and other arena chiefs said violence could erupt if the vote count was flawed
the christian democrats, who had 33 seats in the outgoing assembly but are expected to have fewer than 25 in the new one, deny the charge
arena had 13 seats in the old legislature
talking with reporters thursday, d'aubuisson was calmer than the previous day. but he insisted his party would not permit maneuvers to erode its electoral result
the people's will cannot be subverted,'' he said. ``by tomorrow (friday) afternoon we believe the central elections council will be in a position to announce definitive official results that will confirm the triumph of our party.''
but there was no promise from the council that final results would be ready today
council president mario samayoa told reporters: ``we will take as long as is necessary to make sure the electoral law is fulfilled, whether certain parties or individuals like it or not.'' companion</head>
an 18-year-old anti-nuclear activist charged today he was tortured for two days at the headquarters of president corazon aquino's security force and his companion was murdered
a spokesman for mrs. aquino said he was unaware of the allegations. military chief of staff gen. renato de villa said he was willing to have authorities investigate the charge
hilario bustamante recounted his ordeal to reporters who interviewed him at a government hospital. he was recovering from a deep wound in the back of his neck doctors said must have been inflicted with a machete or an ax
the injury was similar to that which killed bustamante's companion, rey francisco, whose body was found by police monday night in a field on the outskirts of the capital. the field is near where a private security guard found bustamante's near-dead body hours earlier
speaking in a low voice and unable to move his body, bustamante said an unidentified woman was also hacked that same night. police have not reported finding any female body in the field
bustamante said he, francisco and five other members of the leftist youth for democracy and nationalism were pasting up posters against nuclear arms and u.s. military bases saturday when about six armed men in a jeep chased them
he said the men, in civilian clothes, claimed they were police ``authorized by malacanang (presidential palace)'' to arrest the youths. the men caught bustamante and francisco a few blocks away, but the others escaped
bustamante claimed he and francisco were taken to a military compound behind the presidential palace, where he said they where they were handcuffed, blindfolded, interrogated and tortured
the compound houses the headquarters of the presidential security group
they wanted us to admit we were members of the sparrow unit, that we were npa,'' bustamante said, referring to the communist new people's army and its assassination unit. ``they kept asking us whether we killed such and such policeman or soldier.''
they beat us with iron rods and burned us with cigarettes,'' he said
late monday, bustamente said three men drove him, francisco and the woman to the field and hacked them
deputy presidential spokesman danilo gozo said he was unaware of bustamante's charges
we will ask the presidential security group, but it sounds odd,'' gozo said. ``we will have to check if it is a fact.''
de villa called on bustamante to provide evidence to back up his charge
i'm willing to have all these kinds of incidents investigated,'' he told reporters. ``we do not tolerate, we do not condone the use of torture. we are willing to subject our people to genuine investigation.''
earlier this month, amnesty international charged in a report released in london that the philippine military was using torture and murder to fight the 19-year communist insurgency. mrs. aquino called the report one-sided
thunderstorms pelted parts of texas and arkansas early today with large hail and destructive winds, while a tornado damaged houses and injured a man in missouri
showers and thunderstorms lined a cold front that extended from eastern wisconsin through the middle mississippi valley into louisiana. the strongest thunderstorms were scattered from arkansas into louisiana
the tornado tore through texas county, mo., thursday evening, damaging 10 houses and injuring a man when the side of his home blew out. he was treated for cuts in texas county memorial hospital, an ambulance official said
officials said the tornado cut a 12-mile path through the south-central missouri county, trapping a family in their home until rescue workers freed them unharmed
jim and barbara maples of rural nixa, mo., said they jumped out of their mobile home just minutes before winds tore off the top. ``i just hung on to the pickup and (jim) said, `there goes the roof,''' said mrs. maples
thunderstorms produced large hail and damaging winds across arkansas and northeast texas late thursday and early today. hail 1} inches in diameter pelted clarksville and fannin county, texas, while 1-inch diameter hail hit mena, ariz., near checotah, okla., and near desoto, sherman and dallas, texas
dierks, ark., was pounded by wind gusts to 60 mph along with 1-inch hail, and hail of a similar size covered the ground at tom, okla. texarkana, ark., had 1-inch hail, heavy rain and winds gusting to 50 mph
