when ``the gospel at colonus'' sings, it soars, raising the roof of broadway's cavernous lunt-fontanne theater and the spirits of everyone within shouting distance
there isn't a more joyous expression of song on broadway, and that may be enough for some people. it's when the production stops to tell its tale that the show sags, marking time until the next musical explosion
this overlong gospel celebration, which opened thursday, offers a sketchy and an often confusing version of sophocles' ``oedipus at colonus,'' set within the framework of a rousing black pentecostal church service. what little is left of the greek tragedy in lee breuer's adaptation is overwhelmed by religious fervor
oedipus, in this version, comes to colonus seeking redemption but is rejected at first by its citizens. when his prayers for forgiveness are heard by theseus, king of athens, oedipus and his two daughters antigone and ismene are welcomed back to the holy city
the daughters are seized by creon, king of thebes, but then released after the intercession of theseus. oedipus then prepares for a happy death
breuer, according to program notes, sees the show as a sermon or series of parables on fate, and much of the story is delivered between songs by a minister, played by morgan freeman. he's a commanding figure on stage but must muddle through the rudimentary narrative that rarely clarifies its characters
the real passion comes from the singers, many of them gospel music veterans, led by clarence fountain and the five blind boys of alabama. they all sing different facets of the role of oedipus
fountain has an ingratiating, swivel-hipped stage presence, a booming voice and sass to spare. he gets ample support from several other soloists and gospel groups including jevetta steele and the j.d. steele singers and j.j. farley and the soul stirrers
the entire production is backed up by the institutional radio choir, a brooklyn-based church group. its 30 members, dressed in colorful african robes, sit on bleachers that climb high above the stage. large greek columns, designed by alison yerxa, rise behind them
the choir shouts its affirmation to much of freeman's preaching, and their enthusiasm is infectious. the choir is the focal point of the evening's two show-stopping numbers _ ``no never,'' a rousing hymn of welcome, and ``lift him up,'' a song of redemption after oedipus has gone peacefully to his death
the music by bob telson is melodic, just right for hand-clapping and toe-tapping, while breuer's lyrics are simple without being simplistic
breuer also directed the musical, and he could have trimmed the show without diluting its impact. as it stands, ``the gospel at colonus'' is often a long wait between the hosannas
in other reviews:
this is a show that never stops advertising its high-mindedness, whether in its program notes or on stage,'' writes frank rich in the new york times
but happily, there is the music, too, and it is so rousing ... that the considerable spoken text ... can never completely upstage it. ... even a cynic may feel that the tidal wave of music is lifting him to some higher, ecstatic plane.''
in the daily news, don nelson called the conception ``innovative and brilliant,'' although the show itself ``seemed somewhat longer than it should be ...''
but, he said, ``the power of this production cannot be denied. there is no broadway musical _ none _ that attains the rarefied heights that `gospel' does at its best.''
leslie anne monk of england won the less-than-coveted ``red lantern'' award, finishing last in the iditarod trail sled dog race and eight days after winner susan butcher
the rookie musher crossed the finish line in the 1,150-mile anchorage-to-nome race at 10:22 p.m. thursday, in 45th place at 19 days, 13 hours, 22 minutes and 55 seconds. fifty-two teams started the 16th annual iditarod on march 5
butcher crossed the finish line on march 16 to claim her third straight iditarod victory
monk said she walked 11 of the last 22 miles until a lead dog that had run in a previous iditarod recognized the trail and got the other six moving again
the iditarod, named after an old supply route to the gold mining districts of interior alaska, draws its inspiration from a 1925 relay of diphtheria serum to nome, which was hit hard by an outbreak of the disease
elliott ``pete'' estes, an engineer who rose through the ranks at general motor corp. to retire as president, has died after apparently suffering a heart attack, officials said. he was 72
estes, who lived in paradise valley, ariz., served as gm's 15th president and chief operating officer from 1974 until his retirement in 1981
he collapsed thursday outside o'hare international airport while waiting for a ride, police said. he was on his way to a meeting of the kellogg co. board of directors. he was pronounced dead on arrival at resurrection hospital
pete estes was one of gm's brightest stars. in whatever role he assumed for the corporation, he performed at peak capacity,'' gm chairman roger b. smith said in a statement
a native of mendon, mich., estes began a lifetime relationship with gm in 1934 when he enrolled at general motors institute in flint, mich. he joined gm research laboratories as a cooperative student while at the institute
in 1939 he became a research engineer and later worked in the company's oldsmobile, pontiac and chevolet divisions
estes was named executive vice president for operations staff in 1972 and was elected president by the company's board of directors in 1974
estes is survived by his wife, connie, and three sons, thomas, edward and william
