women who let sexually transmitted diseases go untreated run the risk of dangerous pregnancies, researchers say
medical investigators at the national centers for disease control in atlanta explored 22 possible problems they thought might lead to ectopic or tubal pregnancies, in which the fetus develops outside the womb
their study is reported in today's journal of the american medical association
ectopic pregnancies occur tens of thousands of times annually, and account for 10 percent of all u.s. maternal deaths and are a major cause of infertility, the researchers said
they examined 274 cases of ectopic pregnancy diagnosed from 1935 to 1982 in rochester, minn., and compared the cases with 548 live-birth deliveries during the same period among similar women
one of four problems researchers identified more often among women with ectopic pregnancies was previous pelvic inflammatory disease, an infection of the upper genital tract that can result from untreated diseases of the lower tract
the study's lead authors, polly a. marchbanks of the cdc, said a history of venereal disease alone does not appear to increase ectopic pregnancy risk, but appears to increase risk if it advances to the upper genital tract
that means women have another good reason to seek medical help if they think they have a sexually transmitted disease, she said
other problems in women with ectopic pregnancies were previous infertility for at least one year and having undergone reproductive surgery of the fallopian tubes, the researchers said
and they found a strong association between conception while using an intrauterine birth control device and ectopic pregnancies. women who had an ectopic pregnancy were 13.7 times more likely to have been using iuds at the time of conception than women in the comparison group, the study said
a cdc researcher not involved in the study, dr. nancy lee, said that figure is inaccurate because it compares two groups that shouldn't be compared: women using birth control and women using no birth control
in an ectopic pregnancy, the fertilized egg lodges somewhere in the abdomen besides the womb. in 97 percent of cases, the site is in the fallopian tubes, where as the fetus enlarges, it can rupture the tubes or cause severe bleeding
though ectopic pregnancy is dangerous, it can now be detected early and the pregnancy ended surgically before damage makes a woman infertile, wrote dr. robert n. taylor, in an editorial accompanying the study
softball players would break considerably fewer bones if breakaway bases replaced anchored bags on recreational league diamonds, says a study published today
no system is foolproof, because poor technique can defeat a lot of safety measures,'' dr. david janda, one of the study's four authors, said thursday. ``but this is one place where we can do something almost immediately.''
breakway bags could reduce injuries by more than 90 percent, according to the study published in the journal of the american medical association
the study even contains some good news for baseball purists worried that using breakaway bases would detract from the game's tradition
we did not have a single problem about an out call from either a player or an umpire in the more than 600 games we looked at,'' said janda
not only was there not one complaint, but we had a meeting of managers after the season, and virtually everybody said we had to have breakaway bases on the rest of the fields,'' he added
janda, two colleagues from the orthopedic surgery section at the university of michigan at ann arbor, and a director of the city's softball league gathered data from 633 softball games on diamonds that used breakaway bases and 627 games on stationary-base fields
stationary bases usually are anchored with a nut-and-bolt type arrangement in a tube driven into the ground. a set of three breakaway bases costs $295 vs. $150 for stationary bases
the breakaway bases used in the study had two parts: a rubber plate mounted flush with the ground and a base secured on top with suction and small rubber grommets that can pop loose
there were 45 sliding injuries, or about 7.2 per 100 games, on the stationary-base fields compared to two, or about 0.3 per 100 games, on the breakaway field _ a ratio of nearly 23-to-1
medical costs for the 45 injuries totaled more than $55,000
dr. jeffrey sacks of the atlanta-based federal centers for disease control, took the numbers from the study and extrapolated them nationwide
if all games were played on stationary bases _ and we know they're not _ we could expect 1.7 million sliding injuries and medical costs over $2 billion,'' sacks said
put those same people on fields with breakaway bases and the numbers are just over 70,000 injuries and $24 million in medical costs,'' he said
janda said his study revealed that most of the injuries resulted from ``things like not knowing how to slide, poor conditioning, late decision-making on when to slide, and even alcohol consumption.''
janda, who described himself as ``a no-hit, no-field'' second baseman, declined to say how frequently alcohol figured into the equation
nobody on our team drinks,'' he said, ``but we've played teams where everybody does.''
delays in illinois medicaid payments could force private residential-care facilities to evict hundreds of mentally retarded patients in the coming months, officials say
if nothing changes, we will see 50 to 1,500 people discharged from community residential centers throughout the state,'' said peter mule, director of the riverside oundation, a home for retarded adults in lincolnshire
earlier this week riverside received a reimbursement check from the state department of public aid for december, but is still owed at least $250,000 for care provided since then, mule said
another non-profit agency, clearbrook center in suburban rolling meadows, will have to close within three months if $446,000 owed by the state can't be found elsewhere, center president guerin fischer said
reimbursements are slow now, and they're bound to get worse, said edward duffy, state public aid director. ``i'm not choosing to do this, i'm running out of money,'' he said
duffy said because the general assembly underfunded the medicaid program by $159 million last year, reimbursement money will run out
requests received after april 15 won't be paid until july, duffy said
we're working along with banks to help these agencies get credit lines,'' duffy said. ``but the only real solution is more money.''
if the private homes are forced to evict their residents, the state would have to make room for them in already crowded facilities
we would have to put these people up on cots in gymnasiums,'' said david devane, a spokesman for the department of mental health. ``they would be without programs, without any treatment that is not life sustaining.''
gov. james r. thompson's proposed $22.2 billion budget for fiscal 1989 includes a $342 million increase for the public aid department to pay past-due bills and reduce the delays in medicaid reimbursements
what do you get when you take a jacket and combine it with batteries, loudspeakers and a cassette or compact disc player?
the sonic jacket, which toshiba america inc. sees as the logical next step from portable cassette and cd players
people are taking their music with them, so forward-thinking designers thought, `why not build them into our clothing to keep the hands free?''' said david shoults, toshiba's national sales promotion manager
the sonic jacket, developed at toshiba's wayne offices, is made of cotton and twill and has pockets in the front that house four c-size batteries and a cassette or cd player
five feet of wires sealed by velcro into the jacket's lining are connected to four speakers _ two low-frequency speakers in the lining of chest pockets and two ``tweeter-type'' speakers on the shoulders, shoults said
the jacket, currently available in limited supplies, has detachable sleeves, comes in three sizes in white and black, and sells for $199.95
as clothing goes, the sonic jacket is not loud, shoults said
this is intended to be personal electronics,'' he said. ``you can't really turn these things up so loud. they just don't play that loud.''
shoults said that if the sonic jackets prove to be a success, sound systems could turn up in a variety of clothing
what's next? sonic shorts? 
a burglar who stole a computer from a tax preparer's office turned out to be a user-friendly thief _ he mailed tax return information on 150 clients back to his victim
he also called elizabeth savano to apologize, she said thursday
the $9,000 computer and a printer were taken from her office in this city near oakland on march 5
when savano opened her office the same day, she found a note from the thief saying he would return the hard disk containing the program for calculating taxes and other information. he also called that day
i'm still haunted by it,'' savano said
four days later, savano received a package in the mail. it didn't contain the hard disk, but there were 20 floppy disks and a note from the burglar explaining how he had transferred the information onto the floppies
it's just weird,'' savano said
the tax preparer said she was glad the information was returned. ``that helped, but i'm still out the computer.''
subway gunman bernhard goetz and his girlfriend attended the opening of a murder trial of a woman who claims she stabbed her abusive boyfriend to death in self-defense
this trial should not be happening,'' goetz said after opening arguments in state supreme court, the state's trial-level court, in manhattan on thursday
damian pizarro is accused of killing her boyfriend, emerson gaylor, on aug. 19, 1986. her attorney, peter neufeld, said gaylor began abusing ms. pizarro after she became pregnant with his child in 1984
goetz' girlfriend, lisbeth theisen, said the couple decided to attend ``to show support'' for ms. pizarro
goetz is free on bail while appealing his conviction in the shooting of four teen-agers on a subway train in december 1986. goetz, who maintained he fired because he felt threatened, was convicted last june on a weapons charge
more americans are learning about the causes of aids and discussing it with their kids, according to a new federal report
the national center for health statistics, which launched its aids awareness interviews in august, reports that children are getting more education about aids at school and at home
the most notable changes between the november survey results _ the latest available _ and those from one month earlier ``were in the proportion of adults who reported having discussed aids with their children and who stated that their children had received aids education at school,'' the center reported
in november, 68 percent of those surveyed said they had discussed aids with their children ages 10-17. that was up 5 percent from october, and up 8 percent from august, according to the report, released thursday by the center's parent agency, the federal centers for disease control
also in november, 51 percent of the adults surveyed said their kids had received aids instruction in school; that was up 6 percent from october, and 15 percent from august
throughout the surveys, about one-third of the adults questioned did not know if their children had learned about acquired immune deficiency syndrome in school
the center also reported that public awareness about aids increased noticeably over the first four months of surveys
for example, in august, only 61 percent of the americans surveyed by the center believed it very unlikely or impossible to get aids from shaking hands with a patient; in november, the percentage had risen to 70
and only 53 percent of those surveyed in august believed it very unlikely or impossible to get aids from working near someone who has it; by november, it was up to 61 percent
aids experts say the disease is not spread through such casual contact. aids, which had struck 57,024 americans and killed 31,836 as of march 21, is spread most often through sex or shared drug needles
the 3,333 adults questioned in november were not the same group interviewed in previous months. the survey is designed with a margin of error no more than 1 percent
a new non-profit group is saving old computers from the scrap heap and shipping them to third world countries
equipment which is outdated here is often state-of-the-art in africa, asia and latin america,'' said phillip friedman, executive director of global technology foundation
the group based in boulder hopes to improve the quality of life in the third world, create new markets for advanced equipment and provide tax breaks for donors of old computers
it has filed for tax-exempt status with the internal revenue service so corporations would be able to claim the book value of donated equipment, while individuals could deduct fair market value, friedman said
the philippines is targeted for a pilot project because a distribution system is already established there through another non-profit group, he said
we will focus on sending equipment into communities, rather than government bureaucracies,'' friedman said
more than $80,000 in equipment already has been donated, officials said
the research nuclear reactor at the center of a debate over whether taiwan has an atomic weapons program has been closed temporarily, but not because of u.s. pressure, a top government official said today
liu kuang-chi, secretary general of the government atomic energy council, told the associated press the reactor is being converted to a system that no longer requires heavy water, which is used to control the splitting of atomic nuclei
local newspapers have reported the military-run chungshan institute of science and technology shut down the reactor at lung tan, 25 miles southwest of taipei, after the u.s. government suspended delivery of heavy water
the new york times reported wednesday that the reagan administration pressured taiwan to close the reactor and stop work on a secret installation that could have processed the reactor's spent fuel to extract plutonium, a key component of nuclear weapons
the reactor was not closed because of u.s. pressure,'' liu said during a brief interview as he left a meeting with lawmakers. he declined comment on the report of a secret installation to process spent fuel
liu said plans to convert the reactor are four years old and designed to make the facility compatible with the island's three nuclear power plants. he refused to elaborate
the reactor was closed in january for the remodification, according to liu, who would not say when the facility will restart
he said taiwan reported the plans to the vienna-based atomic energy agency last week. he refused to explain why the notification was made two months after the closure
chang kuo-lung, professor of physics of the national taiwan university, said the remodification plan was uneconomical
this is like buying a car and replacing its engine with one from another car,'' he said
local newspapers, without disclosing their sources, have said the u.s. government learned from col. chang hsien-yi, former deputy director of the institute's nucleary energy research center, that taiwan had plans to make nuclear weapons
chang has been missing since january, and local newspapers have claimed he is working for the cia and living in the united states. taiwan officials say they do not know his whereabouts but are investigating the case
government officials have reiterated taiwan's position that it has not developed any nuclear weapons. communist china has said taiwanese production of atomic weapons would be a reason for invading the island, which beijing views as a renegade province
lawmaker jaw shau-kong of the ruling nationalist party today asked the government to lodge the ``strongest protest'' to washington if the united states is found to be involved in col. chang's disappearance
the united states can have nuclear weapons. many other countries have their nuclear weapons,'' jaw said at the legislative yuan, taiwan's highest lawmaking body. ``we may not want to develop nuclear weapons, but we cannot give up our high-technology research work because of this.''
jaw said taiwan ``can never tolerate the central intelligence agency to recruit one of our colonels and then get him to the united states.''
a day earlier, jaw urged the government to ask the united states to resume supplying heavy water so the lung tan reactor could continue production of isotopes used in certain x-ray techniques, cancer treatments and scientific research
police arrested 23 people in connection with a mob-controlled betting operation that netted $75 million a year from wagers on college basketball, a spokesman said
authorities seized two satellite dishes, 33 telephones, four shotguns, a stolen handgun, ammunition and $25,000 in cash while making arrests thursday night in manhattan, the bronx and queens, said police sgt. raymond o'donnell
the betting ring was controlled by the genovese crime family, o'donnell said. he said police were not sure how long it had been in operation
all 23 people arrested were charged with promoting gambling, possession of gambling records and possession of gambling devices, all felonies, the spokesman said
the arrests and seizures followed a six-week investigation involving city police and state police from new york and new jersey, o'donnell said
a philadelphia teen-ager whose parents and brothers were found slain in a bathtub was arrested by tennessee state troopers at a truck stop
jose enrique hernandez, 17, was scheduled to appear today in a detention and extradition hearing in charlotte. philadelphia police were in tennessee to escort him back to pennsylvania to face four counts of murder
hernandez was arrested early thursday at reed's truck stop near interstate 40 after he had bought a cup of coffee
when he got out of the car, he looked real surprised to see us. then he looked like he made every attempt to act like he didn't notice us. he kept his head down,'' trooper joel deal said
deal and trooper richard austin checked the honda's pennsylvania license plate number with the national crime information center
it was kind of shocking,'' deal said
the troopers found hernandez was wanted in connection with the deaths of his 4-year-old stepbrother, frankie; 9-month-old stepbrother, jonathon; his father, catalino hernandez, 34; and pregnant stepmother, carmen hernandez, 23
the bodies had been dead six days when hernandez's aunt found them in the family's apartment monday. the bodies were stacked and covered in a bathtub
hernandez did not resist arrest and said nothing to the troopers, deal said. the youth slept as he was driven to the davidson county juvenile detention center in nashville
there was really no emotion from him at all,'' deal said
investigators searched the honda for clues to the killings, but nothing was found, deal said
officers have failed to find the .22-caliber handgun that killed hernandez's father and stepmother. frankie was strangled with a bandage and jonathon was beaten to death with a blunt object, possibly a baseball bat, police said
the killings followed an argument between hernandez and his father, police said
police fears that a movie about southern california gangs might spark new violence when it is released next month show how out of control the problem is, its director says
i live in a gang area. i live in venice (beach),'' dennis hopper, director of ``colors,'' said recently
the film, starring robert duvall and sean penn as policemen fighting gang drug dealing and street crime, drew fire from real law enforcement officers who were given a preview
the movie, scheduled for release in mid-april, features graphic depictions of gang violence, including a gang drive-by shooting and the killing of a police character by gang members
several detectives said the film glamorizes the gang lifestyle and could trigger violence among gang audiences. assistant police chief robert vernon suggested it be banned
hopper, best known for his acting in such films as ``easy rider,'' ``apocalypse now,'' ``hoosiers,'' and ``blue velvet,'' said the official reaction shocked him
he said banning the movie would be ``like burning books ... and they wanted to burn it before it could even be seen or read.''
what they're basically saying is that they have a police problem and they can't handle it,'' hooper said. ``the gang thing is out of control.''
hopper defended his use of real gang members as extras and the realistic presentation of gang dominance in many los angeles neighborhoods, using some statistics in the film to show what police are up against
at the beginning we point out that there are 250 men and women in law enforcement working against 600 gangs with over 70,000 members,'' he said. ``how can they possibly handle it?'' graf pvs, gephardt is.</note>
rep. richard gephardt predicted today that his struggling presidential bid would be revitalized by a michigan victory and dismissed reports that he would opt to run for re-election to the house if he loses here
i think we're going to turn this race back around here in michigan,'' gephardt said on cbs-tv's ``this morning'' show. ``we're going to get back in the middle of this thing and i'm going to go ahead and win.''
asked why he was planning to file for re-election to his house seat by missouri's tuesday deadline, gephardt replied: ``no decision on that at all. ... i'm going to be the nominee. i'm going to be the next president.''
but before a crowd of laid-off auto workers, enthusiastic about his call for tough foreign trade policies, gephardt on thursday acknowledged his presidential candidacy is in need of extraordinary help from michigan democrats
this saturday we're going to have a miracle in michigan _ the michigan miracle,'' gephardt said, mimicking michael dukakis and his description of massachusetts' economic turnaround during his three interrupted terms as governor
gephardt is running third in the polls in michigan, behind dukakis and jesse jackson. after suffering major losses across the south and elsewhere on super tuesday two weeks ago, gephardt launched a major effort to climb back into contention with the michigan contest
aside from winning his home state of missouri on super tuesday, his only other victories have been in the south dakota primary and iowa's lead-off caucus
aides, speaking on condition of anonymity, said gephardt was making plans to file for re-election to his house seat in missouri by the deadline tuesday if michigan does not give him the victory he seeks
that's right. he will be out if doesn't win in michigan,'' said a campaign aide who would not be quoted by name
asked about the aide's comment, gephardt said: ``no. i'm running for president and i've doing very well here in michigan. ... i'm going to win in michigan. i'm going to continue and do well
my mother always told me to cross one bridge at a time. that's what i'm trying to do,'' he said
his wife jane reinforced the notion that michigan was a do-or-die state for gephardt
i think dick has to come in first or a real strong second to remain in the race, because at some point if you don't do well here, it becomes difficult to raise money,''' she said. ``dick's message will be very popular in the industrial states, but if we don't do well here, we will not be able to continue.''
in flint, gephardt spoke in a roped-off street between a union hall and the general motors' fisher body assembly plant that gm shut down last december, leaving an already reduced work force of 3,500 workers without jobs. the plant manufactured large, rear-wheel drive gm autos
many of the several hundred people present carried signs saying they were unemployed auto workers. a billboard above the union hall said, ``there is hope,'' and was signed by the uaw 581 bible group
while it may be cloudy and a little gloomy here today, what we're going to do in 1988 is we're going to win an election for the presidency and we're going to bring the sun back out in the american economy,'' gephardt said
he repeated his familiar call for tough trade sanctions against countries that do not open markets to u.s. products, and resumed his attack on dukakis for changing positions on trade policy
he said he welcomed dukakis' recently announced support for senate legislation that would toughen trade policies, and then added: ``i just hope he doesn't change his trade policy again after leaving michigan.''
a motorist whose car was mistakenly towed from a service station searched frantically for three days before he found his prized chevy _ in a junkyard pile
it was squished, just like a little metal cube,'' john geraca said thursday. ``all the wheels and the doors were gone. it was about 20 inches high.''
geraca took his last ride in the 1975 chevrolet monte carlo on march 11, when he went to the service station to pick up the cadillac he had dropped off for a tuneup, police said
after paying the bill for the work, geraca drove away in the cadillac and left his red chevy behind in the parking lot, intending to pick it up later, police said
but it was gone when he returned after two hours. another red chevy, this one a 1976 impala, was still in the parking lot, however
the owner of that car had asked that it be junked, and no one at the station noticed when the tow truck picked up the wrong car
i guess he just pulled up, hooked up on a chevy and away he went,'' said station attendant richard logan. ``he didn't ask anybody about it.''
sam parisi, owner of southern auto parts junkyard, said it was an honest mistake because the description of the two red chevys was identical
right about now, they're probably making toyotas out of it,'' said parisi, one of four people arrested on racketeering and theft charges last week at the culmination of a fort lauderdale and pompano beach police investigation of suspected chop shops
we're completely honest here, and all we're trying to do is make an honest buck,'' parisi said. ``we don't steal cars.''
scrap cars fetch about $25 at a junkyard. police said geraca's car was worth about $1,000
investigators have told geraca, who says the car held $16,000 worth of marine electronics equipment, that the case is a civil matter, coral springs police sgt. jim hanrahan said
rescue workers struggled through the night to free victims trapped in the crushed cars of two passenger trains that crashed head-on outside shanghai, killing at least 28 people and injuring 109
chinese officials said today that 27 japanese high school students and one chinese passenger died in thursday's accident
a spokesman for the shanghai foreign affairs office said by telephone that 37 students from gakugei high school in southern japan's kochi prefecture and 72 chinese passengers remained hospitalized
ten other japanese from the 193-member school tour group were treated for injuries and released, said fu yatao, a foreign affairs spokesman
it was china's fourth fatal train collision this year, bringing the total death toll to 169
fu said the cause of the crash was still under investigation
bundo takagi, deputy director of the foreign ministry's second consular division, said a team of three japanese doctors will leave for shanghai saturday morning to assist in the treatment of injured students
the school group arrived in china on march 21 for a tour of the shanghai area and the nearby city of hangzhou
the crash occurred at 2 p.m. thursday when train no. 311, carrying the japanese group, ignored a stop signal as it left shanghai station for hangzhou and smashed into the southbound train no. 208 arriving from changsha, in the shanghai suburb of fengban
the japanese group was traveling in the first-class cars in the front of no. 311. the cars were knocked off the track along with the baggage car of no. 208
fu said the trains were not traveling at high speeds at the time of the crash
chinese officials responded last month to the string of transportation disasters by demanding greater attention to safety. china's railway minister was forced to resign to take responsibility for three fatal train accidents in january
efforts to educate minorities about aids have failed to stop the deadly disease because they have largely ignored differing customs and languages, witnesses told a presidential commission
most black men with acquired immune deficiency syndrome in san francisco are homosexual or bisexual, yet have been nearly untouched by efforts to halt the spread of the disease among white gay men, said amanda houston-hamilton, chairwoman of san francisco's black coalition on aids
we believe these men have fallen through the cracks,'' houston-hamilton told members of the presidential commission on the human immunodeficiency virus epidemic
they are dying alone, frequently coming for medical services when they are too sick to walk, incontinent, demented,'' said houston-hamilton, one of a panel of asian, hispanic, native american and hemophiliac leaders who testified thursday as the commission began a three-day visit here
there are 32 distinct asian ethnic groups, with different languages, cultures, traditions and customs. these differences have been been largely overlooked by aids education programs,'' said davis y. ja, of the san francisco-based asian aids project
the group represents the filipino, chinese, japanese, korean and vietnamese communities and runs the only asian aids education program in the nation with $230,000 in federal funds and a staff of six
lillis stephens, of the sacramento-based hemophilia council of california, told the panel that of the state's 2,300 hemophiliacs, at least 1,600 are infected with the virus, an infection level exceeding that of gay and bisexual people in the state
an estimated 10 to 20 percent of sexual partners of infected hemophiliac men infected are also infected with the aids virus, according to surveys by the organization
although the centers for disease control estimate 53 cases of aids among native americans nationally, phil tinsley, a community leader, contended the number is much higher and will mushroom as a result of a 20.8 percent teen-age pregnancy rate and the nation's highest levels of drug abuse
john wahl, a san francisco gay activist and former co-chair of the national mobilization against aids, told the commission it should use its influence against those who claim the virus justifies discrimination against homosexuals
the aids epidemic will not destroy our liberation movement, but attempts to misuse the fear of aids to suppress us will be very destructive to social peace,'' he said
the testimony will be considered by the full 14-member commission, which is about two-thirds of the way through its national tour. the commission will deliver its recommendations for a national strategy to stop aids to the white house by june 24, said spokesman tom brandt
acting premier li peng today told delegates to the annual session of the national people's congress that china must emphasize reform as it continues on its path of economic development
li's report to the 2,970 delegates of china's legislature also said that in the next five years, china will maintain its policies of market-oriented reforms, opening itself to the outside world and making its political system more democratic
li, 59, is expected to be confirmed as head of government at the legislative session, which will last 20 days. with his report, li displayed his full support, at least publicly, for the reforms set in motion by his protege, senior leader deng xiaoping
in the next five years, li said, china must ``put reform at the center of all our undertakings and integrate it more closely with economic development so that the two are coordinated and promote each other.''
veteran military leader yang shangkun, 81, an ally of deng, is likely to replace li xiannian, 79, in the largely ceremonial post of president
deng, 83, who entered semi-retirement last fall at a major communist party meeting, sat on the podium between li and zhao ziyang, the former premier who now heads the communist party
the delegates also are expected to pass laws giving greater authority to factory managers
li, a soviet-trained technocrat regarded as being cautious toward reforms, also sounded several conservative themes on economic problems in his speech, the keynote address of the congress
among those problems, he said, are rising prices, ``the outstanding problem in our economic and social life today,'' inadequate investment on agriculture, and economic crimes committed by those seeking personal gains
in the past five years, reforms have brought china an annual growth rate of 11.1 percent, provided jobs for 37 million people, substantially raised living standards and opened china to foreign investment and trade, he said
li outlined 10 objectives for the next five years, led by the need for further reforms in agriculture. chinese leaders have been concerned about stagnating grain production as farmers switch to more lucrative cash crops, and li stressed that more money and effort must be spent to ``mobilize the peasants' enthusiasm for agricultural production.''
li also stressed that china must revitalize its enterprises by instituting contract systems for managers and reducing government interference in factories. heading the legislation to be passed at the congress is an industrial enterprise law to guarantee the rights of managers to operate their factories without interference
he hit hard on the problem of rising prices and said inflation must be fought by reforming the irrational, heavily subsidized pricing system and expanding supplies while controlling some prices
officially, inflation was 7.3 percent last year, but prices in most larger cities rose at double-digit rates
li mentioned march 5 anti-chinese riots in the tibetan capital of lhasa, saying the buddhist monk-led demonstrators ``violated the law and undermined the unity of the motherland. the rioters must be severely punished.''
congress officials have promised that the session will be the most open ever, with foreign journalists allowed to attend some of the legislature's discussion groups as well as the opening and closing sessions
access to the discussions is part of the government attempt to show the outside world that the congress, long belittled as a rubber-stamp body for policies set by the party, has become more democratic and influential
all major decisions are still made by the party politburo and its standing committee, but under outgoing congress chairman peng zhen, 86, the body has gained some stature as a forum to debate, and sometimes revise, policies handed down by the party
a federal prosecutor has alleged that former mayor lee alexander, sentenced 10 years in prison for running a $1.5 million extortion-kickback scheme, did not surrender all of his illegal profits
alexander, one of the most visible u.s. mayors of the 1970s, also was ordered to repay the city $100,000 in lieu of a $100,000 fine recommended by prosecutors
we're satisfied. it's what we requested and recommended and what we felt was appropriate,'' u.s. attorney frederick j. scullin said after the sentencing thursday
but scullin said he still doesn't think alexander has been truthful about surrendering all his assets, as stipulated in the plea bargain the former mayor made with the government jan. 6
alexander has turned over $1.4 million to the government, but scullin alleged during thursday's hearing that alexander is hiding $200,000 and has lied about other kickbacks
alexander, 60, who spent 16 years as mayor of new york's fifth-largest city, had faced up to 30 years in prison for his admission to charges of racketeering, conspiracy to obstruct a government investigation and tax evasion. but u.s. district judge thomas j. mcavoy followed the sentencing recommendation made by prosecutors
i've brought great pain to my loved ones and the people of my city and stand here now ready for my punishment,'' alexander said at the close of a 10-minute statement he gave before his sentence was pronounced
the punishment you are about to impose on me ... pales against the pain and remorse i feel.''
alexander was indicted july 16, 1987, by a special grand jury empaneled 18 months earlier to investigate public corruption in syracuse
alexander initially denied the charges. but he sought a plea bargain after being faced with evidence the government had gathered, including testimony from alexander's bagmen and other co-conspirators
he admitted running the extortion-kickback scheme during his four terms as syracuse mayor between 1970 and 1986. a 40-count federal grand jury indictment charged that alexander extorted kickbacks of up to 25 percent from businessmen, professionals and consultants doing work in the city
alexander will be eligible for parole after about 40 months, but scullin said he believes alexander will serve at least five years. he must surrender by april 14
also thursday, seven co-conspirators were sentenced to terms ranging up to 2{ years
president hosni mubarak has warned that an israeli attack on saudi arabia's new intermediate-range missile launchers would ``blow up the entire peace process'' in the middle east
mubarak said thursday he had sent an urgent message to president reagan urging him to ``use his influence with israel and urge it to stop threatening arab states in this irresponsible way.''
he said he also sent a verbal message to israeli prime minister yitzhak shamir via egypt's ambassador to israel, mohammed bassiouny. the egyptian president said other senior israeli officials also had been contacted
mubarak's remarks to local reporters was egypt's second sharp response to israeli warnings about saudi arabia's chinese-supplied css-2 missiles
on wednesday, an unidentified egyptian official said cairo would consider any israeli attack on the installations an attack on egypt itself
mubarak's comments were distributed by the state-owned middle east news agency
i warn against any attack on ... saudi arabia, which is a sister and friendly country,'' mubarak said. ``this is a grave, grave matter. if an attack on saudi arabia occurred, it would blow up the entire peace process.''
jordan and syria also have said they would regard an israeli attack on saudi arabia as aggression against them
the egyptian warning, however, appeared to carry greater weight because of its 1979 peace treaty with israel, the only one between an arab country and the jewish state. egypt also is the arab world's strongest military power
saudi arabia recently acquired the missiles, which have a range of 2,200 miles, enough to reach iran and israel. the missiles are capable of carrying nuclear warheads, but both china and saudi arabia have given assurances they will be fitted only with conventional warheads
after disclosure of the missile deal, shamir was reported to have told u.s. officials that the saudis must get rid of them
on sunday, israeli radio quoted close shamir aide yossi ben aharon as referring to israel's reputation not to let potential dangers become actual ones, an apparent reference to israel's 1981 air raid on a nuclear reactor being built in iraq
shamir said later that ben aharon denied making the statement, but the premier said tuesday that israel and the united states were ``making efforts to deal with ... the grave development.'' data</head>
two defense contractors and five executives are facing charges of defrauding the pentagon, one by faking test results on electronics for a missile system, the other by selling reconditioned aircraft parts as new
consolidated aeronautics corp. of north hollywood and its top two officers were charged thursday with one count of conspiracy and four of submitting false claims about hydraulic parts provided under a $1 million contract beginning in 1984
another indictment accused genisco technology corp. of rancho dominguez and one current and two former executives of conspiracy and falsely certifying that sensing devices used in air-to-ground missiles and helicopters had been tested
fraud in defense procurement and in the production of strategic and military hardware is the no. 1 `white collar' crime priority of the u.s. attorney's office,'' said gary feess, chief assistant u.s. attorney
the parts in the consolidated contract were destined for use in the steering systems of a-7, f-4 and f-104 jet fighters, the b-52 bomber and the c-141 transport plane
the hydraulic parts were certified by the company as new but actually had been refurbished, the indictment alleged. all the parts that have been tested failed, and flight crews could have been endangered had the parts been used, officials said
consolidated could be fined $3.5 million if convicted
also charged were gordon strube, 65, of beverly hills, consolidated president and chief executive officer, and ronald guy, 42, of granada hills, vice president of sales
telephone calls to the company went unanswered thursday
if convicted, strube could be sentenced to up to 7{ years in prison and fined up to $1.25 million; guy faces up to 15 years in prison and a $750,000 fine
the genisco contract was worth several hundred thousand dollars a year, feess said. genisco faces a maximum $7.5 million fine
genisco attorney tom holliday suggested that any wrongdoing was the fault of officers and former officers of the company's transducer products division in simi valley, and he called indictment of the company unwarranted
also charged were werner brinkschulte, 50, of simi valley, former general manager of the division; danny k. evans, 34, of simi valley, former division supervisor, and robert l. kersnick, 51, of sepulveda, quality assurance manager of the division
the three face up to five years in prison and fines of up to $250,000 on each count
the transducers, the size and shape of small cigars, measure pressure in liquid or gas. they are used to help guide the high-speed anti-radar missile, which is fired from planes; to measure oil pressure in the coast guard's hh-65a dolphin search-and-rescue helicopter, and to operate a navy torpedo test device
a year ago today, police discovered three half-naked women chained in a north philadelphia basement and limbs of another in the house's freezer
a grisly tale unfolded of how they were kept prisoners, one for four months. the trail led to a new jersey forest where the naked body of another woman was found
the man who lived in the house, gary michael heidnik, 41, faces trial april 4 on rape and murder charges in a case that has already attracted the attention of authors and could lead to a movie
any profits from such a venture cannot go to heidnik if he is convicted, and at a federal bankruptcy court hearing wednesday, attorneys debated what should be done with the money
heidnik's attorney, a. charles peruto jr., said two-thirds of the profits should be assigned to the estates of heidnik and a sect he started, united church of the ministers of god. if heidnik were convicted, the money would then go to his victims
both heidnik and the church are in bankruptcy
if i bring in money to enhance the estates, i get one-third of what i enhance,'' peruto said. ``the estates would get two-thirds.'' as part of the agreement, the lawyer would not get any legal fees for defending heidnik
assistant district attorney harriet brumberg argued the state's victim compensation law provides that 100 percent of such book or movie profits goes to the victims
if anything in the book contains any thoughts, feelings, impressions of mr. heidnik, that belongs to the victims,'' she said
