this u.s. navy frigate found and retrieved an armed power launch apparently abandoned by the iranians in the strait of hormuz
the craft, with a twin-barrel 25mm anti-aircraft gun mounted on its bow and protected by a canvas, was brought alongside the uss reuben james in a tense, three-hour operation hampered by high seas thursday
the find could advance american knowledge of how the iranians operate in the persian gulf, navy officials said. ``i'm not sure what all this is going to lead to in the way of intelligence,'' said cmdr. john j. kieley iii, skipper of the reuben james. ``but i think it will go a long way in helping us to understand the kind of thing that goes on out here.''
the captain repeatedly tried to approach the boat late thursday with his 443-foot frigate when it was found about 12 miles off the coast of oman at the entrance to the strait of hormuz. but seas up to 10 feet and strong winds made maneuvering difficult, and the irananian boat disappeared into the darkness until it was relocated two hours later
two seamen was finally lowered onto the deck of the iranian boat from a helicopter hovering overhead
i was scared,'' said eight-year navy veteran tony santos, 24, of bozeman, mont., one of the lowered seamen. ``i didn't know what to expect, whether it was booby trapped or whether to look for someone lying down on the boat or what.''
lines were attached, and the iranian craft was tied to the frigate's stern for towing
its rusty but functioning anti-aircraft gun had ammunition boxes attached and was ready for firing. spent shells littered the floor of the boat, along with several sealed boxes of ammunition, cans of diesel fuel and other items
the area where the ship was found is close to main shipping lanes where tankers and other commercial vessels are frequently attacked by iran's naval frigates and armed patrol boats
the suicides of three teen-age boys in two weeks have shocked students and faculty at a high school here, but they are trying to avert further tragedies with a vigorous counseling program, including teen advisers
it's a scary situation,'' said patty l. kelly, 18, one of several students receiving training as a peer group counselor at reitz high school after the suicides. ``even people who didn't know them are affected by it.''
more than 600 parents and students attended a meeting at the school auditorium thursday night to talk about the deaths, the latest of which occurred wednesday morning
we're concerned about the families it happened to,'' said judy g. elfreich, whose daughter is a freshman at reitz. ``i'm not really worried about more (suicides), but you just can't predict things like that.''
along with the peer counseling groups, reitz principal christine settle said the school would begin a ``buddy system'' to pair newcomers with older students
in addition, six school psychologists and two counselors were sent to the school of 1,350 students on wednesday to assist the four counselors normally assigned to reitz
i hope all this helps,'' miss kelley said. ``people have come to me to talk, but they're afraid to tell their parents because they know they'll get sent to get help. and then they'll have to come back (to school) and have people tell them, `well, we know you're crazy now.' so it's a lot easier for them to talk to us.''
vanderburgh county sheriff clarence c. shepard told the audience that an investigation had turned up no connection between the deaths and satanism or cults, despite rumors to that effect
shepard said before the meeting that ``all three were immediate, personal, emotional problems with the young men. one was a boyfriend-girlfriend problem, and the others were family problems.''
the three victims were boys who knew each other and were in the same year in high school, the sheriff said. two were reitz sophomores, and the third was a former student who transferred to another school
the latest victim, larry e. ``j.j.'' orth, 15, was found dead of a self-inflicted gunshot wound at 6:30 a.m. wednesday. orth left a note indicating he was having family problems
eric g. sanders, 16 and also a reitz student, died march 10; and steven r. schaefer, 15, who left last year, died march 13. both sanders and schaefer also shot themselves
the school system began a weeklong spring vacation today, and school officials hoped the break would help settle the students
they will still see their friends, but they won't be together in one building and rumors won't be spreading as much,'' said susan g. mcdowell, head of psychological services for the evansville-vanderburgh school corporation
we think that will help,'' she added
