red army troops patrolled the tense armenian capital today to enforce a ban on public demonstrations by armenians locked in a violent territorial dispute with neighboring azerbaijan
the kremlin took a series of decisive steps to quell the ethnic violence, which has claimed more than 30 lives and posed a serious challenge to soviet leader mikhail s. gorbachev
soldiers and helicopters were deployed to yerevan, the armenian capital, to prevent the kind of massive demonstrations staged by armenians to demand the return of the disputed nagorno-karabakh region that is now part of azerbaijan
demonstrations had been planned for saturday, but armenian activists reported they had been called off
armenian activists reported that authorities have ordered disbanded an armenian committee that spearheaded the drive to annex nagorno-karabakh to armenia
the government on thursday announced an eight-year plan to build more housing, roads, schools and social services in the disputed region, where nearly 75 percent of the population of 160,000 is armenian
the kremlin has accused the demonstrators of being extremists and demanded an end to the armenian protest actions as ``intolerable.'' the demonstrations led to retaliation aganst armenians in azerbaijan, where at least 32 people were killed and nearly 200 injured
sources in armenia told the associated press by telephone that the atmosphere was tense, but they reported no outbreaks of violence. western reporters have not been allowed to visit the area
hovik vassilian, an activist in the protest, said the armenian literary gazette newspaper announced today that the committee to annex nagorno-karabakh was being disbanded ``because it was working against the people's interests.''
vassilian said the planned demonstrations saturday ``won't happen.'' he said they have been called off ``considering the situation.''
armenians, who are predominantly christian, have been demanding that the nagorno-karabkh region, which is smaller than delaware, be annexed to the neighboring armenian republic, though there is no common border. azerbaijan is overwhelmingly moslem
the kremlin plan for nagorno-karabkh also assures the local population that television transmission will be upgraded so they can receive broadcasts in armenian as well as the national network and azeri programming
other assurances, such as better supplies of armenian-language books and preservation of historical and cultural monuments, address issues that incited armenians to demand annexation for the mountainous region, which has been part of azerbaijan since 1923
in azerbaijan, radio baku reported today that public assemblies, meetings and street demonstrations will be allowed only by permits, which must be applied for at least 10 days in advance. those violating the order face criminal penalties, according to the broadcast monitored in london
armenia instituted a similar ban on unsanctioned demonstrations earlier in the week, according to radio yerevan
it was not immediately clear whether the government plan would succeed in pacifying armenians worried that nagorno-karabakh is losing its ethnic identity. but one official source in armenia reported a generally quiet, though tense, atmosphere today
a duty officer at the republic's ministry of internal affairs, responsible for police operations, told the associated press by telephone from yerevan that the city was ``fairly quiet.''
the officer, who declined to give his name or detailed information, confirmed red army helicopters and security troops were patrolling the capital to keep order
calls to azerbaijan did not go through today
moscow-based dissidents reported thursday that the atmosphere in armenia was ``filled with tension.''
on wednesday, the soviet government rejected as ``intolerable'' the armenian campaign for annexation, indicating it would not bend to pressure brought on by mass demonstrations and strikes in the republic last month
the unrest brought an unusual personal appeal from soviet leader mikhail s. gorbachev for calm and reason in dealing with the ethnic dispute. gorbachev also promised the leadership would review armenia's claims to nagorno-karabakh
gorbachev's address calmed the demonstrators in yerevan. but on feb. 28, ethnic extremists went on a rampage of murder, rape, robbery and other crimes in the azeri city of sumgait. study</head>
this small, ohio river town has been chosen as the focus of a $4 million, two-year, privately funded study aimed at reducing heart attacks, strokes and high blood pressure, officials said
sponsors of the pilot program said they chose wellsburg because of its small population _ 4,000 _ and because west virginia registered the highest obesity rate in the country at 24 percent in a 1986 federal study that also found 31 percent of west virginians smoke cigarettes
west virginia trails only iowa in the annual death rate from heart disease, according to state health director dr. david heydinger
education, especially health education, is lacking in west virginia,'' said john w. bertram, administrator for the brooke county health department and a member of the program's advisory board
the program, one of the first privately funded public health education programs aimed at rural areas, is sponsored by the bayer co., an aspirin and over-the-counter drug manufacturer, and glenbrook laboratories, bayer's new york-based parent
however, aspirin, recently linked to the prevention of heart attacks and strokes, will not be part of the program, said robin d. mills, president of the bayer co
we already have ongoing research into that,'' mills said. ``what we want to develop is a health program that we can offer to rural americans.''
the program will begin in may when 1,000 volunteers will be checked for high blood pressure, high cholesterol, obesity and other cardiovascular risk factors
participants must be at least 21 years old and willing to return for checkups every three months over a two-year period
health professionals will attempt to lower the weight, cholesterol and blood pressure of participants and eliminate other risk factors through education and behavior modification
some aspects of the study, including nutrition seminars, weight reduction techniques and smoking clinics will be available to all of the town's 4,000 people, mills said
the company will also sponsor walks, runs and other exercise activities for the town, which is about 40 miles southwest of pittsburgh
if people listen, it will be a good thing,'' said nora hartley, 46, owner of nora's novelty nook, as she smothered a cigarette in a full ashtray
i'd go crazy if i had to quit smoking and i don't have to lose weight, but i'll probably check it out,'' she said
cardiovascular disease _ the leading cause of death in the united states _ kills nearly a million americans each year, according to the national center for health statistics. nearly one-fifth of those deaths occur in people under the age of 65. killed, army saying it is investigating, not denying. other details. changes byline. no pickup.</note>
israeli soldiers fired on palestinian demonstrators who hurled rocks and broken bottles in the occupied west bank today, killing two and wounding six, hospital officials and witnesses said
the army said five protesters were wounded in the attack on a makeshift army headquarters in tarqumia and in a clash in the nearby city of hebron. it said it was investigating the reports that two were killed
officials close to prime minister yitzhak shamir protested a meeting planned saturday between secretary of state george p. shultz and two palestinian-americans tied to the plo
as part of a campaign to crack down on leaders of recent unrest, the army arrested a prominent gaza lawyer under special laws allowing detention for up to six months without trial
israel radio quoted an unidentified military source as saying the military had evidence that the attorney, raji sourani, was linked to the organization of the uprising. the army has not commented
more than 4,000 palestinians have been detained since the unrest began dec. 8 in the occupied west bank and gaza strip, and 3,000 remain in jail. but unlike previous roundups, which focused on stone-throwers, the current one has zeroed in on the underground leadership
in tarqumia, a village of 9,000 near hebron, hundreds of stone-throwing youths set out before dawn to attack a school that troops had turned into makeshift headquarters, said naim odeh, a 52-year-old schoolteacher
the troops came into the village at 4 a.m. and took over the school,'' odeh said. ``then about 500 youths marched out to the school and started throwing rocks and broken bottles.''
troops responded by opening fire, odeh said, and the confrontation lasted several hours. he said two youths were shot and killed
villagers and an official at hebron's alia hospital identified the dead as khaled hassan ahmed murktan, 18, who was shot in the stomach, and walid abdul fatatta, 18, who was shot in the chest
odeh said the bodies were buried in the town's cemetery. there, villagers pointed out to a journalist two freshly dug mounds of earth, with an inscribed rock beside them
in hebron, soldiers surrounded al haras mosque following noon prayers on the moslem sabbath when 20 youths took up positions on the roof and began throwing stones and waving a palestinian flag, which is outlawed in israel
as a reporter watched from a nearby vantage point, troops fired tear gas and the sound of shots also could be heard
three protesters were shot and critically wounded, the arab-owned palestine press service said
later, three arab teen-agers were seen sitting on the ground with their hands tied behind their backs. a soldier was seen kicking one of the young men, who was wearing a blue sweater
the army said an empty passenger bus headed for the jewish settlement of qiryat arba near hebron was surrounded by residents of an arab village, who beat the driver and set the vehicle on fire
israel radio said the driver was hospitalized with two broken arms
