in the heady days following his southern victories, democratic presidential candidate albert gore jr. depicted rival michael dukakis as having the electoral appeal of george mcgovern and walter mondale
two weeks later, the harsh rhetoric is gone. with recent polls showing dukakis _ not gore _ as the only democrat running even nationwide with gop front-runner george bush, gore is having a more difficult time pinning his rival with the image of the democrats' landslide losers of 1972 and 1984
gore, the tennessee senator who needs a victory in the north to remain a top contender, has hardly mentioned dukakis, jesse jackson or his other rivals for the democratic presidential nomination as he campaigns in michigan and wisconsin. instead, he is focusing on bush and the reagan administration in a slight retooling of his new populist message
his silence on dukakis has caused some to speculate about gore's intentions _ whether he is holding his fire against a candidate who could, as nominee, offer him the second spot on the ticket. gore maintains he has ``no interest'' in the vice presidential nomination _ a statement that stops short of ruling it out
there are also suggestions gore may be awaiting a better opportunity to engage dukakis, when the field has narrowed and gore can find a state where he does not speak from a position so far behind dukakis that his remarks seem born of desperation
gore catapulted to the top tier of democratic presidential contenders through his victories in the south and west on super tuesday, march 8. two days after that, campaigning in chicago toward illinois' primary, gore delivered a strong assault on dukakis as representing the democrats' past losing formula
for those who want another election blow-out, and see the democratic party losing 49 out of 50 states, vote for michael dukakis,'' gore said then
how long will it take for us to learn the approach that michael dukakis represents does not sell to the american people?'' he asked
campaigning this week across michigan's sparsely populated upper peninsula, gore was asked why he is not continuing that language, and did he no longer think dukakis would be a ``blow-out'' loser
i said that the approach he represents runs that risk,'' gore responded. ``i'm not going to say any of my opponents are not electable
i think the recent history suggests there are only two kinds of elections in modern history _ republican landslides or democratic squeakers. this is going to be a democratic squeaker.''
when he was pinning his hopes on appeal among the south's independent and conservative-minded democrats, gore argued that he is the most electable democrat
two polls this week _ one by cbs news and the new york times, the other by the washington post and abc _ both showed dukakis and bush in a virtual dead heat. gore, meanwhile, was far behind bush when paired against the likely gop nominee
gore now refers to the ``electability'' issue as one of importance primarily to the democratic ``super delegates,'' the nearly 650 elected officials who will get delegate berths and be free agents at the convention, unbound by primary or caucus results in their states
he still contends he has demonstrated an appeal to swing voters that dukakis and jackson have not. but he usually couples it with an acknowledgement that it is more an issue for party insiders than average voters
many democrats, particularly the so-called super delegates, are interested in finding a candidate who has the best chance of winning in the fall, the best chance of appealing to the independently thinking voters who hold the balance of power, the best chance of carrying areas like the south, west and midwest, where we have lost overwhelmingly these last several elections,'' gore said
i think it's a legitimate question to ask _ who can best win.''
gore disputed the answer presented in the recent polls, saying it is too early to measure such sentiment accurately
hypothetical matchups of that kind ... are entirely meaningless,'' he said
socialist labor leader joe bossano, a staunch defender of independence for this british colony, was declared the victor today in local elections
bossano, who rejects a competing spanish claim of sovereignty over the fortress colony at its southern tip, received 8,128 votes, or 58 percent of the votes cast thursday
incumbent chief minister adolfo canepa was next with 4,442 votes, or 29 percent, in the most lopsided victory ever by a gibraltar party
the incumbent leads the advancement of civil rights party, which had long dominated gibraltar politics
the party of bossano, branch officer of the 7,000-member transport workers general union, won eight seats in the 15-seat house of assembly. canepa's party won the other seven
the conservative independent democratic party led by former civil servant joe pitaluga got 13 percent of the vote, but none of its candidates won enough votes to gain a seat
in his first comments to reporters after the victory, bossano asserted that most of gibraltar's 29,000 residents reject a 1984 british-spanish accord known as the brussels agreement. under that accord, britain for the first time said it would discuss the question of sovereignty with spain
spain ceded gibraltar to britain in the 1713 treaty of utrecht following its defeat in the war of succession. the treaty stipulates that spain recover sovereignty over the territory if britain relinquishes it
canepa is a protege of longtime party leader and gibraltar chief minister joshua hassan, who governed the colony for 40 of the last 43 years
in campaigning for canepa, hassan accused bossano of being a radical who would harm gibraltar's relations with britain and spain. but bossano said he intended to better relations with both countries
presiding senior election officer eugene howes said 13,473 votes were cast, representing just over 76 percent of the colony's 17,500 registered voters. the highest previous turnout had been 74 percent in 1984 elections. graf: ``it said...'' to correct iranian troops to iraqi troops. pick up 9th graf pvs: ``baghdad's al-thawra...''</note>
iran said today it hammered iraq's southern port of basra with missiles and shellfire and repulsed an iraqi counterattack in the northern kurdistan mountains, killing or wounding 500 men
both sides claimed to have shot down four jets, and iraq claimed it attacked two ships off iran's coast in the persian gulf
iran's official islamic republic news agency said revolutionary guards in northeast iraq pushed back four infantry battalions and a brigade _ about 7,200 troops _ that iraq moved up from its southern 7th army corps to reinforce the northern front
the agency, monitored in nicosia, said the fighting centered around the rishan mountains east of the town of sayyid sadiq
