tehran radio reported four iraqi fighter-bombers were shot down by ground fire today and the pilots killed
the official iraqi news agency, monitored in nicosia, said four u.s.-built iranian f-5 jets were shot down by iraqi anti-aircraft fire over the battle zone
it said iraqi fighters destroyed four iranian helicopters on the ground. irna, quoting military communiques, said iranian jets carried out 14 attacks on iraqi troop concentrations in the northeastern battle zone and around al-amarah in the south. it said all the planes returned safely to their bases
baghdad's al-thawra daily, the mouthpiece of the ruling arab baath socialist party, said iraq's air force flew 224 combat missions thursday
that was one of the highest one-day totals in the last year and underlined the growing intensity of the current fighting. the newspaper said the planes dropped nearly 200 tons of bombs and destroyed three iranian jets and two helicopters
irna said six missiles were fired during the night into the strategically important city of basra and the border town of mandali, 80 miles east of the iraqi capital of baghdad
the agency said long-range artillery also pounded ``military, economic and industrial centers'' in basra and the border town of al-gharbi farther north
there was no immediate word on casualties. in recent weeks, hundreds of civilians on both sides have been killed or wounded in missile, air and artillery attacks in the so-called ``war of the cities.''
the iraqi news agency said iraqi fighter-bombers attacked two ``large maritime targets,'' which usually means tankers, off the iranian coast during the night. it reported ``accurate and effective hits.''
there was no immediate independent confirmation of the ship attacks
iraq said 13 people were killed and 68 wounded thursday when two iranian missile crashed into downtown baghdad
among the victims was a woman, killed in a hospital bed while breast-feeding her newborn baby, ina reported. the infant was found alive in his mother's arms several hours later
iraq said it fired six long-range missiles into tehran, a city of 6 million. irna said 10 civilians were killed and 100 wounded when the missiles hit two schools, two mosques and two hospitals as well as shops and houses
both sides have fired more than 250 missiles into each other's cities since feb. 29, when tehran was hit by long-range iraqi missiles for the first time in the war
iran said thursday that its troops advanced further into iraq's northeastern kurdistan province. it claims to have killed or wounded 11,000 iraqis, captured 4,500 and destroyed 200 tanks and armored vehicles in the 10-day offensive. iraq claims it has killed thousands of the invaders but has admitted losing several towns
iranian president ali khamenei, meanwhile, intensified a propaganda campaign against iraq for allegedly dropping chemical bombs on three towns captured by the iranians
