women who began taking birth-control pills as teen-agers and used oral contraceptives over several years do not face an increased, long-term risk of breast cancer, according to a study published today
previous studies have disagreed over whether the use of birth-control pills increases the risk of breast cancer for women through middle age. some researchers have suggested the conflicting conclusions might be the result of a long-term latent effect from early use
but we found no direct human evidence for such a latent effect,'' said dr. bruce stadel, one of four authors reporting on the study of more than 9,000 women in today's journal of the american medical association
early and prolonged use of birth-control pills was defined as using oral contraceptives for at least six years before the age of 25, according to stadel and his colleagues, who were from the uniformed services university of the health sciences at bethesda, md
researchers collected case histories and interviewed 4,714 women through age 54 who developed breast cancer, then matched them with a control group of 4,540, breaking the subjects into comparable sub-groups depending on how long they had used oral contraceptives
this was a very, very large study ... and these data are immensely reassuring,'' said stadel who was at the national institutes of health when the study was conducted and now is with the u.s. food and drug administration in bethesda, md
the study also gave reassurances about different dosages in birth-control pills, stadel said today on cbs' ``this morning'' show
the work you're seeing in this paper reflects the experience of birth control pill use during the 1960s up through the mid '70s, when doses tended to be higher than they are now,'' he said. ``the fact that we find no increased risk from that type of pill use, has implications that the lower dose should not be even that much concern.''
despite the results of the study, stadel said researchers believe additional large studies should be conducted in the 1990s, ``when the women we interviewed will be in their mid-60s.''
more than 50 million women around the world are on the pill and the cumulative lifetime risk for breast cancer is about one in 10. when you consider those two things together, you can understand why we'd want someone to take another look,'' stadel said. builds</head>
striking unions representing people who perform in commercials have agreed to meet with a federal mediator in two weeks, while fallout from the scriptwriters' walkout builds in the television industry
television production companies said they have laid off more than 1,000 people because of the writers' strike, costing workers more than $4 million in salaries and benefits
union actors who appear in radio or television commercials walked off the sets march 21 in a dispute over payments from ads run on cable television
but thursday, negotiators for the screen actors guild and the american federation of television and radio artists agreed to meet with advertisers and a federal mediator in new york city on april 6
performers' unions and representatives for the american association of advertising agencies and the association of national advertisers said no preconditions were attached to the planned talks
the writers guild of america went on strike march 7 when talks broke down with producers over rerun payments and creative control on the set. no new talks are scheduled, and representatives from both sides expect a long strike
about 125 writers and producers have had to suspend tv development deals at a cost to them of about $1.5 million a week, according to the alliance of movie and television producers
some prime-time tv shows ended production early when scripts ran out, and several projects in the works had to be shelved. talk shows like johnny carson's ``tonight show'' and ``late night with david letterman'' are broadcasting reruns until the strike is settled
sag and aftra represent more than 100,000 actors and announcers working on commercials, while the wga represents more than 9,000 script writers coast to coast
an investigating magistrate has released a lebanese man held in a series of paris bombings because of insufficient evidence, a well-informed source said today
mohamed mouhajer, who was arrested last march in a police sweep, was freed thursday by magistrate gilles boulouque, according to a source in the magistrate's office. seven tunisians also were arrested in the sweep
mouhajer was released ``because there was not sufficient evidence to keep him in temporary detention'' any longer, according to the source, who spoke on condition of anonymity
boulouque has been in charge of investigating a series of paris bombings in 1985 and 1986 that left 13 people dead and 250 injured
french authorities have said mouhajer, a former philosophy student at the sorbonne, was an ideologist for the committee for solidarity with arab and middle east political prisoners, a group which claimed responsiblity for five of the violent attacks
the source said mouhajer was held while police investigated his relationship with fouad ali saleh, a tunisian immigrant described by authorities at the time of his arrest as the leader of a pro-iranian terrorist network. saleh has been charged in several of the bombings, including a sept. 17, 1986, attack at the tati department store that killed six people and injured 51 others
mouhajer still faces charges of criminal association and illegal possession of arms and has been forbidden to leave the country. neither charge is related to the terrorist bombings, the source said
a french newspaper today implied that mouhajer's release might be connected to conservative premier jacques chirac's hopes for the upcoming presidential election. four frenchmen are missing and believed to be held captive in lebanon
the daily liberation said, ``in this electoral period, jacques chirac would not be displeased with the release of some french hostages in lebanon.''
earlier this week, jacques kosciusko-morizet, national secretary of chirac's party, the rally for the republic, visited damascus where he met with a number of syrian officials
syria is the main powerbroker in lebanon and maintains troops in west beirut
on his return to paris, kosciusko-morizet told the french news agency agence france-presse that the meetings were not related to the french hostages in lebanon
in all 22 foreigners are missing and believed to be held captive in lebanon. the longest held hostage is terry anderson, chief middle east correspondent for the associated press, who was kidnapped march 16, 1985
a robbery suspect who lived in a cave was lured into custody with promises of cigarettes and a hot meal, police said
the man who allegedly put the suspect in a cave was later arrested as well, and apparently tried to commit suicide, police said
joseph e. steffani, 24, had long, dirty hair and apparently had not shaved for at least a week when he was arrested wednesday night for investigation of robbery, according to sgt. dan mercado
he said steffani was addicted to tranquilizers and was put in the cave by kenneth hawtin, 37, of el cerrito, who was arrested thursday
in what police say may have been a suicide attempt, hawtin jammed a key into an electrical outlet at a police station and was knocked unconscious. he was taken to a hospital and booked for investigation of robbery
steffani was held at the oakland city jail
steffani, who told officers he had been addicted to tranquilizers since he was was 14, admitted at least 15 robberies in alameda and contra costa counties, mercado said
police said steffani had lived with hawtin until last week, when hawtin took him to the cave in the hills above the community of canyon
steffani has a history of emotional problems and ``was afraid to be around people,'' mercado said
hawtin and a few other friends knew of steffani's hiding place, mercado said. they would drive to the area with food and other supplies, and honk to let steffani know they were there
when the two undercover officers following a tip drove to the area wednesday night and honked, all they could see at first was ``eyes in the bushes,'' mercado said
nasa, in conjunction with the italian and west german space agencies, arranged to launch a highly advanced scientific satellite today from a site off the coast of africa, an agency spokesman said
the satellite, carrying five payloads, was to be launched from the italian-owned san marco platform off the coast of kenya, said spokesman duane brown. three of the payloads are american, one is italian and the other is german, he said
the 521-pound spacecraft will be launched with an american scout rocket. its mission is to study the earth's atmosphere, brown said
the launch was postponed from last week because of mechanical problems
two teen-agers were killed in separate street-gang attacks and five others were wounded, police said
one 19-year-old man died after being shot thursday night in monrovia, while another 19-year-old was killed later in los angeles, sheriff's deputy bill wehner said today. the victim of the second killing was identified as ronnie c. easley
deaths due to gang violence have been reported at a record pace this year, with more than 50 people killed to date. nearly 350 people, including gang members and bystanders, died from gang-related attacks in 1987
three others, including two teen-agers, were wounded in the second attack, wehner said. troy foreman, 18, was in critical condition and aaron patton, 15, was in fair condition at martin luther king jr.-drew medical center, wehner said
another victim, gary steptor, 25, was treated for a gunshot wound and released, he said
in a third shooting, two 17-year-olds were wounded by gunfire, said police sgt. tony rosa. study says</head>
more than 1,000 vietnam veterans involved in the spraying of the herbicide agent orange show no unusual health problems to date, according to updated results of a government study
in a statement thursday, u.s. air force medical officials called ``reassuring'' the findings that the chemical defoliant hasn't caused disease in vietnam veterans, but warned that the results weren't conclusive
this is the definitive study on agent orange in vietnam veterans, and so far it shows that disease is not related to apparent exposure, that there is no increased incidence of major long-term health effects,'' dr. william wolfe, senior investigator in the government's 20-year agent orange probe, was quoted as saying in the statement
these results are reassuring,'' said wolfe, chief of epidemiology at the u.s. air force school of aerospace medicine at brooks air force base in texas
the findings reflect the latest tests of 2,309 veterans in the government's investigation into agent orange and its impact on soldiers who handled the dioxin-containing herbicide. the study will conclude in 2002
some vietnam veterans are seeking compensation for ailments they say are tied to exposure to the toxic chemical
no matter how good this study is, it will never lay to rest the issue for people who argue they were hurt,'' said dr. arnold gass, head of the agent orange registry operation at the la jolla veterans administration medical center
he said the study is scientifically sound but handicapped by its focus on operation ranch hand, air force servicemen involved in handling and dropping the herbicide from aircraft
it doesn't answer the question about what happened to the man in the field,'' he said. ``the ranch handers flew in, flew out. the men in the field were there for days. they didn't take showers.''
ranch handers are used because they are assumed by the government to have had the greatest amount of exposure to the chemical
the study, begun in 1982 and conducted for the past four years at scripps clinic and research foundation in la jolla, examined 1,016 men involved in operation ranch hand and 1,293 air force veterans not involved in the operation
scripps clinic physicians assessed each participant for general health, malignancy, and the neurological, psychological, gastrointestinal, dermatological, cardiovascular, hematological, renal, endocrine, immunological, pulmonary and nervous systems
these examinations found no evidence of a relationship between agent orange exposure and adverse health,'' the statement said
a number of minor medical differences were seen but they appear to be unrelated to exposure to dioxin. they will be monitored and re-evaluated during the next scheduled examinations in 1992.''
last year, a veterans administration study found increased deaths due to lung cancer and certain lymph cancers among vietnam veteran marines, providing what veterans' groups called the first clear scientific data implicating agent orange
the scripps clinic statement cautioned that the latest results are not conclusive because the study used estimated levels of herbicide exposure based roughly on amount of contact, not by actual bloodstream dioxin levels
scientists have recently discovered a way to detect dioxin levels in blood even years after exposure. analysis of blood samples from 2,010 veterans is expected to be completed within two years
thursday's findings were released three days after an air force report admitted that an often-cited 1984 government study had been flawed because it didn't make clear that it couldn't exonerate the chemical from veterans' health problems. be linked to abu nidal's group and assault aimed at french crew; gives age as 35. picks up 9th graf pvs, `hundreds of...</note>
an attacker shot and wounded the captain of an italian jetliner today after the plane landed at bombay's airport and tossed two grenades at pursuers before he was captured, authorities said
the assailant fired four shots from an automatic pistol at vittorino sanataniello, who had landed the alitalia airliner a few minutes earlier after a flight from australia. police said sanataniello and 12 other crew members were climbing onto an airport bus bound for a city hotel when they were attacked
police sources, who spoke on condition of anonymity, said the attacker, identified as abbas mohammed ali shahadi, was believed to be a member of the abu nidal palestinian terrorist group. they said he apparently had intended to attack a french airline crew
an air france flight was due to land at bombay about 40 minutes after the alitalia plane set down. the sources said police had received warnings of a possible attack on air france targets
abu nidal is the pseudonym of sabri al-banna, who broke with yasser arafat's palestine liberation organization in 1974. his group has since claimed responsibility for terrorist attacks around the world aimed at israel and other targets
the attacker was overpowered by two off-duty policemen who chased him as he fled the bus, said police commissioner vasant saraf. the two grenades he lobbed failed to explode
sharaf said a second attacker may have escaped in the confusion
the captain was hurt in the thigh and waist, but his life wasn't in danger, said an alitalia official in bombay
the police sources discounted early reports that shahadi, 35, was iranian. they said he claimed to be a lebanese national but carried no travel documents. he appeared in court today and was being held in a bombay jail
initial reports described the attack as an attempted hijacking, but police later discounted that theory because the crew had already left the airplane and passed through the airport terminal
police were investigating whether the attack was linked to the discovery of unexploded grenades in the visitors' lounge of the saudi arabian consulate wednesday in bombay
hundreds of police converged on the airport and saraf ordered a red alert throughout bombay, sealing city exits. foreign consulates and airline offices in bombay were asked to increase security
at the airport, visitors were banned and security strengthened with the deployment of reserve police
shahadi was being interrogated by police for motives in the attack, the police commissioner said. police seized a handbag, which contained clothes and two loaded magazines
the airplane had landed at bombay after a flight from sydney with stops at melbourne and singapore. it left bombay about two hours after the shooting and was bound for rome
a u.n. relief agency today appealed to the kidnappers of british journalist alec collett to free him on the third anniversary of his abduction
collett, a new york-based journalist, was kidnapped in beirut's moslem sector on march 25, 1985 while on assignment for the united nations relief and works agency
a group calling itself the revolutionary organization of socialist moslems claimed responsibility. the group is believed to be linked to the fatah-revolutionary council, a radical palestinian faction led by abu nidal
we call on those who unjustifiably kidnapped the innocent alec collett to let him return to his family immediately,'' said per olof hallqvist of sweden, director of unrwa in lebanon
our recent experience of the kidnapping of william jorgensen and jan stening has reminded us about the inhuman horrors and anxieties which the families of the kidnap victims have to go through,'' hallqvist said in the english-language statement
stening, 44, a swede, and jorgensen, 58, a norwegian, were kidnapped by palestinians near the southern port city of sidon on feb. 5. both worked for unrwa. they were released march 1 after unrwa, which takes care of palestinian refugees, threatened to cut its services in lebanon
collett's kidnappers have demanded the release of three fatah revolutionary council members imprisoned in britain for the attempted 1985 assassination of israel's ambassador to london at that time, shlomo argov
the kidnappers claimed april 23, 1986, that they had killed collett,66, in retaliation for british support for u.s. air raids on libya several days earlier
the group later issued a videotape showing a body it said was collett's hanging from a makeshift scaffold. but collett's body has never been found
in all, 22 foreigners are missing in lebanon, including nine americans. the longest-held foreign captive is terry anderson, 40, chief middle east correspondent for the associated press. he was kidnapped in west beirut march 16, 1985. the pro-iranian islamic jihad, or islamic holy war, claims to hold him. sted 16, and other details. no pickup.</note>
a passenger train today struck a bus carrying nursery school pupils home for the easter holidays, killing 15 people, including 10 children, a government spokesman said
the victims included six boys and four girls, said francisco castillo, a spokesman for lerida province. the bus driver and four teachers also were killed, he said
eighteen children were injured, four of them seriously. the children, who attended the los angeles nursery school in juneda, were between the ages of 1 and 6
the accident occurred at a rail crossing between the towns of juneda and puigvert, 11 miles southeast of the city of lerida in northeastern spain
the state-owned railway renfe said the bus driver apparently ignored a clearly marked stop sign and moved to go over the rail crossing at the same time a renfe passenger train passed by
railway officials said no injuries were reported among passengers of the train, which was headed for the coastal city of tarragona from lerida
it was the second fatal train accident in spain in a month. on march 3, eight people died when one renfe train rammed into a second standing in a railway yard in a station in the northern city of valladolid
affidavits released today show that authorities found a skeleton buried in the police chief's yard after being told the man died during a fight with the chief, who is now married to the victim's ex-wife
authorities on march 14 found the skeleton of russell bean about 20 feet down after they were told to dig in police chief robert chambers' front yard
chambers, who has since resigned as the part-time chief, has not been charged in connection with the death. his lawyer has said chambers had nothing to do with it
an autopsy showed that bean, 25, died 10 years ago of severe blows to the head and chest
affidavits unsealed in district court today paint a picture of wife swapping, brutality and alcohol abuse by bean and chambers, who was a logger at the time
the statements allege that chambers told his father 10 years ago that he had accidentally killed a man in a fight and that father and son buried the body
the affidavits allege that chambers, now 36, and bean, who were considered close friends, had been drinking together in marlow and got into a fight, and that bean fell and hit his head and died
the affidavits, used to obtain a search warrant to excavate the yard, contained statements by melissa chambers, lorrie chambers and louis lacourse. melissa is chambers' sister, lorrie is her daughter, and lacourse is married to chambers' sister susan
melissa said her father, clifton, 61, told her about the incident twice, but made her promise not to say anything until after his death
the elder chambers died march 9 of natural causes. melissa went to police the next day
lorrie's affidavit confirmed melissa's story
state police sgt. clayton young was quoted as saying that he learned from the family that bean's wife, sylvia, telephoned bean's mother in september 1978 to say he had disappeared. sylvia told bean's mother that she had learned from chambers that bean had borrowed money, and chambers had given him a ride to the vermont state line and dropped him off
mrs. bean won a divorce in june 1979, and she and chambers were married in september 1979
lacourse's affidavit said chambers initiated a conversation about bean shortly after the man was last seen
lacourse said chambers told him that ``he hit him so hard, no one would ever see him again
robert chambers told russ to hit the road and russ did.''
lacourse said chambers also told him that he, bean, sylvia and chambers' then-wife, debbie, were swapping partners for sex
melissa's statement was similar. she said the relationship between the two couples ``was weird. ... i know robert always beat debbie, that was why she ran off. (she) couldn't take it any longer.''
in addition to his marlow job, chambers has taken a leave of absence as part-time chief in nearby gilsum and has been suspended as a trainee with the winchester police department
dr. frank calabro glanced out a window just in time to see his beach house trundling down the street on a truck
i looked out the window and my house went by with a police escort. i ran onto the street and said `where are you going with my house?''' calabro said today
calabro already had planned to move the two-bedroom, 960-square-foot beach house, which he valued at $12,000
i guess he (the thief) walked by, saw a house he liked on moving stilts and decided he was going to take it,'' said calabro
calabro was visiting a real estate office thursday when he saw the traveling house and ran out and told the police escort it was his house
he thought i was crazy,'' said calabro. ``how often do you stop a police escort and say, `this is my house'? he stopped the truck. we were standing out there laughing hysterically. i had the contract in my car for the house.''
the thief, who was in a separate car behind the convoy, fled
had i not seen it go by, we would have never found it. how do you report a stolen house?'' said calabro
john williams, spokesman for suffolk county district attorney patrick henry, said an arrest was expected
calabro, a physician with a family practice in mastic beach, said he already had accepted a deposit to sell the house to someone else. ``they didn't know they were going to get a famous house,'' he said
about 40 minutes after willie brown walked out of prison, he married the woman who fought for five years to get him off death row
i search for words to describe what i'm feeling. so far the proper words to describe it haven't surfaced,'' brown said thursday after he and esther lichtenfels exchanged vows on the lawn of the clay county courthouse
i feel like i'm getting out of prison myself,'' his bride said before they left for their new home in springfield, mass. ``i feel wonderful. i'm so happy i can't tell you.''
brown, 37, was on parole from a massachusetts prison when a pinellas county judge sentenced him to 20 years for armed robbery in 1976. on july 7, 1981, while he was serving the time at union correctional institution, fellow inmate earl owens was stabbed to death
brown and another prisoner were charged with the slaying after a third inmate, frank wise, said he saw them leaving owens' cell shortly before the murder was discovered. the two were convicted and condemned
ms. lichtenfels met brown on christmas 1983 when she was with a group visiting condemned prisoners who had no holiday visitors
he was the saddest face i'd ever seen when i met him. it was a spiritual love right from the start,'' recalled ms. lichtenfels, 54, a divorcee with three grown children
it was at her prompting that defense lawyers pursued and won an appeal on technical grounds in november that overturned the convictions of brown and co-defendant larry troy
ms. lichtenfels then she hired a private investigator and tracked down wise. they agreed to meet and she was given a hidden microphone, with which wise was recorded admitting that brown was innocent and asking for $2,000 to recant his testimony
wise was arrested on bribery charges in december and assistant state attorney harris tobin said in february that he would not to prosecute brown and troy again because wise's credibility was damaged
brown said that while ms. lichtenfels was fighting for the appeal, he considered her optimism unrealistic. he tried to talk her out of it, he said
but ``i didn't know what kind of person she was,'' he said. ``she believes in action.''
brown must complete his parole term in massachusetts
