an opposition leader returned to panama vowing to rid the nation of gen. manuel antonio noriega, and sources today said the roman catholic church would issue its harshest denunciation yet of the military strongman
it was the fifth day of a general strike that has paralyzed the economy
ricardo arias calderon, head of the christian democratic party, arrived thursday to find panama in the midst of the anti-noriega general strike, which has shut down more than 90 percent of business and industry
the government refused to allow arias calderon into the country when he tried to return from a business trip to the united states on feb. 25, the day president eric arturo delvalle tried to fire noriega. delvalle was in turn ousted by noriega supporters
there was no reason given for blocking arias calderon's return, and there was no reason given for his being allowed back. a spokesman for the christian democratic party, william cochez, said without elaborating that ``the government backed down.''
rep. gary ackerman, d-n.y., said local u.s. officials warned arias calderon to be prepared for a ``longer haul'' before noriega is forced from power. ``nobody's talking about hours, nobody's talking about days,'' said ackerman, who is on a fact-finding tour with rep. pete kostmayer, d-pa
noriega is the country's de facto leader by virtue of his influence as chief of the defense forces
ackerman said he had been assured that the church soon would release a statement carrying a ``strong message'' against noriega
sources from the opposition national civic crusade, speaking on condition of anonymity, said the message would be the church's strongest statement yet against noriega
panama's episcopal conference of bishops, led by archbishop marcos g. mcgrath, has sharply criticized noriega in the past but fallen short of calling for his ouster
mcgrath met with noriega on thursday. mcgrath had refused to discuss the talks, saying only that he was not negotiating noriega's departure
today was payday for the 15,000-strong defense forces. on monday, noriega must come up with money for retirees already forced to wait an extra week for their pensions
a banking source who spoke on condition of anonymity said thursday the government had pleaded with local banks to hand over an estimated $70 million in their vaults. but the banks said the money belonged to their depositors and they could not legally give it up
in an attempt to force noriega into exile, the united states has frozen panamanian deposits in u.s. banks and withheld payments for use of the panama canal. the u.s. dollar is panama's currency
the country has been in an increasingly chaotic state since noriega was indicted on u.s. drug traffickng charges last month
arias calderon arrived on a commercial flight from miami and told a cheering crowd that noriega must go
his return had ``but one objective _ to get rid of noriega,'' arias calderon said. he was accompanied by christian democratic leaders from venezuela, costa rica and west germany
arias calderon, a likely presidential candidate in scheduled may 1989 elections, said he would meet with other opposition leaders to plan a strategy for ousting noriega
the government stepped up its propaganda attacks thursday against the united states and its military presence along the panama canal. the state radio station again urged panamanians _ particularly soldiers and youth _ to be on guard against ``any aggression by the united states.''
the foreign relations ministry denounced a background briefing for journalists at the u.s. southern command headquarters on saturday. the ministry accused the u.s. military of ``instructing'' reporters that they ``must help remove'' noriega
the last of 670 military police and support personnel arrived thursday at u.s. bases to beef up security
southern command officials had said earlier the reinforcements were ``simply good planning in view of the current unrest in panama.''
president reagan told high school students in vienna, va., thursday he had no plans to take military action to get rid of noriega
we're not going to be the big colossus of the north once again, coming in to ... our smaller neighbors' places of living and business and trying to guide and direct them,'' reagan said. success</head> newspaper reaction, other developments. pick up 3rd graf pvs: ``both sides...''</note>
a temporary cease-fire between the sandinistas and contra rebels held today, and the army pulled out of jungle war zones across the country to avoid clashes that would imperil a new peace accord
radio liberacion, the contras' radio station, has reported no combat since monday, the first day of cease-fire talks between the government and contras at the border town of sapoa
an international verification commission was in its second day of an inspection of the northern border with honduras. the group was asked by the sandinista government to prove that its troops were not across the border
the cease-fire talks ended wednesday with the peace accord between the government and the u.s.-supported contras
the sandinista newspaper barricada today ran a special edition about the pact. a front page editorial said, ``the yankee warmongers fail to give the final blow.''
the four-page extra said the reaction of nicaraguans was that ``reagan and the contras should comply.''
the editorial called on the united states to open talks with the nicaraguan government. with the end of american aid to the contras, the ``reagan administration has been disarmed, without pretexts to ask for more funds for its warriors.''
both sides had called the sapoa talks nicaragua's last chance for peace, and civilians greeted word of the pact with hope. one critic of the leftist sandinista government called it a miracle
vice president sergio ramirez, in mexico city to brief mexican president miguel de la madrid, called thursday night for direct talks with the reagan administration to ensure the truce holds
the white house has rejected previous sandinista calls for such talks, saying the sandinistas had first to negotiate with the rebels
in nicaragua, sandinista troops withdrew thursday from a jungle war zone in central chontales province, said a state security official who spoke on condition of anonymity. the province has been a hot spot in the 6-year-old war that has cost more than 40,000 lives
to celebrate the accord, dozens of women gathered in the main square of the chontales city of juigalpa and ``lit candles to the virgin mary,'' a defense ministry spokesman said
as part of the agreement, contra and sandinista leaders extended the informal cease-fire to april 1, when a 60-day truce takes effect and they will meet in managua to seek a permanent peace
provisions of the agreement meet requirements of the regional peace plan signed aug. 7 by five central american presidents _ ending the fighting, granting political amnesty and restoring democratic freedoms
the opposition says the sandinistas promised democracy when they overthrew rightist president anastasio somoza in july 1979, but instead established a marxist regime
enrique bolanos, president of the private enterprise council and staunch critic of the government, called the pact ``a miracle.''
in costa rica, president oscar arias said it offers ``a new and firm hope that all central americans can live in peace.'' arias won the 1987 nobel peace prize for authoring the regional peace plan
on monday, sandinista and contra negotiators will meet to designate areas inside nicaragua to which rebels will go during the first two weeks of april
nothing is said in the agreement about the contras laying down their weapons, so that may be taken up in next week's meetings. in past negotiations, the rebels insisted on keeping their weapons until provisions of any accord were carried out
the pact provides a gradual amnesty for nicaragua's 3,300 political prisoners that starts on sunday. it also also guarantees ``unrestricted freedom of expression,'' a condition demanded by the rebels, and permits all exiles to return home and participate in the political process
once rebel fighters have moved into the truce zones, the contra leadership can send up to eight delegates to participate in national reconciliation talks under way as part of the regional peace plan, the agreement says. picking up 3rd graf pvs, `chambers, 21 ....'</note>
jurors in the case of a man accused of strangling a young woman during a central park tryst began their ninth day of deliberations today after a tumultuous day during which one juror reportedly asked to be dismissed
jurors were expected today to begin rehearing medical testimony that state supreme court justice howard e. bell estimated would take a day and a half to two days to complete
but shortly before noon, the jury had yet to hear a single word of testimony and had not appeared in the courtroom. it was not clear if the panel was deliberating the fate of robert e. chambers jr. as they awaited the readback of testimony
on thursday, a juror asked supreme court justice howard e. bell to be dismissed because of an argument over the meaning of medical testimony in the case, said a source, speaking on condition of anonymity
chambers, 21, is accused of second-degree murder in the death of 18-year-old jennifer levin on aug. 26, 1986. he could be convicted of the lesser crimes of first- or second-degree manslaughter or criminally negligent homicide
bell, defense attorney jack litman and prosecutor linda fairstein met in the judge's robing room. despite requests from lawyers for the new york post and newsday, the judge refused to divulge what was discussed
litman and fairstein referred to ``that matter discussed in your honor's robing room'' without providing details
one of the 12 jurors _ who have heard eight weeks of testimony _ could be replaced by an alternate at this point only with the consent of both sides, and a mistrial could result if a juror wanted to leave
jurors were expected back in the courtroom today to begin rehearing medical testimony that bell estimated would take 1{ to two days to complete
the prosecution contends chambers strangled miss levin in a rage. the defense has argued he killed her accidentally when he yanked her backward to stop her from hurting him during rough sex in central park
at jurors' request, bell on thursday instructed them on several points of law, including burden of proof, circumstantial evidence, reasonable doubt and presumption of innocence
the jury's request for a rereading of most of the medical testimony by key defense and prosecution witnesses means lawyers must go through about 1,500 pages of transcripts
the jury asked to hear testimony that bears only on the facts on miss levin's injuries, not experts' theories on how they occurred. pvs, shultz said</note>
president reagan said today he welcomes the cease-fire in nicaragua but ``there is reason to have caution'' as to whether the couantry's leftist government will observe it
of course we look forward to this and hope it continues, but i think we should keep in mind that, just as in some other meetings that have gone on in which i have been involved, i think that we should keep in mind that both parties must be dedicated to the things that are said and agreed to in those meetings,'' the president said
when a reporter said that it sounded as though he were suspicious that this would not be the case with the sandinistas, reagan replied, ``i think there is reason to have caution; they have a past record that indicates that we should be.''
the president did not say who he was talking about, but he supports the contra rebels and has often said that he considers the sandinista government unreliable
the exchange with reporters took place as reagan was preparing to meet with visiting president joaquin belaguer of the dominican republic
earlier, secretary of state george p. shultz raised the possibility that the administration will seek legislative authority for a quick vote on military aid to the nicaraguan rebels if the cease-fire there breaks down
shultz said thursday night that the prospect of additional military assistance to the rebels would be added insurance that nicaragua's leftist government will abide by promises it makes under its cease-fire agreement with the contra rebels
but house speaker jim wright, d-tex., indicated that he would oppose any effort by the administration to have an ``expedited procedures'' provision for military aid included in a contra humanitarian assistance package the congress will take up next week
i want to emphasize positive things, and not anticipate failure,'' said wright, who was interviewed with shultz on pbs' macneil@lehrer ``newshour.''
the reaction of both the administration and the congress was generally positive to the agreement reached by the sandinistas and the contras, which calls for a 60-day cease fire during which talks on a final settlement will take place
there is agreement among the administration and the lawmakers that the united states should provide humanitarian aid to the contras _ permitted under the agreement _ but the comments of shultz and wright indicate the military aid issue is not dead
i do think there is great merit ... to have in it (the humanitarian aid package) a mechanism for a fast track vote,'' shultz said. he said there should be a guaranteed early vote on ``whatever the president might ask for.''
wright said such a provision in the humanitarian aid package is tantamount to having a discussion of terms for divorce during a wedding ceremony
i think it's inappropriate at this time to be anticipating failure,'' he added
sen. john mccain, r-ariz., a longtime contra aid supporter, said he thought that any differences over an expedited procedure provision could be ironed out
the agreement ``reduces the requirement, in our view, for lethal aid,'' mccain said, adding that he believes real compromise is now possible with wright on that issue. ``our differences of opinion are not major,'' he said
rep. david bonior, d-mich., a critic of administration policy, said he hopes the agreement will encourage the administration to turn its attention away from ``a military approach, and will begin to work in the context of this agreement for a lasting peace in nicaragua.''
senate majority whip alan cranston, d-calif., said: ``the u.s. government now has a profound responsibility not to do anything except what is in strict conformity with the precise terms of the cease-fire, neither more nor less. we must not tinker with what the nicaraguans themselves have agreed to.''
shultz said he welcomes the agreement but that the sandinistas have a ``history of broken promises.''
we have to maintain strength to go with negotiating efforts,'' he said
he added that the real issue in nicaragua is democracy and not whether the sandinistas are in or out of power
if there is an open system and an election that's truly a democratic election, and the people now in the government get elected, we have no objection to that,'' he said. ``it's the process that's the key.''
the democratic presidential candidates could have stifled all that derisive early campaign talk about being ``the seven dwarfs'' by simply playing along with the gag, says professor joseph boskin
if they were smart they would have labeled themselves _ `i'm grumpy, i'm doc' _ and that would have undercut it. whatever happened to play in america?'' said boskin, who is writing a book about the connection between humor and social change
the boston university history professor is disturbed that this year's presidential candidates generally seem about as funny as a doorknob
he labels vice president george bush the most sanctimonious in a field full of self-righteousness and calls former candidate gary hart ``a clear example of a dour approach to life.''
the other men who would be president are no better when it comes to humor, he said. ``they're basically a sterling bunch but i don't hear the humanity of humor in them.''
boskin, 58, believes candidates need humor to prove they are human, quick-thinking and slightly self-effacing _ ``not humor as a form of oppression or a weapon but as a means of liberation or perspective.''
he links a demise of lightness with the rise of electronic media, starting with radio. until the 1930s, storytelling was an art form, and public figures could rise a long way with a knack for spinning good yarns
now, with television time so precious and expensive, boskin said, ``politicians think they have to get everything in in a minute instead of seeing things in a larger contextual way.''
the candidates do manage an occasional jab, an occasional jibe, he admits. bushy-browed massachusetts gov. michael s. dukakis recently joked that rep. richard gephardt had ``eyebrow envy'' _ a line fed to him by an aide
you don't hear them spontaneously making things up as they go along,'' boskin said. ``what i've often argued is dukakis needs a levity adviser. the story about him is he's so straight he even lines up his socks in his top drawer.''
so who among recent u.s. leaders had a light touch? boskin admired john f. kennedy and hubert humphrey
asked why he appointed his brother attorney general, kennedy once replied ``because he needs the experience.'' boskin said humphrey ``would poke fun at himself for talking too long. he would say `i should shut up now, but i can't.'''
and which of this year's candidates are featured in the jokes that criss-cross the nation and sometimes connect with pop culture via television comedians?
i hear jokes about bush and hart and nobody else,'' boskin said. ``and a continuance of ronald reagan jokes and how ridiculous he is. he's fallen in prestige. you can tell through the humor.''
according to boskin, president reagan is a ``throwback'' because he tells stories. reagan displayed an ability to laugh at himself after he was shot in 1981, quipping that he hoped the doctors were republicans and quoting winston churchill about being shot at ``with no apparent effect.''
if you can't laugh at youself and laugh at a situation it bespeaks an inflexibility,'' boskin said
i think one of the problems in america is we separate humor out from seriousness. politicians who are obviously concerned about getting elected are more hypersensitive to this than others. they think if they use humor they can't be taken seriously.''
on the contrary, boskin argues, if candidates show a sense of humor the public is more likely to warm to them when talk turns to weightier issues
to counter the seven dwarfs talk, the democrats ``should have gone to the five and dime and bought masks and gone before the cameras,'' boskin said, in all seriousness
surrogate mother mary beth whitehead-gould has asked for twice-a-week visitation with baby m, while the child's father wants to block all visitation, according to court briefs
... only a suspension of visitation will ensure that melissa is provided with a loving, supportive, nurturing and peaceful environment, free from interference, at the critical stages of her development,'' said gary skoloff, a lawyer for the girl's father, william stern
in legal papers released today by superior court judge birger m. sween, skoloff said he will present testimony at a visitation hearing monday that will show the child's psychological welfare is at stake
indeed it is contended that the proofs will indicate that the emotional and psychological burden which melissa will have to sustain in establishing a relationship with mrs. whitehead will be significantly more damaging than any benefit which might occur to her as a result of visitation at this time,'' skoloff said in the 25-page brief
the visitation hearing was ordered by the state supreme court in its landmark ruling feb. 3 that restored mrs. whitehead-gould's parental rights while awarding custody of the baby, now known as melissa, to stern and his wife, elizabeth
mrs. whitehead-gould has been allowed to see melissa once a week, for two hours, under supervision at a youth center here. court papers released thursday by mrs. whitehead-gould's attorney called that schedule ``insufficient.''
the east brunswick housewife, who gained notoriety by refusing to turn over the child she agreed to bear under a $10,000 contract, says in court papers that she wants her visits with the child to be expanded eventually to half the summer and some holidays
mrs. whitehead-gould also rejected a request by stern to terminate contact between mother and child for at least six years. she contends that a break in visitation could be harmful to the child
mrs. whitehead-gould has fashioned an excellent relationship with melissa and is devoted to promoting an even more flourishing and productive relationship,'' her attorney argued
legal briefs from both sides were filed with sween earlier this week. the judge released them today after he had time to review them. however, harold cassidy, an attorney for mrs. whitehead-gould, released his brief thursday
the warm, satisfying relationship which has come into existence over the past two years would be lost to melissa if visitation were suspended,'' mrs. whitehead-gould's attorneys said
mrs. whitehead-gould requested that the visits be expanded immediately to two days a week, eight hours each time, at her home for the next six months
she also requested the scheduled be expanded to allow her to see melissa overnight every other week, alternate weekends when melissa is 3, and half the summer and one week of christmas vacation when the child is 5
the court papers say that when melissa is 12 she may ``voice a desire for more or less visitation.''
skoloff has said the sterns want to delay visitations ``as long as possible.''
about 142,200 individuals or their families will be eligible for a new military medal honoring american prisoners of war, the defense department said friday
the medal will be issued at no cost to any person who was taken prisoner of war and held captive after april 5, 1917,'' the pentagon said in announcing it was ready to begin issuing the award, which congress authorized two years ago
to qualify, an individual must have been taken prisoner during an armed conflict; i.e., world war i, world war ii, korea and vietnam, and must have rendered honorable service during the period of captivity,'' the pentagon statement said
the medal can be awarded posthumously to legal next-of-kin, but the pentagon said the criteria established by congress would not allow relatives of servicemen ``who are listed as missing in action, but for whom there is no evidence of captivity as a pow,'' to receive the medal
the defense department estimated that 142,200 individuals or their next-of-kin were eligible for the medal, which features an eagle surrounded by barbed wire and bayonet points and includes the inscription, ``for honorable service while a prisoner of war.''
the public law establishing the pow medal specifies that it will be displayed immediately following decorations awarded for individual heroism, meritorious achievement or meritorious service, and before any other service medal, campaign medal or service ribbon,'' the pentagon said
a toll-free 800 telephone number has been set up for qualified individuals to request an application form for the medal, the pentagon said. the application forms will also be distributed by a number of veterans organizations and public service agencies
using the form, an applicant will be expected to provide his full name, service number, social security number, veterans administration claim number, date and place of birth, branch of service, unit of assignment when captured and dates of confinement and release
processing of the applications will take anywhere from 45 days to 90 days because of the need to verify military records, the pentagon said
the pentagon said it would prefer individuals to use the application form, but would accept a personal letter mailed to the proper military records center providing the same information as that sought on the form
applicants may also submit their requests through a third party, such as a veterans organization or public official, who will agree to receive the medal and present it to the requestor,'' the pentagon said
the phone number for requesting an application form is 800-873-3768
personal letters requesting award of the medal or more information should be sent to one of these three addresses:
_for former army prisoners of war: u.s. army reserve personnel center, attn.: darp-pas-eaw, 9700 page blvd., st. louis, mo. 63132-5200
_for former navy, marine corps and coast guard prisoners of war: u.s. navy liaison office, national personnel records center, 9700 page blvd., st. louis, mo. 63132-5199
_for former air force and army air corps prisoners of war: air force reference branch, national personnel records center, 9700 page blvd., st. louis, mo. 63132-5199
yugoslav workers cheated west germany of up to $60 million in unemployment funds, authorities said friday
bavarian police spokesman gerhard hoppe said 74 yugoslavs had been arrested in the past two weeks in the case. he said more arrests were possible
those arrested were suspected of fraudulently obtaining jobless compensation worth $303,000. but he said other yugoslavs apparently bilked the west germany government of $30 million to $60 million
the suspects had formerly worked in west germany and applied for unemployment compensation after losing their jobs, according to hoppe. they later moved back to yugoslavia but made regular trips to west germany to continue collecting unemployment funds, he said
west german law stipulates only residents of the country are eligible for unemployment payments
about 590,000 yugoslavs live in west germany. most are employed as ``guest workers'' who remain citizens of their home countries
a man linked to a leftist opposition group probably died from police torture, but no one can be charged because the authorities' own inquiry was substandard, a judge ruled friday
njenga karanja, 42, was held without charge and incommunicado for three weeks before he died in february 1987 with injuries consistent with beatings, according to testimony at the high court inquest
government special branch officers, who are responsible for internal security, arrested karanja at a coffee shop he owns in nakuru, 100 miles northwest of nairobi, on feb. 7, 1987. they accused him of links with mwakenya, a clandestine marxist group
the group opposes the one-party state run by the western-leaning, capitalist government of president daniel arap moi's kenya african national union
ooki ooko-ombaka, a lawyer for karanja's family, told the inquest karanja's death was the result of officials ``gone crazy with unchecked power.''
amnesty international, a london-based human rights group, said in a july report on kenya that karanja reportedly was tortured by special branch officers
chief magistrate joseph mango said he suspected the prisoner had indeed been tortured. however, he said the special branch's own investigation into karanja's death was ``not up to standard'' and conducted ``with some kind of fear.''
he recommended that attorney general matthew muli's office further investigate the case, but muli wasn't bound by mango's ruling
karanja, also a well-known road rally driver, is one of six people who have died in police custody in kenya in the last 14 months
angry palestinians on friday buried six of the eight women guerrillas killed in an israeli air raid, and they vowed to avenge their death by continuing the fight against the jewish state
allahu akbar (god is great), we shall avenge your death!'' chanted the mourners, many with their eyes brimming with tears
we shall kill all those who killed you! your blood will not go cheap!'' shrieked the mother of one of the dead women
the coffins, draped in palestinian flags, were driven to beirut in ambulances from the southen port city of sidon, where the eight were killed wednesday in an israeli air strike on bases manned by guerrillas of abu nidal's fatah-revolutionary council
about 3,000 palestinians, men, women and children, carrying palestinian and lebanese flags marched in the funeral procession from west beirut's mar elias refugee camp to the cemetery
children carried wreaths from various palesitnian and lebanese leftist factions. a wreath, signed fatah-rc, led the procession ahead of a contingent of armed palestinian guerrillas
many mourners carried placards proclaiming the palestinians' determination to continue the fight to liberate palestine
women ululated as the procession marched slowly to the accompaniment of palestinian revolutionary songs blared from loudspeakers
only six of the women were buried in beirut's martyrs' cemetery. the bodies of the other two were buried in refugee camps elsewhere in lebanon
helmeted syrian soldiers in charge of security in west beirut fired their soviet-made kalashnikov rifles in a final salute as the six coffins were lowered into the ground
the fatah revolutionary council group is led by convicted terrorist abu nidal, who broke away from yasser arafat's mainstream palestine liberation organization in 1974
abu nidal, whose real name is sabri al-banna, tops the wanted lists in the united states and europe
in addition to the eight girls killed in wednesday's raid, another 15 people were wounded
an israeli air raid thursday against fatah-rc bases in the same three villages of bekesta, majdelyoun and salhiyeh south of the port city of sidon left nine people dead and five wounded
members of a condominium association say they were mistaken in refusing to let a blind man rent an apartment
we're hoping he's going to move in and be a neighbor. if he moves in, he's going to be two doors from me. we're hoping this can end up a positive thing from a negative thing,'' said morris barnett, director of the keswick b condominium association at century village
larry tomecek, 35, whose lawyer filed a discrimination complaint march 4, said thursday he didn't know if would accept the offer
he said he wanted to be sure ``all hostilities have cooled, calmed down, that i feel comfortable and everybody feels comfortable.''
i think it looks optimistic,'' said tomecek, a part-time musician who says he has lived on his own the last four years in pennsylvania. ``it's probably the first time they met a blind person.''
if tomecek accepts, his discrimination claim would be dropped, said his attorney, larry corman
the president of the condominium in a letter to the owner of the unit tomecek was planning to rent said he was rejected because he ``unfortunately is blind.''
four san diego zoo employees tested positive for tuberculosis after being exposed to infected monkeys, and a state health official blamed improper quarantine procedures
three of six endangered tibetan macaques have died of tuberculosis since arriving last march from the chengdu zoo in china, officials said thursday. the other macaques remain quarantined although they tested negative for the disease
none of the four workers has tuberculosis so far, though one is under medication, the san diego union quoted an unidentified source as saying
a veterinarian who inspected the zoo for the state last spring said thursday he found several deficiencies that could have led to the infection
edmond bayer, a consultant with the state department of health services, said employees did not regularly wear masks or gloves while around the infectious macaques and were not told to wash their hands before leaving the quarantine area
don janssen, the zoo's director of veterinary medicine, said those safety procedures weren't in effect at that time. a memo shows janssen implemented changes last may to comply with bayer's findings
among those infected with tuberculosis was debbie hewitt, 27, a senior hospital keeper
i was upset and i'm still upset because we didn't have any policy about quarantine procedures at the time,'' hewitt said. ``i'm working there and i expect my employer to protect me about things i don't know about and that wasn't being done.''
in another incident, the federal occupational safety and health administration recently fined the zoo $1,060 for two violations stemming from improper animal and keeper contact
zoo officials say the facility is contesting the citations and declined comment
osha officials said their inspection was prompted by a complaint and not related to the tuberculosis infection or the state inspector's findings
osha cited the zoo for failing to protect its employees from the possibility of contracting infectious diseases from animals, and because keepers failed to use such protective equipment as boots, gloves, aprons, pants, and protective eye wear or face shields
tuberculosis, a bacterial disease, once was a leading cause of death in the united states. it now is rarely fatal. those who test positive for the disease don't necessarily develop active cases, said nancy bowen, tb control officer for the county
two prisoners escaped from the concordia parish jail and left a note thanking deputies for the tools they used, officials said
george hunter iii, 28, and ronnie batteaste, 28, escaped late wednesday or early thursday, authorities said
deputies said the men used a hammer, srewdriver and hacksaw to dismantle a light fixture in their cell block and crawl through a ventilation shaft
thank you for leaving the escape route and a box of tools,'' the note said. ``see you later, suckers.''
batteaste was being held on charges of burglary and escape stemming from earlier incident. hunter escaped the same jail in 1984 while he was being held on armed robbery charges. he was caught more than a year later in california
hunter was convicted on the armed robbery charges wednesday in district court and was to have been sentenced friday. he faced a possible maximum of 99 years in prison for each of two counts. surrender'</head>
conservative republican members of congress are wary of the cease-fire pact in nicaragua _ one calls it a ``disguised surrender'' _ and say the united states will have to continue pressuring the sandinistas until they install a truly democratic system
at the same time, the congressmen _ attending a gop retreat here _ say it was american pressure and american aid to the contras that forced the sandinistas to deal with the contras
the result was this week's dramatic turn of events: a 60-day cease-fire agreement signed by representatives of the nicaraguan government and the guerrilla leaders, and a sandinista promise to institute democratic reforms
the goal has never been just a cease-fire,'' said rep. dick cheney, r-wyo., one of six dozen gop lawmakers at the retreat
the provisions on democratic reforms in the cease-fire pact are ``weak,'' he said, and the united states should try to keep the contras alive as a fighting force ``as a spur to continued good faith on the part of the sandinistas.''
rep. newt gingrich, r-ga., said it was ``reasonably implausible'' that the sandinistas would live up to their promises for reforms. but if they do, it would have made the years of supporting the contras a successful policy
the values of the west will have won,'' he said. ``our goal was to have freedom, not to have a war.''
gingrich said one of the reasons he had doubts about the pact was because the contras were negotiating from a weakened state, their u.s. aid having been cut off by congress a month ago
it's too early to tell, he said, ``to what degree this is a true negotiation and to what degree this is a disguised surrender'' by the contras
cheney acknowledged that the contras were ``in difficult straits'' but said they ``still have some potential.''
rep. rod chandler, r-wash., who has co-sponsored a plan to renew military aid to the contras, said the sandinistas had ``failed miserably'' when they crossed over into honduras recently in what he said was an attempt to ``deal a knockout blow to the contras.''
chandler said the sandinistas were under pressure not only because of the contras but because of their war-torn economy that has resulted from the insurgency. ``if we had never supported the contras, they'd have never been a factor,'' he said
but if the contras fold their tents and it is ``back to the usual sandinista behavior'' of totalitarian rule, he said, the united states will have to ``take some action with external forces ... external, including the united states.''
it's down to that,'' he said. ``it's definitely a new era.''
in the meantime, chandler said, he expected congress to rapidly approve some new humanitarian support for the contras with the option of adding military aid if things turn sour
democratic leaders have been discussing with the white house and with congressional republicans a $48 million, year long package of non-lethal aid. the plan would allow expedited consideration of arms shipments if president reagan requested them
rep. mike dewine, r-ohio, said that he felt the contras ``were not put in a very good bargaining position by the united states congress.'' he said he hopes that democracy takes root, but added: ``i'm a cynic.''
dewine said he feared ``this is just the beginning of the end for the contras.'' he said he wouldn't be surprised if the sandinistas over the next six to nine months tightened up their authoritarian rule and at that point the united states is left with ``very little leverage.''
it's a containment policy at that point'' with the u.s. trying to help neighboring countries such as el salvador and costa rica maintain democracy
dewine said he supported peace but, he added, ``is it the peace of slavery? is it the peace of eastern europe? is it the peace of north korea? is it the peace of cuba?''
rep. bill mccollum, r-fla., said he was more optimistic
if they really live up to their commitments, then it really is a good deal,'' he said. if not, however, ``then we've got really big problems.''
the reagan administration today launched its final effort before leaving office to remove four-decade-old prohibitions on industrial homework in five industries
the labor department said it will publish proposed regulations next week that would allow employers to contract work from people in their homes in producing gloves and mittens, embroideries, buttons and buckles, handkerchiefs and some jewelry
unlike the administration's two earlier attempts to deregulate industrial homework, officials said this time they will not try to remove the ban on women's apparel
assistant labor secretary fred alvarez acknowledged that the exclusion of women's apparel, an area in which investigators have found about half of the violations of the current law, was aimed at defusing opposition from the 210,000-member international ladies garment workers union
the proposed revisions also do not attempt to overturn state bans on the same type of work at home in hawaii, california, pennsylvania, massachusetts, connecticut, new york, rhode island and new jersey
the ilgwu, other unions and employer associations in california and new york led a firestorm of attacks on the administration's last two efforts to repeal the bans in 1981 and 1986
as a result, only the ban on knitted outerwear was lifted in 1984
alvarez said the latest proposal will be open for 30 days of public comment after it is published in the federal register next week
despite expected challenges from unions and anticipated court appeals, he said the administration hopes to have the prohibitions removed before reagan leaves office next january
it seems to me we ought to be able to get a final rule sometime this summer,'' he said
all of the current prohibitions were adopted from 1941 to 1943 under the fair labor standards act in response to what then was perceived as rampant exploitation of mostly immigrant home workers paid on a piecework basis
the recommendations of this administration demonstrate that it has learned nothing from history,'' said the afl-cio. ``the record shows that industrial homework has brought nothing but unfair competition, long hours and low wages for our poorest and most disadvantaged workers.''
alvarez, however, said unions have not yet had a chance to study the latest proposal, which includes what he called a new set of ``enforcement teeth'' such as requiring bonds from employers with records of paying less than minimum wages or other labor law violations. today, picking up 11th graf pvs, `mecham agreed ....'</note>
gov. evan mecham's son testified today that the family auto dealership was in ``very strong'' shape and that an $80,000 loan from the governor's protocol fund was intended to provide higher interest for the fund
dennis mecham, general manager of mecham pontiac, testified at the governor's impeachment trial that his father called him in mid-july 1987 and ``asked if i could use $80,000 in the dealership operations.''
the governor was expected to take the stand later today
dennis mecham said his father told him ``they were looking to generate additional interest'' for the protocol fund
the prosecution has contended that the dealership was in dire financial straits and needed the loan to meet its payroll
however, dennis mecham, asked by defense attorney jerris leonard to describe the dealership's general financial condition at the time, said, ``it was very strong.''
about $6,000 of the loan was repaid to the protocol fund in early october, and the governor's son said he was asked oct. 22 by mecham then-chief of staff jim colter to repay the balance ``since there was a political question.'' the repayment was financed by family members, he said
on thursday, former mecham special assistant sam steiger said he did not consider the protocol fund to be public money and thus the loan was legal
i think we have a politically stupid thing that was done, but not an illegal thing,'' steiger said. ``i think it's a very clear demonstration that here was a man, governor mecham, who had total confidence that he was going to be able to repay this
he did not sense the public perception of what that might appear to look like to other people because he was so convinced of the correctness of his own approach,'' steiger said. ``now that's the man that i knew as governor.''
steiger is scheduled to go on trial monday on a charge of theft by extortion for allegedly trying to influence the vote of a state parole board member
mecham is accused of misusing the protocol fund, which was created with inaugural proceeds and intended to pay for gifts for visiting dignitaries
prosecutors claim the money became public funds when it was turned over to the governor's office and that mecham tried to cover up the loan
however, the defense contends the protocol fund was private money and that the loan was a good business deal because it earned a higher interest rate for the fund
mecham agreed thursday in tucson that borrowing from the protocol fund ``was a dumb thing to do politically,'' but he insisted it ``wasn't illegal.''
he accused house prosecutors of having ``to make some kind of a devious program out of this in order to have any fabric to say anything about us.''
they would be laughed out of any court in the country, really,'' mecham said. ``the only place they've got any standing is because this is a political issue; it's really kind of a tragedy, but i think our case will take care of that very easily.''
the senate already has heard testimony on the first impeachment allegation that mecham tried to thwart an investigation of an alleged death threat by a state official against former top mecham aide donna carlson
the third allegation charges him with concealing a $350,000 campaign loan
a conviction would remove mecham from office, although the trial could continue on whether to bar him from holding any future office
a two-thirds vote of the 30-member senate is required to convict mecham. he is the first u.s. governor to be impeached in six decades and the first ever in arizona
mecham is scheduled to go on criminal trial april 21 on six felony charges of hiding the $350,000 loan and faces a may 17 recall election. chryst is a former member of the joffrey</note>
choreographer robert joffrey, who founded a dance troupe on a shoestring and built the joffrey ballet into one of the nation's top companies, died this morning. he was 57
joffrey, who had curtailed his duties at the company because of illness, died at 6 a.m. at new york university hospital, said pennie curry, a spokeswoman for the company
he had suffered from a liver ailment caused by medication he was receiving for asthma and a muscle condition, and had been in intensive care for two weeks, she said
a lifelong asthmatic, joffrey suffered severe asthma attacks in august and had been working from his home since then, she said
joffrey became ill in april 1986 and was diagnosed as having severe myositis, which causes deterioration of the muscles, enlarged liver and asthma. earlier this month, he announced a three-person advisory group to help gerald arpino, the company's associate director, run the company
he had a passion and a love for dance. he respected dancers so much. he loved to bring dance to parts of thew world that had never seen it,'' said gary chryst, a former member of the joffrey who dance with the company for 11 years
in 1956, joffrey borrowed a station wagon and sent his fledgling dance company _ six dancers, one of whom could double on piano _ out to tour the united states. he stayed in new york, where he held a job to pay for the tour
today, the joffrey ballet ranks with the new york city ballet and american ballet theater as one of america's big three ballet companies
joffrey built by far the most far-ranging repertory. nobody had ever tried to recreate vaslov nijinsky's 1913 ``the rite of spring,'' but joffrey engaged two dance historians to see whether they could recreate the ballet. the joffrey version opened last september in los angeles
joffrey brought into the company ballets of strong classical base and flowing quality by the british royal ballet's frederick ashton; the 1932 stylized anti-war masterpiece, ``the green table,'' by kurt jooss; a group of ballets created for serge diaghilev; john cranko's full-length ``romeo and juliet,'' dances by american choreographers from agnes de mille to the avant-garde. his own ballets include ``the nutcracker'' in 1987 and his striking 1967 ``astarte,'' where a couple dance in front of a billowing white silk curtain on which a movie of them dancing is projected
joffrey was the first artistic director to invite experimental modern-dance choreographers to work with a major ballet company. he brought twyla tharp to ballet in 1973. arpino, one of the original six dancers, is resident choreographer
money was always a problem for the company, and joffrey was innovative in solving it. he decided that two bases were better than one and announced a bi-coastal company, with boards and fund-raising in both new york and los angeles
last summer, he worked on his $1.5 million production of ``the nutcracker'' in iowa city, iowa, with one-third of the money coming from new york, los angeles and the university of iowa, where it premiered
joffrey was born abdullah jaffa anver bey khan, in seattle, dec. 24, 1930. his father was a native of afghanistan and his mother was italian. he had asthma as a child and a doctor suggested that he take dance classes, for the breathing exercises
he started dance classes in seattle, studied at the school of american ballet in new york and later with two modern-dance teachers. his short performance career began with a solo concert of his own works in seattle. he danced with roland petit's ballets de paris in 1949 and from 1950-52 danced sometimes in the concert group of one of his modern-dance teachers, may o'donnell
the robert joffrey ballet concert performed at new york's ymha in 1954 but joffrey dated the founding of his company from 1956, when he taught six dancers four pieces he had choreographed and sent them out in a station wagon to 23 cities. tours were annual through 1964
joffrey taught at the high school of peforming arts and choreographed for the new york city opera and other opera companies, including choreographing ``alcina'' in dallas in which joan sutherland made her american debut
by the spring of 1962, the company had 38 dancers and 21 ballets. that fall, the government sent the joffrey ballet on a 15-week tour of the middle east. it was co-sponsored by the rebekah harkness foundation. the foundation sponsored the joffrey ballet until march 1964 when rebekah harkness kean decided to use the money for a new harkness ballet, keeping dancers, costumes, sets, scores and choreography from the previous two years
the ford foundation made a grant to get the joffrey ballet going again. joffrey did intense fund-raising and re-established the company,which became the resident dance company at the city center in new york
joffrey did not do much choreography in recent years. he choreographed part of a new production of ``the nutcracker suite'' that was performed this year; his last full production, ``postcards,'' was performed during the 1970s
he left no immediate survivors
ms. curry said a memorial service would be scheduled at a later date. a viewing was planned for frank b. campbell's funeral home on sunday and monday. from boyfriend.</note>
a young irish woman, who came here to visit a sweetheart but found him jailed on murder charges, was struck by a car on st. patrick's day and lapsed into a coma, say her family and friends
the girl is a beautiful looking girl. when i first saw her lying there in the hospital, i thought to myself, `it's snow white in a trance,''' said gerry archbold, a director of the city's irish-american heritage center
margaret hanley, 22, was listed in critical condition today at weiss memorial hospital, where her parents are keeping a vigil at her bedside
stephen and ann hanley left their 13 younger children behind in coolock, a suburb of dublin, and flew to chicago to be with her. neighbors collected money to help pay for their trip
miss hanley's father said he was against his daughter's trip to the united states earlier this month. ``but she wanted to travel the world, you know,'' he said. and she had a special reason for her trip
last year she met a man named danny stokes, the brother of a girlfriend, who'd returned to ireland for a visit. she was attracted to him
he took her out, and they must have communicated (when he returned to chicago),'' archbold said. ``she was infatuated with him.''
so miss hanley, an aspiring actress who dreamed of traveling the world, left her home for a three-week vacation and a visit to stokes
when she arrived in chicago, she learned that stokes was in jail, charged with murder, archbold said. he said he did not know the details of the case against stokes, but officials at the cook county jail confirmed thursday night that a daniel stokes was held there on murder charges
stokes said today in a telephone interview from jail that miss hanley knew he was in custody before she came and wanted to help him
it was very hard to accept, the emotional stress of seeing me behind bars,'' he said
a disillusioned miss hanley called her family, telling them she'd decided to return home and was planning to leave last friday. ``she said she'd explain it all to us later,'' her father said
but the day before she was to leave, miss hanley was struck by a car as she crossed a street on the north side
her leg and hip were broken, but she was conscious as she was taken to a hospital emergency room, where she slipped into a coma apparently induced by a blood clot, doctors said
her parents spend their days at their daughter's bedside and their nights at a room given to them by priests at the st. patrick fathers home
all we can do is wait,'' hanley said. ``there is nothing we can do for her. where there is life, there is hope.''
sales of existing homes, after declining for three straight months, posted a modest increase of 3.8 percent in february, a real estate trade group reported friday
the national association of realtors said that existing single-family homes were sold at a seasonally adjusted annual rate of 3.29 million units in february. while this was 11.3 percent below the sales level of a year ago, it was the first advance since a 1.2 percent rise in october
sales fell 2.9 percent in november, 1.2 percent in december and 4.8 percent in january as the housing market was rocked by volatile mortgage rates and consumer worries sparked by the october stock market collapse
the february increase in sales was credited to better economic news, falling interest rates and renewed consumer confidence. fixed-rate mortgages, which stood at 10.61 percent at the beginning of the year, have fallen into single-digits, standing at 9.92 percent currently
lower interest rates have brought the consumer back into the market,'' said john tuccillo, chief economist for the association. ``february's existing home sales numbers indicate good health on the part of the housing sector, which, in the sixth year of expansion, is far from dead.''
tuccillo predicted the lower mortgage rates would help boost sales even further in the months ahead
the rise in home sales was accompanied by a slight increase in home prices. the median or mid-point price of a home increased to $88,300, up from $87,400 in january
the increase in sales was led by a 12.8 percent jump in sales in the south, which rose to an annual rate of 1.23 million units, still 4.7 percent below the level of activity a year ago. this region has been hard hit by depressed conditions in the oil industry
sales were also up in the northeast, climbing 8.2 percent to an annual rate of 660,000 units
sales fell 5.4 percent in the midwest to an annual rate of 870,000 units, but analysts blamed this decline on unusually severe weather in the region during february. sales dipped a small 1.9 percent in the west to an annual rate of 520,000 units. belaguer elected.</note>
president joaquin balaguer of the dominican republic met with president reagan today, declaring that his island nation is ``as peaceful and tranquil as it can possibly be in today's world.''
balaguer was expected to seek increases in aid and sugar quotas during the meeting, according to a senior administration official who spoke on condition he not be identified
the official said the united states was ``looking for ways to be helpful.''
as the two leaders posed for photographers before their meeting, balaguer was asked if everything was calm and peaceful in his country, which has seen violent uprisings in the past
yes, everything is calm and peaceful,'' he said. ``as peaceful and tranquil as it can possibly be in today's world.''
reagan, asked if the same could be said of the united states, replied, ``i would say that the situation is normal.''
balaguer, elected to his fifth term as president of the caribbean island nation in 1986, arrived in washington on thursday and was meeting with secretary of state george p. shultz and secretary of defense frank c. carlucci as well as reagan today
reagan's meeting with balaguer follows a visit thursday to a high school in the washington suburb of vienna. appearing with education secretary william j. bennett, reagan praised a trend toward ``free-market principles'' in education that provide incentives for teachers who achieve superior performance
the united states has sharply reduced aid to the dominican republic in recent years and has lowered its quotas on imports of sugar, a major dominican crop
their economic difficulties, and they have economic difficulties, are largely the product of our sugar policy,'' said the senior official, who spoke on condition that he not be identified
our imposition of lower and lower sugar quotas every year has diminished their ability to sell sugar to the united states and that has been a really crippling blow to the dominican economy,'' the official said
the reagan administration has pressed congress unsuccessfully for changes in u.s. sugar policy
inflation is running at around 30 percent and unemployment at close to that figure in the dominican republic, the official said
we are very appreciative of the efforts of president balaguer to keep the economy of his country on an even keel,'' the official said. ``i don't think there is anybody in the dominican republic who is appreciative of our aid cuts or cuts in the sugar quota.''
although the dominican republic has received substantial u.s. aid in the past, it is down for nothing in either economic support funds or military assistance in the fiscal 1988 budget. the figure for development assistance is a relatively modest $18.7 million
the sugar quota declined about 27 per cent this year and is ``on a downward trend,'' the official said
in 1983 the united states bought 500,000 tons, or $188 million worth, of dominican sugar. this year the total was 125,000 tons, valued at about $50 million
they will ask for additional aid, either direct financial aid or other forms of assistance,'' the official said
we are looking for ways to be helpful,'' he added.  
soviet armenia's government ordered the dissolution friday of a committee agitating for annexation of a region in neighboring azerbaijan. soldiers and helicopters patrolled tense yerevan, the capital, in case of trouble
the kremlin declared this week that the campaign for annexation of the nagorno-karabakh region was ``intolerable.''
public protests had been called for saturday in yerevan, but radio broadcasts in armenia and azerbaijan warned citizens of both caucasus republics friday against illegal demonstrations
the broadcasts announced new regulations requiring permits 10 days in advance of all public gatherings
hovik vassilian, an armenian activist reached by telephone, said the saturday demonstrations ``won't happen.'' vassilian said they were called off, ``considering the situation.''
he also said activists had learned that armenian nationalist paruyr arikyan was arrested thursday night. he said they did not know the charges, but arikyan had provided information about the protests to foreign reporters in moscow
an armenian communist party newspaper reaching moscow on friday said the republic ``remains tense and explosive.'' it spoke of ``unpredictable consequences'' if the demonstrations were held
activists and official sources in yerevan most armenians appeared to be wary of illegal protest because of the crackdown
a duty officer at the police ministry described the security precautions by telephone and said yerevan was ``fairly calm.'' he would not give his nam
vassilian said groups of three to five soldiers of the internal security forces were patrolling with police and that helicopters had been circling over the city for three days
repeated attempts to telephone azerbaijan on friday were unsuccessful
on thursday, the national party's governing politburo issued an eight-year plan for dealing with complaints about discrimination against ethnic armenians in nagorno-karabakh, where they are more than 75 percent of the population
pravda and izvestia, the party and government newspapers, gave prominent display friday to letters from readers urging reason and patience in resolving the territorial dispute between armenians, most of whom are christians, and the predominently shiite moslem population of azerbaijan
the letters, and official commentaries, had the apparent purpose of portraying the leadership's approach to the sensitive ethnic issue as a wiser course than strikes and demonstrations
tass, the official news agency, said the politburo's eight-year plan provides for more housing, roads, schools and social services in the disputed region, and more armenian television programming and literature
concern that nagorno-karabakh was losing its traditional armenian character was among the reasons prompting calls for annexation
armenian residents of the area began protests in mid-february after the national party central committee rejected a request from the the nagorno-karabakh government for union with armenia. the region, slightly smaller than delaware, was part of armenia until 1923
official media described the annexation drive as an extremist action, and hundreds of thousands of armenians demonstrated in the streets of yerevan. the mass unrest abated only after soviet leader mikhail s. gorbachev appealed for calm and reason
on feb. 28, extremists in sumgait, azerbaijan, went on a rampage to protest the armenian demands, and officials said at least 32 people were killed. the official reports said 197 were injured and about 400 arrested for murder, rape, robbery or other crimes in the industrial city
armenian supporters of the annexation proposal, including some prominent officials in the southern republic, formed a committee to press the nagorno-karabakh issue and called the protests for saturday
the committee withdrew the appeal for protests, but nonetheless became a target of authorities
wednesday's issue of kommunist, the armenian party daily that reached moscow on friday, accused the committee of blackmail, threats and anti-party attacks
it said officials were ordered to ``take measures necessary to avert meetings on march 26'' and party organizations were told to ``neutralize activities of nagorno-karabakh `committees' because at present their actions are politically harmful.''
vassilian, the activist, also said the committee was ordered ``closed'' friday
prominent officials and literary figures appealed on radio and television for patience and an end to protests and strikes, he said
pravda said it was suspending an armenian journalist who contributed to a report on the nagorno-karabakh dispute but denounced it after publication monday
the party newspaper said it had handwritten copies of the information submitted by the journalist, identified as y. arakelyan, and his report conformed with the published article. it did not give details of his original material. pvs, each state</note>
the head of the nation's largest teachers' union today proposed that every state designate a school district as a ``living laboratory'' for experiments aimed at producing better educated students
national education association president mary hatwood futrell said she will ask her state affiliates to work with governors, state legislators and state school officials to bring about such experiments on a broad scale
she told a news conference that teachers, parents and others in the experimental districts would have the union's blessings to ``turn their school systems upside down or inside out'' in pursuit of improvements
in response, secretary of education william j. bennett said in a statement:
it's rather ironic to hear a call for reform from the organization that has done the most to resist meaningful education reforms in recent years. but if they are serious, it will be a welcome and refreshing change to have nea begin supporting real education reform.''
each state should have at least one district operating ``as an experimental, living laboratory for education reform,'' futrell said
in these 50 school districts, school employees, working through their local association, would join with school boards, parents, civic leaders and business to develop whatever innovative or creative program they deem appropriate to improve education,'' she said
those 50 local communities would be free to turn their school systems upside down or inside out,'' she said
they would be free to open their school doors to 4-year-olds, or end the arbitrary division of class periods into 50-minute chunks, or experiment with alternatives to student tracking,'' she said
futrell said the idea must still be approved by delegates to the nea's annual convention in new orleans in july
futrell told the news conference that if a laboratory school district decided to adopt a merit pay plan, the national union would not object
she also said the nea was prepared to provide some financial support for the experiments and said that bold action is needed to revive what she called lagging efforts to improve america's schools
five years after `a nation at risk,' lack of funding is strangling education reform in state after state,'' she said, referring to the landmark report on the state of education
she said secretary of education william j. bennett ``wants america to believe that excellence costs nothing, that just talking about reform _ and blaming people _ will substitute for money. it won't.''
state and local governments have poured more money into public schools, she said, ``but they can't do the job without help from the federal government.''
the federal share of the public school budget has slipped from 9.2 percent in fiscal 1980 to 6.2 percent in fiscal 1988, she said, and education's share of the overall federal budget has dropped from 2.5 percent in fiscal 1979 to 1.8 percent in fiscal 1987. people injured, picking up 3rd graf pvs, `the men ....'</note>
