ten people were still hospitalized today, including a 5-year-old boy and a 32-year-old man reported in critical condition with burns, hospital officials here and in wichita said. one man was listed in serious condition, and the others were in fair condition
the men, women and children were gathered in front of the oil rig shortly before 10 p.m. thursday and were ``supposedly bringing in a new well'' when it exploded, ness county sheriff gary o'brien said
flames engulfed the building before firefighters could control the fire, o'brien said. crews extinguished most of the fire by 11:30 p.m. the cause of the fire and explosion has not been determined
o'brien said he did not know the name of the company that owned the well, about 3{ miles northwest of ness city in western kansas
king birendra of nepal called for solidarity among the globe's 650 million hindus friday as he opened the world hindu conference
about 1,200 participants from 19 countries attended the opening ceremony of the four-day meeting in katmandu
representatives from bangladesh, canada, fiji, guyana, indonesia, india, kenya, mauritius, nepal, netherlands, new zealand, norway, pakistan, sri lanka, singapore, spain, the united kingdom, the soviet union and west germany paraded through the conference venue at national stadium
king birendra, in his inaugural speech, said the conference would ``succeed in establishing unity and solidarity among hindus wherever they be showing the ideal way of life.''
hindus live in significant numbers in at least 80 countries worldwide, with the vast majority in india. their religion grew from a synthesis of indigenous beliefs with culture brought to india by the aryan people around 1500 b.c
japanese monopolies on trade in tobacco and beef must be eliminated because they are barriers to u.s. exports, a former agriculture department official said friday during his confirmation hearing for the post of top u.s. negotiator on farm trade
the monopolies must go,'' daniel g. amstutz, a former undersecretary of agriculture, told the senate foreign relations committee. ``they are barriers to trade just as sure as import quotas are. ... they are a kind of marriage between industry and government.''
he said the u.s. government is insisting on elimination of japanese quotas on beef imports
i think we'll be successful,'' he added
amstutz agreed with sen. mitch mcconnell, r-ky., who urged u.s. negotiators to push international sales of cigarettes and other tobacco products
this is not the place to make moral judgments,'' amstutz said after the hearing
the official u.s. campaign against smoking was not discussed at the session itself. mcconnell said moral judgments about practises in other countries are ``not up to us.''
mcconnell estimated that the u.s. share of japan's cigarette market rose from 2 percent to 11 percent in two months after u.s. pressure succeeded in easing restrictions on japanese imports. he urged amstutz to be aggressive in getting restrictions eased in south korea too
he said that despite the popularity of turkish tobacco, many turkish workers acquired a taste for american tobacco as ``guest workers'' in west germany and created a demand for it when they returned home. smoking in turkey is on the increase and the united states should take advantage of the opportunity, he said
amstutz declined to say what priority he would give to pressing cigarette sales
everything is first,'' he said
he explained that at the big international trade discussions in geneva, switzerland, known as the ``uruguay round,'' an effort is being made to keep the negotiations away from particular products
on farm products, the emphasis has been on reducing government subsidies. the reagan administration has proposed that all government farm subsidies be phased out by the year 2000. other governments have called the goal unrealistic
the committee is expected to approve amstutz's nomination next week
a judge sentenced 20 taxi drivers to jail friday after they defied the city's new anti-smog ban
the new rules, which allows taxis and private cars in a 5-square-mile area of downtown only on alternate weekdays and on weekends, are aimed at dispelling the acrid cloud that hovers over the city in still weather. the cabbies say they are not at fault and the ban hurts their business
the 20 taxi drivers were sentenced to five weeks in jail. another 35 cabbies were fined $150 each, said a judiciary spokesman requesting anonymity
the 55 cabbies drove into the banned area on monday and tuesday during protests organized by their union, which seeks daily access for all the city's 15,000 taxis
the spokesman said all 20 cabbies were freed after appealing the sentences
the chancellor of fayetteville state university is so sure he can raise the quality of the school's education students that he will offer a warranty on every teacher graduating after 1993
if a teacher fresh from fsu, or the school district where he or she is employed, can identify weaknesses in the teacher's preparation, a team of fsu specialists ``will make their product good,'' chancellor lloyd hackley said
the specialists will make recommendations on course work, consultation or counseling, and establish a baseline to document the teacher's improvement
hackley announced the warranty thursday as part of a sweeping plan for improvements
hackley said the school's development has been retarded by a lack of adequate state and federal funding during most of its existence, plus low financial support from alumni
three boys removed from a religious commune by court order and returned to their fathers, at least temporarily, had been physically and emotionally abused by cult leaders, the fathers say
deputies surprised devotees of the tony and susan alamo foundation communes in saugus on thursday, reuniting the children with their fathers before a custody hearing in orange county superior court
there was a lot of confusion and cries of anguish from the adults,'' los angeles county sheriff's sgt. larry brakebush said. ``there were people everywhere, people running around the grounds shouting.''
the boys' mothers weren't at the alamo holy christian church commune when the raid took place
alamo gained notoriety when he vowed that his wife susan, who died of cancer in 1982, would be resurrected. he kept her embalmed body on display for six months while followers prayed
the custody dispute involves brothers carey and robert miller of orange, who were banished from the commune after 15 years as members following a disagreement over control of a trucking firm they operated in arkansas
my wife is absolutely and completely brainwashed by tony alamo to the extent that she has now consented to live with another man as husband and wife,'' carey miller, 34, said in a sworn statement. ``i am given to understand that i was now an outsider and would be prevented from seeing my wife and children.''
the men filed court statements contending the children were abused, physically and emotionally, by their mothers and cult leaders, and that they feared their sons would soon be taken to canada if they didn't act to regain custody. both have begun divorce proceedings
they also said they were wrongly separated from their families after a business dispute with church leaders, contentions the commune's founder denied
they abandoned their wives and children, embezzled money from the church and lied in court about it,'' alamo said thursday in a telephone interview from new york
the foundation has sued the brothers for allegedly emptying the trucking company's bank accounts when they left the commune. alamo said commune members agree to sign over all property to the church, something the brothers balked at doing with their trucking company
judge ronald owen granted the millers temporary custody of the boys, ages 11, 9 and 4, until an informal mediation session april 6 and a court hearing five days later to hear arguments about permanent custody
attorneys for the two mothers, carol ann and susan miller, and the church said the women were in new york city selling clothes made at the commmune northwest of los angeles
the miller brothers said they fled the commune in fear of their lives in september after an altercation with alamo and church officers
i never threatened anybody,'' said alamo
alamo and his wife started preaching on hollywood's sunset strip in 1966. they attracted numerous young followers and formed a commune in saugus, later moving it to arkansas. recently they moved their headquarters back to california but still have centers in chicago, miami, arizona and arkansas
health authorities have warned that eggs from two farms near the site of a chemical fire last year contain toxic dioxin at levels 100 times greater than in normal eggs
officials of the state health services department said thursday they advised about about 45 familes living near the koppers wood treatment plant not to eat eggs or chicken from the two family farms
koppers was the site last april of a fire and explosion that left residues of a toxic wood preservative used at the plant
dioxins are a class of toxic chemicals found in a variety of chemical compounds, including some preservatives. minute levels are also generally found in all animal products
while there is no proof that dioxin has ever killed anyone, a 1980 report by the environmental protection agency said immediate effects of exposure to dioxin can include burning in the eyes, nose, and throat; headaches; itching, swelling and redness of the face; dizziness; nausea and vomiting
there is also increasing evidence of an association between occupational exposure to dioxins and a rare form of tumor called soft tissue sarcoma, according to the national centers for disease control
the eggs and chickens may have been contaminated as a result of the koppers accident, but an investigation is continuing to pin down the source, said state health services director ken kizer
if we knew the cause of the contamination, we would say so,'' said bob borzelleri of the department's toxics division
samples taken from the two affected farms last may showed dioxin levels of 10 parts per trillion, compared with levels of 0.1 parts per trillion found in eggs a few miles away
samples taken this month show dioxin levels ranging from 15 to 30 parts per trillion
eating one contaminated egg a day over a 70-year lifetime would increase a person's chances of developing cancer from 250-in-1,000 to 253-in-1,000, the department's scientists estimate
herb lightle, who owns one of the farms, said he was angry that the state testing took so long
one of my daughters loves to eat eggs. ... i'm worried for my kids,'' lightle said. ``the state told us after the fire it was ok to eat our eggs and stuff out of the garden. they should have issued an advisory from the very start. i would rather have buried the eggs or thrown them out.''
acting premier li peng declared friday that economic reform was irreversible but cautioned against hasty change as he opened the national people's congress
the 59-year-old technocrat is expected to be confirmed as premier during the legislature's 20-day session
in the 2{-hour speech, li resoundingly endorsed the nation's reform goals. but he stayed true to form by sounding repeated notes of caution against expecting rapid prosperity or making changes faster than people can accept them
we must not rush headlong into mass action, issue arbitrary orders and spoil things by excessive enthusiasm,'' li warned. ``we cannot succeed if we are too impatient for quick results.''
the new national people's congress, which sits for five years, is expected to approve key measures giving legal underpinning to the market-style economic reforms that have doubled chinese incomes over the past decade
the congress itself is intended to be a showpiece of the reforms. its 2,970 delegates were elected by provincial legislatures and the military using multiple candidate balloting for the first time
several working meetings are being opened for the first time to foreign reporters, in addition to the ceremonial opening and closing sessions. before the start of friday's session, reporters were allowed to mix freely with delegates as they drank tea at small tables in the cavernous entry room of the great hall of the people and watched ``tom and jerry'' cartoons on a small tv at one end
in his speech, li applauded the achievements of china's economic decentralization and said the state's role in the economy gradually will be reduced from that of planner to indirect market regulator
li generally is regarded as more cautious than his predecessor, communist party chief zhao ziyang, who has become the leading architect of all-out economic and political decentralization
however, he echoed zhao's words by declaring that increased productivity must be ``the criterion for judging all our work.''
at a major party congress in october at which he was named party general secretary, zhao said development must take precedence over ideology if china is to end its chronic poverty
we should continue to put reform at the center of all our undertakings,'' li said in agreement. ``it has become an irreversible trend for the masses and cadres alike to take an active part in the reform.''
zhao, who sat behind li on the stage, appeared restless during the long speech. on his left, senior leader deng xiaoping, 83, the initiator of the reforms, followed the text closely while chain-smoking
he said price increases were china's no. 1 economic and social problem, but for the first time in public endorsed continuing the gradual decontrol of prices long distorted by stae subsidies
however, he said workers will be given direct subsidies for some staple foods, on which price ceilings will be imposed. inflation was 7.3 percent nationwide last year but hit 19 percent in some cities during the summer
li said that in the next five years, china must increase grain production, encourage scientific development, revitalize the bureaucracy and reduce controls on enterprises
one of the few specific goals he set was to raise grain production by about 8 million tons, or 2 percent, per year. grain production hit a record of 407 million tons in 1984 but since has declined, causing shortages of livestock feed and pork rationing
delegates interrupted li's speech with applause 17 times, generally at natural pauses in the text. when he finished, applause was brief and perfunctory and the huge hall emptied within five minutes as top officials rushed to their chauffeur-driven mercedes benzes and ordinary delegates to their buses
li, grinning widely, was congratulated by his colleagues in the party and government leadership as he walked back to his seat and gulped tea
the congress will hold four more plenary sessions to hear reports from top officials before gathering april 13 to vote on proposed legislation and elect top officials
the congress also is expected to name gen. yang shangkun as successor to outgoing president li xiannian
although the congress long has served as a rubber-stamp body for communist party decisions, in the past few years it has taken a more active role in debating and even amending party proposals. picking up in 2nd graf pvs, all five; deletes 25th graf pvs, kansas sen.; cuts last 5 grafs pvs</note>
bob dole conceded today that george bush was almost certain to win the republican presidential nomination, saying, ``i can read the numbers.'' on the democratic side, richard gephardt denied reports that his candidacy was near an end and declared ``we're going to turn this race back around'' in michigan's caucuses
dole, the senate republican leader, indicated he was in the process of re-evaluating his presidential campaign and would likely ``have something to say about that'' before the april 5 wisconsin primary
i've been saying now for some time as a candidate all the things i thought we should focus on and nobody really seems to care,'' dole told his audience. ``i think it's probably a foregone conclusion what's happening on the republican side.''
but i still have some things to say,'' he added. ``lo and behold, as your candidacy weakens, you find more people willing to listen.''
still, he said, ``i can read the numbers and i probably know what's happening.'' bush has won a huge lead in delegates in the past month
all five democratic presidential candidates were in michigan today, scouring the state for votes on the eve of saturday's caucuses with 138 delegates up for grabs
gephardt clearly had the most at stake in michigan, a state his own aides described as a do-or-die situation for his once vital presidential campaign. the missouri congressman mimicked rival michael dukakis' claim of an economic miracle in massachusetts, saying he looked forward to a ``michigan miracle'' to revive his candidacy
i think we're going to turn this race back around here in michigan,'' he said on cbs' ``this morning'' program. ``we're going to get back in the middle of this thing.''
his aides said thursday that without a win this weekend, the missouri congressman would end his presidential bid and run for re-election to his house seat. the filing deadline for the house seat is tuesday
sen. paul simon of illinois, a democratic rival, said today at a lansing airport news conference, ``my hope is that dick can stay in the race.''
as for the possibility that he himself would win no delegates in michigan, simon said, ``i recognize that's a possibility but it's not fatal to my campaign.''
fellow democrat jesse jackson campaigned in detroit's county jail today, telling inmates they must take control of their lives and shun the ``short-term thrill, long-term chill'' of drugs. he urged the inmates at the wayne county jail to ask for absentee ballots and vote in saturday's caucuses
bush campaigned thursday in connecticut, where he was expected to cruise to an easy win in tuesday's primary. he grew up in the state, and his father was a u.s. senator from connecticut
bush has been under fire in recent days for supporting president reagan's veto of a sweeping civil rights bill. congress overrode the veto this week
the vice president said he favored the basic premise of the bill, but didn't want to go against the president on the matter. besides, he said, the legislation was flawed. jackson has scoffed at that, saying bush lacks leadership
perhaps rev. jackson was talking when he should have been listening,'' bush retorted thursday. ``if he's the nominee, we'll have a chance to discuss civil rights records and i'll lay my record on the ground with anybody.''
bush suggested jackson's democratic rivals were too timid about criticizing him. ``it's not that i'm afraid to do what some democrats are afraid to do _ go after him,'' he said
at a news conference, the vice president also expressed admiration for former white house aide oliver north, who pleaded innocent thursday in washington to criminal charges in connection with the iran-contra affair
i think anybody who sheds his blood for his country and wins a purple heart _ three of them _ and a silver star deserves whatever accolades one gets for that kind of stellar heroic performance,'' he said
bush said he did not expect the arms-for-hostages affair to hurt his campaign
the democrats will be trying to raise it and make an issue out of it,'' he said, but added: ``i don't think anyone has ever implicated me or suggested any wrongdoing.''
for the second time this week, a poll suggested bush would have a tough fight on his hands if he were running against democrat michael dukakis. a cbs-new york times poll indicated 46 percent of all registered voters polled favored bush and 45 percent backed dukakis. the margin of error was plus or minus 3 percentage points
a survey by abc news and the washington post also put the two neck and neck, with dukakis polling the best against bush among the democrats
dukakis had a round of appearances today in michigan. on thursday, he was replenishing an already impressive campaign treasury with fundraisers in california
in los angeles, the massachusetts governor fielded questions in english and spanish. asked whether he would consider a hispanic running mate, he answered ``vamos a ver'' _ we'll see
republican pat robertson, who was crushed in the big round of super tuesday contests earlier this month, said no matter what the press or anyone else says, his candidacy isn't dead
i don't think they are aware of the resurrection,'' the former television evangelist told supporters in falls church, va
at recent appearances, however, robertson has acknowledged he has little chance to win the nomination and is concentrating on his role at the convention and his impact on the party
president reagan said friday the record of nicaragua's marxist-led government indicates ``there is reason to have caution'' that it may not live up to the cease-fire agreement reached with the u.s.-backed contra rebels
it was the first time reagan had commented in any detail on the 60-day nationwide cease-fire, effective april 1, that was announced wednesday after negotiations in sapoa, nicaragua
of course we look forward to this and hope it continues, but ... just as in some other meetings that have gone on in which i have been involved, i think that we should keep in mind that both parties must be dedicated to the things that are said and agreed to in those meetings,'' the president said
when a reporter said that it sounded as though he were suspicious that this would not be the case with the sandinistas, reagan replied, ``i think there is reason to have caution _ they have a past record that indicates that we should be.''
the exchange with reporters took place as reagan was preparing to meet with visiting president joaquin balaguer of the dominican republic
during his daily white house news briefing earlier, presidential spokesman marlin fitzwater told reporters ``we are having discussions with the resistance leadership'' about the new cease-fire plan
we're very hopeful that it works,'' fitzwater said. ``we want to do whatever we can to see that it works.''
but at the same time, the spokesman said the administration is ``very hopeful'' that a package of humanitarian assistance to the contras can be approved by the house and senate before congress' easter recess
he said that while the administration remained somewhat skeptical of the sandinista intentions, a mutually agreed cease-fire between the marxist regime and the contra rebels ``was the no. 1 item on the agenda'' in the joint peace plan that reagan offered last august in coordination with house speaker jim wright, d-texas
fitzwater also said friday the united states had no intention of entering into direct discussions with the sandinistas _ as suggested by nicaraguan president daniel ortega
we have never envisioned bilateral talks. ... we have said that once a cease-fire was reached ... we would be willing to talk on a multilateral, regional basis'' involving the leaders of central american democracies
fitzwater declined to speculate on what motivated the resistance fighters to enter into a cease-fire agreement, although he did say ``it's certainly understandable that they would find the congress less than supportive,'' given the defeat of new aid packages on capitol hill
the spokesman reiterated administration statements urging the soviet union to lower the level of military assistance it has been sending to nicaragua
we have talked to the soviets. we have made our views, publicly as well as privately,'' fitzwater said. but he also said ``we believe it's very important to have an (u.s.) aid package (for the contras) ... as a means of keeping pressure on the sandinistas'' to institute democratic reforms
senate conservatives were voicing some muted criticism of the agreement, but appeared willing to put the sandinistas to the test and wait to see whether pledges of amnesty and political pluralism are fulfilled
they've gained something,'' sen. james mcclure, r-idaho, said of the rebels, but added: ``it's an agreement that's shaded on the bad side... what they're after is a pluralistic government with human rights, and they have none of that.''
sen. jesse helms, r-n.c., said ``a sense of euphoria is not in order. the sandinistas promised all of this (the pledges in the agreement) at the time they took power. i don't believe i've ever heard of a leopard changing his spots.''
helms said the agreement removes the united states, at least for the moment, from any influential role in nicaragua. ``we are in a position of wait and see,'' he said. ``the only improvement is that the heat will really now be on the sandinistas to put up or shut up.''
sen. ted stevens, r-alaska, said ``i don't have any real problems with this agreement if it's kept,'' but he was skeptical about whether that could occcur
it's incumbent on us now to find out what other pressure we can keep on the sandinistas. we can't afford not to be players. the end product of what they've agreed to still leaves a soviet puppet state in central america,'' receiving large amounts of weaponry
that worries me in terms of our relationships with the nations that surround nicaragua. i view nicaragua as being more worrisome for our future than cuba.'' edit to conform, picking up 13th graf pvs, `gardner, appearing ....'</note>
police and firefighters today agreed to end their day-and-a-half bout of ``blue flu'' and return to work after city officials promised to set up a committee to discuss their salary complaints, a police representative said
apparently, the mayor is appointing a committee this afternoon comprised of members of the city council,'' said cpl. dave dickens, adding that the committee would meet with police officers monday
he said police and firefighters would return to work this afternoon as part of an agreement that included creation of the committee
mayor chuck gardner this morning ordered police and firefighters to end their sick-out, saying there's a strong possibility those who refused to return to work would be fired
on thursday, officers ignored similar back-to-work orders from a circuit judge and the city council, forcing city officials to call in state police, shut down two fire stations and declare a civil emergency
this morning, 119 of 144 police officers remained off the job for the second consecutive day to protest a 2 percent pay raise, but 30 of 44 firefighters reported for work, said ed esposito, a city hall aide
they seem to be recognizing the concern that firefighters who had been on duty since 8 a.m. wednesday were exhausted,'' he said, adding there was no indication the firefighters were ending their sick-out. most of the firefighters held over when the job action began were sent home this morning to rest
at a press conference today, gardner said that thursday was ``a grace period, allowing cooler heads to review this situation.''
i believe the last 24 hours have given police and firefighters enough time to obey the court order and return to work, and in keeping with uniformed services policy i am ordering all police personnel to report for duty by 2 p.m. this afternoon, and all fire personnel to report for duty by 6 p.m.''
when asked what would happen if the officers remained defiant, he said there was a ``strong possibility'' that those who ignored his order would be fired
the job action in this state capital of 63,000 people, west virginia's largest city, began after city officials announced a 2 percent pay raise for city employees effective july 1. police and firefighters say the raise is inadequate
gardner said today he will not meet with police and firefighters until they return to work, and that there is no money for larger raises
let them come forward and show me where the money is,'' he said
firefighters and police who return to work today face no punishment, gardner said, but must have a doctor's excuse
gardner, appearing on television thursday night, read a statement announcing that two fire stations in outlying areas of the city were being closed temporarily because of manpower shortages
at this time i am again asking the police and the firefighters to return to duty at the earliest time or on their next shift,'' gardner said on wsaz-tv
earlier in the day, gardner _ after declaring a state of emergency _ warned absent workers that ``if you don't come back to work, you are in contempt of court.''
less than an hour before an emergency city council meeting thursday, kanawha county circuit judge patrick casey issued a temporary injunction ordering police and firefighters to return to duty
the order was ignored, with 42 of 44 firefighters not reporting and about a dozen policemen out on a shift that normally has 16 or 17 officers, gardner said
at most, three patrol cars cruised the city thursday, police chief ed garnett said. ``we're at skeleton now,'' garnett said, but the public was ``helping out quite a bit'' by not making unnecessary calls to dispatchers
in addition, two state police cruisers patrolled charleston because of the sick-out, state police sgt. don cook said
two fire trucks were taken out of service thursday evening because of a manpower shortage and officials said an additional fire station could be shut down today if the protest continued
the city council thursday unanimously suspended the city's sick-leave policy, meaning those who called in sick would have to have a doctor's excuse to get paid for any additional absences
the sick-out had the ``potential effect of rendering the city unable to maintain public order,'' gardner told the 26 council members
about 20 police officers' wives picketed city hall on thursday. passing motorists honked their horns in support, and some _ aware that patrols were down _ took the opportunity to run red lights
many of the wives denied their husbands were striking. ``mine is sick. i don't know about everybody else,'' vicki robinson said. ``there's no strike.''
the 2 percent raise averages $438 per employee annually, mayoral aide ed esposito said. he said the uniformed services got a 3 percent raise in the last fiscal year and raises totaling 8 percent over the past five years, he said
the city budget, approved monday night, includes appropriations for 165 policemen, 147 firefighters and 10 paramedics
police salaries range from $18,589 for a patrol officer at three years to $27,673 for a captain with 20 years' experience. firefighters pay ranges from $18,409 for a first-year firefighter to $27,673 for an assistant fire chief with 20 years' experience
