the strike stranded scores of passengers at larnaca airport
it came after the state-owned company placed a ban on overtime pay for cabin attendants
secretary of state george p. shultz today arranged to meet with two members of the palestine national council and discouraged americans from traveling to the israeli-held west bank and gaza
the travel advisory cited ``continuing disturbances'' in the areas. in nearly three months of palestinian protests, 111 palestinian arabs and an israeli soldier have been killed
we are not issuing am advisory for israel itself,'' phyllis oakley, the state department's deputy spokeswoman, said. ``israel is safe for american travel.''
shultz will hold the meeting with edward said, a professor at columbia university, and ibrahim abu-lughud, a professor at northwestern university, on saturday ``to discuss our approach to the middle east peace process,'' the announcement said
mrs. oakley stressed that said and abu-lughud are u.s. citizens. she said the 13-year-old u.s. policy of not dealing with the palestine liberation organization remained intact
there is no change in u.s. policy on negotiating with or recognizing the plo,'' she said. ``that policy remains as it has been since 1975.''
the council is the legislative arm of the plo. the brief announcement identified said and abu-lughud only as ``prominent americans with an intimate knowledge of contemporary middle eastern politics.''
the united states, in persuading israel to relinquish territory to egypt and syria, promised in 1975 it would not deal with the plo, which is committed to dismantling the jewish state. the pledge subsequently was incorporated into u.s. law
asked if the plo had given said and abu-lughud permission to meet with shultz, the u.s. official said, ``i have nothing on that.''
mrs. oakley said shultz initiated the meeting. ``he will discuss the palestinian point of view,'' she said. ``they have an intimate knowledge of middle eastern politics.''
the travel advisory cautioned americans to avoid going to the west bank and gaza ``until further notice.'' it said americans living there ``should exercise particular caution.''
the situation in east jerusalem, which was held by jordan until 1967 and is now part of israel's capital, was described as ``unpredictable.'' the advisory said americans should check with u.s. diplomats in the city before entering the area
under all circumstances, americans should avoid demonstrations and other situations that have the potential to lead to violence,'' the advisory said. ``american travelers should carry their u.s. passports at all times.''
moshe arad, the israeli ambassador, telephoned m. charles hill, an assistant to shultz, on thursday to protest the meeting as a violation of the pledge
said and abu-lughud could not be reached immediately to be asked what they intended to take up with shultz and whether they had sought plo approval for the meeting
earlier this year, shultz met here with two palestinians from the west bank and gaza. their visit was arranged with israel's cooperation
shultz had excluded the plo from his proposal to open arab-israeli negotiations on may 1. his plan calls for palestinians approved by the plo to participate in a joint delegation with jordan
during a mideast shuttle last month, shultz tried to arrange a meeting in jerusalem with 15 palestinian arabs. apparently under plo orders, none of them showed up
shultz went to a hotel in east jerusalem, stood in the floodlit courtyard and read a statement suggesting the palestinians were fearful of working with the united states
opportunity knocks loudly on your door,'' he said then. ``now is the time to get to work. we have a workable plan, and we are ready to commit our efforts to it. the time is right, together, to make decisions of historic proportions.''
some 1.5 million palestinian arabs live on the west bank of the jordan river and in gaza, along the mediterranean. the lands were held by jordan and egypt until they were lost to israel in the 1967 six-day war
the chief of libya's forces in chad has joined a group opposed to col. moammar gadhafi, the opposition group said friday
the national front for the salavation of libya reported the defection of col. khalifah abu el-kassem haftar, a participant in gadhafi's 1969 revolution against the libyan monarchy, in a statement distributed to cairo news agency offices
considered the strongest libyan exile opposition group, the national front's headquarters are in the egyptian capital
telephone calls to mohamed yusef al-magariaf, the front's secretary general and gadhafi's former libyan ambassador to india, went unanswered
the front statement quoted haftar as saying that hundreds of libyan officers in chad agree on ``the necessity to struggle together with their brothers in the nfsl ... to save the country from gadhafi's terrorist and dictatorial rule.''
the statement did not indicate where haftar is or say when he was supposed to have defected. a national front spokesman known by the nom de guerre abu el-nour said the man was a prisoner of war in chad before his defection
libyan claims to a large zone of northern chad along their border have been the object of a long-running war between the two north african nations. gadhafi backs rebel forces against the current central government in n'djamena
if the national front statements were true, haftar's defection apparently would be the first of such a high-ranking officer among libyan forces in chad. colonel, gadhafi's rank, is the highest attainable in the libyan armed forces
brake failure caused two passenger trains to collide head-on outside shanghai, killing 28 people and injuring 99, officials said friday
among the dead were 27 members of a japanese high school tour group
the two trains crashed head-on thursday in a shanghai suburb, crushing and derailing several front cars. about 400 rescue workers were dispatched to the scene
the crash injured 99 people, 17 of them seriously, the state-run xinhua news agency quoted officials as saying at a shanghai news conference
most of the survivors from the 193-member japanese tour group boarded a chartered plane in shanghai on friday night to return home. dozens of relatives of the japanese dead and injured, meanwhile, arrived in shanghai
xinhua quoted mu kaixiang, deputy director of the shanghai railway administration, as saying the no. 311 train from nanjing to hangzhou tried to halt at a station as scheduled
but its brakes failed and it continued 460 feet into the path of train no. 208 arriving from changsha. the driver of no. 208 applied his emergency brakes but was unable to prevent the collision, xinhua quoted mu as saying
both trains were moving slower than 25 mph, he said
the japanese students and teachers were in the two first-class cars of train no. 311, which were derailed and badly crushed
acting premier li peng sent a telegram to japanese prime minister noboru takeshita on friday expressing ``deep sympathy'' to the families of the japanese victims
japan's vice minister of foreign affairs, hamada takujiro, also arrived to take charge of arrangements for the japanese involved, xinhua said
the school group, which included 11 teachers and 182 students, had arrived in china on monday to visit shanghai and nearby hangzhou
the nationally televised evening news said rescue workers labored until 3 a.m. friday to free passengers trapped in the crushed cars
it showed the baggage car of one train resting partially on top of the other train's engine and passengers being passed out of train windows on stretchers
the collision, china's fourth fatal train accident this year, came one day before li convened a session of the legislature, the national people's congress, at which the railways ministry is expected to be reorganized
a derailment jan. 24 killed 88 people, a train collision on jan. 17 killed 19 and a train fire jan. 7 killed 34
railways minister ding guangen resigned this month in disgrace because of the earlier train crashes, and no replacement has been appointed
a jury awarded two nurseries $1.5 million to cover losses to their citrus stock during the 1984 canker scare in a case that could set precedent
a circuit jury returned its verdict thursday night in a trial to set damages
mallory horne, representing the state department of agriculture and consumer services, had argued that $600,000 would be a fair settlement for the loss of 280,000 trees at mid-florida growers inc. and himrod &amp; himrod citrus nurseries
the nurseries had received $248,000 from the state and federal governments as compensation after their stock was destroyed. that amount will be deducted from the $1.5 million judgment
richard polk has a similar suit pending for the destruction of 510,000 trees
statewide, more than 20 million nursery-stock or newly planted trees were burned after inspectors discovered what they thought was a virulent strain of incurable citrus canker in august 1984. it later was found to be a much less threatening form of disease and some nursery owners sued, claiming the burning unnecessary
the florida supreme court determined that state officials acted properly to protect the state's multibillion-dollar industry, but ruled that owners should receive full compensation for destroyed propery
pete packett, spokesman for the florida department of agriculture, said friday he expected the state to appeal
police seized 880 pounds of cocaine worth about $45 million and arrested 12 people friday in what they described as the largest seizure of the drug in european history
authorities believe the find could be linked to the ``cartel de medellin'' ring of colombia, the alleged supplier of 80 percent of the cocaine to the u.s. market, according to madrid drug enforcement chief florentino gomez
among the suspects arrested in madrid were four colombians, three ecuadorians and a spanish woman. the others were not identified
police on friday were still gathering the drug hidden inside prefabricated housing panels inside a warehouse in the madrid suburb of fuenlabrada. the total weight of the seizure could eventually surpass 880 pounds, gomez said
gomez said the seizure capped an eight-month investigation. authorities made a breakthrough when they tracked a container sent from ecuador to the port of barcelona, which was later trucked east to the fuenlabrada warehouse, he said
the chief of the national plan to combat drugs, miguel solans, said the drug haul represented a major blow to international drug traffickers. mainly south americans dealers have converted spain into a gateway to the european drug market
on nov. 11, british and dutch drug agents claimed the previous largest seizure in europe after they found 550 pounds of cocaine aboard a colombian freighter in britain
an attempt by townspeople to protect mating salamanders from being killed by cars was thwarted when all but one of the amphibians ignored tunnels installed for them beneath a busy street
the 50 people who turned out in drizzle thursday night to watch the first salamander crossing of the year ended up barricading the street and carrying about 40 of the yellow-spotted salamanders across to a breeding pond
the animals spend the winter hibernating in woods and try to reach the pond every spring with the first warm rain
shouts went up when one salamander was discovered crawling along a fence leading to one of the tunnels under henry street. the salamander made it through in five minutes, 20 seconds, said shutesbury teacher ken lindsay
it was an historic event,'' lindsay said friday. ``it was the first salamander to go through a tunnel all on its own.''
the world's first salamander tunnels were installed after a public outcry over the amphibians' plight
many salamanders faced certain death when they slithered across the road. local naturalist robert winston persuaded town selectmen to close the street last year until all the salamanders, members of the mole salamander family, made the trek, which usually takes a week
the salamanders are not on the state's endangered species list, although the henry street population is the last in town
the three 19-inch-high tunnels were donated by aco polymer products of cleveland and installed in november for about $2,000. volunteers erected fences in january to guide the salamanders to the tunnels
the fences failed their first test, but townspeople said it was too early to tell how the whole experiment would fare
lindsay said there were very few salamanders out thursday night
winston's wife, janet, said the salamanders may have changed their usual migration pattern to start at a spot beyond the fence
lindsay said they might have been hibernating between the fence and the road. richard minear, chairman of the board of selectmen, said the tunnels might not be wet enough for the discriminating amphibians
in any event, the salamanders took townspeople by surprise, said mrs. winston, one of the flashlight-toting helpers at the crossing. ``they came a little sooner than we were quite prepared for,'' she said
the town's superintendent of public works said he hadn't yet hung the ``salamander crossing'' signs designed by shutesbury fourth-grader rachel mackintosh. c.</note>
faced with a financial crisis, legislators are on the verge of handing gov. buddy roemer more power than any louisiana chief executive has had since the days of huey long
bills nearing passage in a special session would give roemer authority to slash spending and close state institutions, and state agencies would be free to hike fees without public hearing or legislative review
another bill would permit the state to float bonds to pay off an operating debt that has grown to $1.3 billion since 1982
all of them just say `give it to the governor and ' we may as well have passed just one bill and said the legislature is hereby abolished,'' said c.w. ``bill'' rlet him decide.oberts, a top aide to former gov. edwin w. edwards
roemer took office march 15. edwards decided to retire after three terms rather than contest a runoff election against the former congressman
at the beginning of a 10-day special session on monday, roemer said the state was in a ``terrifying financial crisis'' and asked for temporary authority to slash spending until the legislature meets in regular session april 18
roemer said the state faces a $210 mia much less threatening form of disease and some nursery owners sued, claiming the burning unnecessary
the florida supreme court determined that state officials acted properly to protect the state's multibillion-dollar industry, but ruled that owners should receive full compensation for destroyed propery
