it's a big silly gold chain,'' he said, adding he hopes to have it melted down. ``i hope it's worth more than $905.'' rages</head>
the toddler who was trapped for 58 hours in an abandoned well celebrates her second birthday saturday without the cameras and reporters that greeted her rescue last fall
jessica mcclure and her parents, reba and chip, plan a quiet observance at home, said a spokesman, pete snelson of midland
but a controversy between rival associations of rescuers over telling the tale for televison is far from quiet
the rescuers were among more than 200 firefighters, law enforcement officers, cave explorers, construction workers, drillers, welders and others who worked for three days to free jessica from the 8-inch well shaft
personally, i hope it doesn't get to the point where you're embarrassed to say you were involved in the rescue,'' said richard galle, a caver who assisted at the well site
galle, odessa's recreation superintendent, handled climbing harnesses for dusty workers who repeatedly descended a newly dug parallel shaft and bored horizontally through solid rock to reach the girl, 22 feet down
the two rescuers' groups _ one mostly volunteers and the other city officials and employees _ are negotiating separately with producers for a television movie
the jessica mcclure rescuer's association, a group of more than 30 volunteers, is committed to a movie deal with los angeles producer larry spivey, president of highland communications group inc. the group has asked all rescuers to join them
kragg robinson, the association's president, said members have signed a contract that includes an initial $200,000, plus future payments, to be divided among the members. spivey has yet to negotiate a deal with a network
the other group, the mcclure rescue association, comprises 11 municipal officials and has not yet committed to work with a producer
the rescuers' gatherings started calmly enough. some, in the spirit of solidarity and friendship, agreed to meet regularly for reunions and an informal group was created, said david lilly, a new mexico mining expert
jessica's parents have not yet signed any movie agreements, said snelson
it's a beautiful, heart-warming story'' that needs to be told in the right way, he said. the mcclures are ``appreciative of everyone and haven't measured one group against the other.''
police cpl. jim white, a member of the municipal workers' group, said its members harbor no animosity toward the volunteers' association
we just don't agree on movie producers,'' said white
ashland oil inc. says it will dismantle a 3.4 million-gallon petroleum storage tank it was building with 18-year-old steel at an ohio river terminal
ashland stopped construction on the tank jan. 6, just four days after a 4 million-gallon tank built with 40-year-old steel collapsed at its terminal in jefferson, 27 miles south of pittsburgh on the monongahela river. about 730,000 gallons of diesel fuel spilled into the monongahela and ohio rivers
ashland spokesman roger schrum said the company decided to tear down the tank, which was 90 percent completed, because ``we decided we didn't want to use a used tank at that location.''
dismantling will begin within a week, he said
skinner tank co. of yale, okla., which erected the failed tank in jefferson, was reassembling the tank in midland. the partially erected tank, 56.5 feet tall and 100 feet in diameter, is about 1,000 yards from the ohio river in a tank farm purchased from pennzoil inc. about a year ago, the company said
the tank was being constructed with steel from a shell oil co. tank built in cincinnati in 1970. it was one of 11 tanks, and one of two that were to be reconstructed from used steel, ashland planned to build at the midland terminal. schrum said construction had not begun on the other tanks
we still have plans to build a good, first-class terminal in midland, but we still haven't totally decided how many tanks we will build up there,'' he said thursday
schrum said the company's report on the jefferson tank collapse, and one being done at ashland's expense by the battelle institute, won't be completed for several more weeks
a judge ruled that 80 children held by a masked gunman last month at a private school will not have to testify at a preliminary hearing next week
an attorney for james harvey jr., charged with 84 counts of kidnapping in the daylong ordeal, had sought to subpoena the west end christian school pupils for tuesday's preliminary hearing
at a brief hearing thursday, district attorney charles freeman accused defense attorney michael cornwell of trying to ``create a circus atmosphere.''
cornwell said the prosecutor ``is trying to create a lynch-mob atmosphere.''
i think some people have concluded that mr. harvey is guilty and all this is a waste of time,'' cornwell said. ``thelevision and read the papers. everybody knows he's guilty.''
harvey is expected to be bound over to a tuscaloosa county grand jury at next week's hearing.y saw him on te
harvey and another man, both wearing ski masks, allegedly entered the tuscaloosa school feb. 2 and took the 80 pupils and four teachers hostage
the other man, john rhodes, gave up a few hours later and charges eventually were dropped against him when authorities determined he had been tricked into the abduction
twelve hours after the ordeal began, harvey laid down his weapons and was arrested after watching a videotape of gov. guy hunt signing a phony pcouch-potato economy'' that will be marked by low unemployment, more savings and rising productivity, economists and population experts say
the dawning of a couch-potato economy is the best thing that could happen to the united states after years of yuppie splurging, says edward yardeni, the economist who coined the term
yuppies are slowing down. we're all getting older, a little less frivolous,'' yardeni, 38, director of economics and fixed-income research for prudential-bache securities inc., said this past week
exhibit no. 1 in yardeni's case is the shift noted last year in consumer-spending priorities after the go-go years of 1985 and 1986
in 1985, the two fastest-growing segments were brokerage and investment fees and audio and video equipment
in 1986, the leaders were boats and recreational vehicles
in 1987, america seemed to turn suddenly sedentary. books and maps finished first, followed closely by funeral and burial expenses
the numbers from the commerce department may be misleading because the biggest percentage risers are small segments that fluctuate widely, but yardeni is convinced that they tell a story
i'm not promising you that the transformation definitely happened in '87,'' but something is afoot, yardeni said
he said the shift could point to an increased savings rate. ``and that should leave room for a boom in exports and a boom in capital spending. which is not a bad mix at all.''
one reason for japan's extraordinary success is its high savings rate, which creates a pool of money for investment
trailing behind the american baby boomers is the ``baby-bust'' generation _ the smaller complement of workers that is entering the work force now
there are too few qualified baby busters to fill all the entry-level jobs. but yardeni optimistically sees a positive side to that: it will force business to find ways to automate more, he says, increasing the nation's productivity
yardeni's ideas are supported by others, including cheryl russell, editor-in-chief of american demographics magazine in ithaca, n.y
as baby boomers settle down, they are beginning to put aside money for their children's education and their own retirement, ms. russell said
but baby boomers will still be spending, too, something that is good news for producers of consumer goods
baby boomers are entering their peak earnings years, so they will be able to spend more and save more at the same time,'' ms. russell said
in spite of the free-spending reputation of the young, ms. russell said, households headed by people aged 35 and over lead their juniors in every broad category of spending except two: alcohol and rented dwellings
the mix of spending is what is changing. couch potatoes spend less money on movie tickets, more on things like vcrs. and, of course, couches
the changing habits of the nation are more than a myth. the roper organization last year reported a poll finding that more than half of people over 30 prefer doing things at home, while more than half of people under 30 prefer doing things outside the home
the median age in the united states is rising, ms. russell notes, and it has just passed 30
everyone's tired,'' said thomas miller, 30, editor of the public pulse, a roper newsletter. ``some peole call it the cocooning phenomenon. some people call it the couch-potato economy. we think it's mainly exhaustion.'' report says</head>
thirty-six states have established ``rainy day'' funds as a hedge against economic downturns, although seven states have put no money in them and most of the rest haven't put in enough to deal with serious financial troubles, a report issued friday said
two of the states, alaska and wyoming, both suffering from the drop in energy prices, actually have drawn upon those reserves to avoid deep spending cuts and to keep their budgets balanced, the report said
that proves the funds are working,'' said raymond scheppach, executive director of the national governors' association
the association, along with the national association of state budget officers, put together the report on the financial condition of the 50 states, ``fiscal survey of the states.''
in general, the report found that most states tightened their budget belts last year and are reluctant to start major new programs this year because of uncertainty about the economy
states such as louisiana and west virgina are facing tough financial times because of their reliance on the troubled energy industry. but the majority of states are in sound health, the report said
still, that figure belies the fact that most states are close to the financial edge. the report found that the majority of states will end the year with only small budget balances. those balances are expected to fall to 1.5 percent of total expenditures at the end of next fiscal year, the lowest level since the recession of 1983, when it was 1.3 percent
california and new jersey, both with booming economies, are among the handful of states expecting to end the next fiscal year with large balances. california is projecting a $1.1 billion balance and new jersey, $231 million
louisiana, on the other hand, is the only state forecasting a deficit at the end of next fiscal year _ an estimated $731 million
the report also found that some states are putting money aside into contingency funds instead of counting unspent dollars as end-of-the-year balances. such reserves are a relatively recent phenomenon, formed to buffer state finances from the disruptions of an uneven economy, the report said
but the funds, overall, are small. at the end of last fiscal year, the reserves totaled $2 billion, or just under 1 percent of expenditures, the report said. the amount of money in the reserves is expected to increase slightly to $2.3 billion at the end of this fiscal year, but that still will equal just 1 percent of expenditures
clearly,'' the report said, ``small reserves can help relieve less serious fiscal conditions, but states will still be unprepared for an extended economic downturn.''
seven of the states have yet to put money into their reserves: alaska, idaho, iowa, utah, virginia, washington and wisconsin, the report said
the other 29 states that have established such reserves are california, colorado, connecticut, delaware, florida, georgia, indiana, kentucky, louisiana (which refers to its program as a deficit elimination fund), maine, maryland, massachusetts, michigan, minnesota, mississippi, missouri, nebraska, nevada, new hampshire, new mexico, new york, ohio, oklahoma, pennsylvania, rhode island, south carolina, tennessee, vermont and wyoming
new jersey and hawaii are considering creating a ``rainy day'' fund
most states expect little fallout from last october's stock market collapse, although florida, washington, tennessee and new york are planning for revenue losses
the report found that the economic picture generally differs by region, with new england in a strong financial position. one measure of its strength was its unemployment rate, which averaged 3.4 percent in 1987, far below the national rate of 6.2 percent
the mideast also boasts a strong economy, while recessions in the midwestern farm states and western energy states seem to have bottomed out, the report said. in the south, the economic picture is mixed, with some states, like florida, north carolina and virginia, experiencing strong growth and louisiana, west virginia and kentucky facing economic hard times
rep. james howard, d-n.j., chairman of the house public works committee, died today, a day after suffering a heart attack while playing golf, his office said
howard, 60, a 22-year house veteran, collapsed thursday on a suburban maryland golf course, according to his office. his staff said he suffered a heart attack and cardiac arest
doctors labored for nearly two hours to start the spring lake heights, n.j., lawmaker breathing on his own after the attack . howard had not regained consciousness since he was stricken
howard, who had suffered two previous heart attacks, was revived by doctors at montgomery general hospital in olney, md. he was then rushed by helicopter to the sophisticated cardiac unit at the hospital center here
a former wall township schoolteacher and principal, howard has been in congress since 1965. he is the second most senior member of the new jersey congressional delegation after rep. peter rodino, who has announced he will not run for re-election this year
pope john paul ii stressed the value of celibacy in a letter sent to priests worldwide and released by the vatican on friday
the analogy between the church and the virgin mother has a special eloquence for us, who link our priestly vocation to celibacy, that is, to making ourselves eunuchs for the sake of heaven,'' the pope said in his annual holy week message to priests
in the past, the pope has washed the feet of 12 men in a holy thursday service to re-enact christ's last supper with his apostles, who are considered the first priests of the roman catholic church
telling priests that their lives are the ``equivalent'' of ``spiritual fatherhood'' because the church has a special relationship with the virgin mary, the mother of jesus, the pope wrote: ``on holy thursday we need to deepen once again this mysterious truth of our vocation....''
the pope urged priests to turn to mary for guidance in keeping their vocation, saying, ``it is necessary that our priestly choice of celibacy for the whole of our lives should also be placed within her heart.''
john paul encouraged priests to ``seek also a proper relationship with women.'' as examples, he cited how jesus showed compassion to an adultress who was on the verge of being stoned by a crowd. he asked the spectators, according to the gospel of john, ``let him who is without sin ... be the first to cast a stone upon her.''
he noted also that jesus first conveyed the ``easter good news of his resurrection'' to women who had come to his tomb
by reason of his vocation and service, the priest must discover in a new way the question of the dignity and vocation of women both in the church and in today's world.''
the pope did not elaborate on what a church vocation could mean for women, who are barred from the priesthood. `desecration''</head>
edgar m. bronfman, president of the world jewish congress, on friday condemned the payment voted by austria's parliament to compensate victims of nazism as ``a desecration.''
the decision to grant between $200 and $400 to each victim ``represents a desecration of the memory of the victims of the holocaust at the very moment of austria's reflection on the 50th anniversary of its union with nazi germany,'' bronfman said
the parliament in vienna voted overwhelmingly wednesday to pay a one-time sum of $4 million to victims of nazism
some 68,000 austrian jews died in nazi concentration camps during world war ii, and more than 120,000 others were incarcerated in camps or fled the country. in all, the nazis exterminated some 6 million jews
bronfman's statement noted that the austrian decision was in marked contrast to west germany's 1952 agreement to compensate the victims of nazism for life with monthly reparation payments
the world jewish congress, based in new york, has been at the forefront of a two-year campaign to expose the nazi past of austrian president kurt waldheim. ``the recent attention focused on kurt waldheim's nazi past has exploded the long-held myth that austria was a victim of nazi persecution rather than its very willing collaborator,'' bronfman said
a team of international historians found that waldheim was implicated in nazi persecution while serving as an officer in the german army during world war ii. that some facing death penalty. no pickup.</note>
