the federal reserve board's index measuring the value of the dollar against 10 other currencies weighted on the basis of trade was 89.37 friday, off 0.10 points or off 0.11 percent from thursday's 89.47. a year ago the index was 98.31
late closing prices as of 3:00 p.m. eastern time as gathered by first american bank of new york
c-commercial rate, f-financial rate, y-official rate, z-floating rate, r-revised
varryl thomas says her family had two choices: ``it was either come here to st. tammany and live in a tent or stay in new orleans and live in the streets.''
st. tammany gave the family an unexpected third choice _ to move the tent because it was violating sanitation and building codes
however, the deputy who ordered them to move put them in touch with a church, which is helping them find a home
we have no relatives around here and didn't know anybody,'' mrs. thomas said. ``we had no place to go. my husband's disabled and i don't have a job. if it wasn't for the churches, we would be some pitiful people.''
the thomases' problems began in new orleans about a month ago, when the house they were living in was sold. they'd been living rent-free in exchange for watching the property, mrs. thomas said
we didn't have enough money to rent a new house,'' she said. ``rent there is about $175. plus you have to have that much more for a damage deposit and more money for utility deposits.''
they took their $277 monthly welfare check and every penny they could scrape up and made a $200 down payment on a 75-by-125-foot lot in a subdivision near madisonville
last weekend, they loaded their belongings in plastic garbage bags, put them on a small pickup truck and drove across the causeway to their new lot. several of the bags blew into lake pontchartrain on the way over
that didn't help matters,'' larry thomas said
their 9-by-12-foot tent made it, however. the family improvised an outhouse from a blue tarpaulin over a hole in the ground
the couple and their children _ benjamin, 4, alaster, 5, and luwana, 6 _ planned to live there until they could afford to build a small house
we didn't know we weren't supposed to put up a tent on the lot,'' mrs. thomas said. ``we were told the only thing you couldn't put on the lot was a trailer.''
after learning the family's plight, the st. tammany parish sheriff's deputy who ordered them to move called st. anselm catholic church in madisonville. deacon philip baham put the family up in a motel for the rest of the weekend and found them a house in covington, mrs. thomas said
the church paid $100 for a month's rent and the covington food bank and the vincentian center in covington gave the family food, said food bank manager beverly sharp
mrs. thomas said the family paid $200 down and $125 in closing costs for the $9,500 lot. the 17-year mortgage was to be paid at $95 a month
we were going to try to pay it out of our welfare check, i guess. and i was hoping to find a job,'' mrs. thomas said
sharp said the vincentian center is trying to find a job for mrs. thomas, who has worked as an auto mechanic
but i'll do anything at all,'' mrs. thomas said. ``i'm not choosy about a job. i went to three places today, but they didn't have any openings.''
a shy ``caveman'' with a toy gun and a man who allegedly drove him to stickups and ordered him to hide in the cave are suspected of at least 16 robberies, police said friday
joseph e. steffani, 24, of oakland, was lured from his cave by undercover officers who promised him cigarettes and a hot meal, then arrested him, said sgt. robert chenault
he looked like grizzly adams without the long beard,'' said chenault. ``he wore an old ragged jacket, dirty pants and sneakers and he smelled pretty bad.''
kenneth hawtin, 37, of el cerrito, who steffani claims took him to the robberies and told him to stay in the cave, also was arrested for the robberies that netted a total of about $1,500 since march 7, chenault said
hawtin would drive steffani to the places they would rob, convenience stores, florist shops, ice cream parlors and liquor stores, easy places to hit,'' chenault said. ``steffani would walk in, throw a bag on the counter, say `this is a stickup,' show the gun in his belt and tell them to fill the bag.''
no one was hurt in any of the holdups
we didn't believe it at first when we heard a caveman was pulling these robberies,'' chenault said. ``but it turned out to be true.''
in an apparent suicide attempt, hawtin stuck a key into an electrical outlet in a police interview room thursday after admitting his involvement in the robberies, chenault said. he was knocked unconscious and was hospitalized overnight for observation
steffani and hawtin also were being treated for heroin and cocaine addiction, chenault said. steffani told police he's been addicted to the tranquilizer valium since he was 14 and was afraid to be around people without the drug
hawtin and steffani split the money from the robberies, chenault said, and apparently used it to buy drugs
police said hawtin befriended steffani last christmas and lived with him in el cerrito until last week, when he took steffani to the cave above the tiny town of canyon
only a few friends knew of steffani's hiding place, said sgt. dan mercado. they and hawtin would drive to the area with food and supplies and honk their horns
steffani would come out of his hiding place, see who it was and either ``get the things or run back into the bushes and hide,'' mercado said
mercado said police were tipped off by an informant. undercover officers went to arrest steffani late wednesday night and honked their horn. at first, mercado said, all the officers could see was ``eyes in the bushes.''
steffani eventually gave up without a struggle. hawtin was arrested the next day, and a plastic replica handgun allegedly used in the robberies was found in his car, chenault said. subs pvs 3rd graf from end, ``a senior,'' with 2 grafs to update with reagan, balaguer comments</note>
the senate, voting 92-0, urged president reagan on friday to increase u.s. economic pressure against panamanian military strongman manuel antonio noriega as part of a campaign to drive him from office
the unanimous vote was intended to demonstrate noreiga has lost all u.s. support
the non-binding resolution also urged the white house to consider ``a comprehensive package of emergency financial and other economic assistance'' to help a democratic successor government rebuild panama's economy
an administration official, speaking on condition he not be identified, said, ``we have been aware of the senate resolution for days and consider it to be completely complementary to u.s. policy in panama.''
the impression in all our minds is that noriega must go,'' said sen. claiborne pell, d-r.i., chairman of the senate foreign relations committee
he will go, and this will help him down the slippery slope,'' pell said
to gen. noriega, we say step aside now, while you still have the chance _ for your own sake and for your family''s future,'' said sen. edward m. kennedy, d-mass., a principal sponsor of the resolution
the resolution declared that noriega's military rule and his alleged involvement in large-scale international drug running and money laundering represent ``an unusual and extraordinary threat to the national security, foreign policy and economy of the united states.''
but senators stressed that any action the united states takes against noreiga is in response to the direct request of president eric arturo devalle, who was ousted as panama's chief executive on feb. 25 after trying unsuccessfully to remove noriega as head of the panamanian defense force
this battle is going to be won or lost by the panamanian people,'' kennedy said. ``but i think it is important that in this struggle they know where the united states stands.''
several senators urged noriega to reconsider his refusal of a justice department offer not to seek his extradition for trial on u.s. narcotics-trafficking charges if he gives up power and goes into exile in spain
noriega needs to know that offer is not good forever _ and that he will not be free to pursue his sordid activities without fear of paying the consequences,'' said sen. david durenberger, r-minn
if he thinks this is the end of it _ if he feels this is all we are going to do _ he'd better think again,'' said sen. jesse helms, r-n.c. ``this is a man who is a symbol for destroying liberty.''
among the options available to the united states is the imposition of a total trade embargo against panama, a step the administration has resisted in favor of a more measured, incremental approach
many members of congress originally called for such action before joining forces behind the resolution approved friday
after two federal grand juries in florida charged noriega with multimillion-dollar drug trafficking and money laundering, president reagan cut off the flow of u.s. dollars to panama
panama uses dollars as its own currency and the move paralyzed the panamanian banking system
before meeting in the oval office with dominican president joaquin balaguer on friday, reagan was asked whether noriega might seek exile in the dominican republic
no,'' he replied. ``that's not far enough.''
reagan, asked about the senate resolution at a departure ceremony for balaguer, said, ``we're considering everything, but i can't take any questions.''
balaguer said in an interview with the voice of america that he would grant asylum to noriega if asked
meanwhile, the federal agency for international development has agreed to release $250,000 in emergency funds to buy food for the poor in panama
the food will be purchased in panama if it is available and distributed through caritas, a roman catholic relief agency, said aid spokesman jim kunder
there will be no organized union boost behind a single candidate in saturday's democratic caucuses in michigan, a state where union members can wield more clout than almost anywhere else
while national labor leaders are assuming michael dukakis will be the eventual nominee, they are prevented from endorsing him by what appears to be growing rank-and-file support for jesse jackson, who has gotten more union votes than any of the other candidates in primaries so far. richard gephardt also has considerable union support
none of the democratic candidates appears to have won the hearts _ or votes _ of a majority of the state's 750,000 rank-and-file union workers, nearly half of them members of the united auto workers
afl-cio president lane kirkland has held out the possibility of an endorsement before the democratic national convention in july if it appears that two-thirds of the labor federation's 14.2 million members have agreed on a favorite
so far they haven't. exit polls from the march 8 southern primaries showed jackson holding the greatest support among union members at 37 percent, followed by dukakis at 25 percent
there's not going to be an endorsement before the covention,'' communications workers of america president morton bahr, who also is an afl-cio vice president, said this week
despite uaw president owen bieber's known affection for gephardt, the union itself has carefully maintained an official position of neutrality in accord with afl-cio guidelines
so have the other big unions in michigan _ the teamsters with 72,000 members, the american federation of state, county and municipal employees with 60,000, the service employees with 27,000 and the united steel workers with 24,000
but that ``neutrality'' by the international unions hasn't prevented their former leaders and the hundreds of local union officers in michigan from taking sides
bill marshall, former president of the michigan state labor federation, endorsed gephardt on friday. former uaw president doug fraser endorsed dukakis earlier this month
it's kind of schizophrenic, said jon ogar, a spokeman for the michigan state labor federation. ``most of the unions here have people in everybody's camp.''
afscme, for example, is running separate sets of get-out-the-vote phone banks on behalf of both dukakis, the clear favorite of their national leaders, and jackson, who has the endorsement of the union's top officials in detroit and michigan
half the presidents of the 40 locals representing about 85 percent of the communications workers of america's 20,000 members in the state have endorsed dukakis. but the other 20 locals appear equally divided between jackson and gephardt
i personally came out for gephardt but i've taken a lot of heat for it because he supported president reagan's tax law,'' said robert shukwit, president of cwa local 4008 in detroit
but i don't think we've seen the candidate yet,'' shukwit added, indicating a lingering dream among many trade unionists that new york gov. mario cuomo might emerge as an alternative
meanwhile, the uaw remains the most important labor voice in michigan. and it has taken several steps to dissociate itself from the endorsement its 10,000 members in iowa gave gephardt in february
for example, the union is running tv commercials in michigan stressing a need for an activist government. prior to the iowa caucuses, it ran ads in that state focusing on the trade issue gephardt has championed
one uaw official, speaking on the condition of anonymity, said bieber, the union's president, probably believes dukakis is going to be the nominee and doesn't want to stir trouble with him
at the same time, endorsing dukakis would infuriate jackson loyalists among blacks, about 25 percent of the uaw's membership, and arabs, a large contingent of its ford workers in dearborn, the official said
nonetheless, another union official predicted that gephardt will fare much better in saturday's caucuses than he has in polls over the past two weeks in the state, which has lost 400,000 union jobs to imports since 1982. that official mentioned an internal poll showing gephardt holding a narrow lead over jackson with dukakis a distant third among union members
a high-ranking official indicated friday that israel might take action if the united states fails to deal with long-range chinese missiles sold to saudi arabia
other officials, however, denied that israel was considering an attack on the arab kingdom
israel has a tradition of not standing by quietly when there is a real threat against it,'' said yossi ben-aharon, a senior aide to prime minister yitzhak shamir. ``the question is if this is a threat or not. there are people to deal with it, the cabinet, the government.''
saudi arabia recently acquired the css-2 missiles, which have a range of 2,200 miles, enough to strike anywhere in the middle east. they also are capable of carrying nuclear warheads
both the chinese and the saudis said the missiles won't be armed with such warheads, and saudi arabia has said it purchased the weapons to deter attacks on its territory during the iran-iraq war
but israel radio reported friday that saudi arabia issued a warning through the united states that it would use any remaining missiles to strike at the jewish state if israel attempted a pre-emptive strike
ben-aharon said the issue should be left for u.s. officials, ``who told us they are going to deal with the matter the best they can, both in china and in saudi arabia.''
the washington post quoted u.s. intelligence sources as saying the israeli air force has been conducting unusually intensive low-lewel bombing practice. it said such runs could be preparation for a strike on saudi arabia, though there was no hard evidence to support that interpretation
the paper also noted that such exercises could help israel prepare for raids on palestinian targets in lebanon
shamir's spokesman, avi pazner, denied that israel had made any threats. ``we did take up our concern with the united states. but we never made any threat against saudi arabia,'' he said
earlier reports of a similar ben-aharon statement sparked strong warnings from egypt and syria, and the u.s. state department expressed concern
the syrian government said monday that ``any agression against the sister saudi arabian kingdom would obviously be an attack against syria.''
egypt's president hosni mubarak said he sent an urgent message to president reagan asking him to ``use his influence with israel and urge it to stop threatening arab states in such irresponsible way.''
egypt is the only arab country to have peace treaty with israel
an israeli official who demanded anonymity said syria and egypt were ``overreacting to a report that has been denied.''
the official said israel was going to mount a diplomatic campaign to ``take the missiles out,'' but stressed that ``we never made any threat to take them out militarily.''
the united states will stage its biannual ``ocean venture'' exercise during april with more than 40,000 servicemen participating, the pentagon said friday
the exercise will be staged in the atlantic ocean, gulf of mexico and caribbean sea as well as at selected bases in florida and puerto rico, the pentagon said. it will begin on april 1 and extend through april 22
ocean venture exercises are held every two years and are designed to demonstrate the joint forces capability of the u.s. atlantic command to rapidly project military power,'' the pentagon said
ocean venture 88 will exercise command-and-control of participating forces; their rapid deployment and employment, as well as the integration of military reserve units into the active force.''
the exercise will include aircraft carrier operations; airborne, amphibious and infantry assaults; live-fire exercises, and port security, harbor defense and combat search and rescue drills, the pentagon said
it added that ``members of the dutch royal marines from the netherlands antilles will also participate in this exercise.''
moslem countries ended an international conference friday by denouncing an absent iran for riots last year in mecca and for refusing to sign a cease-fire in its war with iraq
iran's delegation to the organization of islamic conference in amman had stormed out of the five-day meeting thursday. it complained that the 46-member conference was only serving the interests of iraq, its enemy in the 7{-year-old persian gulf war
the foreign ministers and other officials of moslem nations worldwide, in their final communique, lamented what they called ``terrorism'' by iranian rioters in saudi arabia in july, according to jordanian foreign minister taher masri. they also praised saudi measures, announced thursday, to control future disorders
the rioting occurred as saudis tried to stop iranian pilgrims at the holy city of mecca from marching in a political demonstration. the violence left 402 people dead, including 275 iranians and 80 saudi security men
the moslem nations specifically approved the saudis' decision to set limits on the number of pilgrims traveling to mecca and medina this year
masri, who chaired the final session of the gathering, said the conference also agreed to ``make extensive efforts to force the united nations to take the necessary measures to force iran to accept'' u.n. security council resolution 598. that document calls for a cease-fire in the iran-iraq war and a return to international borders
iraq has agreed, but iran says it first wants its enemy branded as the aggressor
iran, a mainly persian nation, has often been the target of criticisms from arab lands
the conference also:
_ declared its support for palestinian protests in the israeli-occupied territories. however, no specific action was given
_ welcomed soviet leader mikhail gorbachev's offer to pull troops out of afghanistan and called for it to be put into effect immediately
_ asked non-islamic countries with moslem populations, such as bulgaria, to take steps to guarantee the rights of the minorities
_ withheld full recognition of moslem rebels from the philippines who are fighting the manila government
sen. bob dole, saying ``i can read the numbers and i know probably what's going to happen,'' conceded friday that his uphill race against vice president george bush for the republican presidential nomination appears doomed
in downbeat comments that departed from his prepared text, the senator from kansas, who has 178 delegates to bush's 788 in the latest associated press tally, told the u.s. chamber of commerce: ``i think it's probably a foregone conclusion what's happening on the republican side.''
however, a dole spokesman later said the candidate isn't ready to abandon the race
dole himself suggested he was re-evaluating his campaign
whatever happens in the next few days or the next few weeks, i still have some things i want to say,'' dole told the business group, which gave him a standing ovation
i intend to be a leader in my party. whatever the role may be, it will be a role of leadership, constructive leadership, keeping the white house republican,'' dole added
speaking with reporters afterward, dole gave a clear indication that, at the very least, he would scale back his campaign appearances
i said i had a different strategy, and i think you're seeing some of it,'' he said
asked about his change in tone and comments that bush's gop victory seemed a ``foregone conclusion,'' dole told reporters:
i can read the numbers and i know probably what's going to happen.''
after finishing first in the iowa republican caucuses feb. 8, dole lost a series of gop events to bush, including a defeat in the new hampshire primary feb. 16 and losses in the big round of primaries and caucuses on super tuesday march 8
despite his poor showings, dole had vowed to press ahead with his campaign
but on friday he told reporters:
my view is that there's some things i want to say in this campaign and i think sometimes if you're not out there making four or five stops a day, people are more apt to listen.''
asked if these were things he planned to say on his way out of the race, dole said, ``no. i'm not going out. i'm just going out of here,'' meaning the building where he had been speaking
walt riker, a dole spokesman, later said that despite dole's comments, ``we haven't made any official announcements'' on a dole withdrawal from the race
his hallmark is his candor, and today's statement reflects that,'' riker said. ``we're the underdog, the big underdog. we've never said anything different about that. we know the numbers and we know what the score is.''
but that doesn't mean we have to give up. we have to re-evaluate the campaign day by day,'' riker said
when dole was asked by reporters whether he planned to push on at least to the wisconsin primary on april 5, he replied: ``i may tell you that later this week, probably next week.''
in his remarks to the chamber of commerce, dole opened on a pessimistic note. ``i've been saying now for some time as a candidate all the things i thought we should focus on and nobody really seems to care,'' he said
but i still have some things to say,'' he added. ``lo and behold, as your candidacy weakens, you find more people willing to listen.''
dole told the business audience that ``it's going to be a tough race'' for republicans this year and it was time for the party to pull together
we need to keep a republican in the white house. that's where i'm coming from. and if it can't be me, it will be george bush,'' he said
i'm not here in a partisan sense. i'm not going to attack any republican,'' he added
turning to congressional races, dole said: ``if i can count, the next president of the united states will be dealing with a democratic congress.''
he told his audience that the federal budget deficit, $150 billion last year, was ``public enemy no. 1'' and reiterated his proposal for a one-year across-the-board freeze on all federal spending
a strong earthquake occurred in canada's northwest territories friday and was felt over a wide area of canada, the u.s. geological survey said
the tremor was recorded at a preliminary magnitude of 6.2 on the richter scale and occurred at 12:37 p.m. mst. usgs earthquake monitors in golden, colo., said seismographs placed the center of the earthquake about 320 miles west of yellowknife, the capital of the northwest territories
early reports said the tremor was felt over a wide area, including at yellowknife; at whitehorse, the capital of the yukon territory; and at edmonton, the capital of alberta province
usgs scientists said two other strong earthquakes occurred in the same general area late in 1985: a magnitude 6.6 tremor oct. 5 and a magnitude 6.9 earthquake two days before christmas on dec. 23
the richter scale is an open-ended gauge of energy released by an earthquake as measured by ground motion recorded on a seismograph. every increase of one number means that the ground motion is 10 times greater
a quake with a magnitude of 4 can cause moderate damage in a populated area, a quake of magnitude 5 considerable damage, a magnitude 6 quake severe damage, one of magnitude 7 widespread, heavy damage and a magnitude 8 quake, a ``great'' earthquake capable of tremendous damage
a quake of magnitude 2 is the smallest normally felt by humans
the reagan administration launched a final attempt friday to overturn a 46-year-old law that prohibits manufacturers from hiring people to produce apparel in their homes
the labor department said it will publish proposed regulations next week that would allow employers to contract work from people in their homes in five industries: gloves and mittens, embroideries, buttons and buckles, hankerchiefs and some jewelry
however, unlike its two previous attempts to deregulate so-called industrial homework, officials said this time they will not try to remove the ban on women's apparel. also, any allowed jewelry work would be limited to stringing beads and packaging
assistant labor secretary fred alvarez said excluding women's apparel, where investigators have found about half of the violations of the current law, was aimed at defusing opposition from the 210,000-member international ladies garment workers union
however, the president of that union, jay mazur, said it will vigorously oppose any relaxation of the current ban, calling the administration's latest proposal ``a betrayal of the rights and protections held by american workers for generations.''
we will take legal action as we have in the past,'' he said, indicating that the union will likely seek to overturn any changes in the courts if the administration tries to implement them
officials for the amalgamated clothing and textile workers union and the service employees international union indicated said they also anticipate filing court challenges to any attempt to lift the current bans
mazur said he also has asked the house and senate labor committees to launch investigations of what he called the administration's ``unwillingness'' durig the past seven years to enforce the current prohibitions on industrial homework
the proposed new regulations do not attempt to overturn state bans on the same type of work at home in hawaii, california, pennsylvania, massachusetts, connecticut, new york, rhode island and new jersey
the ilgwu, other unions and employer associations in california and new york led a firestorm of attacks on the administration's last two efforts in 1981 and 1986 to repeal the industrial homework bans
as a result, only the ban on knitted outerwear was lifted in december 1984
mazur said his union's review of government records show that since then only 72 knitted outwear employers have been granted licenses to contract out work to a total of less than 1,000 home workers ``in a universe that is 10 to 15 times that size.''
we recognize what's happening; we're not fooled,'' he said. ``if they get these bans, they'll come after us next. they've had this licensing program in outerwear for 40 months now and they've found violations in 80 percent of the cases they've looked at. it hasn't worked.''
alvarez said the government does not know how many people in the five industries that employers have illegally contracted to work at home, citing estimates by others ranging from 10,000 to 100,000
what we've got is a balance of more enforcment techniques and increased flexibility in attempting to open up new opportunities,'' he said. ``the underlying policy is that people ought to have the freedom to work at home.''
the latest proposal will be open for 30 days of public comment after it is published in the federal register next week
despite expected challenges from unions and anticipated court appeals, alvarez said the administration hopes to have the prohibitions removed before reagan leaves office next january
it seems to me we ought to be able to get a final rule sometime this summer,'' he said
the current prohibitions were adopted between 1941 and 1943 under the fair labor standards act in response to what then was preceived as rampant exploitation of mostly immigrant home workers paid on a piecework basis
removing them was a cornerstone of president reagan's campaigns in 1980 and 1984. and business groups such as the u.s. chamber of commerce have won repeated promises from adminstration officials that it is the one thing that will be accomplished before he leaves office
the recommendations of this administration demonstrate it has learned nothing from history,'' the afl-cio said. ``the record shows that industrial homework has brought nothing but unfair competition, long hours and low wages for our poorest and most disadvantaged workers.''
alvarez, however, said unions have not yet had a chance to study the latest proposal, which includes what he called a new set of ``enforcement teeth'' such as requiring bonds from employers with past records of paying less than minimum wages or other labor law violations
the socialist labor party sailed to a record victory friday in local elections, marking stiff local opposition to spanish claims of sovereignty over the british colony
in his first comments to reporters after his win, joe bossano, who rejects spanish demands for a return of sovereignty over the enclave at its southernmost tip, restated his objection to a 1984 brussels accord. in that document, britain for the first time agreed to discuss sovereignty with spain
spain ceded control over the 2-square-mile limestone rock to britain in 1713 following its defeat in the war of succession
bossano also said he intended to start his four-year term as new chief minister with objections to a british-spanish accord in december allowing spain access to the colony's commercial airport and partial control of its administration
a conservative spanish party leader publicly expressed worry about the election results. christian democrat party leader javier ruperez said bossano's position ``makes it evident we're headed for stormy times.''
final election results showed bossano received 8,128 votes or 58 percent of votes cast thursday to unseat incumbent chief minister adolfo canepa of the long dominant centrist association for the advancement of civil rights
canepa, a protege of longtime party leader sir joshua hassan, received 4,442 votes or 29 percent of the total
also reacting to final results friday in madrid, juan lena, a spokesman for the government of socialist prime minister felipe gonzalez, said the election results would have no effect on spain's claims on the colony and its ongoing dialogue with britain
the elections are of great importance for the colony itself, but they will not affect the nature of the british-spanish negotiating process and discussions on cooperation on gibraltar, including the question of sovereignty,'' he said
bossano told reporters friday he was prepared to meet with gonzalez in madrid to discuss bilateral issues. but such a meeting appeared unlikely because spain accepts britain as its only legitimate negotiating partner on the matter
bossano heads the 7,000-member transport workers general union, the sole industrial union in the colony. he won fame for gaining parity in pay with britain for workers at the colony's shipyard
his party won eight votes in the 15-seat house of assembly, and canepa's party gained the other seven
democratic presidential candidate michael dukakis, a longtime opponent of u.s. aid to the nicaraguan contras, said friday he would support aid to the rebels to support the new ceasefire and the regional peace plan of costa rican president oscar arias
in a final day of campaigning for saturday's michigan caucuses, dukakis praised the ceasefire agreement reached this week in nicaragua and called on the reagan administration to support it
after seven years of a failed and illegal policy, it is time for the administration to ... get behind the peace plan _ not next week, not next month, but now,'' he told reporters at a united auto workers union hall in this grand rapids, mich., suburb
the massachusetts governor is leading in opinion polls in michigan, but he warned his supporters not to take anything for granted
friends, you're looking at a guy who was 50 points ahead in the polls in 1978 when i first ran for re-election ... and i lost,'' he said. ``i don't pay any attention to the polls and i hope you don't.''
it's a very important state. if we can do well here, it will be a giant step on the road to the nomination and the presidency,'' dukakis said
he had planned a full day of campaigning in michigan, but logistical problems snarled those plans. bad weather kept dukakis from returning to the state early friday morning, causing cancelation of events in detroit and saginaw
he held a town meeting with uaw workers and retirees in comstock park and then held a final rally in hamtramck
dukakis had emphasized repeatedly his opposition to all aid to the contras. asked friday if he supported any aid to the contras now _ as laid out in the ceasefire agreement _ dukakis told reporters:
only if it is for the very limited purpose of carrying out the provisions of the arias plan ... providing it is channeled through international relief agencies, neutral agencies and not the cia and the agencies of the federal government.''
dukakis said he doesn't want the reagan administration to handle the money because ``i don't trust this administration to provide that aid directly.''
asked if his position is consistent with his earlier stance that ``not one dollar'' of aid go to the contras, he replied: ``yes, because this is for the purpose of implementing the peace plan.''
he said the ``non-lethal'' or ``humanitarian'' aid proposed in the past for the contras was for the purpose of pursuing the war against the government of nicaragua
`non-lethal' or `humanitarian' or `the resistance' _ all of this stuff is pr stuff coming out of the administration. i don't buy it. we ought to decide what we are talking about here. a great deal of the aid that was called non-lethal was direct aid for the contras. and i think we know that
if what we are about here is genuinely implementing the arias plan or the ceasefire or both, then it may make sense to provide some assistance through international relief agencies,'' dukakis said
president joaquin balaguer of the dominican republic said friday he would grant asylum to panamanian strongman manuel antonio noriega if asked, but president reagan said the dominican republic isn't far enough away
balaguer, in an interview with the voice of america, said: ``we are willing to receive anyone who has political problems. if mr. noriega or anybody else requests our hospitality, we would give it to them, not because we agree with his regime, but rather that the traditional policy of our country has been one of open doors to all political refugees.''
reagan, asked whether he expected noriega to go to the dominican republic, replied, ``no, that's not far enough.''
a senior administration official said reagan referred to this remark during his private 50-minute meeting with balaguer, but the veteran dominican leader did not respond
the official, speaking on condition he not be identified, said, ``we do not believe that having him (noriega) that close to panama is a sensible move.''
noriega has been indicted on drug-trafficking charges by two federal grand juries in florida. the justice department has said it would not seek his extradition if he would agree to leave panama and take asylum in an agreed-upon country elsewhere. spain has offered him exile
the apparent disagreement over noriega came during a washington visit in which balaguer met with reagan, other administration officials and senators and expressed hope that his pleas for higher u.s. sugar quotas would be heeded
there are problems which subsist in our relations, especially in connection with the lowering of our sugar quota, but this we have discussed with president reagan and with his senior advisors in this area of expertise,'' balaguer said in a departure statement
we also discussed the subject this morning on capitol hill with a number of senators who are friends of the dominican republic,'' he said. ``we found there a very receptive climate and feel confident that the problem will be solved, taking into account the interests of both our countries.''
reagan, in his remarks at the departure ceremony on a porch facing the white house rose garden, did not refer to the issue of sugar quotas, a touchy issue with the dominicans since sugar is their major crop
the annual quota for sugar imports from the dominican republic to the united states has been reduced from about 750,000 tons in the early 1980s to 123,000 tons this year
the senior official said the administration will continue to press congress for changes in u.s. sugar policy. he said balaguer ``asked for help,'' both with the sugar quotas and with the declining levels of u.s. aid
reagan and secretary of state george p. shultz told balaguer the united states would make available $10 million worth of surplus u.s. corn, providing the dominicans with food as well as $10 million in foreign exchange, the official said
reagan, in his departure remarks, said, ``within our budget limitations, we will continue to support development and growth in the dominican republic.''
as a duo, the judds are an award-winning combo, but the mother and daughter say they'd team up with others if it would help country music
we'll do just about anything as long as it's legal to promote the goodness of country music,'' said daughter wynonna judd
we're pretty joined at the lips, you know,'' added her mother, naomi
after collecting another vocal duo of the year award from the academy of country music here monday night, the women talked about the responsibility each new award means
you have people who support you. you read your mail,'' wynonna said. ``we get lots of letters from people saying, `you helped me through such a hard time in my life
you get so much support from people that you really feel you want to do your best. you want to be the best you can be.''
pulitzer prize-winning columnist ellen goodman says women have been successful in getting into the male world, but have not been able to get that world to adapt to their needs
the workplace, though welcoming more women than ever, still is a man's world and that perpetuates a conflict between work and family, she said
in addition, women in the work place are seen as isolated individuals with no families, she said thursday
speaking at the 25th anniversary celebration of the university of missouri-kansas city family study center, goodman said individual rather than community goals are being emphasized in this decade
eleven-year-old nikki edwards says she'll never wash her face again, at least not the cheek that singer michael jackson kissed
so every time i take a shower, i put a wash cloth over my face so it doesn't get wet,'' she said friday, a week after the kiss
nikki and her sister, mari anna miller, 24, were in the front row at jackson's concert march 18 in indianapolis when the fifth-grader was selected to come on stage
a burly man grabbed nikki's arm and ms. miller, thinking the fellow was trying to hurt her sister, belted him
he flashed his light on mari anna's face and then on his security badges,'' nikki said. ``the security man said, `mr. jackson was wondering if you would appear on stage with him.'''
when jackson led nikki on stage, ``i thought to myself here he comes and i'm going to die,'' she said. ``then i thought what a way to go.''
jackson, a gary native, hugged her while he sang ``she's out of my life.''
dennis hopper says he was shocked by the police reaction to the new movie he directed, ``colors,'' which features police battling drug dealing and street crime by violent southern california gangs
real law enforcement officers were given a preview and several detectives said the film glamorizes the gang lifestyle and could trigger violence among gang audiences. assistant police chief robert vernon suggested it be banned
hopper says that reaction shows how much the gang problem is out of control
at the beginning we point out that there are 250 men and women in law enforcement working against 600 gangs with over 70,000 members,'' he said. ``how can they possibly handle it?''
the film, scheduled for release in mid-april, stars robert duvall and sean penn as policemen
