gary hart's financial adviser is hoping $110,000 from hart's aborted 1988 presidential campaign can eventually be applied to the former candidate's 1984 debts
bernard schneider, who serves as hart's financial adviser, says he is happy with thursday's fec ruling that allows hart to pay off debts left from his 1984 campaign with excess funds from his most recent 1988 camaign
schaefer expects $110,000 to remain after the 1988 campaign clears its debts and returns a share of matching funds to the fec
since his 1984 campaign, hart has reduced his $4.75 million debt to $1.1 million through fundraisers and debt settlements
it's a very good record for a losing presidential campaign,'' schneider said. ``people lose sight of that in this whole feeding frenzy around gary.''
a vote of confidence can sometimes be as good as a vote itself for vice president george bush _ just ask 101-year-old mary fishbyrne
bush sent her an autographed color portrait of himself after learning that fishbyrne, who prefers to be called miss mary, had been frustrated when she tried to vote for him in louisiana's super tuesday primary
miss mary, a registered democrat who has voted in every presidential election since women were granted suffrage in 1920, thought bush was a smart man and ``would make a good president.'' but she could not cast her ballot for him because voters in the state's presidential primary aren't permitted to cross party lines
a bush campaign spokesman said a campaign worker heard of miss mary's frustrations on super tuesday and decided to send her the picture in appreciation for her would-have-been vote
she said bush has her support in november. ``if i can make it there, i'll vote for him.''
