at a news conference, casey gave two reasons for his decision
it was clear a number of democratic candidates have substantial support amng the voters of this state,'' he said, adding that voters should have a chance to express their views
casey also said his supporters have pledged to a number of the candidates and if he made a choice it would undercut their positions
the governor said he was not leaning toward any of the five democrats still in the field
the united states will begin a series of mock inspections next month to prepare its new force of arms control inspectors and escorts to deal with soviet facilities and personnel, a ranking pentagon official said friday
the exercises will be staged at the 21 sites in europe and the united states where soviet inspectors will be allowed to visit to ensure compliance with a treaty banning intermediate and shorter-range nuclear missiles, the official added
the mock inspections will begin april 6 and should be completed by may 10, hopefully in plenty of time to allow final preparations for the real inspections that will begin 30 days after the u.s. senate ratifies the pact, the source said
the official agreed to meet with a group of reporters friday to discuss the defense department's formation of the on-site inspection agency, or osia, only on condition he not be identified publicly
the agency is to be the arm of the federal government responsible for verifying russian compliance with the new treaty. signed by president reagan and soviet leader mikhail gorbachev on dec. 8, the treaty specifies that all nuclear missiles in the two superpower arsenals with a range of roughly 300 miles to 3,500 miles be destroyed within three years
the osia will be responsible for escorting soviet inspectors who travel to the united states and sites in western europe to monitor the removal and destruction of american nuclear weapons, as well as performing the same role inside the soviet union by visiting russian facilities and deployment sites
the official said next month's practice sessions would involve both inspectors and escorts, with the inspectors pretending to be soviet officials who are met by the american escorts
under the treaty, there are 10 sites open to soviet inspection inside the united states and another 11 in western europe. all 21 sites will be tested to ensure they're ready for hosting russian inspectors, the official said
and we will challenge them (the escorts) with all kinds of possible variances in the (inspection) routine,'' said the source
according to the official, the task of staffing the osia has now been completed. the agency will keep in place 20 teams of 10 members each for the inspections, plus a headquarters' staff of 50 in washington. perhaps a third of the inspectors are women, the official said, and a sufficient number of russian linguists have been located, although with some difficulty
the u.s. military airlift command will be responsible for providing the aircraft and crews needed to ferry american inspectors to two ``entry points'' into the soviet union and to move russian inspectors around inside the united states, the official continued
the two entry points for the russians will be washington, d.c., and san francisco, calif., and the pentagon intends to inform the news media when the soviets arrive for spot inspections, the source said
the head of the osia, brig. gen. roland lajoie, and his soviet counterpart have already met once _ during a technical meeting in moscow earlier this month _ and will meet again in washington starting april 12, the official continued
the technical meetings are being held to sort out questions about the type of monitoring and survey equipment that will be used by the inspectors, the source said
conan owen knew it was thursday once again when officials served up beef stew in gallery one of the model prison
owen, a 23-year-old free-lance photographer from annandale, va., has been marking off the days in his stark white cell for more than a year, ever since a spanish civil guard found more than four pounds of cocaine in a suitcase registered in his name
i don't belong in here because i'm innocent, and if this were the united states, i would have been out a long time ago,'' owen said in an interview in this 85-year-old prison in the heart of downtown barcelona
owen, whose case has drawn the attention of attorney general edwin meese iii, is to stand trial saturday before a three-judge panel. the prosecution is asking for a 10-year sentence
he arrived at barcelona's el prat airport on march 13, 1987 _ friday the 13th _ on a flight from santiago, chile, via amsterdam. he said he was on his way to spain for the first time to shoot pictures for tourist agency travel brochures
i was working as a free-lance, and the guy offered me $1,000 for four days' work. i like to travel, so i accepted and thought i was taking a suitcase full of travel brochures and film to someone in spain,'' he said
owen was booked on charges of cocaine smuggling, denied bail and taken to the modelo, as the jail is known here
this is the worst jail in spain, the oldest and the most-crowded,'' said guard manuel escobedo. ``it was meant to hold 600 people, but there are about 2,400 in here now.''
according to the u.s. embassy in madrid, as of last month there were 25 u.s. citizens in jail in spain. six are serving prison terms following conviction on drug-related charges, and another nine, including owen, are awaiting trial
owen's attorney, ana campa, plans to enter as evidence results of a polygraph test administered to owen by an agent of the u.s. drug enforcement agency, which she says indicates owen is telling the truth about his photo job and the suitcase
on feb. 5, george barahona, the man who offered owen the job, pleaded guilty in u.s. district court to a drug conspiracy count. he told the court he had shared a hotel room with owen in santiago and planted the cocaine-lined suitcase on the unsuspecting photographer
barahona received a two-year suspended sentence and a promise he would not be extradited to spain in return for his cooperation
following his testimony, three spaniards and three bolivians, all fugitives, were indicted by a federal grand jury in virginia on cocaine conspiracy charges in connection with the case
it was my parents who first confronted barahona, because my cousin maria teresa corrales knew him and he lived in the area,'' owen said. ``at first he denied everything, but then he told the truth.''
when meese came to spain to sign an annex to a 1970 extradition treaty feb. 9, he also handed over copies of barahona's statement to spanish judicial authorities
owen is a 1986 graduate of syracuse university and in 1984 was a summer intern in vice president george bush's office
the walls of the halls leading to the five sections of the prison are decorated with travel posters for catalonia, the region in which barcelona is located, and neighboring france
owen said what he has seen of spain consists of the barcelona airport, the court where he was arraigned and the modelo
during his year in jail owen has read 150 books, written letters and walked miles around the patio during the daily morning and afternoon recreation periods
guards in spanish jails are unarmed, and inmates wear street clothes. prisoners in the modelo are allowed one, one-hour conjugal visit every month with a woman of their choice
it's the boredom that gets you more than anything, the lack of stimulating conversation, someone to talk about serious things with,'' said owen
the united states should think very carefully before permitting highly secret u.s. submarine technology to be sold to canada, two senators said friday
this is a decision that should be very carefully scrutinized before we decide to go ahead,'' said sen. james j. exon, d-neb., chairman of the senate armed services strategic weapons subcommittee, in a speech on the senate floor
we have a number of questions which need to be answered before this decision is made,'' agreed sen. john warner, r-va., ranking republican on the armed services committee and a former secretary of the navy
canada last year proposed to construct a fleet of 10 to 12 nuclear-powered submarines and is considering building boats which are updated versions of the british trafalgar-class subs or the french rubis-class subs
the trafalgars use u.s. technology, which means the information could not be supplied to canada by the british unless the united states approves, both exon and warner said
if the pentagon decides to permit canada to use the american technology, congress could block the plan within 90 days if both the house and senate pass resolutions of disapproval, exon added
the pentagon has not yet decided to grant a waiver to britain, navy secretary william ball iii told the armed services committee earlier this week
exon noted that u.s. nuclear-powered sub technology had only been transferred once in the past, to britain, and he questioned whether canada has ``the money and the enormous infrastructure'' needed to safely operate the subs
in this era of nuclear phobia, we must maintain and enhance our shipboard standards of nuclear propulsion,'' exon said. any accidents aboard canadian subs which involve u.s. technology would raise fears about u.s. subs and could hamper the american navy's operation, he told his colleagues
warner said, ``before we approve this decision, we need to know how canada proposes to fund this program, how canada proposes to insure that the standard of nuclear safety will be at least as high as the united states and the british.''
exon said the technology involved may be outdated and he noted that the soviets are building a bigger, faster class of attack boats
a 3-year-old boy scalded to death in a welfare hotel reportedly was removed from foster care and returned to his mother and father last summer despite a judge's reservations
police have charged that the mother, marian mckenzie, 21, murdered quintin by holding him in 136-degree water because he had soiled his diaper. the boy's father, calvin, 23, has been charged with beating him earlier that day
the mckenzies received custody of quintin and his older sister, tanisha, after judge joseph esquirol of family court in brooklyn dismissed a case brought in december 1986 by city child welfare authorities
the city sought to remove the children from the mckenzies on grounds that the father had beaten quintin at a shelter in new jersey where the family then was living
new york newsday and the daily news reported that after numerous delays during which the city produced no evidence of a beating, esquirol dismissed the case may 26
the judge stayed return of the children to june 3 and urged that city or new jersey officials refile the case
i know i certainly didn't want to return the children. the mother had admitted to new jersey authorities that the father beat her and the children,'' the judge told newsday. ``it was very, very frustrating.''
william grinker, head of the city's human resources administration, has declined to comment before completion of an investigation of his agency's handling of the case
quintin had spent more than half his 41-month life in foster care or hospitals, including the first six months of his life. he weighed only 1.8 pounds when he was born prematurely. chief's yard</head>
sworn statements that led authorities to dig up a body in a police chief's yard tell of a friendship that allegedly developed into wife-swapping but ended in homicide
a district court judge allowed the affidavits to be released friday, a week after he rejected arguments by the state attorney general that they should be sealed to protect a continuing homicide investigation
robert chambers, who resigned as part-time chief after the body was found, has said through his lawyer that he is innocent of any wrongdoing. no charges have been filed
mark sisti, a public defender representing chambers, called the affidavits ``low-quality, unsubstantiated blatant hearsay.''
the attorney general's office said friday it was satisfied with the progress of the investigation and expected an arrest, though it did not say when
according to sworn statements given by chambers' sister, his niece and a brother-in-law, the following story emerges:
chambers, 36, and good friend russell bean, then 25, worked together at a factory in keene, and ``were having a wife swap.'' sometime in september 1978 the two were drinking at an abandoned quarry when they got into a fight and bean died. robert, with the help of his father, clifton chambers, buried bean's body
after bean disappeared, chambers divorced his wife, deborah, and married bean's wife, sylvia
robert and sylvia chambers settled in his five-room cabin on a dirt road three miles outside of marlow and he became the part-time police chief for the town of 600 three years ago. he also became the part-time chief of nearby gilsum and a police trainee in winchester. he has a leave of absence from gilsum and is suspended with pay from winchester
on march 11, police began digging in chambers' front yard with a backhoe. three days later, bean's skeleton was found 20 feet deep
pathologists determined bean had been beaten on the head and chest
on march 2, clifton chambers told his daughter, melissa, and granddaughter, lorrie wheeler, that robert came to him in the middle of the night 10 years ago and said ``he had just killed russell and wanted to know what to do.'' robert said the two were drinking, got into a fight and robert hit bean, who fell back, hit his head and died instantly
the father, in ill health, made melissa and lorrie promise not to say anything until after his death
one week later, clifton chambers, 61, suffered a cerebral hemorrhage and died. that same day, melissa and lorrie told the story to the keene police, who relayed the information to state police
sgt. clayton young of the state police major crimes unit interviewed the women and louis lacourse, the husband of melissa's sister, susan. authorities then sought a warrant to excavate the chief's yard
the relationship between robert, russ, sylvia and debbie was weird,'' melissa said in her statement. ``it's called wife-swapping, that was going on before debbie ran off and russ disappeared. i know robert always beat debbie, that was why she ran off. (she) couldn't take it any longer.''
deborah, who was admitted to a keene hospital with an undisclosed illness after the digging began, left chambers in july 1978
bean was last seen in september 1978, and his wife moved in with chambers that october. in january 1979, she divorced the missing bean. chambers divorced deborah in march and chambers and sylvia married in september 1979
young's affidavit said sylvia wrote bean's mother two letters about his disappearance. the first said bean had borrowed money from chambers, who then gave bean a ride to the vermont state line and let him out
later, she wrote that she feared chambers, and that she was afraid chambers had harmed bean
lacourse told police that after bean disappeared, chambers told him he ``would not have to worry about seeing him (bean) again. he (chambers) hit him so hard no one would ever seen him again.''
melissa, who lived with her father and lorrie in a trailer behind robert chambers' home, said her mother, now deceased, warned her to ``look out for robert.'' last year, her father ``warned (me) about my brother being dangerous,'' she said
mickey and minnie mouse led baby boomers and their swivel-hipped soul mates of all ages back to the 1950s friday as 1,527 people simultaneously spun hula hoops at disneyland to claim a world record
the crowd _ certified by a turnstile count _ gyrated to the strains of ``whole lotta shakin' goin' on'' until a representative of the guinness book of world records was satisfied he had witnessed history's biggest crowd of hula hoopers
but for most of the swirlers, making hula hoop history took a back seat to having fun
i'm reliving my childhood,'' said frank samagaio, 36, an investigator with the san diego district attorney's office
i was 7 years old when these came out,'' samagaio said, demonstrating that hula hooping, like riding a bike, is a skill one never loses entirely
some hoopers woke up as early as 4 a.m. to reach the park from distant points of southern california. they were all given t-shirts, free park admission and hula hoops
the record try was a promotion by disneyland and hula hoop maker wham-o, which is celebrating the 30th anniversary of the toy this week
some inept hoopers twirled the hoops on their wrists while others madly twisted while the hoops inexorably spun farther and farther down their legs
it's in the hips,'' confided jackie eastman, 11, of penasquitos, who got a hoop for her birthday march 9 and already can twirl it for 10 minutes at a stretch
after three false starts, dan roddick, a wham-o employee who also serves as a guinness field representative, proclaimed success, which he had earlier defined as everyone putting his or her hoop through three revolutions at once
while guinness doesn't actually recognize a mass hula hoop record at present, roddick said the largest known mass swivel appears to have been performed by about 350 people some 25 years ago in the northwest. that event is recorded only by a photograph, he said
for some of the teens and young adults in friday's crowd, the event was sort of a ticket to more innocent times, symbolized for them by pompadour hair-dos and the do-wop music of the 1950s and early '60
it was happier,'' said sarah culver, 20, a college student from tustin who favors 1950s music, dance and clothes
the styles, they fit better, they're more feminine,'' miss culver said. ``you can dance with the guys _ closer _ you don't have to dance by yourself.''
gov. bob martinez said friday that investigators will look into claims that attorneys for death row inmates asked witnesses to lie to save the prisoners' lives
martinez, who earlier this week ordered the florida department of law enforcement to check out the methods of the state-funded defenders, said he didn't plan to interfere
i probably won't make any more announcements now until the report comes in. it wouldn't be appropriate,'' he said
martinez also established an independent seven-member commission to review the investigation's findings to avoid any appearance that he was mounting a political attack against the office of capital collateral representative, a 3-year-old agency that has won stays of executions for dozens of inmates
the st. petersburg times reported friday that allegedly false affidavits were given to martinez and attorney general bob butterworth after witnesses _ two prison inmates, a miami prosecutor and a miami lawyer _ complained about the conduct of several employees of the collateral appeals office
in each case, inmates who testified against men on death row say they were asked to sign false affidavits that would be used to gain a stay of execution
ronald guralnick, the miami lawyer who represented one of the inmates, said attorneys from the office of capital collateral representative in tallahassee told him they had filed a motion alleging ``everything possible'' and would ``try to prove it later,'' the newspaper said
in both cases the affidavits, allegedly prepared by the death row lawyers, accused police who handled the murder investigations of inventing testimony that witnesses later repeated in court
larry spalding, the lawyer who supervises the collateral appeals office, said he has questioned the lawyers involved in one instance and will support them until he sees evidence to change his mind
the other one i know nothing about, but i will immediately talk to those involved,'' spalding said thursday
spalding blamed the investigation on the continuing controversy between his office and a governor who, he said, wants to speed up executions
spalding's office was established in 1985 to handle appeals filed by death row inmates. those appeals traditionally involve issues not concerning guilt of innocence, but legal procedures
the stae set up the appeals agency to provide lawyers for indigent inmates making their final appeal and do away with claims that inmates were not properly represented
sen. albert gore jr. portrayed his democratic presidential opponents as too liberal on friday, saying ``you don't have to be very far to the right to be to the right of this crowd.''
gore also said he was optimistic about his chances in saturday's michigan caucuses
wherever we have had a level playing field and enough time to get the message out and become known by the voters, we have won,'' he told a radio audience in detroit. ``the time in michigan has been short ... but we've got a lot of good friends working for us and i hope that we'll do significantly better than people expect.''
gore has steadfastly tried to depict himself as the moderate candidate in the presidential field
the tennessee senator addressed the subject anew on friday after being asked a question on his defense posture
it's not conservative. i've never used that word. let me hasten to add, you don't have to be very far to the right to be to the right of this crowd,'' he said
earlier, in racine, wis., gore rolled up his sleeves and joined foundry workers at their jobs. wearing a shiny white hardhat, blue jeans and a leisure shirt, gore took a 1{-hour tour of the racine steel casting plant
the campaign stop gave gore a chance to shovel chunks of metal into a furnace, to help a worker form a casting mold and to drive a forklift and unload large metal sprockets
i think getting some hands-on experience is a way to communicate symbolically with the workers,'' he said
gore told reporters he will continue to campaign heavily in wisconsin, which will hold its primary april 5
i predict we're really going to surprise people in wisconsin,'' he said. ``wisconsin has a chance to play a unique role.''
gore also picked up the endorsement friday of one-time presidential candidate eugene mccarthy
mccarthy, who was a senator from minnesota when he sought the democratic nomination in 1968, said he endorses gore because of his experience and voting record on foreign affairs and economic and environmental issues
there is no better preparation for the presidency than being in congress, especially the senate,'' mccarthy said
i've felt for some time that the governorship is the worst preparation for the presidency,'' mccarthy said. ``it provides a great oversimplification of how the federal government operates.''
allowing surrogate mother mary beth whitehead-gould to continue visiting baby m will hurt the child psychologically, the toddler's father argued in court papers released friday
william stern, who won custody of the baby in a landmark state supreme court ruling feb. 3, asked a superior court judge to discontinue visitation. stern's attorney said he will call expert witnesses to show that halting visitation would be in the best interest of the child, now legally known as melissa stern
testimony will again reconfirm ... that visitation at this particular point could only have a destabilizing influence on the child and result in very grave consequences on her future mental health,'' attorney gary skoloff said in court papers
mrs. whitehead-gould has asked that she be allowed to spend more time with the baby, with the meetings expanded eventually to half the summer and some holidays
she has been allowed to see melissa once a week, for two hours, under supervision. court papers released thursday by mrs. whitehead-gould's attorneys call that schedule ``insufficient.''
she contends that the child would be harmed if those visitations were discontinued
mrs. whitehead-gould has fashioned an excellent relationship with melissa and is devoted to promoting an even more flourishing and productive relationship,'' said court papers filed by mrs. whitehead-gould's attorney, harold cassidy
the documents, filed earlier this week, give an indication what both sides will argue when superior court judge birger m. sween on monday convenes a visitation hearing that may be the final legal skirmish in the fierce battle over the child, who turns 2 sunday
mrs. whitehead-gould's $10,000 contract with stern became a highly publicized court case after she refused to turn over the child she agreed to bear. since the case began, mrs. whitehead-gould divorced her first husband, richard whitehead, and married a wall street broker, dean gould
this has been a long trial, a long process for my client and for the levin family,'' defense attorney jack litman told the court in announcing the plea agreement
the pleas are acceptable to the people,'' prosecutor linda fairstein told the court
the plea bargain followed two days of turmoil in the case, and fairstein and litman spent most of the last two days in chambers meeting with state supreme court justice howard e. bell
president reagan warned israel on friday that the united states would be ``totally opposed'' to any israeli attack on saudi arabia's new intermediate-range missile launchers
state department spokeswoman phyllis oakley, meanwhile, confirmed that the administration has cautioned israel not take action against the newly delivered chinese missiles
mrs. oakley refused to comment on reports that the israeli air force has been conducting low-level practice bombing runs
reagan, asked how the united states would feel about israeli attacks on the saudi sites, said, ``naturally, we would be totally opposed to any such thing and hope that they are not considering any such act.''
egyptian president hosni mubarak said in cairo thursday that he had sent an urgent message to reagan urging him to ``use his influence with israel and urge it to stop threatening arab states in this irresponsible way.'' mubarak said such an attack would ``blow up the entire peace process'' in the middle east
reagan was asked about the situation as he prepared to meet with visiting president joaquin balaguer of the dominican republic
on wednesday, an unidentified egyptian official said cairo would consider any israeli attack on the installations an attack on egypt itself
saudi arabia recently acquired the missiles, which have a range of 2,200 miles, enough to reach iran and israel. the missiles are capable of carrying nuclear warheads, but both china and saudi arabia have given assurances they will be fitted only with conventional warheads
in jerusalem, yossi ben-aharon, a senior aide to prime minister yitzhak shamir said, ``israel has a tradition of not standing by quietly when there is a real threat against it. the question is if this is a threat or not. there are people to deal with it, the cabinet, the government.''
israel radio reported that saudi arabia issued a warning through the united states that it would use any remaining missiles to strike at the jewish state if israel attempted a pre-emptive strike
ben-aharon said u.s. officials had ``told us they are going to deal with the matter the best they can, both in china and in saudi arabia.''
white house spokesman marlin fitzwater said the reagan administration was ``concerned about any instability that is introduced by weapons changes in the area'' and had made its views known to both the israelis and the saudis. he added that ``our protests have gone to the nuclear capability as opposed to the site.''
