secretary of state george p. shultz will meet saturday with two members of the legislative arm of the palestine liberation organization as americans are being warned to keep away from the israeli-held west bank and gaza
professor edward said of columbia university, one of the two palestine national council members invited by shultz, said they notified plo chairman yasser arafat and he approved of the session
as u.s. citizens, said said he and professor ibrahim abu-lughud of northwestern university did not need a `'green light'' from arafat to see shultz. ``we did notify chairman arafat, and that was fine with him _ absolutely,'' said said in a telephone interview
the state department said the meeting did not represent a change in the 13-year-old u.s. policy of not dealing with the plo. both the united states and israel have condemned it as a terrorist organization
in another action friday, the state department issued a travel advisory against the israeli-held west bank and gaza. americans were cautioned not to travel to the areas
the announcement coincided with the approach of easter and passover, christian and jewish holidays that usually attract tourists to the holy land
said said he and abu-lughud were interested in ``an exchange of views'' with shultz. he said they wanted to know more about the u.s. proposal for arab-israeli negotiations
i am not a diplomat,'' said said. ``we're going to tell him about the palestinians' view of the whole matter.''
asked if the plo should participate in the negotiations, the columbia professor replied without hesitation: ``absolutely.''
he said he did not know if the meeting changed u.s. policy toward the plo. ``i have no idea. i`m not too concerned about this,'' he said
a state department announcement friday described said and abu-lughud as ``prominent americans with an intimate knowledge of contemporary middle eastern politics.''
their membership on the palestine national council was not mentioned in the announcement but was confirmed later by state department spokeswoman phyllis oakley
israeli ambassador moshe arad protested shultz's invitation to the two as in conflict with the u.s. policy against dealing with the plo, which is pledged to dismantling israel as a jewish state
the state department, meantime, cited ``continuing disturbances'' in urging americans to stay away from the west bank and gaza. a total of 111 palestinian arabs and an israel soldier have died in violent protests and other incidents since dec. 9
we are not issuing an advisory for israel itself,'' mrs. oakley said. ``israel is safe for american travel.''
however, with the statement coming during the easter season, which attracts many religious pilgrims to the area, the impact on tourism and on israel's economy could be severe
the west bank was held by jordan and gaza by egypt from 1949 until 1967 when the arabs lost the territories to israel in the six-day war. about 96 percent of the population is palestinian
the travel advisory cautioned americans to avoid travel to the areas ``until further notice.'' it said americans living in the areas ``should exercise particular caution.''
the situation in east jerusalem, which is part of israel's capital, was described as ``unpredictable.'' the advisory said americans should check with u.s. diplomats in the city before entering the area
under all circumstances, americans should avoid demonstrations and other situations that have the potential to lead to violence,'' the advisory said. ``american travelers should carry their u.s. passports at all times.''
shultz will hold the meeting with said and abu-lughud ``to discuss our approach to the middle east peace process,'' the separate announcement said
he is trying to open negotiations on may 1 to provide self-rule for the palestinians. the plo would not participate. however, palestinians with plo approval would be part of a delegation with jordan
mrs. oakley stressed that said and abu-lughud are u.s. citizens. she said the u.s. policy of not dealing with the plo itself remained intact
there is no change in u.s. policy on negotiating with or recognizing the plo,'' she said. ``that policy remains as it has been since 1975.''
the united states, after persuading israel to relinquish territory to egypt and syria, promised in 1975 it would not deal with the plo. the pledge subsequently was incorporated in u.s. law
asked if the plo had given said and abu-lughud permission to meet with shultz, mrs. oakley said: ``i have nothing on that.''
she said shultz initiated the meeting. ``he will discuss the palestinian point of view,'' she said. ``they have an intimate knowledge of middle eastern politics.''
arad, the israeli ambassador, telephoned m. charles hill, an assistant to shultz, to protest the meeting as a violation of the pledge. mrs. oakley declined to describe the conversation
on capitol hill, rep. charles shumer, d-n.y., also contended that the meeting would violate the pledge, which also was included in law in 1984, and called on shultz to reconsider it. reps. mel levine, d-calif., and benjamin gilman, r-n.y., also wrote the secretary of their concern that the meeting ``might be seen as an erosion of the u.s. position regarding the plo.''
however, the american-arab anti-discrimination committee lauded the meeting as ``a reflection of the reality that legitimate palestinian representation is essential to any peace in the region.''
during a mideast shuttle trip last month, shultz tried to arrange a meeting in jerusalem with 15 palestinian arabs. apparently under plo orders, none of them showed up
shultz went to a hotel in east jerusalem, stood in the floodlit courtyard and read a statement suggesting the palestinians were fearful of working with the united states
opportunity knocks loudly on your door,'' he said then. ``now is the time to get to work. we have a workable plan, and we are ready to commit our efforts to it. the time is right, together, to make decisions of historic proportions.''
in january, shultz met here with two palestinian arabs, hanna siniora, a jerusalem editor, and fayez abu rahme, a gaza lawyer
we feel we got his attention to the situation in the territories,'' siniora said afterward
mrs. oakley, meanwhile, confirmed the united states had cautioned israel not to take any action against chinese missiles delivered to saudi arabia. she refused to confirm reports the israeli air force has been conducting low-level practice bombing runs
riot police used water cannon friday to break up a roman catholic demonstration for religious freedom held in downtown bratislava in defiance of an official ban, western observers said
clashes broke out when police tried to clear the square of thousands of catholics who gathered in front of the notre dame cathedral. injuries and arrests were reported, but no figures were available
bratislava is a southern city near the czechoslovak-austrian border
witnesses said it took security troops and riot police about 45 minutes to push the catholics, who were singing, praying and holding candles, into side streets to end the protest
two television teams, sent to bratislava from the austrian state radio-television corporation, orf, and the west german ard station, were seen being shoved by police and detained as catholics gathered on the square. they were prevented from filming the protest
frantisek miklosko, a slovak catholic activist, had told authorities of plans for a peaceful rally and organizers were expecting up to 70,000 people would take part
but communist authorities thurday banned the demonstration, saying it was ``an event guided from abroad'' and directed against the socialist system
protesters defied the ban, saying they wanted a free and independent church and 10 bishops appointed to fill vacant bishoprics throughout czechoslovakia
government officials have been arguing with the vatican over the vacancies. organizers also wanted to show support for a petition calling for separation of church and state and for free expression of religion, which has been signed so far by more than 430,000 czechoslovak catholics
the austrian tv crew was released after 2{ hours, orf journalist otto hoermann reported
in a broadcast telephone call from his car driving toward the nearby border, hoermann said he and his colleagues saw about 100 catholics who were taken to police headquarters
they were totally drenched,'' he said, referring to police use of road-cleaning trucks and water cannon. ``it has also been raining. so bratislava must be today the cleanest city in central europe.''
hoermann said he saw many police with clubs around bratislava as he drove from the city
demonstrators began gathering at 3.30 p.m. a witness said shortly before 6 p.m., when the crowd was several thousand strong, people clutching candles sang the slovak and czech national anthems
police began moving street-cleaning trucks and police cars toward the square. authorities used loudspeakers to urged demonstrators to vacate the square, saying: ``this demonstration has not been allowed according to state laws. will you please disperse?''
but the appeal went unheeded. police cars, six abreast, drove through the crowd. the scene became chaotic as demonstrators blocked off some of the cars
elderly women, middle-aged people and youngsters were among those resisting
then came the street-cleaning trucks, spewing water
most of the demonstrators stood fast on the square
authorities brought in riot police and three water cannon drenched the crowd. the demonstrators still were not entirely dispersed, and security troops shoved people off the square, herding them into side streets
students were warned this week not to take part in the protest and threatened with losing their place at universities and dormitories, the austrian catholic news agency kathpress reported wednesday
kathpress said the organizers insisted the event was registered officially as a ``peaceful assembly of citizens.''
they were also quoted as saying, ``is it unlawful to stage a rally for religious freedom, observance of human rights and appointment of bishops by the pope ?''
the state news agency ctk later said members of illegal church structures tried to organize a ``quiet religious demonstration,'' the aim of which was to abuse religious feelings of believers, violate relations between the socialist state and the church, and undermine negotiations with the vatican
a strong earthquake shook a sparsely populated area of the northwest territories on friday. there were no reports of injuries or damage
the quake registered 6.0 on the richter scale and was centered about 95 miles west of fort simpson, 750 miles northwest of edmonton, said bob wetmiller, a federal seismologist
an earthquake of that magnitude can do serious damage, but wetmiller said it was too far from populated areas to pose a danger
it struck 12:36 p.m. mst and was felt in communities several hundred miles away, he said
the last earthquakes of that magnitude in the region were in 1985. one of 6.6 was reported oct. 5 and another of 6.9 on dec. 23 that year
the richter scale is an open-ended gauge of energy released by an earthquake as measured by ground motion recorded on a seismograph. every increase of one number means that the ground motion is 10 times greater
a quake with a magnitude of 5 can cause considerable damage in a populated area; a magnitude 6 quake severe damage, one of magnitude 7 widespread, heavy damage and a magnitude 8 quake, a ``great'' earthquake capable of tremendous damage
a quake of magnitude 2 is the smallest normally felt by humans
a scuba instructor was sentenced friday to 10 years in prison for fatally shooting his boss, who authorities said was a suicidal millionaire who badgered and bribed the employee to pull the trigger
frederick wisniewski, 27, of linden had pleaded guilty to aggravated manslaughter and aiding a suicide in the nov. 25 death of julius ``alex'' bittmann, 44, of north brunswick
i am sorry for it,'' wisniewski told superior court judge paul r. kramer at sentencing
wisniewski told authorities bittmann badgered him for two months before he agreed to kill him in return for $40,000 in cash and a $60,000 mercedes benz
wisniewski said bittmann pleaded, ``do it, do it!'' before he killed bittmann with a shot from a .357-caliber magnum pistol in a forest, authorities say. bittmann had attempted suicide four times previously, authorities said
authorities said wisniewski told them he drank a six-pack of beer and some scotch and snorted cocaine before going through with bittmann's request
burlington county prosecutor stephen raymond said the sentence ``sends out a clear message that this type of conduct isn't excusable.''
julius bittmann really did do everything but actually pull the trigger,'' he said
wisniewski will be eligible for parole after three years and three months, authorities said
bittmann owned a scuba shop in edison where wisniewski worked as a diving instructor. bittman amassed his fortune through several businesses and real estate
relatives and acquaintances have said that they do not know what led to bittmann's chronic depression, but that he had been taking excessive amounts of anti-depressant drugs in recent years. ... ''</note>
jesse jackson denounced president reagan and george bush on friday for opposing civil rights legislation and accused presidential rivals in both parties of ``not offering leadership to stop the flow of drugs.''
jackson, striving for a win in a big industrial state, campaigned at the county jail, inner-city union halls and a suburban high school, blending his criticism of republicans with stirring calls to shun the ``short-term thrill, long-term chill'' of drugs
on the eve of michigan's statewide democratic presidential caucuses, jackson provided his own answer to those who ask what he seeks to accomplish with a candidacy that is dogged by the assumption he cannot win the nomination, even as he leads the democratic field in popular votes cast
people always ask, no matter how we're winning, what does jesse jackson want,'' jackson said before a crowd of more than 1,000 people, jammed into the united auto workers local 212 next door to a shut-down chrysler plant
what does jesse want? i want to wipe out illiteracy,'' he said
what do i want? i want to raise the minimum wage. what do i want? i want comparable worth for women. ..
i want head start and day care early on, rather than jail-fare and welfare later on,'' jackson said
he called reagan's veto of legislation extending a civil rights law, and bush's support for that veto, ``an attempt to turn back the clock.'' congress on tuesday overrode reagan's veto of the bill, which covers discrimination by institutions that use federal money. reagan argued that the legislation would expand federal power
any man who stands ... against civil rights restoration in this country is not fit to lead our nation,'' jackson said
linking drugs to problems of inner cities such as the one where he was campaigning, jackson criticized vice president bush repeatedly and noted bush's position as head of the administration's fight against drugs
george bush ... he's over the drug commission, and offers no leadership,'' jackson said at the uaw hall
mr. reagan, mr. bush, my competitors, are not offering leadership to stop the flow of drugs,'' jackson said
later in flint, jackson named rivals michael dukakis and albert gore jr., and said he was outspent 50-to-1 by them in the south ``yet we got the most votes.''
if they had my budget, they would surrender. if i had their budget, they could not compete,'' he said
jackson spoke at a baptist church where the crowd was so large people stood outside unable to get in. he also spoke in the parking lot beside a uaw hall where democrat richard gephardt spoke a day earlier. across the street was a gm auto assembly plant closed three months ago, laying off some 3,500 workers
foreign labor is not better labor, it's just cheaper labor,'' jackson said. ``south korea didn't take jobs from us, gm took jobs to them.''
at each stop jackson gave careful instructions on how to vote in michigan's unusual caucus system. at one rally he called all the young children in the crowd to gather around him
who are you going to vote for?'' he asked them. ``jesse,'' they responded
jackson was running in a tight michigan race with dukakis, according to most polls in michigan, with gephardt running third in a state where he must win
jackson, the black civil rights activist, is counting on doing well in heavily black detroit, even though the city's black mayor, coleman young, is backing dukakis
a jackson victory in michigan would be a major achievement for his candidacy in a state of the industrial north _ one where only 16 years ago george wallace won a stunning democratic primary victory
he spoke in a detroit neighborhood not far from empty factories, vacant lots and gutted storefronts
what does it matter to have civil rights, if you can march downtown but can't walk down your own neighborhood streets?'' jackson asked
hours earlier, he visited the wayne county jail and met with about 30 inmates, all facing misdemeanor charges, and urged them to use their time to read and learn and to reject drugs
just because you're down, you don't have to be out; you can change your situation,'' he said
jackson urged the inmates to ask for absentee ballots and vote in the presidential balloting being conducted at saturday's caucuses
a doctor said friday he was looking out his office window when he saw his house passing before his eyes
it was on a flatbed truck, headed out of town with a police escort
i ran down the street and yelled, `hey, where are you going with my house?''' dr. frank calabro, a general practitioner and part owner of a real estate business, said in relating thursday's events
the cop looked at me like i was crazy,'' said calabro, 55
this is your house, mister?'' the officer asked
this is a house-napping,'' calabro told him
the officer stopped the convoy and walked to the back to talk to the man who had ordered the house moved. he was gone
we all stood in the street laughing,'' said calabro. ``it seemed so ridiculous. who would steal a house?''
the answer, provided by the boss of the flatbed truck, was a guy who sold it to someone else for $500, then hired the mover to deliver it
the concept of a man's home being his castle has been shaken to its very foundation,'' suffolk county district attorney patrick henry said
the two-bedroom yellow beach house with a white door had been placed on runners for removal because calabro had sold it _ a $12,000 value _ earlier in the week. partisans</head>
austrian president kurt waldheim, while serving in the german army, received and then forwarded adolf hitler's order to kill captured greek partisans, according to documents released friday
the documents from the u.s. national achives are waldheim's army group's war diary and a corresponding nuremberg war trial document. they were provided by the world jewish congress
the chief witness against kurt waldheim is the one he can never refute _ his own name on the captured nazi war records,'' said elan steinberg, executive director of the world jewish congress
john russell, a justice department spokesman, confirmed friday that the war diary and nuremberg records were among documents used in deciding to place waldheim on the ``watchlist'' that bars undesirable aliens from the united states
the austrian government has protested that the u.s. government has not disclosed the documents. waldheim, u.n. secretary-general from 1972 to 1982, has denied committing any war crimes, although his army unit was accused of them
waldheim served with the german army during world war ii in the occupied balkans. he was a lieutenant in the german general staff attached to the 11th italian army in athens
the documents show that on aug. 8, 1943, waldheim entered hitler's order to kill captured greek partisans in his army group's war diary in athens and on the same day transmitted the order by radio to a german division in the field
the diary entry signed by waldheim said: ``according to a new fuehrer order bandits (partisans) captured in battle are to be shot. others suspected of banditry, etc., are to be taken prisoner and sent to germany for use in labor details.'' the translation was provided by the world jewish congress
the word ``bandit'' was used to describe partisans
the nuremberg document shows the actual transmission of the order: ``to the 1st mountain division: reference teletype ia no. 959-43 secret of 7 aug. 1943 concerning shooting of bandits. a new fuehrer order is at hand, which will be transmitted. bandits taken in battle are to be shot. other bandit suspects etc. are to be arrested and evacuated for `sauckel' labor service.''
ss gen. fritz sauckel, sentenced to death at nuremberg, ran a network of slave labor camps. the 1st mountain division was operating against the anti-nazi resistance in northern greece
steinberg said the documents were made available at this time because waldheim, despite his protests, has failed to appeal the ``watchlist'' decision
these documents demonstrate the basis for that decision and the evidence is devastating,'' he said
an austrian ``white book'' rebutting charges against waldheim makes brief reference to the war diary but does not mention his role in forwarding the hitler order and does not mention the nuremberg document
steinberg said that in the ``white book'' waldheim ``ignores half the diary entry which says these instructions on treatment of bandits are being transmitted.''
the world jewish congress located the waldheim war diary and nuremberg document at the u.s. national archives in 1986 and turned them over to the justice department
a commission of historians appointed by the austrian government issued a report earlier this year saying waldheim was in a position to know of atrocities but did not try to stop them. hospitals</head>
soviet officials agreed in principle during a human rights conference that ended friday to allow american psychiatrists to visit soviet mental hospitals, a high-ranking state department official said
that could lead to examination by americans of soviets believed to be incarcerated in mental institutions solely because they are dissidents
richard schifter, assistant secretary of state for human rights, said the agreement was reached during a unique ``roundtable discussion'' between soviet and u.s. psychiatrists and legal experts
the purpose of the conference, from the american side, was to press the soviets to put into practice recent pledges to improve human rights, to allow judicial review of government actions affecting human rights and to explore ways the soviets could moderate policies on capital punishment, control of religious activity and use of mental hospitals
unlike the united states, where commitment is a legal process, the soviet union permits incarceration in a mental hospital if two psychiatrists sign the order
for years, the united states, soviet activists and psychiatrists around the world have accused the russians of using the system to lock up dissidents who are perfectly sane. the practice has reportedly been stopped in new cases, but schifter said: ``there are certain persons whose names have come up _ still in psychiatric institutions _ who in the opinion of a great many people may be there for reasons other than their mental health.''
under the agreement at the conference, in addition to visiting the soviet institutions, there may be requests for visiting psychiatrists to examine specific patients, schifter said. ``i consider that a possibility.''
soviet psychiatrists will also visit u.s. mental institutions
schifter said the u.s. government would not be involved in the exchanges, but would leave all arrangements to private psychiatric groups
at the conference, schifter said, the soviets also were willing to discuss the issue of capital punishment. he said the soviet union performs 10 times as many executions as are carried out in the united states each year and that there have been some indications moscow is examining whether to continue applying the death penalty for major economic crimes
he said the u.s. participants also suggested the soviets consider dropping use of capital punishment in national security cases. the last spies executed in the united states were julius and ethel rosenberg, who were convicted in the early 1950s of giving atomic bomb secrets to russia
among the participants in the roundtable _ the first conference of its type under a 1975 agreement to hold them _ were loren roth, of the western psychiatric institute, roger peele, director of st. elizabeth's hospital in washington and frank kaufman, a federal judge in baltimore
the soviet delegates included anatoliy l. adamishin, the deputy foreign minister, vasiliy a. vlasikhin, of the usa-canada institute and gennadily n. milekhin, of the serbskiy institute, a soviet hospital
paul kamenar of the washington legal foundation said the chief accomplishment of the conference was ``the recognition by the soviets that they have shortcomings; that they have problems.'' he said the soviets agreed to hold several workshops on human rights and appeared to be eager to talk about the rights situation
talk is cheap, but this is a beginning and we'll see where it goes,'' kamenar said. and edits to conform.</note>
president oscar arias hailed a 60-day cease-fire between the nicaraguan government and rebels as offering a ``a new and firm hope that all central americans can live in peace.''
the presidents of mexico and guatemala, meeting friday at mexico's caribbean resort of cancun to discuss the cease-fire accord, denounced what they called foreign interference and military threats in central america
they did not specifically name the united states, but their remarks appeared directed at washington
mexico is demanding absolute respect for the sovereignty of peoples'' in central america, mexican president miguel de la madrid said in a speech welcoming president vinicio cerezo of guatemala
cuba, which along with the soviet union has been helping nicaragua with military advisers and weapons, called the truce agreement a hope for peace but said it would not undermine the revolutionary principles of nicaragua's leftist sandinista government
in a dispatch, the cuban news agency prensa latina noted that president reagan said he welcomed the agreement between nicaragua and the rebels, but that he also added there ``is reason to have caution'' because of the sandinistas' past actions
it would not be surprising if the united states would now exert pressure on the contra leaders to abhor the agreement with managua and force them to retake the path of war,'' prensa latina said in its dispatch, received friday in mexico city
arias, who won the 1987 nobel peace prize for drawing up a central american peace plan that calls for cease-fires in the region's wars, said thursady he believes the nicaraguan agreement can succeed
i want to be optimistic and trust the good faith of those who signed the document,'' he said
the agreement was signed wednesday in the nicaraguan border town of sapoa, near the costa rican border
if an effective cease-fire is achieved for 60 days and can be extended there is no reason whatsoever not to advance in fulfilling the other points'' in the peace plan, he said
the peace plan, signed by the five central american presidents last aug. 7 in guatemala, also calls for democratic reforms, amnesties and an end to outside aid to insurgencies
arias said the region's conflicts also must be dealt with by the united states and soviet union ``who will have to do their share so that they get their hands out of central america.''
de la madrid and cerezo are to hold two days of talks in cancun. high on their agenda is the nicaraguan pact and u.s. efforts to force panamanian strongman gen. manuel antonio noriega out of office
we observe with worry how in central america military threats and foreign interference are taking on a new impulse ... along with economic aggression and military intimidation,'' de la madrid said in his welcoming speech
cerezo, referring to u.s. troops in honduras, said, ``we are ready to do everything possible so that the nations of the world learn to respect us and to help other peoples of the world become masters of their own destinities.''
the reagan administration sent 3,200 american soldiers to honduras last week at the request of honduran president jose azcona hoyo, who accused nicaraguan troops of crossing the border into his country to attack base camps of the u.s.-backed contras
nicaragua denied its troops had entered honduras. honduran officials said earlier this week the sandinistas had withdrawn
de la madrid and cerezo made no mention of the nicaraguan cease-fire agreement in their remarks at cancun
arias told a news conference thursday in san jose the united states was not justified in sending troops to honduras and there was no reason for them to remain there any longer
he also said he had discussed with cerezo the possibility of another meeting of central american presidents
there is much to talk about and clarify,'' he said, but did not elaborate
the 3,200-man american expeditionary force that flew here last week during a honduran-nicaraguan border crisis will start returning to the united states on monday, military intelligence sources said
the sources said the first troops of the 82nd airborne division, based at fort bragg, n.c., will return monday and the entire force will be back home within two or three days after
there was no immediate confirmation from u.s. military spokesmen here. the sources spoke on condition of anonymity
the americans were deployed here from the united states in a dramatic show of force after president jose azcona hoyo asked for help, charging that nicarguan forces had penetrated honduran territory while chasing u.s.-backed contra rebels
honduran government officials said tensions had subsided along the border and that the sandinista troops had withdrawn
it's peaceful on the border,'' presidential spokesman lisandro quesada said. ``there are no sandinista troops in honduras.''
honduras has reported several smaller incursions since the arrival of paratroopers from fort bragg and light infantry from fort ord, calif., on march 17-18
the u.s. forces continued joint training exercises friday with honduran troops at four bases throughout the country, cap. brian deloche, a public affairs officer at palmerola air base said
deloche said the soldiers expected to go home next week, but were still awaiting orders. deloche spoke by telephone from the base, about 40 milies northwest of the capital of tegucigalpa
deployment of the reinforcements brought u.s. military strength in honduras to more than 6,000, alarming even the friendly governments in the region
the sandinistas accused the united states of either preparing to invade nicaragua or using the training exercises to cover up the delivery of arms and equipment for the contras, whose u.s. military aid was cut off by congress last month
some congresmen voiced similar suspicions about the equipment brought here with the troops, including combat helicopters and large quantities of weapons
auditors from the general accounting office, congress' watchdog, were to come to palmerola to make sure the equipment went home with the troops
u.s. embassy spokesman michael o'brien said the auditors were coming at the request of several u.s. lawmakers. neither he nor deloche could say when the auditors were due in honduras
since the troops' arrival, there have been major developments in the six-year war between nicaragua's leftist government the rebels. the two sides agreed wednesday to a 60-day cease-fire as a prelude to talks on permanent peace
meanwhile, honduran military air reconnaissance thursday of the frontier in olancho and el paraiso provinces detected no sandinista activity in honduras, said eugenio castro, a foreign ministry spokesman
the ministry had filed what it called an ``energetic protest'' with nicaragua thursday over what it said were two border incursions involving a total of about 350 sandinistas this week
no confrontations were reported
in guatemala, a meeting of representatives of the five central american nations who signed a regional peace accord on aug. 7, 1987, apparently broke down over the issue of u.s. troops
nicaragua demanded withdrawal of u.s. troops from honduras and honduras countered by demanding that nicaragua withdraw a complaint filed with the world court in the hague, netherlands. the complaint accuses honduras and costa rica of harboring contras
torrential rains swept across central argentina friday and civil defense officials reported six storm-related deaths. they said flooding forced the evacuation of about 20,000 people
two women were electrocuted by downed power lines as they tried to cross streets in suburban buenos aires, according to the officials. they said a 19-year-old woman drowned in villa ponsati and three people drowned in florencio varela _ two girls ages 3 and 4 and a 24-year-old man
it was the second day of haevy rains. among those evacuated were many of the 11,000 residents of moron and quilmes near buenos aires
flooding disrupted rail and road transportation and telephone service
there were widespread power outages in buenos aires, which has a population of 10 million, and the port city of la plata, 30 miles south of the capital
weather forecasters said the rains could continue through sunday
on aug. 25, 1986, dorrian's red hand was just another upper east side bar catering to the young and upwardly mobile: a hangout for yuppies and preppies, where the izod crowd came to knock back a few
twenty-four hours later, all that changed
with the death of jennifer dawn levin early on the morning of aug. 26, dorrian's became _ fairly or unfairly _ a symbol of youthful decadence, of teen-agers with too much money and no place to go
among them was robert chambers, who sat at the bar drinking shots of tequila with beer chasers the night he killed miss levin
he fouled everybody's life up,'' bar owner john f. ``jack'' dorrian said recently. ``who needs this guy?''
after miss levin's death, investigators returned to dorrian's and closed the bar for 10 days for serving underage patrons in november 1986. dorrian has put the bar up for sale; no buyer has been found
chambers, now 21, had been a regular at dorrian's. he also was a college dropout who had a very proper upbringing
dinner at the chambers house, located next to the former andrew carnegie mansion a few blocks north of dorrian's, ``always had silver involved,'' said ralph destino, a friend of chambers, shortly after his arrest
chambers apparently had no steady job at the time of his arrest, yet was drinking and flirting ``five or six nights a week'' at dorrian's, said its owner
interviews in the months since the slaying indicate dorrian's remains attractive, a place where young people can gather in front of an ornate fireplace and play backgammon at the tables
regulars said they avoided dorrian's after miss levin died, fearing the bar had been taken over by the curious. but the young men and women who grew up in the wealthy neighborhood and knew one another in the best prep schools came back
miss levin was not a regular at dorrian's but was known there. patrons don't talk much about the case, they said
i come here when i feel like sitting around like i'm in my living room,'' said alyssa donati, 21, who said she has been frequenting dorrian's for five years
dorrian himself knows who's who in the bar; he can point out the child of a well-known writer and the daughter of a presidential adviser. john zaccaro jr., son of ex-democratic vice presidential nominee geraldine ferraro, was tending bar the night of the death
chambers would no longer be welcome, dorrian said. other regulars would say tourists, out-of-towners and the curious are not welcome either
parents like their kids to come here,'' miss donati said 17 months after miss levin's death. ``here they know the people are from at least good families, they've been to good colleges, and they're not out to rape people.'' storm across argentina, six deaths. picks up 5th graf pvs, `petrehn, head of...' adds 3 grafs at bottom on flight plan.</note>
an attempt by two u.s. adventurers to circle the earth in a balloon in 9 to 14 days was scuttled friday by bad weather, officials said
the attempt by john petrehn and rowland smith, both of kansas, to launch their 360-foot-high balloon from mendoza was canceled by heavy rains, and poor weather forecast this weekend jeopardizes the entire project, said u.s. embassy spokeswoman patricia rosker
torrential rains lashed central argentina from the atlantic to the andes for the second day and officials on friday blamed the storms for six deaths. weather forecasters said the rain would continue through sunday
ms. rosker said of the balloonists, ``the last word i have is that they're planning to launch on tuesday. that will be the final day. after that, the project will have to be canceled, which would be a pity because of all the effort they've put into this.''
the balloonists are trying to do what no one else has: circle the earth around the 45-degree parallel in the southern hemisphere using longitudinal winds that carry them to the east, ms. rosker said
petrehn, head of the project, is a 52-year-old businessman from topeka, kan., while smith, 50, is a former vietnam war pilot and a kansas-based pilot for trans world airlines
they chose mendoza, 660 miles west of buenos aires as their launch and landing site because ``apparently it was the part of the world where there are more days of sun and good weather and because it had good wind conditions,'' ms. rosker said
the balloonists have received about $2.5 million in donations for the project, which includes scientific experiments measuring ozone levels along the 45th parallel, she said
they plan to ride in a specially devised gondola. it contains a small porthole for a window, a bed and one chair. they plan to maintain contact along the route with radar and sophisticated radio equipment, she said
it has a small window like a mini-sub and is quite uncomfortable. also very dangerous because practically all the time they will be flying over water with no help. if a storm arises and it's not predicted by satellite, they will be in trouble,'' she said
two balloons, one of hot air and the other of helium, will ride piggyback above the gondola, allowing the craft to rise and fall by opening valves of hot air as it travels east with the prevailing winds, ms. rosker said
they can reach an altitude of 30,000 feet. the gondola is pressurized for their comfort and they will use the same type of food as astronauts, dehydrated food and lots of water,'' she said
according to petrehn, smith and members of the crew of 24 that helped bring the balloons and gondola to argentina, the flight would be the first non-stop, unrefueled, manned balloon trip around the world
the craft's intended flight from el plumerillo air base outside mendoza would take it over the atlantic, about 200 miles south of africa, across the indian ocean, south of australia, over the southern new zealand island of campbell island to chile where it would cross the andes and arrive back in argentina after 17,545 miles
petrehn and smith said the longest manned balloon flight was that of the double eagle v, which in 1981 crossed the pacific and covered about 5,000 miles. clarify when trial opened, update with explanation of plea bargain and quotes from victim's mother and a juror, and add detail on prior relationship of defendant and victim. picks up 18th graf pvs, `for four ...' trims last two grafs.</note>
robert chambers pleaded guilty to a lesser charge of manslaughter friday for strangling a young woman during sex in central park, halting jury deliberations in the ``preppie murder'' case after nine days
state supreme court justice howard e. bell asked chambers whether he intended to cause ``serious injury'' to 18-year-old jennifer levin ``and thereby cause her death.'' state law defines first-degree manslaughter as causing a death while intending to cause serious injury
looking back on everything, i have to say yes,'' chambers, 21, said. ``it breaks my heart to have to say that.''
at that, prosecutor linda fairstein shot up and said loudly, ``we're asking about his mind and his hands, not his heart.'' the judge repeated the question, and chambers replied, ``yes.''
chambers' mother, phyllis chambers, stared straight ahead, showing no emotion. his father, robert, also sat silently
miss levin's death in the summer of 1986 focused attention on the lives of wealthy young new yorkers. it also drew protests from feminists, who argued that chambers' defense was an example of blaming women for male violence
chambers had maintained that he never intended to hurt miss levin, whom he had dated before, and killed her accidentally with a swipe of his arm when she hurt him during rough sex. the sexual encounter was not their first
chambers originally was charged with second-degree murder, which carries a maximum sentence of 25 years to life in prison
under a plea bargain, he will be sentenced to five to 15 years. he could have received up to eight and one-third to 25 years on the charge. sentencing was set for april 15
the plea bargain, reached after two days of negotiations, came as the jury was in its ninth day of deliberations. chambers' trial began with jury selection oct. 21. opening arguments started jan. 4
manhattan district attorney robert morgenthau said that the prospect of a possible mistrial, the strain on the levin family and the circumstantial nature of the evidence prompted the plea bargain
i'll feel better tomorrow when he's in jail, where he should be,'' said ellen levin, jennifer's mother. ``he wasn't the lily-white altar boy he appeared to be.''
chambers, who was free on $157,500 bail during the trial, will surrender saturday morning, said his attorney, jack litman
chambers also pleaded guilty to second-degree burglary in an unrelated indictment, with his sentence to run concurrent with his manslaughter sentence
one juror said the votes on the murder charge swung from 8-4 for acquittal to 9-3 for conviction, and the last vote was 7-5 for acquittal. but he said he felt the jury could have reached a verdict. the judge had sealed the jurors' names, and the juror who spoke would identify himself only as mike
when lawyers involved in the burglary case appeared earlier in the day, prompting speculation about a plea bargain, miss levin's grandfather arnold domenitz, 72, said he found such talk ``sickening.''
if that wasn't so tragic, it would be funny,'' he said
shortly after miss levin's body was found, chambers told police in a videotaped statement that she had ``molested'' him sexually and hurt his genitals
for four hours during his closing argument, litman appealed to the jury to acquit chambers. ``what he was doing was reacting to the pain,'' litman said. ``he was trying to stop her'' and the result was a ``tragic accident.''
fairstein called the story ``ludicrous.'' she said he attacked miss levin in a rage, punched her, chased her when she tried to flee, caught her and ``squeezed the life out of her.''
fairstein, holding a photo of miss levin taken in a bar hours before her death, told the jury: ``one can't help but look at that photograph and pray for time to stand still, for time to grab her and say, `don't go with robert chambers.'''
the judge told the jury that while ``motive is not an element of the crime charged here,'' the lack of one is a circumstance from which they might infer innocence
fairstein had been hard put to offer a motive, and suggested chambers strangled miss levin after an argument which started when he was impotent after a night of drinking
perhaps he couldn't perform because he had too many beers and shots of tequila that night,'' she said
at 11:30 p.m. aug. 25, 1986, chambers arrived at dorrian's red hand. the bar-restaurant on manhattan's upper east side, in the heart of one of the city's wealthiest areas, was popular among privileged young people, many of them younger than new york's legal drinking age of 21
the atmosphere, bartender john zacarro jr. testified, was festive. patrons on their way to colleges table-hopped, embraced friends and laughed
that night chambers, a boston university dropout, talked with miss levin, who was planning to go to college that fall. they left together
the prosecution presented 25 witnesses and 120 exhibits, including many color photos of miss levin's bruised and nearly nude body beneath a tree behind the metropolitan museum of art where she was found by a bicyclist at daybreak
the prosecutor argued the victim's left eye, red and swollen, and the fracture in a small bone in chambers' hand show that the defendant assaulted her with ``hands as deadly as any arsenal.''
harolds club, the last remaining property in the gaming empire of the late howard hughes, has been sold, it was announced friday
the lincoln group, which owns fitzgeralds hotel-casino across the street from harolds and operates the nevada club next door, announced the purchase from hughes properties inc. the price was not disclosed
harolds club was founded in 1935 by gaming pioneer harold smith
hughes arrived in las vegas in 1966 and began buying gaming properties the following year with the purchase of the desert inn. within a few years he owned the desert inn, the landmark, the frontier, the sands, the silver slipper and the castaways in las vegas and harolds club. the reclusive billionaire died in 1976
lincoln group president phil griffith, who was president of harolds club from 1978 until 1984, called the purchase ``a project close to our hearts.'' the lincoln group also owns fitzgerald's hotel-casino in las vegas
the lincoln group said it will take over harolds on may 31 and close it for about a month for remodeling
hughes revolutionized gaming in the late 1960s by introducing corporate ownership into a business previously dominated by individual owners like smith
hughes' company in december sold its last two las vegas properties, the frontier and the silver slipper
earlier last year, it sold the desert inn and sands resorts to financier kirk kerkorian and previously sold the castaways to golden nugget owner steven wynn
the government began using newspaper ads friday to drum up information about nazi war criminals, apparently in reponse to charges it has not been energetic in pursuing perpetrators of world war ii atrocities
war criminals _ evidence wanted,'' read the heading of the ad that appeared in the times of london and other papers with national circulations
the advertisements were taken out by a special war crimes inquiry panel set up after the nazi-hunting simon wiesenthal center accused the british government of failing to seek and prosecute war criminals
it is alleged that some war criminals responsible for genocide, murder or manslaughter in germany or german-occupied territories during the second world war are in the (united kingdom),'' the ad says
others with british nationality may be living elsewhere in the world. the names of some suspects have already been sent to the home office.''
the advertisements say that when the inquiry is complete, home minister douhlas hurd will advise the government ``whether there is sufficient evidence to justify the prosecution of the alleged offenders.''
they ask anyone with ``any information that you think may be relevant'' to write the home office. the ads are to be repeated in newspapers sunday
the inquiry panel is headed by the former director of public prosecutions, sir thomas hetherington, and william chambers, a former senior government official in scotland
hetherington and chambers will spend a year investigating evidence and interviewing people with information in britain and abroad, including the soviet union
efrain zuroff, director of the wiesenthal center's israel office, last month gave british officials the names of two more alleged war criminals and more evidence against nine suspects the government already confirmed are living in britain
zuroff said at that time that the center expects dozens of suspected war criminals living in britain and other western countries to stand trial within 18 months as new legal changes close in on the suspects
he said in an interview in london last month that, before hurd set up the inquiry, britain was the only major western country that refused to take any action against alleged war criminals
the los angeles-based wiesenthal center has submitted the names of a total of 256 suspects to eight countries _ australia, brazil, britain, canada, sweden, the united states, venezuela and west germany _ where they are alleged to have fled after the war ended in 1945
the suspects are mainly from the ukraine, latvia and lithuania, all now part of the soviet union. they are accused of collaborating with nazi invaders in killing jews and others
british-resident suspects include a former lithuanian platoon commander, 71-year-old antanas gecas, who lives in edinburgh, scotland
the wiesenthal center alleges gecas killed more jews than klaus barbie, the so-called butcher of lyon. gecas, a retired mining engineer, says he is innocent and the accusations have wrecked his life
the wiesenthal center tracked down the suspects, mostly over age 70, after gaining access to international immigration data in late 1986
west germany and the united states are probing cases identified by the center, while australia and canada set up inquiry commissions and changed their laws recently to allow prosecutions
zuroff charged last month that brazil, sweden and venezuela have done little or nothing to trace the individuals or prosecute. was told he could use money for practically `any damn thing.' no pickup.</note>
gov. evan mecham, fighting charges he misused $80,000 from a ``protocol fund'' by loaning it to his auto dealership, testified friday he was told he could use the money for practically ``any damn thing that you want.''
the first-term republican said he had never heard the money referred to as public funds
testimony at the governor's senate impeachment trial in recent days has focused on his borrowing at 9 percent interest money that had been raised by his inaugural ball
state law had barred him from using the money to pay off campaign debts, and a ``protocol fund'' was set up instead last year. witnesses said the fund was intended to promote arizona through events and gifts to visiting dignitaries
the prosecution contends the fund was public money; the defense contends that it was private and that it was borrowed because mecham's dealership was in desperate financial straits
mecham said he received instructions on use of the money from william long, chairman of mecham's inaugural committee, which had raised the funds before learning they could not be used to retire campaign debts
mr. long said, `we have gone through all of this rigamarole and you can spend it for any damn thing that you want,' those were his words, `except you can't spend it for politics or personal living expenses,''' mecham testified
i never heard the words discussed, `public funds,''' the 63-year-old governor said under questioning by his attorney, jerris leonard
a key piece of evidence in the case is a letter of agreement signed by long and the maricopa county attorney agreeing that money placed in the fund could be used only to promote the interests of arizona and encourage public service
however, long, in an affidavit submitted by the defense friday, said he ``did not intend to transfer these monies as a gift to the state of arizona.''
the misuse of funds charge is the second of three impeachment counts before the senate, which earlier heard testimony on an allegation mecham attempted to obstruct an investigation of an alleged death threat. the governor has also been accused of concealing a $350,000 campaign loan
mecham, the first u.s. governor to face an impeachment trial in six decades, also faces a recall election may 17 and a criminal trial april 21 on charges of concealing the $350,000 loan
mecham, who took the stand shortly before the trial recessed for the weekend, began answering allegations that his mecham pontiac dealership was in financial trouble and needed the $80,000 borrowed in july
he and his attorney presented documents that they said showed the company had an unencumbered net value of $2.5 million at the time. a prosecution accountant had testified the company owed more than it was worth
asked about a $101,900 loan that was in default last summer, mecham said that was a mistake
quite frankly, i wasn't watching my details,'' he said. ``i was a little red faced when they caught up with me and i took care of it.''
in testimony earlier friday, mecham's son denied the family car business was in financial distress when the $80,000 loan was made in july
dennis mecham, 37, who took over as general manager of mecham pontiac when his father was elected in 1986, supported his father's statement that he borrowed the money only so it would earn higher interest than it was getting
he called up and asked if i could use $80,000 in the dealership operation,'' dennis mecham recalled of his talk with his father last july. ``i said yes. i'd say yes to anyone who had $80,000 to loan me.''
he said it was the inaugural fund and it was just sitting there,'' the younger mecham recalled. ``he wanted to roughly double the interest it was getting
i needed the money, but the rate of interest had to be reasonable. i didn't want him to stiff me,'' the younger mecham said with a laugh. ``of course, i knew he wouldn't.''
about 200 guerrillas blew a hole in the wall of el salvador's largest prison friday, entered the compound and fought guards in a half-hour battle that left two people dead, officers reported
gen. rinaldo golcher, deputy security minister, told reporters about 10 prisoners escaped from the mariona penitentiary just north of the capital of san salvador as the lestist guerrillas withdrew. no guerrilla casualties were reported
officials did not give a breakdown on the number of common criminals and the number of rebels held in mariona, a facility that normally holds 1,000 prisoners
seven guards were wounded by rifle fire and grenade shrapnel and ``some prisoners'' also were injured, golcher said. ``there are probably some dead,'' he added
a guard interviewed by journalists as he left the prison said two civilian employees were killed. some inmates set fires as the left-wing rebels launched their attack in the early afternoon, according to the guard
he said ``about 200'' guerrillas made the assault and golcher reported a large number managed to get into the prison grounds during the ``very strong'' attack
a first-aid worker said three civilian employees suffered serious bullet wounds and were taken by ambulances to hospitals
journalists were kept hundreds of yards away from the penitentiary as scores of soldiers were rushed to the prison. two helicopters flew over the compound
the guerrillas have been fighting the u.s.-backed government since 1979. prosecution, sted defense, contends dealership was in financial trouble.</note>
