phoenix, ariz. _ gov. evan mecham, defending himself on charges he misused $80,000 from a protocol fund, says he was never told that it was public money and was given carte blanche to do ``any damn thing that you want'' with the funds. should stand. by laurie asseo

pn calling reagan `extra-terrestrial,' congressmen's remarks, canal pilots say problems resolved. edits throughout to trim.</note>
the armed forces that keep gen. manuel antonio noriega in power went unpaid friday and the broke and beleaguered government ordered businesses closed by the general strike to reopen
in a decree issued under a week-old state of emergency, the civilian government that does noriega's bidding said it would take away the commercial licenses of any businesses ``offering goods and services to the public'' if they remained closed
the decree specifically mentioned grocery stores, pharmacies, transportation companies and gasoline stations
an estimated 90 percent of panama's industry and businesses have shut down in the strike, called to force noriega's removal as the head of the 15,000-member defense forces that includes the military and police
the government's inability to pay the defense forces kindled hopes in the opposition that loyalty for him will wane
several members of the defense forces, including a secretary at military headquarters, said army, navy, police and air force personnel did not receive their semi-monthly paychecks as scheduled friday
we did not receive our wages and we were not told when we would receive them,'' said the secretary, who declined to give her name. soldiers questioned by reporters also said they had not been paid
in mid-march, most of the 130,000 public employees were given partial payment of at least $75 on their salaries. those employees whose monthly salaries are $1,000 or more were not paid. social security checks have been postponed
demonstrators at the roman catholic cathedral protested the church's failure to issue a denunciation of noriega as expected
pilots who guide ships through the panama canal and claimed they had been harassed by soldiers in panama city demanded protection and met with the panama canal commission. some pilots had spoken of a strike, but commission spokesman frank castsrellon said the situation was resolved at the meeting. he did not elaborate
john maher, president of the panama canal pilots association, said: ``there is no problem now.''
noriega remained obstinate
he was asked at a military ceremony about president reagan's renewed call for his departure and he replied:
my president is called (manuel) solis palma and my geographic space is called panama. i don't take orders from extra-terrestrials.''
solis palma was named chief executive by the legislature when president eric arturo delvalle was ousted on feb. 26, the day after he tried to fire noriega
two members of the house foreign affairs committee, reps. gary ackerman, d-n.y., and peter h. kostmayer, d-pa., ended a two-day visit friday and told a news conference they thought the reagan administration should increase economic pressure on noriega
noriega is under indictment in the united states on narcotics charges. the reagan administration has cut the flow of money to panama, which uses the u.s. dollar as its currency
a threat to seize stores that refuse to open was in decree no. 16 issued under the state of emergency that enables the government to act as it deems necessary ``to secure public order,'' including suspending civil liberties
it did not say how authorities would force businesses to open
another decree issued friday said any establishment that had been closed for the past five days and sold food, meats or canned goods ``cannot reopen unless it is first inspected by the health ministry.''
it said store owners who do not comply face ``temporary suspension of their licenses or, in case of repeated violations, the cancellation of their commercial licenses.''
the strike began monday and was called by the national civic crusade, a broad alliance of noriega's opposition. crusade leaders said it would continue until noriega was ousted
panama canal employees have worked throughout protests and general strikes against noriega that began last june. the canal continues to operate normally while the nation around the waterway is at a virtual standstill
most of the canal's 230 pilots are american citizens
soldiers man roadblocks around the capital and they demand identification from drivers, search cars and rummage through personal belongings. some pilots complained about those actions
about 100 people stalked out of the cathedral after archbishop marcos g. mcgrath opened a special mass by telling worshipers and observers the church would not issue the anticipated anti-noriega statement
we don't know how this mistaken rumor originated,'' mcgrath said. ``we are sorry, but it is not our fault.''
civic crusade leaders and ackerman had said they had been assured the church would issue a strong condemnation of noriega
those who walked out stood on the steps of the gray stone cathedral chanting, ``justice! justice!'' and ``noriega must go!''
mcgrath told those remaining inside that he and noriega had a ``preparatory meeting'' thursday. he did not explain and said he could not discuss the conversation
the active-duty strength of the nation's military services declined in february from both the previous month and the year-earlier period, the pentagon said thursday
as of feb. 29, the army, navy, marine corps and air force had 2,163,193 men and women on active duty, down 2,625 from jan. 31 and a decrease of 8,914 from the feb. 28, 1987, tally
it is not unusual for military strength to swing up and down on a monthly basis during the year, primarily because of differences in the flow of new recruits
the strength totals are expected to vary even more widely than normal this year, though, because the pentagon is reducing its active-duty strength in a budget-cutting move
according to the latest ``military strength'' assessment, three of the four armed services reported personnel reductions in february
the marine corps reported 198,231 men and women on active duty, down just 12 from january. the air force had 603,599 on active duty, down 975; and the army listed 776,415, down 2,308
the navy, meantime, reported an increase of 670 personnel in february, with 584,948 on active duty at the end of the month
the marine corps and air force reported declines in strength compared with feb. 28, 1987, while the navy and army reported slightly increases
the soviet union is lending nine rare works of islamic art for an exhibition of ancient persian art and culture planned next year at the smithsonian institution's arthur m. sackler gallery and the los angeles county museum of art, it was announced thursday
the art works from the hermitage museum in leningrad and the state armory at the kremlin in moscow have been seen rarely outside the soviet union and never in the united states
the soviet loan will include a pair of 14th century gold bowls with dragon handles, two 15th century bronze oil lamps commissioned by the central asian warlord timur, also known as tamerlane, and a polychrome tile mosaic from timur's monumental tomb in samarkand
in exchange, the sackler gallery and the los angeles museum will lend master islamic paintings, calligraphies and ceramic vessels to be exhibited at the hermitage for its 225th anniversary next year
the exchange was authorized by a protocol signed recently by the soviet union, the sackler and the los angeles museum under terms of a cultural agreement reached at the 1985 geneva summit meeting between president reagan and soviet leader mikhail s. gorbachev
the american exhibition, ``timur and the princely vision: persian art and culture in the 15th century,'' will appear at the sackler from april 14, 1989, through july 9 and in los angeles from aug. 13 through nov. 5
initial support for the exhibition is being provided by the national endowment for the humanities and the smithsonian's special exhibitions fund
the federal communications commission on thursday reaffirmed its decision to abolish its policy requiring broadcasters to air conflicting views of controversial issues
the action will allow a lawsuit filed by supporters of the fairness doctrine to go forward in the u.s. court of appeals for the district of columbia
the fcc voted 3-0 to deny reconsideration of its aug. 4 decision to scrap the doctrine on the grounds that it violated the first amendment and chilled broadcasters' coverage of controversial issues of public importance
we anticipated this. we're happy the commission finally acted'' so the court case can move along, said attorney donna lambert, who with henry geller, a former fcc general counsel, are asking the court to revive the doctrine
the case before the court stems from allegations by the syracuse peace council that meredith corp. station wtvh-tv in syracyse, n.y., violated the fairness doctrine by broadcasting editorial advertisements favoring construction of a local nuclear power plant without presenting opposing views
the fcc's decision to abolish the doctrine infuriated democrats in congress, who mustered the votes to pass legislation to reinstate the policy but were unable to override president reagan's veto of the measure
these supporters say they will make another attempt to revive the policy this year, against the wishes of broadcasters who oppose the doctrine
two men were charged friday with murdering five supermarket employees during a robbery sept. 4 in which the victims were shot in the back of the head after being ordered to lie on the floor
one suspect was arrested without incident friday after a grand jury handed up the indictments; the other remained at large, said police capt. charles mccrary
each was charged with five counts of murder, one of robbery and two of assault in connection with two supermarket employees who were wounded in the hold-up after closing time by gunmen posing as a cleaning crew
investigators have said they believe the two gunmen surprised and shot to death a supermarket security guard. the four other slain employees, including a 16-year-old bag boy, were shot while lying on the floor
the gunmen robbed the cash register of several hundred dollars. most of the store's cash was kept in a safe that could be opened only with the help of a wells fargo guard, police said
mccrary said the key to the arrests was the discovery of the security guard's .38-caliber revolver in the trunk of a car brentwood police stopped for speeding
the police captain said the investigation continued another four months because ``a lot of information needed to be checked into.''
donnie blankenship of overland had been jailed since november on charges of receiving stolen property and unlawful use of the guard's weapon, but posted bail in the last week or two and remained at large, mccrary said
the other suspect, marvin jennings of overland, was taken into custody friday, mccrary said
mccrary said more people may have been involved in the crime
i'm pleased we've got the indictments, but there's more work to be done,'' he said. ``we're still at a critical point in this investigation. there are still a lot of things we can't tell you.''
relatives of the victims expressed relief
it brings a little justice if they got the right people,'' said sonja spahn, the widow of the slain security guard, 27-year-old david spahn
the pentagon on thursday expressed reservations to a house panel's plan to kill funding for a trident nuclear submarine and instead build two destroyers that would give japan more security without disclosing secret u.s. technology
it really isn't the answer,'' said lt. cmdr. chris baumann, a defense department spokesman
the house armed services seapower subcommittee voted this week to delete the administration's request for $1.4 billion for a 16th trident submarine in the fiscal 1989 budget
rep. charles e. bennett, d-fla., subcommittee chairman and architect of the funding maneuver, is wary of an administration plan to sell sophisticated aegis radar systems to japan for new japanese destroyers
instead, he wants the united states to build two extra aegis ddg-51 destroyers and station them in japanese waters under u.s. control, a move that would provide japan with extra security while not divulging technology
but baumann said bennett's plan would hinder u.s. efforts to have japan patrol its own waters. under an agreement reached early in the reagan administration, japan agreed to patrol waters out to 1,000 miles and u.s. forces would cover the rest of the pacific
what we're trying to do is get japan to do more, not to do less,'' baumann said. ``all of a sudden, we would be taking their mission.''
bennett, however, said keeping a tight rein on technology secrets should take precedent
i just don't want them to have our secret of our aegis ships,'' bennett said in a telephone interview. ``it's not just against japan. we shouldn't unnecessarily share a secret with anyone. ... it opens another channel of opportunity for spies.''
the issue comes before the full armed services committee next week, and chairman les aspin, d-wis., plans to oppose the move, said a congressional source who spoke on condition of anonymity
bennett said he did not know if the full committee would support his plan. he said that if he loses, he will take his case to the house floor, where he predicted he would prevail
meanwhile, lawmakers from connecticut and rhode island, where tridents are built by the electric boat division of general dynamics corp., vowed to fight the move
sen. john h. chafee, r-r.i., a former navy secretary, wrote to house armed service committee members urging them to reject the bennett proposal
at a time when u.s. defense resources are so stretched, and when increased burden-sharing by japan has been endorsed by both houses of congress, it seems unwise to sacrifice a crucial trident submarine in favor of this new naval commitment of questionable merit,'' chafee said
the 18,750-ton tridents each carry 24 long-range, multi-warhead missiles. trident contracts create thousands of jobs in southern new england at electric boat's plants in groton, conn., and north kingstown, r.i
the legal battle between eastern airlines and its largest union over the carrier's proposed sale of its east coast air shuttle service moved to a higher court thursday
attorneys for eastern filed papers with the u.s. court of appeals for the district of columbia, asking for dismissal of an earlier ruling that the airline was in contempt
u.s. district judge john h. pratt, who on march 10 found the airline in contempt for attempting to sell the shuttle, on wednesday denied eastern's request that he overturn his own ruling
the case pits the miami-based carrier against the international association of machinists and aerospace workers, which represents 12,000 mechanics and other ground workers at eastern. the union and the airline are in mediation seeking new contract terms
eastern, whose parent company is texas air corp., has proposed selling its shuttle to another texas air subsidiary for $225 million. company officials say eastern needs cash, but union leaders say the sale is simply an attempt to pare the union's membership
the shuttle flies between washington, new york and boston and earned a $17 million profit for eastern last year. overall, eastern lost $182 million in 1987
in another dispute, pratt ordered eastern last july to refrain from taking any actions that would alter the machinists' working conditions. on march 10, pratt ruled that the proposed shuttle deal violated that order
eastern's lawyers also want dismissal of sanctions pratt levied against the airline on monday. pratt forbade eastern to pursue government permission to sell the shuttle, and threatened $10,000-per-day fines for future transgressions
fielding questions in english and spanish, democratic presidential hopeful michael dukakis on thursday denounced the u.s. role in central america and said he would consider a hispanic running mate
courting the hispanic vote in the nation's largest spanish-language media market, the massachusetts governor said he favored a one-year extension in the deadline for illegal aliens to apply for amnesty
asked in spanish if a dukakis ticket would consider a hispanic as a vice-presidential running mate, he answered ``tal vez (perhaps),'' adding: ``vamos a ver (we'll see).''
dukakis, who noted his own ethnic background as the son of greek immigrants, impressed some spanish-speaking reporters with his command of the language, although he spoke carefully and a translation was sometimes requested
invited to a question-and-answer session were reporters, editors and executives of los angeles' spanish-language media: three daily newspapers, two television stations and at least five radio stations
in blasting the reagan administration's central american policies, dukakis said costa rica's president oscar arias deserved much of the credit for the recent cease-fire agreement between nicaragua's sandinista government and the u.s.-backed contra rebels
the reagan administration's backing of the contras and recent dispatch of u.s. troops to honduras did nothing to contribute to the peace process, dukakis declared
on the amnesty issue, dukakis called for extending the may 4 deadline by which illegal aliens must apply for temporary resident status another year
but regardless of whether congress extends the deadline, dukakis said that as president he would ensure that the immigration bureaucracy does not break up families in cases where only some members qualify for amnesty
the u.s. immigration reform act offers resident status to illegal aliens who can prove they have lived continuously in the united states for the last five years
it also sets stiff penalties for employers who knowingly hire illegal aliens
asked about the minimum wage, a perennial concern of minority groups, dukakis called for an increase
i don't see how you can support a family on $3.35 an hour,'' the candidate said
the government's massive program of public works has created jobs but fueled inflation in this caribbean nation, a top presidential aide said
it's not that we don't want stability. that's a top goal of the balaguer government,'' technical minister guillermo caram said in an interview before leaving with president joaquin balaguer on thursday for a meeting with president reagan in washington
but it has to be understood that we have to sacrifice now in order to strengthen the base for tomorrow's growth,'' caram said. ``for that, we have to make sacrifices today.''
balaguer was scheduled to meet with reagan on friday and then with officials of international lending agencies. on balaguer's agenda was the u.s. sugar quota, which he wants increased, and the dominican republic's $4 billion foreign debt
the government's $600 million program of construction of roads, bridges, schools and hospitals has created 210,000 jobs within the last year, caram said. the money, to be spent through balaguer's four-year term, has spurred the country's economic growth rate to 9 percent, he added
but it also touched off double-digit inflation that private economists say is closer to 40 percent than the official government figure of 30 percent
the foreign exchange value of the peso, the dominican currency, has declined steadily since and now is worth less than 20 cents. just four years ago the peso traded evenly with the u.s. dollar
increases in prices of gasoline, milk, rice and other basic commodities earlier this month touched off strikes and skirmishes between soldiers and stone-throwing youths. the clashes threatened to escalate into full-scale riots such as occurred in april 1984, when more than 100 people died
balaguer fended off protestors by pledging to increase the minimum wage by 30 percent to $75 a month, and to implement price controls. representatives from the government, labor, private business and the influential roman catholic church are to meet for a second time in early april
politically, the 80-year-old balaguer seems to be in firm control. he began a fifth presidential term in august 1986 after being out of office for two consecutive terms
the opposition dominican revolutionary party, split into camps supporting former presidential candidate jacobo majluta and former santo domingo mayor jose francisco pena gomez, has not sought to use the unrest to challenge balaguer
relief may come from washington
balaguer would like the united states to lift its sugar import quota from the dominican republic from its current level of 160,000 tons annually. in 1983, the quota was 525,000 tons a year
in 1987, revenue from sugar sales was a record low $150 million
balaguer also would like international lending agencies to ease his country's debt repayment schedule, which last year totaled $700 million, or almost the entire value of dominican exports
u.s. ambassador lowell kilday traveled with the balaguer delegation, which includes central bank governor roberto saladin
before returning home, balaguer, who suffers from glaucoma and is nearly blind, was scheduled to visit a hospital in boston for an eye examination
u.s. roman catholic bishops, at odds over what role the church should play in aids education, will discuss the issue at their june meeting in minnesota, the president of the national bishops conference said thursday
archbishop john l. may of st. louis said the administrative board of the u.s. catholic conference decided at its two-day session, which ended thursday, to schedule a discussion of ``the pastoral, theological and moral dimensions of aids.''
the board agreed that the discussion should ``be open-ended in format with its direction determined by the will of the bishops,'' may said
he added that the discussion at the june 24-27 meeting in collegeville, minn., would be held in executive session
the bishops conference's board recommended last december that condom use be explained in church-sponsored aids education programs, touching off a spate of criticism from conservative bishops
those bishops, led by cardinals bernard law of boston and john o'connor of new york, said they would not allow condom use to be explained or discussed in their dioceses' schools, hospitals and youth programs. and they argued that abstinence is ``the only morally acceptable way to avoid the sexual transmission of aids.'' aids, or acquired immune deficiency syndrome, is spread through close contact with blood or semen from infected persons
the conservative bishops were particularly concerned that the bishops conference's 50-member board had made the condom recommendation without a full vote of the conference's 380 members
in the wake of the criticism, may had suggested that the full body of bishops discuss the issue at their meeting in minnesota, and the administrative board made that recommendation official. two lawsuits</note>
gary hart won permission thursday to use whatever is left of his skimpy 1988 campaign fund toward paying off the $1.15 million debt from his 1984 presidential campaign
he cannot use any of the $1.12 million in federal matching funds he received, however, leaving the prospect of only a projected $100,000 or so in the kitty to transfer to the 1984 creditors once the 1988 accounts are settled, his campaign said
somewhat ironically, it was only hart's exit from the 1988 race this month that won him federal election commission permission to transfer the funds
were he still a candidate, he would be excluded from using the 1988 money for anything other than 1988 campaign-related expenses, the commission ruling said. he had submitted the request before he quit the race on march 11, so the commission was in a position of applying a different set of rules to the question
once a campaign is concluded, the leftover money can be used for any lawful purpose, election regulations state. that would include paying some of the 1984 debts
but it is unclear how much money hart will have left by the time he pays winding down costs and the fec conducts its lengthy audit process. he must return to the federal treasury anything left of the federal matching funds that he received this year. matching funds accounted for about one-third of his total fund raising for 1988
hart's campaign attorney, bernie schneider, said the campaign was pleased with the fec decision
he anticipated that after final 1988 bills are paid, the campaign will have about $110,000 leftover to apply to the 1984 debt
commissioner lee ann elliott at thursday's meeting raised doubts that any any significant amount will remain
we're going to be talking about a small trickle of money as against the '84 debt,'' she said
and the ruling thursday does not end the saga of hart's nearly four-year-old debt, and schneider said hart will still work on raising money to pay the rest
nobody is running away,'' he said, but he could not specify what kind of fund-raising efforts will be undertaken by the former colorado senator
some creditors have taken hart to court _ so far unsuccessfully _ to try and place liens on the 1988 funds to recoup money they are owed from 1984
one creditor got a court order that resulted in federal marshals seizing $30,000 in proceeds at a hollywood fund-raiser for hart last year
two businesses filed suit in denver. tri-state envelope corp. of beltsville, md., claims hart owes it $133,600. semper-moser associates of venice, calif., an advertising agency, claims it is owed $172,920
hart's most recent campaign financial statement showed that at the end of february he had $488,966 in cash on hand and $34,661 in bills to pay
schneider said the fec audit staff will probably begin its audit in the summer. the agency audits all presidential campaigns as a routine once the campaign is concluded. the agency was still finishing up 1984 audits last year
the fec decision thursday came in response to hart's second request on the same topic. he first asked if he could use 1988 funds toward the 1984 debt last spring. but after the commission denied him federal matching funds on the basis that he was not an active candidate, his campaign withdrew the request as moot
he withdrew from the race for the first time in may in the wake of disclosures about his relationship with part-time miami model donna rice
when hart re-entered the race last fall, he resubmitted the request in hopes of wiping out the nagging 1984 debt
a federal appeals court has refused an immediate ban on the spraying of herbicides on federal rangeland in oregon and washington
in an order made public thursday, a three-judge panel of the 9th u.s. circuit court of appeals denied an emergency injunction sought by rural and environmental groups. the court said it would explain its reasons later
however, no spraying is expected until at least late spring, said norma grier, director of the northwest coalition against pesticides, one of the groups filing suit
she said she hoped the court would rule before then on the groups' appeal of a decision by a federal judge in oregon who ruled the u.s. bureau of land management had adequately studied the environmental effects of the weed-killer
the chemicals, including the controversial 2,4-d, are to be sprayed on weeds that threaten forage or cause other harmful effects on blm land in the two states
u.s. district judge james burns blocked the spraying in 1984, ruling that the blm's environmental analysis had not considered the range of possible danger to humans
the agency, supported in the case by a group of farmers and ranchers, revised its analysis last year and concluded that under the worst foreseeable circumstances, the herbicides were still relatively safe
burns in november lifted his injunction
at a hearing march 7 in portland, ore., opponents asked the appellate court to reinstate the ban while it considers their appeal of burns' ruling
the appellate court's unanimous order thursday did not address the merits of burns' ruling, which remains under appeal
john dilorenzo, a lawyer for a group of farmers, ranchers and herbicide users called oregonians for food and shelter, said he was encouraged by the court's decision. the group considers the herbicides safe
but ms. grier said the government agency had ignored studies showing health problems and had failed to consider non-chemical approaches
the bureau ``should have looked at how to prevent problems before they exist,'' she said. ``are we managing our lands in a way that encourages problem weeds? could we alter the use of land by livestock in a way that would make the land less susceptible to noxious weed problems?''
a record number of voters turned out thursday for an election late polls indicated would oust the incumbent government of this british fortress colony
clive coon, the government press officer, said 13,325 _ or 76 percent _ of gibraltar's 17,530 registered voters cast ballots. the previous record, 74 percent, was set in 1984, the last election for the 15-seat house of assembly
opinion polls among 29,000 citizens this week indicated victory for joe bossano and his gibraltar socialist labor party over incumbent chief minister adolfo canepa of the long-dominant association for the advancement of civil rights
coon attributed the high turnout to ``a lovely day.''
an opinion poll published this week by the gibraltar magazine panorama indicated 63 percent of voters favored bossano, 26 percent were for canepa and 11 percent supported the independent democratic party of joe pitaluga
canepa's party controlled the government for all but three years since 1945 under the flamboyant leadership of sir joshua hassan, who retired last december at age 72
bossano, 48, advocates self-determination and opposes spain's efforts to regain sovereignty over the 2.2 square miles of limestone rock on its southern coast
bell of pennsylvania announced thursday that it is clarifying instructions to sales representatives and mailing information to customers following charges of deceptive sales practices
the announcement came after the state attorney general and consumer advocate filed a suit and a complaint alleging the state's biggest phone company stuck customers with such options as call waiting, three-way calling and speed calling
while insisting the allegations were unjustified, regis filtz, bell vice president and chief operating officer, said the telephone company was taking steps to resolve what he called confusion about the options
we are going beyond what normally we would do to strengthen and clarify and assure there is absolutely no misunderstanding in terms of what customers order, what options they get, what the value of those options is (and) what the prices are,'' filtz said
we believe we go the extra mile to make sure that customers are fully informed about their services, and have every opportunity to change it whenever they wish.''
state consumer advocate david barasch said the company is ``at least in part admitting the allegations we've been making.''
but the state has not withdrawn the suit filed monday in state court or the complaint filed with the state public utility commission
the allegations made by barasch and attorney general leroy zimmerman were based on 32 test calls made to bell representatives. of those calls, more than 70 percent were assigned one, two or three optional services they had not requested or were not told were optional
in one case, an agent posing as a single mother on welfare was assigned service at $28.55 monthly, when basic service could have been obtained for $6.65 per month, the officials said
barasch alleged the representatives were subject to quotas or ``bonus'' plans geared to the optional services
filtz said the workers did not receive commissions but can qualify for prizes including toasters, appliances and pizza lunches based on sales performance
in a complaint filed with the puc, barasch said bell representatives followed guidelines directing them to include certain options, including a maintenance plan, when recommending rates to new customers
the ``clarified'' guidelines do not include such instructions, and also specify that customers be told the services such as call forwarding and call waiting are optional
bell of pennsylvania has more than 3.7 million customers, or about 80 percent of the state's telephone lines
the puc complaint and the lawsuit seek fines, an end to the allegedly deceptive sales practices, and customer refunds that barasch said could involve millions of dollars
federal authorites raided espionage suspects thursday and made at least one arrest, the bild daily newspaper reported
numerous offices and apartments were searched in connection with the operation,'' it said, citing unidentified security experts
bild said the raids may have been connected to the arrest of elke falk last friday as a spy suspect. she was working as a secretary in the federal ministry for economic cooperation in bonn. ms. falk worked in the west german chancellory from 1974 to 1977 and in several ministries in later years
the brief bild account, which was to appear in friday editions, gave no details. it was telexed to other news organizations in advance late thursday
government officials could not be reached for comment immediately
ms. falk is suspected of having worked as a spy for years, according to the federal prosecutor's office
she is being held in investigative custody and has not yet been charged with any crimes, officials said
in the last major spy scandal to rock the government, 15 communist agents were arrested or disappeared between august and december 1985
a family trying to force payment of a $4 million jury award has obtained a freeze on the city's bank accounts, apparently plunging this desperately poor community into a payroll crisis
at least $85,000 in city checks were outstanding when the accounts were frozen wednesday, including about $37,000 in paychecks issued march 15 but not yet cashed by municipal employees, said city treasurer charlotte moore
that kind of puts us in a destitute situation,'' said alderman melvin frierson. ``my real interest right now is payroll. that's critical.''
mayor carl officer and city attorney samuel f. ross jr. did not return calls thursday, but officials have said there was no way a municipality with an annual budget of about $6 million could afford to pay a $4 million
the money was awarded in 1985 to walter debow, a granite city man who suffered permanent brain damage when he was beaten by a fellow inmate in the east st. louis jail
in november, the illinois supreme court ordered the city of 55,000 people to pay the judgment, clearing the way for the debow family to seize its bank accounts
on wednesday, city accounts containing about $1.2 million were frozen at four local banks
clyde kuehn, debow's attorney, said he did not think the city would file for bankruptcy in federal court, a move that would put a court-appointed trustee in control of municipal funds. ``they don't want a trustee running the city,'' he said
as far as the people of east st. louis are concerned, this isn't going to hurt the citizens any more than they already are,'' he said. ``they already don't get their trash picked up. they already have a fire department and police department that isn't properly equipped.''
william stodghill, president of local 50 of the service employees international, said the 35 or 40 city hall employees represented by his union would meet monday to discuss options that could include a walkout
east st. louis, once a thriving industrial city, became one of the nation's poorest with the decline of the industries and the exodus of whites in the 1960s
the city is 98 percent black, and 61 percent of its residents receive some kind of assistance. unemployment is unofficially estimated at 40 percent
debow, who had been arrested for driving with an open bottle of malt liquor, was placed in a cell with a man who was being held on misdemeanor charges but had a history of violent crime
the man beat debow severely, causing permanent brain damage, said kuehn, adding his client would need constant medical care for the rest of his life
a former nuclear technician who claimed he revealed israel's atomic secrets for the good of humanity was convicted thursday of espionage and treason and could be sentenced to 20 years in prison
mordechai vanunu, 34, was found guilty by a three-judge panel after a trial that had been closed to the public since it began in september. his lawyer said vanunu would appeal the verdict to israel's supreme court
mordechai is very disappointed,'' said defense attorney avigdor feldman. ``the court decided that he was a traitor, and he had hoped to be seen differently. but he is not broken. he is looking ahead to the appeal.''
the conviction carries a maximum sentence of death. however, prosecutor uzi chasson said he would ask the court for a sentence of life imprisonment, which in israel is limited to 20 years. sentencing is set for sunday
vanunu, who worked nine years at the nuclear facility in dimona, was charged for revealing details of israel's atomic capacity to the sunday times of london in october 1986
the newspaper said vanunu's information showed israel had stockpiled the world's sixth-largest nuclear arsenal
israel never has responded directly to allegations of its nuclear capacity, saying only it would not be the first country to introduce such weapons into the middle east
vanunu has insisted he made his revelations to alert the middle east and the world to the dangers of nuclear weapons. the state argued he intended to harm israel's security
he was kept under heavy security during the trial, which was closed to the public because authorities feared an open hearing would harm state security
vanunu has been held in near isolation for the last 18 months and has been permitted to see only his attorney and family
the precautions were taken after vanunu managed to flash a message to reporters at a pre-trial appearance by scribbling it on the palm of his hand. in the message he said he had been kidnapped in rome, presumably by israeli agents, and brought to israel for trial
vanunu was fired from the dimona nuclear center in 1985 and went to australia, where he became acquainted with a priest and converted to christianity
he later traveled to london, but disappeared in october 1986, just days before the sunday times published his revelations. israeli officials acknowledged several weeks later he was in custody in israel
details of vanunu's journey back to israel were revealed by his brother, meir vanunu, who said vanunu was lured from london to rome by an american woman named cindy, who promised him sex. in rome, he was abducted by israeli agents and spirited home, meir said
during the trial, feldman argued vanunu did not hurt israel's security because information about israel's nuclear capacity was available in the academic world. he said vanunu had in fact helped state security because allegations of israel's nuclear strength served as a deterrent to arab enemies
andrew neil, editor of the sunday times, said thursday in london that vanunu was warned of the risks before divulging his information. neil said that vanunu replied he was prepared to take them because he wanted israelis to know their country was a nuclear power
but we will always regret that he did not take our warnings seriously enough, with the tragic consequences of his abduction which followed,'' said neil
neil said his paper was concerned about the way vanunu was taken from britain and regretted he was convicted
we understand that democratic governments must protect secrets in the national interest and that most israeli citizens regard vanunu as a traitor,'' neil said. ``but the citizens of every other democratic nuclear power are not debarred from knowing that their countries have nuclear weapons _ the nature of the defense of their countries is one of their fundamental democratic rights.''
stock prices tumbled thursday even as the government reported that americans' personal incomes and consumer spending surged in february
on wall street, the dow jones average of 30 industrials fell 43.77 points to 2,023.87. declining issues outnumbered advances by more than 5 to 1 on the new york stock exchange whose composite index dropped 2.82 to 149.00
analysts cited a continued decline in the dollar, which fell to its lowest level in nearly two months against the japanese yen and west german mark, as contributing to the weakness in stocks
in its latest eonomic report, the commerce department said personal incomes advanced 0.9 percent in february, reflecting strong employment gains in the past few months. spending rose 0.7 percent, up sharply from a tiny 0.1 percent january increase
meanwhile, the government reported the savings and loan industry last year recorded its worst annual loss since the great depression
the federal home loan bank board said a $3.2 billion loss in the last three months of 1987 pushed the industry's red ink for the year to a record $6.8 billion. that was nearly 50 percent greater than the previous post-depression record of a $4.6 billion, set in 1981
elliott ``pete'' estes, who rose from junior engineer to president of general motors corp. during a 42-year career with the automaker, died of an apparent heart attack thursday. he was 72
estes, a resident of paradise valley, ariz., served as gm president and chief operating officer from 1974 until his retirement in 1981
estes collapsed outside o'hare international airport of an apparent heart attack, police said. he was pronounced dead on arrival at resurrection hospital, according to hospital spokeswoman janice youngwith
estes, a native of mendon, mich., began his long-time relationship with gm in 1934 when he enrolled at general motors institute in flint, mich. he joined gm research laboratories as a cooperative student while at the institute
estes became a gm research engineer in 1939, a year before he graduated from the university of cincinnati with a degree in mechanical engineering
in 1946, estes joined the oldsmobile division in lansing, mich., as a motor engineer
in 1961 he was elected a gm vice president and general manager of the pontiac motor divison. he became general manager of the chevrolet motor division in 1965 and executive vice president for gm operations staff in 1972
pete estes was one of gm'ss brightest stars. in whatever role he assumed for the corporation, he performed at peak capacity,'' gm chairman roger b. smith said in a statement
he demanded excellence from his subordinates, but he always drove himself harder than anyone else. ... general motors is a stronger and better corporation because pete estes served it.''
survivors include his wife, connie, and three sons
funeral arrangements were incomplete
iran's hashemi rafsanjani said thursday that britain must help free iranian hostages in lebanon before iran will intervene on behalf of anglican envoy terry waite and another missing briton, the bbc reported
a spokesman for archbishop of canterbury robert runcie said, ``if he (rafsanjani) is confirming that john mccarthy and terry waite are alive and being well treated by captors that is indeed good news.''
at a news conference in tehran attended by british broadcasting corp. correspondent john simpson, parliament speaker rafsanjani said britain must help free three missing iranians kidnapped by right-wing christian phalangists in summer 1982
simpson interpreted his remarks as indicating waite and british reporter john mccarthy were alive. they are among 24 foreigners missing in lebanon. the bbc radio report, broadcast in london, made no mention of non-british western hostages. the longest held hostage is terry anderson, chief middle east correspondent of the associated press, who was kidnapped on march 16, 1985
rafsanjani said at first that he did not know if they were alive or dead,'' simpson said in a broadcast from the iranian capital. but when pressed, he began to talk of the conditions for their release
waite, runcie's personal envoy, disappeared jan. 20, 1987 after leaving his west beirut hotel to negotiate with an islamic group in his efforts to gain the release of western hostages
no claim of responsibility has even been made in waite's disappearance
simpson said, ``he (rafsanjani) accepted that there was a clear difference between on the one hand mr. waite, from a religious background and mr. mccarthy, a journalist and, on the other, a spy or a military man.''
when simpson said that the iranians were almost certainly dead, rafsanjani said someone should show iran the bodies
the news conference took place during an iraqi air strike in which three missiles fell on the city
rafsanjani showed no reaction during the bombing
mccarthy, a journalist for the london-based worldwide television news agency, was kidnapped april 17, 1986
two other britons are being held, along with nine americans and other nationalities
the irish republic's broadcasting service said thursday it gave british police video segments of an angry funeral mob attacking two soldiers at an ira funeral
rte turned over the videotape one day after britain's two television networks, the british broadcasting corp. and independent television news, complied with similar demands for unbroadcast footage from the funeral
britain's defense ministry, meanwhile, denied british news reports that the two soldiers were on an undercover mission when they were hauled from their cars, beaten severely and then shot to death
the three networks initially refused to hand over unbroadcast film on the ground it would endanger crews covering future violence in the british-ruled province
they complied after the royal ulster constabulary, the provincial police force, threatened court action under british anti-terrorist legislation
the two british corporals, derek wood, 24, and david howes, 23, were dragged from a car by a mob at an irish republican army funeral in belfast on saturday. they were beaten with iron bars and then taken to a nearby soccer stadium, where ira guerrillas shot them to death
the crowd stopped tv crews filming when the soldiers were pulled from the car
rte said two detectives called at its offices in belfast and took away a 65-second videotape of the attack. the network said most of the film was transmitted on the network
security forces will examine the film to try to identify those who took part
the defense ministry thursday denied a report in the news, arts and current affairs magazine the spectator that wood and howes were on an undercover mission in west belfast when attacked. they were in plainclothes in an unmarked car at the time
the spectator, which supports the governing conservative party, said: ``we shall never be told, though it seems to be the case, that cpls. wood and howes were on an undercover operation.'' it gave no other details
members of the royal corps of signals are often employed on surveillance work and other undercover activity. but a ministry spokesman, who in accordance with british practice refused to be identified, said the claim in the spectator was ``inconceivable.''
the army has said it thinks the soldiers may have become involved with the cortege purely by accident while on their way to their base at lisburn barracks south of belfast
parliament has passed a law that will provide payments of up to $416 each to people victimized by the nazis when austria was under german rule during world war ii
the law, which had been planned for months, was passed wednesday by all three main political parties in parliament. five of the six deputies from the small greens party voted against it, saying the measure provided too little compensation
under the law, those deemed to have suffered under nazi rule will receive one-time payments of from $208 to $416 at current exchange rates. the payments vary depending on whether the potential recipient was persecuted by the nazis, forced to leave the country or served in the resistance
no estimates have been published of how many people will be eligible for payment
alfred dallinger, the socialist welfare minister in the coalition government, told parliament he hoped the payments would be understood as a symbolic gesture, since no sum could compensate for such suffering
adolf hitler sent his troops to annex austria to the third reich in march 1938, a move many austrians welcomed
austria already pays small pensions to individuals persecuted by the nazis. unlike west germany, however, it never paid compensation to israel or any other state or group for nazi crimes
the proposal was approved by the socialist party, the conservative people's party and the rightist freedom party
austria has been mired in a controversy over president kurt waldheim's wartime past. waldheim served as a lieutenant in a german army unit in the occupied balkans. his unit was linked to war crimes, including the deportation of jews to concentration camps and the murders of partisans
waldheim kept his military service in the area secret until 1986 and has denied wrongdoing since. a historians' commission said waldheim was in a position to know about nazi war crimes and did nothing to stop them. buy</head>
a judge has awarded the state permanent custody of a 2-year-old whose mother accused of having used him as collateral for $50 worth of cocaine
lou ann powell, 26, did not appear at wednesday's court session during which cook county circuit judge claude whitaker stripped her of all parental rights to her son, anthony
the boy has been in foster care since he was found outside a day labor agency june 16
ms. powell told authorities when she identified the child in october that she had a cocaine habit, was behind in payments to a drug dealer and had offered the boy as collateral
she apparently planned to redeem him when she got some money, kind of like when you take a promissory note from the bank,'' frank giunta, a police youth division investigator, said at the time
ms. powell was charged with felony abandonment, said lisa howard, spokeswoman for the state's attorney office
anthony's foster parents already have moved to adopt him, and we hope that becomes final soon,'' said dave schneidman, spokesman for the state department of children and family services
ms. powell is also charged with neglect stemming from her treatment of her younger son, joseph, 13 months old. ms. howard said authorities will seek to have her parental rights to joseph terminated in that case
mayor w. wilson goode on thursday proposed a $1.93 billion budget that would turn trash collection over to a contractor, freeze wages and raise taxes for the first time since he took office in 1984
the mayor of the nation's fifth-largest city, in asking for a $67 million tax increase, left it up to city council to decide which taxes to raise
the increase will help ``meet human needs, create jobs, promote economic development, care for and nurture our children and revitalize our neighborhoods,'' said goode, a democrat elected in november to a second term
his budget for fiscal 1989, which starts july 1, represents a 6.4 percent increase over the current budget of $1.86 billion
goode proposed cutting $50 million in costs through new labor contracts or new contract terms and by turning over garbage collection to private industry, a move that could eliminate several thousand jobs and save $35 million annually
garbage collection in philadelphia has come under attack as sloppy and rife with overtime abuse
i am a lifelong supporter of organized labor and while part of my financial plan anticipates privatization, which they may find difficult, i am resolute in pursuing this only to the extent that labor fails to work with the city to find meaningful and cost effective alternatives,'' goode said
the mayor's budget offers no wage increase to the city's blue-and white-collar employees, whose contracts expire this summer. the spending plan does not include the school system, which has proposed a $1 billion budget
it would add $44.3 million to basic services, which include police and fire protection, street cleaning, job training, housing rehabilitation and programs for children, the homeless and aids victims, who would receive $7.5 million
tax revenue for the current fiscal year is projected at $1.4 billion. the mayor's spending plan for the coming year projects tax revenue of $1.5 billion
everybody's inclination is against a tax increase,'' said councilman david cohen, a democrat
republican councilman thacher longstreth said he considered raising taxes ``a disgrace'' but also said it probably would be done
council president joseph coleman, a democrat, said: ``we are going to have to raise taxes or cut the budget tremendously.''
a pre-dawn fire friday killed 19 female workers in a factory dormitory on the outskirts of seoul and badly injured four, police reported
police officials said 17 workers suffocated from poisonous fumes as the fire consumed rolls of fabric and two workers died in a hospital of injuries
they said 28 women in all were asleep on the third-floor dormitory of a building in seoul's anyang district when fire broke out about 2 a.m. rolls of fabric were stored in the stairway between the second and third floors, police said
five workers escaped unhurt
the cause of the fire is under invetigation, police said
a pilot testified thursday that he took his 4-year-old son with him as cover while flying cocaine into the united states for alleged drug kingpin carlos lehder rivas
i believe he was the youngest drug smuggler at that time,'' said andrew richard barnes, 32
lehder, 38, is on trial on charges of smuggling about 3.3 tons of cocaine into the country from colombia via norman's cay in the bahamas from 1978 to 1980
barnes, a native of england known as british andy, said he transported 3,000 kilograms, or about 6,600 pounds, for lehder while working for him in 1978 and again in 1980
barnes told the jury that he would receive a telephone call the night before each trip from one of lehder's employees
come over and pick up the children and take them to school,'' was the message he said he received. ``children'' was lehder's term for cocaine, witnesses have testified
in october 1980, barnes said, he transported two loads of 450 to 500 kilos each from norman's cay, which was lehder's private island, into fort lauderdale international airport
he (lehder) said it was the largest loads we'd done,'' barnes said, adding he was paid $225,000 for the flights
three other flights were made in the latter part of 1980, and barnes said he took his son with him to appear that they were on a family outing
lehder is charged with conspiracy, possession of cocaine with intent to distribute, importation of cocaine and operating a continuing criminal enterprise
co-defendant jack carlton reed, 57, of san pedro, calif., is charged with taking part in a smuggling conspiracy
jazz trumpeter al hirt was admitted to a hospital thursday for treatment of an infection in his playing hand
the 65-year-old bourbon street musician flew from his home in new orleans to be under the care of his friend, famed heart surgeon michael debakey, at methodist hospital
i had this infection or something in my hand. it's like blood poisoning. it looks like it's from a bite or something. it's all swollen and has red streaks,'' hirt said
but my prognosis is excellent. i'm going to be ok as long as i can keep blowing the trumpet.''
hirt said doctors think the problem may be a related to his trumpet playing and a growth that developed on a finger of his right hand after 59 years of horn work
he was expected to remain hospitalized for at least several days, debakey said. hirt had been scheduled to perform at a benefit thursday for the financially troubled new orleans symphony
the prognosis is excellent for mr. hirt,'' debakey said. ``i am sorry he will miss his performance, but his health is most imporant at this point.'' news digest: washington _ pm-treaty obstacles, a0432; managua, nicaragua _ pm-nicaragua, a0461; undated _ pm-political rdp, a0413; panama city, panama _ pm-panama, a0479; jerusalem _ pm-israel, a0415; charleston, w.va. _ pm-blue flu, a0473.</note>
secretary of state george p. shultz is raising the possibility that the administration will seek legislative authority for a quick vote on military aid to the nicaraguan rebels if the cease-fire there breaks down
shultz said thursday night that the prospect of additional military assistance to the rebels would be added insurance that nicaragua's leftist government will abide by promises it makes under its cease-fire agreement with the contra rebels
but house speaker jim wright, d-tex., indicated that he would oppose any effort by the administration to have an ``expedited procedures'' provision for military aid included in a contra humanitarian assistance package the congress will take up next week
recent polls and his own need to come up with a victory in the north have forced democrat albert gore jr. to back off from his claims that rival michael dukakis can't win in november
in the glow of his southern victories two weeks ago, gore was depicting dukakis as having the electoral appeal of george mcgovern and walter mondale
campaigning in the north now, gore has halted the harsh rhetoric. and with recent polls showing dukakis _ not gore _ as the only democrat running even nationwide with gop front-runner george bush, gore is having a more difficult time pinning his rival with the image of the democrats' landslide losers of 1972 and 1984
