in zurich, the bid price was $451.80, down from $452 late thursday
earlier, in hong kong, gold fell $1.32 an ounce to close at $454.08
silver was quoted in london today at a bid price of $6.68 a troy ounce, up from late thursday's $6.61
the dollar closed slightly lower against the japanese yen on the tokyo foreign exchange market today, while stock prices shed more than 150 points following declines in both currency and stock markets overseas
the dollar opened at 125.68 yen, down 0.62 yen from its thursday closing, and closed the week at 125.74 yen
japan's central bank reportedly purchased an estimated $200-300 million during the morning to prop up the sagging currency. the bank of japan does not comment on its monetary policies, including market intervention
on the tokyo stock exchange, the nikkei stock average of 225 selected issues, which lost 113.95 points thursday, closed today at 25,626.71, down 154.57 points, or 0.59 percent
the tokyo market ``was discouraged largely by an overnight decline in the new york market,'' said masahiro umemori, a stock researcher at nomura securities, japan's largest brokerage firm
the dow jones industrial average lost 43.77 points to close at 2,023.87 points thursday
umemori said stock prices in tokyo kept rising ``at a rapid pace'' in recent weeks and just ``took a little respite the past two days.''
commenting on foreign exchange transactions, a dealer at the bank of tokyo, who spoke on condition of anonymity, said there were ``no major negative market-affecting factors domestically'' to explain the dollar decline
she said there still was a chance for ``the yen's further appreciation against the dollar'' and predicted the dollar would hover at a range between 123.00-127.00 yen next week
