britain's merchandise trade deficit narrowed 8 percent in february, while the country's annual inflation rate was unchanged at 3.3 percent, the government said friday
the trade gap totaled 1.32 billion pounds, or $2.43 billion, far above market expectations of an 875 million-pound gap, but economists warned that new customs rules adopted at the beginning of the year continued to distort the figures
the pound, british government bonds and british stocks nonetheless tumbled on the news. even if the pound shows renewed strength in the near term, analysts said the trade report makes a further cut in interest rates remote
in january, the merchandise trade deficit came to a revised 1.44 billion pounds, the department of trade and industry said
britain had a current account deficit, which includes invisible trade such as financial services, of 720 million pounds last month, narrower than a revised january deficit of 844 million pounds but wider than market expectations of a gap around 270 million pounds
britain's retail price index rose 0.4 percent in february from january and was up 3.3 percent from february 1987, the department of employment said in its inflation report
in january, the index was unchanged from the previous month and also up 3.3 percent from a year earlier
the index, which uses a january 1987 base of 100.0, stood at 103.7 in february, up from 103.3 in january, and up from 100.4 in february 1987
the department said the rise in the index between january and february was mainly the result of higher prices for fresh and vegetables, and with the end of the winter sales period, prices for clothing and other goods were higher
prices were lower for petroleum products and motor vehicles
police have only bits and pieces of disintegrated bank checks to go on as they try to crack a dissolving paper caper that has hit at least two states and cost banks nearly $70,000
the checks, treated with a chemical that makes them disintegrate three or four hours after being deposited, have turned up at five or six banks in the chicago area and two in tennessee, police said thursday
the one i've got in front of me looks like a handful of ashes,'' said capt. james zurawski of the police department's financial crimes division
a check clearinghouse said it has warned 142 banks to be on the lookout for the dissolving checks, which may have an unusual odor and feel oily
the checks, drawn on personal accounts at banks in california and chicago, have been reported in about 12 incidents, zurawski said. authorities are also checking a report of a possible dissolving check in indiana
in most cases, someone opens a new account at a bank with a small amount of money and later make a large deposit with a dissolving check. then the money is withdrawn before the bank learns the big check was bogus
the check's decomposition leaves little for evidence
police believe more than one person is involved, but have no suspects because of the dissolving evidence, zurawski said
so far nobody's been harmed by it. the only clue we've got is we've talked to the tellers. one teller says that the check felt oily, another said it had a funny aroma,'' the captain said
on thursday, zurawski's office received copies of five checks for a total of $20,000 drawn on a chicago bank and deposited at a bank in memphis, tenn. ``they're in bits and pieces,'' he said
the scam has cost banks about $70,000, he said
the chicago clearing house association, which clears checks for 142 members, sent out a memo march 9 warning of the dissolving checks, said vice president tom tucker
the association first learned of the checks from northern trust bank, which has been hit by at least three disintegrating checks since feb. 16, tucker said
chicago police learned of the dissolving checks about two weeks ago, zurawski said. ``what happened was two checks showed up in one of our downtown banks and they literally dissolved,'' he said
northern learned on march 4 that two other checks for more than $8,000 dissolved after being processed by jewel food stores, which offers banking services for some customers
officers from jewel told the bank that a worker saw one of the checks start ``to sweat and deteriorate from its borders.'' the worker tried to prevent further disintegration by putting the check in a paper envelope, but the envelope also began to dissolve, investigators said
northern trust declined to comment. ``we are not at liberty to discuss customer accounts,'' said a spokeswoman who asked not to be identified
south korea's gross national product grew 12 percent last year, down from a growth rate of 12.3 percent in 1986, the bank of korea announced friday
the gnp totaled $118.6 billion last year, compared $98.3 billion in 1986, according to the central bank's preliminary estimate
the central bank had projected a growth rate of 12.2 percent for 1987, based on economic growth in the first three quarters of the year
bank officails said exports, the mainstay in the korean ecnomy, accounted for 46.1 percent of the gnp last year when korean exports soared to a record $47.2 billion, up 36.2 percent from a year earlier
the sharp rise in dollar value of the gnp, which measures the nation's output of goods and services, was attributed partly to the revaluation last year of the korean won against the u.s. dollar. the won rose 8.7 percent last year
icn pharmaceuticals inc. says it has sold the 8.6 percent stake in swiss drug-industry giant f. hoffmann-la roche &amp; co. it accumulated since september, abandoning hopes of merging the companies
proceeds from the sale will be used to buy one or more health-care companies to expand icn's distribution capabilities, the costa mesa-based company said
in announcing the decision to sell its holdings, icn said, ``we understand and respect hoffmann-la roche's desire to remain in family control for the rest of this century.''
la roche is controlled tightly by descendants of its founder, fritz hoffman, and industry analysts never gave icn's overtures much hope of succeeding
icn said it sold its stake for $153,300 per share, or a total of $209 million
the company declined to say whether it had shown a gain or loss on the stock, adding that the information would be released with results of its first quarter ended feb. 29
as of the end of its fiscal year on nov. 30, the company had paid $169.8 million for a 6.3 percent stake. la roche has about 16,000 shares outstanding
separately, icn said that in its first-quarter results, it would reverse $15.9 million of the $19.4 million in unrealized losses it posted at the year's end. most of those losses were atrributable to the company's government and corporate bond holdings
icn's major product is ribavirin, an antiviral drug that has been approved in 28 countries thorughout the world for a variety of viral infections, including influenza, hepatitis b and herpes simplex
bruno's inc., alabama's largest grocery chain, has agreed to buy 82 piggly wiggly stores in georgia for $30 million in stock, company officials said
bruno's, a birmingham-based company, already has 123 supermarkets. under the agreement, bruno's will buy piggly wiggly southern, a vidalia holding company that owns stores in central and southern georgia
the purchase, announced thursday, includes a 585,000-square-foot warehouse in vidalia that serves all 82 stores
bruno's operates supermarkets under the names of bruno's, food world, foodmax and consumer warehouse foods in alabama, georgia, tennessee and florida. with the addition of the piggly wiggly stores, it will have more than 200 stores
the georgia stores that bruno's plans to buy will continue to operate under the piggly wiggly name, said bruno's spokeswoman beth dunnaway
de laurentiis entertainment group inc., struggling to recover from heavy losses caused by a string of box-office bombs, says it will close down its five regional film-distribution offices, eliminating 28 jobs, or about 15 percent of its 200 workers
among the movies that performed poorly at the box office for deg were ``taipan,'' ``million dollar mystery,'' ``weeds'' and ``date with an angel.''
the company said thursday its future sales would be handled out of its corporate office but that the company would ``continue to explore various distribution alternatives.''
those alternatives could include contracting with another film company to handle de laurentiis' production
currently, de laurentiis has seven films, most of them completed except for various amounts of post-production work. that is down from nine films in 1987
the distribution offices to be closed are in los angeles, chicago, dallas, atlanta and new york
while this news may seem discouraging, in reality the closing of our branches is in line with our restructuring plans,'' said laurence gleason, president of the company's marketing and distribution unit
the company's restructuring speeded up substantially after its founder, dino de laurentiis, stepped down in february as chairman and chief executive
in mid-march, the firm sold foreign television, video and non-theatrical rights to virtually its entire 320-movie film library for $69 million. it is still seeking a burying for the remaining rights to its library and for the wilmington, n.c., studio where most of its films have been made
entertainer merv griffin's investment company says it is seeking to meet with rival bidder donald trump in their battle over hotel-casino operator resorts international inc
but griffin at this time has no plans to further increase his $295 million offer, spokesman mark gill said thursday
griffin and an attorney for trump also disclosed separately that the securities and exchange commission has begun looking into alleged violations of securities law in the resorts fight
in another development, griffin announced that the largest holder of resorts' class a common stock had withdrawn its support for trump's $22-a-share offer and asked a delaware court to reject it
the court must act on the offer because it was made as part of a proposed settlement of shareholder suits alleging that trump's initial offer of $15 a share undervalued the company
trump attorney pamela tikellis disclosed the sec investigation in a letter to the delaware court, linking it to ``very substantial gyrations in the marketplace'' for resorts stock
it attributed those stock price movements to statements by griffin and an ally that ``have had a manipulative effect.''
griffin also acknowledged that the sec had begun gathering information in the probe but indicated that it was limited to allegations of violations by trump, including the failure to promptly disclose a new and higher appraisal for resorts properties in making his $22-a-share offer
griffin last week made an offer of $35 a share, or $225 million, for all of the company's stock _ its 5.7 million class a shares, which carry one vote each, and its 752,000 class b shares, which carry 100 votes each
trump owns 95 percent of the class b stock, giving him control over 88 percent of the company's voting strength
this week, griffin boosted his offer to $295 million. except for a proviso that class a shareholders receive an unspecified premium over the $35 offer, resorts' directors would be able to apportion the $70 million increase as they see fit. that was widely seen as a vehicle to shunt most of the money to trump
we are prepared to sit down with mr. trump and the resorts board to discuss obtaining a superior bid for the public stockholders and to satisfy the needs of all parties,'' said michael nigris, the president of griffin co
griffin spokesman gill said the allusion to a ``superior bid'' referred to one that is better than the $22-a-share bid that trump has made. gill said griffin has no plans at this time to again increase his offer
trump has repeatedly said he would not sell his stock _ a condition required by the griffin bid. attorney steve gartner, representing trump, said thursday that the new york-based developer hasn't changed that stance
as a result of trump's objection, resorts' board has twice refused to pursue the offer on grounds it is moot
the shareholder who defected from the settlement agreement with trump was the investment firm of tweedy, browne co., which owns 8.6 percent of resorts' class a stock
trump, based in atlantic city, n.j., has hotel-casino operations in new jersey and the bahamas
