ford motor co.'s non-automotive subsidiaries together earned a $62 million profit in 1987, their first money-making year since 1979, the no. 2 automaker said in its annual report
the businesses, which include rouge steel corp., the only steel company owned by a u.s. automaker, and ford aerospace corp., have been the focus of major efforts to restore profitability rather than sell
the 1987 profit was a strong improvement over 1986's $205 million loss, but still well short of 1979's $181 million profit, ford said
although ford doesn't disclose results for the individual companies, the biggest loser is believed to be rouge steel, which ford once tried to sell to a japanese steel company
instead, ford opted to modernize rouge steel and other non-automotive and supplier businesses. this year, it will spend more than $100 million on rouge steel alone
the biggest winner was ford aerospace, which won three major government space station contracts worth more than $400 million, ford said
ford also said it plans to build a $100 million electronics plant in lansdale, pa., to replace an existing plant and keep 2,400 jobs
grain and soybean futures prices opened steady to mixed today on the chicago board of trade
soybeans opened off more than a penny a bushel due to fairly heavy farmer selling after thursday's sharp gains, analysts said. but prices came back quickly and were narrowly mixed within minutes of the opening bell
soybean prices also were pressured by ideas that the threat of weather damage to the nearly ripe south american soybean crop has passed, said richard loewy, senior grain and oilseed analyst for prudential-bache securities inc. in new york
you haven't had moisture there since mid-february,'' loewy said. ``but the perception in the market is that whatever damage will be done to the crop by the hot, dry weather has already been done.''
he said wheat futures were slightly lower due to slackening export demand; corn was slightly higher on a lack of farmer selling
