uncle sam has clearly broken up the cozy relationship between the nation's commerical banks and the municipal bond market
historically one of the biggest players in that market, banks have dumped more than $51 billion of their municipal bond holdings in the last two years due to changes in the tax law, according to a report by the public securities association, a trade group of bond dealers
the report, released this past week by the psa and based on federal reserve data, showed that individual investors were the leading buyers of municipal bonds for the third consecutive year in 1987, either through the purchase of individual bonds, unit investment trusts or tax-exempt mutual and money market funds
the report noted that households owned 39 percent of the $720.5 million outstanding issues last year, up from 33.6 percent in 1986 and 36.5 percent in the previous year
banks came in second with a 25 percent holding, down from 29 percent in 1986 and 35.1 percent in 1985. their holdings peaked in 1971 with 51.2 percent. property and casualty insurance companies owned 13.1 percent; mutual funds, 9.8 percent; and money market funds, 8.5 percent
the dramatic decline in bank holdings came as a result of the 1986 tax reform act, which removed incentives for bank portfolios to invest in municipal bonds, or ``munis'' as they're known on wall street
banks had been able to deduct from their income taxes 80 percent of the cost of holding these tax-exempt bonds, but the tax law eliminated the deduction except on state and local issues totaling $10 million or less a year. the changes have had a mixed effect on the market so far, analysts and traders said
from an issuers point of view ... you're entering the market realizing that except in very unusual circumstances banks won't be one of your purchasers, so you're heavily dependent on individual purchases who face an entirely different set of incentives than do banks,'' said psa president heather ruth
in the recent past, issuers and banks have had a cozy relationship. as an example, ruth notes that around tax time when some individual investors sold bonds to raise cash to pay their taxes, banks would eagerly snap them up, keeping prices and yields stable
george friedlander, a managing director at smith barney, harris upham &amp; co., says it's not surprising that since the tax law most smaller issues have been doing better than the bigger ones which dominate the market
because banks are still actively buying them, bonds from the smallest of issues are more liquid, meaning they could be traded in a short period of time with relatively small price fluctuations, friedlander said
that price stability means lower yields, reducing borrowing expenses for the small issuers but raising them for the bigger ones
analysts note that volatility in the muni market is likely to continue through 1989, when insurance companies will see their tax incentives wiped out as a result of the overhaul of the tax system
the chicago mercantile exchange said friday it would impose an unusual system of adjustable price limits on its standard &amp; poor's 500 stock-index futures to reduce the volatility of u.s. financial markets
the limits were approved thursday by the commodity futures trading commission and take effect monday, replacing the 30-point price limit the chicago merc placed on s&amp;p 500 futures in the wake of the oct. 19 stock market collapse
the new limits will range from 15 index points to 25 index points depending on the settlement price of the lead-month s&amp;p 500 futures contract on the last business day of the preceding month, the exchange said in a statement to its members
price limits effectively halt trading of a futures contract whenever the price of the contract moves above or below the specified amount
investors use stock-index futures to hedge against losses in the stock market by betting on the price movement of the stocks that make up the index
s&amp;p 500 futures account for more than 80 percent of all u.s. stock-index futures trades
chicago merc officials have said the limits will result in better coordination of u.s. financial markets, a key recommendation of the presidential commission that investigated the stock market crash
a one-point move in the s&amp;p 500 index is roughly equivalent to an eight-point move in the dow jones average of 30 industrials. some analysts had criticized the 30-point limit on s&amp;p 500 futures _ equivalent to about 240 points on the dow _ as being too high to curtail all but the most violent price swings
a 15-point limit will take effect monday because the june contract settled feb. 29 at 268.75 points, within the low-end range of 0 to 275 points
the limit would rise to 20 points if the june contract settled above 275 points on the last trading day of march, or to 25 points if the june contract closed above 325 points
the june contract settled at 264.10 points on thursday
the stock market came under more selling pressure today, extending thursday's sharp drop
