volume on the big board came to 108.59 million shares with two hours to go
most companies stay close to home when they relocate their headquarters, according to a national survey to be released monday
the survey published by cushman &amp; wakefield inc., a business real estate firm based in new york, showed that 85 percent of the companies that relocated their headquarters during the past five years moved to a similar type of location, while 62 percent relocated in the same community
only 7 percent of the relocating companies changed states, the survey indicated
the findings are based on interviews with top executives at 400 organizations, including publicly and privately held corporations, partnerships, non-profit companies and government agencies. all the organizations polled have 50 or more employees at their headquarters and have relocated in the past five years
while the suburbs of large cities rank first as a preferred location for head offices with 36 percent, the survey also suggested a growing tendency for relocating in the biggest u.s. cities, cushman &amp; wakefield said. the survey showed that 28 percent of the relocating companies consider big cities the best type of location
the survey disputes the widespread impression of a sudden wave of headquarters relocations and a mass exodus from the nation's largest cities,'' said arthur j. mirante, president and chief executive officer of the real estate company
only a handful of organizations relocate across state lines,'' mirante added
he said such moves recently as mobil corp.'s from new york to fairfax, va., and firestone tire &amp; rubber co.'s from akron, ohio, to chicago are the exceptions rather than the rule
the need for more space was the most compelling reason for relocating, according to the survey
other reasons were a more favorable company image, lower occupancy costs, a better quality of life for employees, better access to markets, customers or clients, and a major change in the company's strategic direction. none of those factors, however, were considered crucial by more than 24 percent, the survey showed
more than $2 trillion in japanese savings accounts loses its tax-free status next week, and executives from tokyo investment firms to foreign manufacturers are dreaming of tapping into the treasure trove
the april 1 change was prompted by complaints from allies that japan needs to spur domestic consumption as a way to recycle some of its $82.7 billion annual trade surplus
the hope is the new 20 percent tax on interest will encourage japanese to save less and spend more. but many experts do not foresee that happening
the system of tax-free individual accounts _ known as ``maryu'' _ was set up after world war ii to provide a reserve of capital to finance the rebuilding of japan's economy. through it, the average japanese family had built a nest egg worth the equivalent of $82,000 by last year
george nemo, a broker for the investment firm vickers da costa in tokyo, estimates such accounts now hold a total of 300 trillion yen _ or about $2.3 trillion
banks are touting new savings plans to hold onto this treasure, while securities companies are trying to lure it away. foreign countries hope to get part of it through increased sales of exports to japan
but despite the advertising hoopla, nemo and other financial analysts expect much of the money to remain right where it is for now
this is not as spectacular as one might expect,'' nemo said
he said recent surveys of japanese housewives, who handle most of the money in the average japanese family, found they would be willing to pay the new tax and ``leave their nest eggs alone.''
however, he said there is bound to be at least a small percentage unwilling to settle for the low interest that banks pay on such accounts. some of that money will find new homes, most probably in japan's booming stock market
banks pay only four-tenths of 1 percent interest on a regular savings account and up to about 4 percent for long-term deposits
under the maryu system, no tax was charged for interest on savings accounts of up to $47,500, postal savings accounts of $23,800 and installment savings of $4,000. in addition, workers were allowed to build tax-free savings accounts of $40,000 through their employers
the japanese are among the industrialized world's biggest savers. the average family in japan saves 16.1 percent of its annual income, compared with 11.6 percent for west germany, 10.1 percent for france, 7.8 percent for britain and 6.6 percent in the united states
nemo is doubtful the next tax will have much effect on saving
the problem is, they already have just about all the televisions, videos, and smart clothes they could want,'' he said. ``and if they can't afford to buy homes, where are they going to spend the money?''
according to the economic planning agency, 99 percent of the japanese own a color television set, refrigerator and washing machine, 98 percent own a vacuum cleaner and nearly 70 percent own a car
with the high housing and land prices, most japanese can never hope to own their own home, so there is little else to do with the money other than spend it on high-priced cars or travel, invest it in the stock market or put it in a savings account
takasuke koneko, a spokesman for dai-ichi kangyo bank, said japanese are very cautious about where they put their savings because the burden of providing for old age falls on the individual in japan. he predicted many people would be scared off stock investing because of the worldwide plunge in stock prices last october
koneko said some of the money probably will go to life insurance, which is still tax-free if a person signs a contract for more than five years. however, he said, many people will not be willing to wait that long for a return on their investment
the bottom line is that we have to protect ourselves,'' he said. ``we cannot shift our funds. still, we will have to save. in 20 years, when we get ready to retire, the stock market could be two or three times what it could be now, but it could also be one-half or one-third
even with the end of the maryu system, our money has to be kept where it is safe.''

