corn futures prices closed higher while wheat and soybeans finished slightly lower friday on the chicago board of trade
corn turned in the best performance but most of the buying was speculative in the absence of fresh fundamental news, an analyst said
soybeans retreated in line with soybean meal. the soybean complex also was pressured by ideas that the threat of weather damage to the nearly ripe south american soybean crop has passed, said richard loewy, senior grain and oilseed analyst for prudential-bache securities inc. in new york
i just don't think any more crop damage can be done,'' he said
losses in wheat futures were underpinned by the agriculture department's sale thursday of 7.2 million bushels of surplus wheat, an unusally large figure for the thrice-weekly auctions in the face of slackening export demand, loewy said
at the close, wheat was 1 cent to 1} cents lower with the contract for delivery in may at $3.05 a bushel; corn was 2{ cents to 3} cents higher with may at $2.09{ a bushel; oats were \ cent to 1 cent higher with may at $1.68} a bushel; soybeans were unchanged to 2 cents lower with may at $6.48{ a bushel
the arrival of spring has brought signs of recovery to the toy industry following 1987's dismal performance. stores are selling more toys and manufacturers are getting more orders
but toymakers know the fickle tastes of young customers can take a promising product and overnight turn it into a dud. so there is an air of caution in this highly volatile business, although the early trend is positive
it's a very good retail environment for the first time in several years,'' said paul valentine, a toy industry analyst with standard &amp; poor's corp
at toys r us inc., the nation's largest toy store chain, president norman ricken said more customers are in the stores and sales are up ``quite strongly'' over last year
the indications are that it's a better start for the year than most people anticipated,'' said spencer boise, a spokesman for mattel inc., the nation's second-largest toymaker
good consumer demand usually translates into more orders for manufacturers, and that has heartened the big toy companies, most of whom finished 1987 in the red because product lines failed, sales fell off and costs were too high
toys that were big sellers at christmas have remained popular in 1988. among them are nintendo and other video games, games gang ltd.'s pictionary board game, fisher price's fun with food, kenner parker toys' real ghostbusters action game and matchbox toys ltd.'s pee wee herman talking doll
the popularity of such products _ known as carryover toys in the business _ contrasts with the events of a year ago, when toys that had been best sellers at christmas 1986 fizzled
another positive sign is that the success of the current best-sellers is becoming contagious
they spark people to come into the store, and they buy other things,'' ricken of toys r us said. ``there is a lot of impulse buying.''
rick anguilla, editor of the trade publication toy &amp; hobby world, agreed, saying, ``the key is, bring people into the stores.''
several years ago, coleco's trivial pursuit and cabbage patch kids were luring consumers in droves, but pictionary and nintendo are today's top draws, anguilla said
but despite the early trends, manufacturers and the people who track their fortunes are taking a wait-and-see approach for the remainder of 1988
it's a little too early to predict a strong year,'' said anguilla
mattel's orders are running ahead of the company's conservative expectations, but boise warned, ``orders are not necessarily a good indication of how the year might go, because they're cancelable anytime up to delivery.''
the analysts also caution that after the disappointments of 1987, it's easy to show for companies to show an improvement in sales
they're just going from a disaster to a more normal operating environment,'' said harold vogel, an analyst with merrill lynch &amp; co
i think they are doing better, but i don't see anything great happening,'' he said
caution also was the watchword when the industry unveiled its new products last month at its annual trade show, toy fair
burned by the failure of lines such as expensive high-tech dolls, companies showed fewer new toys and leaned toward smaller, less expensive ideas. the early returns indicate the strategy is working
tonka corp. is getting strong orders for starting lineup, a series of sports figures intended to sell under $5 apiece, said robert meek, a company spokesman
tonka's orders are well above 1987 levels, meek said. the company markets a top-selling video game, sega, but all of its divisions are showing improvement, he said
industry watchers say another company doing much better is lewis galoob toys inc.'s. galoob, which lost money on high-tech items in 1987, is focusing on less risky ideas such as plastic charms that contain cosmetics and stationery for girls, tiny dolls and small, transformable military figures for boys
companies, some of which have laid off workers, also continue to look for ways to cut expenses. on friday, tonka announced a restructuring in its canadian operations, including 60 layoffs
such moves will help a company's bottom line, and form a hedge against heavy losses should sales drop off again
vogel predicted for the toymakers this year, ``they'll have some modest profits, but no one's setting the world on fire.''
the stock market declined broadly again today, extending thursday's sharp drop
the dow jones average of 30 industrials, down 43.77 on thursday, dropped 26.52 to 1,997.35 by 3 p.m. on wall street
losers outnumbered gainers by nearly 3 to 1 in the overall tally of new york stock exchange-listed issues, with 389 up, 1,115 down and 434 unchanged
after tumbling thursday in foreign exchange, the dollar showed signs of steadying today
interest rates, which had contributed to the stock market's woes by rising thursday morning, dropped back a bit
but analysts said investors were still leery of stocks. they said thursday's selloff dealt a significant blow to the tenuous confidence that had been building up in the market's rally since late last year
that left the focus of activity on numerous stocks involved in takeover news and speculation
gillette jumped 3| to 47| amid widespread but unconfirmed rumors that philip morris was readying a bid for the company. philip morris shares fell 2 to 89{
sabine corp., which agreed to be acquired by pacific enterprises for $24 a share, gained 3] to 23]
avon products, rumored as a possible buyout candidate, picked up 2} to 27
koppers rose ] to 59[. beazer plc of britain raised its offer for the company from $56 a share to $60 a share
the nyse's composite index of all its listed common stocks fell 1.64 to 147.36. at the american stock exchange, the market value index was down 2.30 at 295.00
volume on the big board came to 131.19 million shares with an hour to go
sheikh ahmed zaki yamani, former saudi arabian oil minister, lost his appeal court bid friday for a temporary injunction against monday's official publication of the book ``yamani: the inside story.''
yamani applied for a temporary order blocking simon and schuster's release of the book by american author jeffrey robinson pending a full hearing next week
the book is also scheduled to be serialized in the sunday express, a london newspaper, this weekend
the judge, lord donaldson, said a full hearing could not be scheduled until wednesday. he said it was regrettable when the courts could not act fast enough to ``preserve the rights of the parties,'' but said yamani should have started court proceedings sooner
yamani claimed the author reneged on undertakings not to refer in the book to the saudi royal family or to the reasons behind his dismissal from the government
pre-publication copies of the book have already been offered for sale in london
the treasury department auctioned off $4.06 billion in short-term bills on friday with an average yield of 6.20 percent
the so-called cash management bill will mature in 22 days and was issued so the government would have enough money on hand to make tax refund payments during the tax filing season
the last time the government had to resort to such short-term financing was during last year's tax filing season when a 20-day bill had an average yield of 5.75 percent
the discount rate understates the actual return to investors _ 6.31 percent with a $10,000 bill selling for $9,962.10. a total of $38.81 billion in bids were received
stock prices tumbled for the second straight session today, closing out the market's worst week so far in 1988
five minutes before the close, the dow jones average of 30 industrials was down 41.94 points at 1,981.93
the stock market took a sharp drop for the second straight session today, closing out its worst week so far in 1988
after tumbling thursday in foreign exchange, the dollar showed signs of steadying today
interest rates, which had contributed to the stock market's woes by rising thursday morning, dropped back a bit
but analysts said investors were still leery of stocks. they said thursday's selloff dealt a significant blow to the tenuous confidence that had been building up in the market's rally since late last year
about the only stocks attracting any buying interest were issues involved in takeover news and speculation
the dow jones average of 30 industrials fell 44.92 points to 1,978.95, finishing the week with a net loss of 108.42
declining issues outnumbered advances by more than 3 to 1 on the new york stock exchange, with 377 up, 1,149 down and 431 unchanged
big board volume totaled 163.17 million shares, against 184.91 million in the previous session. the nyse's composite index lost 2.42 to 146.58. corn</head>
a south korean trade delegation signed contracts in iowa on friday to purchase about 10 million bushels of u.s. corn for about $29.3 million, and an official said about 95 percent of his country's corn purchases this year would be from the united states
that would mark a continued rebound of u.s. shipments, which in 1985 accounted for just 36 percent of the corn purchased by south korea, according to the iowa corn promotion board
the drop in u.s. corn sales mainly reflected an aggressive export drive by china earlier this decade to compete for a growing share of world sales, said economist robert wisner at iowa state university
he said the resurgence of corn sales to south korea by the united states is a result of reduced chinese sales because of growing domestic consumption
south korea, meantime, is stepping up imports of feed grains as it expands its livestock industry, and has increased corn consumption from 3 million metric tons in 1985 to about 5 million metric tons this year, said chan-kung park, head of the trade mission and chairman of the korea feed association
the delegation signed contracts friday to buy 150,000 metric tons, or about 6 million bushels of corn, from continental grain and to buy another 50,000 metric tons, or about 2 million bushels, each from cargill inc. and marc rich co. a metric ton is approximately 2,205 pounds
after subtracting the cost of transporting the grain to asia, south korea paid an average of about $1.85 a bushel for the grain, according to the iowa corn promotion board
those purchases, when added to contracts signed in neighboring nebraska and south dakota, brought sales to the trade mission to 550,000 metric tons
park said that so far this year, south korea had bought more than 2.25 million metric tons of u.s. corn and that most of the remainder of its 1988 purchases would be from the united states. he estimated the u.s. would account for 95 percent of the corn bought by his country in 1988
korea is purchasing as much as possible from the united states,'' park said through an interpreter. he said that with the decline in the u.s. dollar in the past three years, u.s. corn is priced competitively on world markets with grain from china and other asian sources and he said u.s. agricultural policy has been very successful since 1984
in the early 1980s, south korea also bought more than 90 percent of its corn from the united states, before china became a major competitor
iowa is the nation's leading corn producing state
officials of texas air corp. on friday declined comment on press reports that investor t. boone pickens is considering helping unions acquire the company
the wall street journal reported in friday's editions that pickens met recently with representatives of eastern airlines' unions to propose a plan to take over texas air, the parent of miami-based eastern
texas air, based in houston, is the nation's largest airline holding company with about 20 percent of the u.s. market
pickens laid out one strategy whereby his personal investment company, boone co., would assist the unions in seeking a controlling interest in texas air, the newspaper reported
the longstanding policy of the company is never to comment on rumor or speculation,'' texas air spokesman bruce hicks said friday
pickens' spokesman, david batchelder, reached by telephone in amarillo, texas, also declined comment
under pickens' plan, about $1 billion of eastern employees' pension fund money would be used as leverage to fund an offer for the company, the newspaper said
under the arrangement, the unions would negotiate wage concessions in return for a financial stake in the company, the journal said. if the plan succeeded, pickens would receive a fee, and would not participate in the management of the company, the newspaper reported
texas air has about $5 billion in long-term debt, and chairman frank lorenzo has control of the company's voting power
lorenzo and a few close associates own a special class of stock which carries voting rights 10 times those of regular common stock
unidentified participants in the recent discussions between pickens and eastern's unions told the journal they believed between 75 percent and 80 percent of eastern's common shares would have to be tendered in order to dilute lorenzo's voting control to a minority position
campeau corp. says it will not raise its $6.53 billion tender offer for federated department stores inc., but is demanding a fair opportunity to compete with r.h. macy &amp; co. inc. to buy the retailer, federated said in a filing with the securities and exchange commission
campeau is not increasing its price,'' federated quoted campeau as saying in a statement to federated's board thursday. ``it believes its price is already too high.''
this does not mean that you can give macy's a chance to jigger its bid or take any other action with respect to macy's, without giving campeau a fair opportunity to respond,'' federated quoted campeau as saying
the federated filing was made public friday
the cincinnati-based federated, operator of more than 650 stores nationwide with total 1987 sales of $11.1 billion, said thursday it would discuss campeau's tender offer with the toronto-based developer and talk with macy about a possible sweetening of macy's $6.3 billion bid
federated management has already approved a merger agreement with macy
federated, the nation's fifth-largest retailer, said its board would meet by wednesday, and macy chairman edward finkelstein and his counterpart at campeau, robert campeau, both would be allowed to speak at the session
federated said there is no guarantee the negotiations with macy will result in an improved offer
campeau on tuesday raised its two-step, all-cash offer for federated to an aggregate of approximately $73 a share from $68 a share, or $6.18 billion. under the new offer, campeau said it would pay $82 each for 70.5 million federated shares and $37 for the remainder of federated's 89.5 million outstanding shares in a subsequent merger
campeau also extended the expiration of its offer to midnight est april 4, when macy's offer is scheduled to expire
campeau also proposed to federated's board an alternate friendly merger under which it would pay $73 a share for 70.5 million shares in a tender offer and $73 for the remaining shares following the merger
campeau has proposed that a campeau-federated merger be structured along lines similar to a merger agreement between the retailer and macy
macy is offering $77.35 a share in cash for 70.43 million federated shares, for a total of $5.4 billion. macy would exchange shares in the merged company and issue convertible debt securities for the remainder of federated's 89.5 million outstanding shares
analysts value the macy offer at $6.3 billion
federated's divisions include bloomingdale's, abraham and straus, burdine's, filene's, foley's, lazarus and rich's department stores; ralphs supermarkets; gold circle discount stores; and main street and children's place specialty stores
federated also has delayed putting into effect, until at least march 30, a ``poison pill'' amendment to the company's shareholder rights plan that allows shareholders to buy new shares at a steep discount. it is designed to make an unwanted takeover more expensive
it is not clear if federated could apply the pill to campeau but not to macy. some analysts believe the outcome of the takeover fight may turn on that issue, and that a court might ultimately decide whether federated can take such a step
federally subsidized sales of 475,000 metric tons of hard red winter wheat to the soviet union have been indicated by five private exporters, the agriculture department announced friday
the foreign agriculture service said in a statement that the government-owned commodity credit corp. had agreed to pay in-kind bonuses to the exporters at an average value of $21.95 a ton to ship the wheat to the soviets in may
the subsidy payments were being made under the export enhancement program, which provides grain companies and others with government-owned crops as bonuses to stimulate overseas sales of american commodities
since last april, total subsidized sales of wheat to the soviets have totaled amore than 10.8 million tons
melvin e. sims, general sales manager of the foreign agricultural service, identified those receiving the bonuses and the amounts of grain involved as garnac grain company inc., 50,000 tons; richco grain ltd., 200,000 tons; mitsubishi international corp., 25,000 tons; artfer inc., 50,000 and louis dreyfus corp., 150,000 tons
the sales left 525,000 tons still left for the soviets to purchase under a 2 million-ton offer made by the united states on jan. 29
the united states also made the soviets an additional one million-ton offer on saturday
the two countries are preparing to negotiate a new long-term grain agreement to replace the one that expires sept. 30
it calls for the soviets to buy 9 million metric tons a year of which 4 million must be wheat and 4 million corn. the rest may then purchasing the remainder in wheat, corn, soybeans or soybean meal, with every ton of beans or meal counting as two tons of grain
wheat sales to the soviets slumped badly in 1986 despite the agreement but picked up against last year as the united states gave that country the green light for purchases under the subsidy program
david batchelder, who helped oilman t. boone pickens jr. make his corporate raids for the past decade, said friday he plans to leave the firm to start a consulting business that may compete with pickens
batchelder, 38, said he will leave mesa limited partnership at the end of may to move to san diego
it was really more of a case of leaving amarillo than leaving boone,'' said batchelder
ten years in amarillo is enough,'' batchelder said. ``it's a significant sacrifice to live in amarillo,'' which he likened to ``a large truck stop.''
he said he told pickens last year that he would be leaving
my third child _ my son, gary _ is graduating from high school in may,'' he said. ``and i told boone nine months ago, when that happens, i would be leaving.'' he said pickens said that he ``hated to see a great team split up, but he understood.''
batchelder, who helped pickens launch takover attempts against phillips petroleum co., gulf corp., superior oil co., and unocal corp., said he plans to offer other oil and gas interests his experience through a private consulting firm
i think the expertise that i've developed through the years with mesa, i could take out now and advise others,'' batchelder said. ``i think i can generate some ideas that would be helpful to other companies.''
batchelder refuted claims that his departure signals discontent with mesa's recent failed or aborted takeover efforts. in fact, he said, he expected to be involved in more decisions with pickens
i hope to do business with boone and bring him some deals,'' he said. still, he acknowledged he may be competing with pickens and mesa on some ventures
certainly the primary level for expertise i have is in the oil and gas industry,'' batchelder said. ``mesa has recently branched out into the gold industry and the aerospace space industry. but petroleum has been a very profitable venture for mesa and is still very much a viable interest.''
the oklahoma native came to pickens' firm from the denver office of the accounting firm deloitte, haskins &amp; sells, where he made $30,000 a year as an audit manager. he began at mesa as an assistant to a vice president, but rose to the rank of comptroller within two years and ultimately to the presidency of mesa petroleum co
when mesa later became a limited partnership, batchelder began as a consultant
batchelder said he believed mesa would not suffer with his departure
i think it will continue doing exactly what it's been doing,'' batchelder said. ``we have a great team at mesa. the other two members of my team have been with me six years and seven years. they'll go forward with the business.''
batchelder said he did not think he would be replaced at mesa. ``i don't think they need to,'' he said. ``they are very experienced.''
stock prices tumbled for the second straight session friday, closing out the market's worst week so far in 1988
the dow jones average of 30 industrials fell 44.92 points to 1,978.95, finishing the week with a net loss of 108.42
that marked the average's biggest weekly decline since it dropped 143.74 points last nov. 30-dec. 4
declining issues outnumbered advances by about 3 to 1 in the daily tally on the new york stock exchange, with 385 up, 1,156 down and 428 unchanged
big board volume came to 163.17 million shares, against 184.91 million in the previous session. the nyse's composite index lost 2.42 to 146.58
after tumbling thursday in foreign exchange, the dollar showed signs of steadying friday. interest rates, which had contributed to the stock market's woes by rising thursday morning, dropped back a bit
but analysts said investors were still leery of stocks. they said thursday's selloff dealt a significant blow to the tenuous confidence that had been building up in the market's rally since late last year
in the absence of any news to explain the market's weakness, brokers said many traders remained fearful that economic and inflationary pressures might soon reach a point where they would prompt the federal reserve to begin tightening credit
since early february, when the nyse set strictures on computer program trading in the event of a 50-point move in the dow, the average has had five separate gains or losses of more than 40 points without ever activating the 50-point ``collar.''
it rose 47.58 on feb. 10; rose 48.41 on feb. 29; fell 48.24 on march 10, and then suffered back-to-back losses of 43.77 and 44.92 thursday and friday of this week
point-plus losers among the blue chips friday included international business machines, down 2} at 107; general electric, down 1] at 40{; exxon, down 1[ at 41|; merck, down 2} at 161{, and international paper, down 1] at 41{
about the only stocks attracting any buying interest were issues involved in takeover news and speculation
gillette jumped 2} to 46} amid widespread but unconfirmed rumors that philip morris was readying a bid for the company. philip morris shares fell 3 to 88{
sabine corp., which agreed to be acquired by pacific enterprises for $24 a share, gained 3] to 23]
avon products, rumored as a possible buyout candidate, picked up 2| to 26~
as measured by wilshire associates' index of more than 5,000 actively traded stocks, the market lost $39.81 billion, or 1.52 percent, in value
nationwide turnover in nyse-listed issues, including trades in those stocks on regional exchanges and in the over-the-counter market, totaled 189.25 million shares
standard &amp; poor's index of 400 industrials fell 5.78 to 299.53, and s&amp;p's 500-stock composite index was down 4.84 at 258.51
the nasdaq composite index for the over-the-counter market dropped 3.06 to 372.54. at the american stock exchange, the market value index closed at 294.64, down 2.66
platinum futures prices plunged more than $10 a troy ounce friday as the buying interest that had propelled prices sharply higher earlier this week abruptly dried up
on other markets, gold and silver futures also retreated; crude oil prices rose above $17 a barrel; stock-index futures fell sharply; livestock and meat futures were mostly higher; and grains and soybeans were mixed
a five-day rally in the precious metals market skidded to a halt after speculators tried and failed to push prices through key resistance levels, analysts said
platinum took the hardest hit, settling $10.10 to $10.80 lower on the new york mercantile exchange with the contract for delivery in april finishing at $503.10 a troy ounce
from what i understand there was just no interest in buying it,'' said jack barbanel, director of futures trading for gruntal &amp; co. in new york. ``usually the tendency is for the floor traders and speculators to go into the weekend and take their profits.''
inflation fears linked to rising oil prices had supported the precious metals through the week. but even friday's solid gains in oil prices could not keep the metals from slipping
on the new york's commodity exchange, gold settled $1.00 to $1.20 lower with april at $453.30 a troy ounce; silver was 7 cents to 7.4 cents lower with march at $6.665 a troy ounce
crude oil rose above the psychologically important $17-a-barrel mark for the first time since feb. 11 on speculation that the five-member pricing committee of the organization of petroleum exporting countries would take substantive action to stabilize prices when it meets the first week in april, analysts said
in trading on the new york mercantile exchange, west texas intermediate crude oil settled 7 cents to 12 cents higher with may at $17.03 a barrel; heating oil was .38 cent to .47 cent higher with april at 47.78 cents a gallon; unleaded gasoline was .53 cent to .70 cent higher with april at 47.94 cents a gallon
stock-index futures plunged for the second consecutive session, mirroring sharp downward moves in the dow jones industrial average
the contract for june delivery of the standard &amp; poor's 500 index settled 6.35 points lower at 257.75 on the chicago mercantile exchange
analyst bob ray of dean witter reynolds inc. said trading activity was mostly technically motivated
i think we're in the throes of a good correction,'' ray said. ``it's very orderly, very methodical and not what i would call very heavy volume, either.''
live cattle futures posted new contract highs for april and june delivery on the chicago mercantile exchange, where the bullish mood reflected higher cash prices increasing demand
the higher cash prices for beef parts ``suggest that retailers are coming in fairly strong looking to get their needs ready for after easter,'' said tom o'hare, an analyst in new york with smith barney, harris upham &amp; co
they do a lot of hams before easter, then the week before easter they start really getting interested in beef again,'' o'hare said
pork futures prices advanced on higher cash prices and indications of slackening supplies, o'hare said
live cattle settled .05 cent lower to .52 cent higher with april at 74.92 cents a pound; feeder cattle were unchanged to .52 cent higher with march at 82.72 cents a pound; hogs were .18 cent to .67 cent higher with april at 46.25 cents a pound; frozen pork bellies werre .03 cent lower to .62 cent higher with may at 57.37 cents a pound
corn futures prices closed higher while wheat and soybeans finished slightly lower on the chicago board of trade
corn turned in the best performance but most of the buying was speculative in the absence of fresh fundamental news, an analyst said
soybeans retreated in line with soybean meal. the soybean complex also was pressured by ideas that the threat of weather damage to the nearly ripe south american soybean crop had passed, said richard loewy, senior grain and oilseed analyst for prudential-bache securities inc. in new york
losses in wheat futures were underpinned by the agriculture department's sale thursday of 7.2 million bushels of surplus wheat, an unusally large figure for the thrice-weekly auctions in the face of slackening export demand, loewy said
wheat settled 1 cent to 1} cents lower with the contract for delivery in may at $3.05 a bushel; corn was 2} cents to 3} cents higher with may at $2.09} a bushel; oats were \ cent to 1 cent higher with may at $1.68} a bushel; soybeans were 2{ cents lower to \ cent higher with may at $6.48{ a bushel
the omnibus trade bill pending in congress will include a provision allowing the united states to ``get tough'' with a european airplane manufacturer which domestic aerospace companies claim receives subsidies and engages in unfair trading practices, a washington state senator said friday
democratic sen. brock adams said the provision, which he authored, has been approved by house and senate negotiators trying to iron out final details of the trade bill
this amendment is designed to stop the international consortium supporting airbus industrie from using unfair trading practices in the united states,'' adams said
airbus, a consortium of aerospace companies in france, west germany, britain, spain, belgium and the netherlands, is the world's second-largest manufacturer of commercial airplanes with about 35 percent of the market
u.s. rival boeing co., based in seattle, has between 55 percent and 60 percent of the market
adams said his amendment would expand coverage of existing ``countervailing duty laws'' to include countries such as those supporting airbus
at present, adams said, u.s. companies can seek relief from unfair trading practices when their competition is subsidized by just one country, but not when the subsidies are coming from a consortium of foreign countries
boeing can sucessfully compete with airbus, but not if airbus is not playing by the rules and getting huge subsidies from foreign governments,'' adams said
airbus officials have consistently denied that the company was receiving government subsidies or engaged in unfair trading practices
the countervailing duty laws allow domestic manufacturers to ask the u.s. government to impose a duty equal to the amount of foreign subsidy for a product
adoption of the amendment will help ensure a fair arena for competition between boeing and airbus,'' adams said
the adoption of this important amendment by congress also demonstrates once more for european governments the seriousness with which their subsidies are viewed by the united states,'' said l.w. clarkson, a senior vice president of boeing
beazer plc, unable to lure koppers co. into a friendly deal, on friday boosted its hostile tender offer for the building materials and cement company to $1.7 billion
government officials, meanwhile, lashed out at shearson lehman hutton inc. for assuming the unusual role of equity partner in the takeover bid, but shearson maintains it is merely acting as a responsible investment banker to beazer, a long-standing client
to protest shearson's collaboration in the battle for pittsburgh-based koppers, pennsylvania officials said they have terminated a $7-billion-a-year relationship with the new york investment house, and one lawmaker has called for a congressional investigation into shearson's role
koppers has rebuffed beazer ever since it appeared on the scene three weeks ago with a $45-a-share offer. last weekend, beazer sweetened that bid to $56 a share, or $1.52 billion, which koppers characterized as inadequate
before going directly to shareholders with its latest $60-a-share tender offer, the british construction and building materials company tried to negotiate a friendly deal at the same price with koppers management
in staunchly resisting the overtures, koppers said it is prepared to go deep into debt to finance a one-time cash payout to its shareholders as a defensive maneuver. a consortium of banks has agreed to lend koppers about $1 billion to finance the payout
beazer has threatened to sue koppers if the company sells some or all of its construction materials and services business as part of a recapitalization plan
separately, koppers asked the u.s. district court in los angeles to halt beazer's tender offer because of antitrust considerations. beazer had agreed to sell koppers' aggregate plant in los angeles if the deal is consumated to satisfy the justice department's antitrust concerns. beazer called the koppers move ``completely without merit.''
koppers fell 12.5 cents to $58.625 a share on the new york stock exchange
at koppers annual community business luncheon in pittsburgh, president glen tenley, a 33-year koppers veteran, declared management's intention to remain independent
thirty-three years have not been spent with koppers to be put under some other company's ownership just because the dollar is cheap and there are fat financial fees to be made,'' he said
in full-page advertisements appearing friday in papers including the new york times and the wall street journal, the treasurer of pennsylvania criticized shearson and its parent, american express co., for their role in a hostile bid that ``can potentially have a significant adverse impact on jobs in this state.''
g. davis greene, jr., said in a letter to shearson@american express chairman and chief executive officer peter a. cohen, that he suspended all business activity between the state treasury's office and shearson on wednesday
greene said that ``business activity'' totaled $7 billion over the past year
shearson spokesman michael o'neill said he did not know ``what the $7 billion refers to,'' but added that ``overall there is no evidence of any significant business impact.''
british investor brian beazer sees koppers as a strategic step in his quest to build a worldwide building materials empire. as an equity partner in beazer's bns inc., which launched the tender offer, shearson agreed to provide the mortar for the deal with $570 million in bridge financing and about $23 million in equity interest in bns
we're providing a form of interim financing ... but it does not translate into a long-term interest in the company,'' shearson's o'neill said. county natwest ltd., a british investment bank, also agreed to take an equity position
there's a confusion over the nature of our financing ... we're not the acquirer, beazer is,'' o'neill stressed. under terms of a complex financial package, shearson will sell its stake in bns back to beazer
on thursday, rep. doug walgren, d-pa., called for a congressional investigation of shearson's ``unique and highly questionable hostile takeover attempt.''
walgren noted that shearson's bid ``marks the first time that an investment banking firm has both conceived of a hostile takeover and acted as an equity partner in the deal.''
if investment banks take on equity interests, walgren said, ``corporate america will be controlled by banks at unprecedented levels, and america's landscape will be littered with the empty shells of abandoned office buildings and company plants.''
koppers has taken its own action against shearson and american express. earlier this week koppers' management canceled its american express account, through which the company had been buying about $1.5 million per year in goods and services
koppers employees also shredded 175 american express cards in protest
likewise, the pittsburgh chamber of commerce urged citizens to ``leave home without it'' by destroying their american express cards in sympathy
pennsylvania gov. robert casey on friday ordered shearson be dropped as a potential advisor for a pending bond issue. the city of pittsburgh, which has sued shearson to block the takeover, also has suspended business dealings with the firm
the dollar closed mixed after moving in jagged fashion friday amid rumors that central banks stepped in to steady the currency
gold prices eased. republic national bank of new york quoted a bid price for gold of $452.75 a troy ounce as of 4 p.m. est, down from thursday's late bid of $453.15 an ounce
traders said the federal reserve and the bank of japan moved to support the dollar as the yen continued its upward climb against the major currencies. the dollar fell to levels against the yen not seen since mid-january
without the intervention, ``the beating would have been fairly bad'' for the dollar, said albert soria, vice president and foreign exchange manager at swiss bank corp
while sentiment is brewing that the narrowing of u.s. trade deficits might be drawing to a close, traders continued to argue that the dollar's drop is not so much related to fundamentals as it is to the continued strengthening of the japanese yen
there seems to be a very big demand for investors to be into yen,'' said stephen flanagan, an assistant vice president at manufacturers hanover trust co
dealers are wary that the japanese will begin to dump their dollar holdings once their fiscal year comes to a close on march 31, ``so the market is beginning to jump the gun'' by selling the u.s. currency, flanagan said
the dollar mostly weakened in europe, where the pound was the center of attention as it slumped on the heels of a british government report of a disappointing trade deficit for february
the pound was hit by news that britain's merchandise trade deficit narrowed slightly in february to 1.3 billion pounds, or $2.4 billion, from 1.4 billion pounds in january
the current account deficit, which includes invisible trade like financial services, was pegged at 720 million pounds, or $1.3 billion, from 844 million pounds, the department of trade and industry said
in tokyo, where the business day ends as europe's begins, the dollar fell 0.56 yen to a closing 125.74 yen. later, in london, it was quoted at 125.33 yen. in new york, the dollar closed at 125.30 yen, down from 125.575 yen thursday
in london, the pound fell to $1.8360 from $1.8435 late thursday. in new york, it cost $1.84175 to buy one pound, cheaper than thursday's $1.8420
other late dollar rates in new york, compared with late thursday, included: 1.6760 west german marks, down from 1.67725; 1.3865 swiss francs, up from 1.38625; 5.68625 french francs, down from 5.6995; 1,238.50 italian lire, down from 1,242.50, and 1.24205 canadian dollars, down from 1.2421
other late dollar rates in europe, compared with late thursday, were: 1.6760 west german marks, down from 1.6800; 1.3865 swiss francs, down from 1.3885; 5.6860 french francs, down from 5.7120; 1.8820 dutch guilders, down from 1.8980; 1,241.00 italian lire, down from 1,246.95; and 1.2433 canadian dollars, up from 1.2426
gold prices eased. on new york's commodity exchange, gold closed at $453.20, a troy ounce, down from $454.10 on thursday. in london, gold fell to a late bid price of $451.70 a troy ounce from late thursday's $452
in zurich, gold was lower, closing at a bid $451.50 compared with $452 dollars late thursday. earlier, in hong kong, gold fell $1.32 an ounce to close at $454.08
silver closed at $6.665 a troy ounce on new york's comex, down from $6.735 on thursday. in london, the metal was trading at a late bid price of $6.64 a troy ounce, compared with late thursday's $6.61
beazer plc, unable to lure koppers co. into a friendly deal, on friday boosted its hostile tender offer for the building materials and cement company to $1.7 billion
government officials, meanwhile, lashed out at shearson lehman hutton inc. for assuming the unusual role of equity partner in the takeover bid, but shearson maintains it is merely acting as a responsible investment banker to beazer, a long-standing client
to protest shearson's collaboration in the battle for pittsburgh-based koppers, pennsylvania officials said they have terminated a $7-billion-a-year relationship with the new york investment house, and one lawmaker has called for a congressional investigation into shearson's role
koppers has rebuffed beazer ever since it appeared on the scene three weeks ago with a $45-a-share offer. last weekend, beazer sweetened that bid to $56 a share, or $1.52 billion, which koppers characterized as inadequate
before going directly to shareholders with its latest $60-a-share tender offer, the british construction and building materials company tried to negotiate a friendly deal at the same price with koppers management
in staunchly resisting the overtures, koppers said it is prepared to go deep into debt to finance a one-time cash payout to its shareholders as a defensive maneuver. a consortium of banks has agreed to lend koppers about $1 billion to finance the payout
beazer has threatened to sue koppers if the company sells some or all of its construction materials and services business as part of a recapitalization plan
separately, koppers asked the u.s. district court in los angeles to halt beazer's tender offer because of antitrust considerations. beazer had agreed to sell koppers' aggregate plant in los angeles if the deal is consumated to satisfy the justice department's antitrust concerns. beazer called the koppers move ``completely without merit.''
koppers fell 12.5 cents to $58.625 a share on the new york stock exchange
at koppers annual community business luncheon in pittsburgh, president glen tenley, a 33-year koppers veteran, declared management's intention to remain independent
thirty-three years have not been spent with koppers to be put under some other company's ownership just because the dollar is cheap and there are fat financial fees to be made,'' he said
in full-page advertisements appearing friday in papers including the new york times and the wall street journal, the treasurer of pennsylvania criticized shearson and its parent, american express co., for their role in a hostile bid that ``can potentially have a significant adverse impact on jobs in this state.''
g. davis greene, jr., said in a letter to shearson@american express chairman and chief executive officer peter a. cohen, that he suspended all business activity between the state treasury's office and shearson on wednesday
greene said that ``business activity'' totaled $7 billion over the past year
shearson spokesman michael o'neill said he did not know ``what the $7 billion refers to,'' but added that ``overall there is no evidence of any significant business impact.''
british investor brian beazer sees koppers as a strategic step in his quest to build a worldwide building materials empire. as an equity partner in beazer's bns inc., which launched the tender offer, shearson agreed to provide the mortar for the deal with $570 million in bridge financing and about $23 million in equity interest in bns
we're providing a form of interim financing ... but it does not translate into a long-term interest in the company,'' shearson's o'neill said. county natwest ltd., a british investment bank, also agreed to take an equity position
there's a confusion over the nature of our financing ... we're not the acquirer, beazer is,'' o'neill stressed. under terms of a complex financial package, shearson will sell its stake in bns back to beazer
on thursday, rep. doug walgren, d-pa., called for a congressional investigation of shearson's ``unique and highly questionable hostile takeover attempt.''
walgren noted that shearson's bid ``marks the first time that an investment banking firm has both conceived of a hostile takeover and acted as an equity partner in the deal.''
if investment banks take on equity interests, walgren said, ``corporate america will be controlled by banks at unprecedented levels, and america's landscape will be littered with the empty shells of abandoned office buildings and company plants.''
koppers has taken its own action against shearson and american express. earlier this week koppers' management canceled its american express account, through which the company had been buying about $1.5 million per year in goods and services
koppers employees also shredded 175 american express cards in protest
likewise, the pittsburgh chamber of commerce urged citizens to ``leave home without it'' by destroying their american express cards in sympathy
pennsylvania gov. robert casey on friday ordered shearson be dropped as a potential advisor for a pending bond issue. the city of pittsburgh, which has sued shearson to block the takeover, also has suspended business dealings with the firm.   
resorts international inc., target of rival takeover bids from entertainer merv griffin and real estate developer donald trump, is trying to line up $600 million in high-yield bond financing, mostly to complete its overdue and over-budget taj mahal hotel-casino
the financing negotiations were disclosed friday by trump, who controls 88 percent of resorts' voting strength, is the company's chairman and is seeking to buy the rest of its stock and take it private
besides providing money to complete the taj mahal, proceeds from the financing would be used for working capital and to reimburse trump for stock-purchase costs if his tender offer succeeds
while terms of the financing aren't complete, trump said the arrangement is contingent upon the success of his tender offer for the company and upon trump's guarantee that the taj mahal will be finished
if trump's takeover bid fails, the company may seek a smaller amount of financing, trump said
trump has estimated it will take $550 million to complete the sprawling and luxurious taj mahal, which would become atlantic city's biggest hotel-casino with 42 floors and 1,250 rooms
final cost of the project is estimated to be $938.5 million, up from an estimated $535 million when work on it began four years ago
resorts has other hotel-casino operations in atlantic city and the bahamas
trump owns nearly all of the company's 572,000 shares of class b stock, which carries 100 votes per share. he is offering $22 per share to buy the remainder
besides class b stock, the company has 5.7 million class a shares, which have one vote each
griffin last week made a rival bid of $35 per share, or $225 million, for all of resorts' stock, including that held by trump. griffin later increased his offer to $295 million, leaving it up to resorts' board to decide how to apportion the $70 million increase between the two classes of stock
trump has repeatedly refused to sell his stock and has sued griffin for $250 million for allegedly interfering with trump's contractual obligations with resorts
griffin has sued trump and resorts' outside directors, claiming among other things that they breached their fiduciary duty by refusing to pursue griffin's offer. resorts' board said it didn't pursue griffin's proposal on grounds that trump's rejection had rendered it moot
on thursday, the two sides disclosed the securities and exchange commission had begun looking into allegations of securities violations, but they blamed each other's activities for triggering the probe
trump claimed statements and actions by griffin and an ally had a ``manipulative effect'' on the market for resorts' stock
griffin contended the sec was looking into allegations of breach of fiduciary duty and failure by trump to disclose a new and higher appraisal of resorts' value in making his $22-per-share offer
resorts shares rose 12{ cents friday in american stock exchange trading to close at $28.87{
four applications to build a bullet train linking miami, orlando and tampa were submitted friday after six years of planning for the space-age but still conceptual rail system
details of the applications are to be revealed monday in a ceremony with gov. bob martinez and legislative leaders
this is a major milestone in this project,'' said diana hull, spokeswoman for the high speed rail commission. ``today's deadline will put us one large step along toward putting high-speed rail in florida.''
the commission expects to narrow the list to three semifinalists, after a year's review, and award the franchise in september 1991. planners hope trains will be running by 1995, the state's 150th birthday
state guidelines mandate the multibillion-dollar project must link miami, tampa and orlando, but the applicants will determine precise routes, financing agreements and the technology to use
the first thing i want to know is, is what they're proposing a real viable plan? is it a politically do-able deal?'' said cocoa beach developer and attorney malcolm kirschenbaum, one of the seven businessmen on the commission
the team that wins the franchise will be allowed to develop property for rail stations and connecting attractions, a financing plan that mirrors one used by industrialist henry flagler who built a rail line nearly 100 years ago down florida's atlantic coast and eventually to key west
property developed as a way to help finance the system must have some transportation link to the high-speed rail,'' said hull
theoretically, those development deals will allow the franchisee to recoup its $2 billion to $5 billion startup costs, while fares will support rail operation and maintenance
balancing financial arrangements, environmental concerns, growth patterns and evolving technologies, the commission will select the best overall plan _ or reject all of them _ and make a recommendation to the governor and cabinet
initial fees for applicants are $35,000. several months from now, applicants will have to pay about $2,000 per mile, or about $600,000, to cover more detailed reviews of their proposals
the four applicants are:
_tgv of florida inc., a washington d.c.-based team backed by the french company alsthom, which supplies the 160 mph tgv trains to the french national railways, and bombardier inc., a canadian manufacturing consortium
_all american magneplane inc. of new port richey, which has an agreement to purchase a massachusetts institute of technology patent for a magnetically driven rail flight system, said president david ramsey, a civil engineer and developer
the average speed of the train, which still is being developed, is 250 mph, ramsey said
_stone &amp; webster engineering corp., a 100-year-old, boston-based international firm. stone &amp; webster's proposal is based on the french ans turboliner, a 150 mph train that can run on existing track
_florida high speed rail corp., a 40-member, international team based in deerfield beach. headed by amerifirst development corp., the company proposes an electrically powered system similar to swiss, italian, west german and some american trains already operating
a fifth company, orange blossom railroad corp., a division of the dallas-based entrak systems inc. engineering firm, had been considering an application but did not make the 5 p.m. deadline friday, said hull
kansas city southern industries inc. on friday rejected a proposal by new york investor howard kaskel to discuss a merger, saying kaskel actually intended to mount a takeover bid
the railroad and financial services company received a letter from kaskel on monday proposing talks concerning a possible negotiated merger
landon h. rowland, president and chief executive of kansas city southern, said the company's board of directors unanimously rejected the proposal
it is clear to us that mr. kaskel's letter is merely a salvo in his proposed proxy contest,'' rowland said. ``mr. kaskel has not even made a pretense of having sought or obtained financing, confirming our view that he is merely attempting to put the company into play.''
kaskel's investment group owns 11.3 percent of kansas city southern's stock. the group said monday it was offering $60 cash a share, or about $594 million, for the remaining 89 percent
the stock closed friday at $51.62{ per share, down $1.37{ per share in national trading of new york stock exchange-listed issues
kaskel said in his letter that he would attempt to place his own slate of directors on the kansas city southern board if it rejected or failed to act on his offer by april 4
he also accused the board of having erected obtacles ``designed to entrench itself and to prevent stockholders from realizing a full return on their investment.''
rowland said friday that ``contrary to mr. kaskel's careless statements impugning, without foundation, the motives of the kansas city southern industries directors, every action taken by the directors has been entirely dedicated to the best interest of kansas city southern industries and its stockholders.''
the board, after due review of mr. kaskel's letter, reaffirmed its confidence in the company's future and its view that now is not the time to sell the company,'' rowland said
in reaching its conclusion, the company said the board obtained an opinion from its investment banker, lazard freres &amp; co., which reportedly said the kaskel proposal was ambiguous and inadequate
the proposal appeared to be an effort to stimulate trading in kansas city southern stock or to publicize kaskel's plan to nominate two persons to the company's board of directors, kansas city southern said earlier
richard kaskel, one of the nominees, said wednesday the investor group would begin a proxy fight for the two slots. four of kansas city southern's 14 directors will be elected may 3 at the company's annual meeting
kansas city southern's main holding is kansas city southern lines railroad, which is the country's 14th-largest line. the company also owns 87.3 percent of dst systems inc., a financial record keeper based in kansas city, where it and affiliated operations employ about 2,000 people
for the fiscal year that ended dec. 31, kansas city southern reported a profit of $17.7 million, or $1.82 a share, on revenue of $507.6 million
the u.s. customs service ruled thursday that the tiny suzuki samurai sport-utility vehicle will continue to be counted as a truck since it enters the country without back seats, which are added later
suzuki motor co.'s samurais are imported into the united states as trucks because suzuki doesn't have a large enough allocation under the japanese government's voluntary export restraints to ship them as cars or sport-utility vehicles
this decision doesn't make any sense when people see how these vehicles are being used in the united states, but in this case the customs service has no choice,'' said customs commissioner william von raab
these are `trucks' under the law when they enter this country,'' he said
instead of paying a 2.5 percent car tariff, suzuki pays a 25 percent truck tariff on each of the vehicles, which are shipped without back seats to qualify as trucks
rear seats are added either at the port of entry or at dealerships. few, if any of the small sport vehicles actually are sold without rear seats. suzuki sold 81,349 samurais in this country in 1987 and said it plans to sell 100,000 in 1988
michigan democrat john dingell, chairman of the u.s. house energy and commerce committee, criticized von raab's decision
it appears that customs is still winking at the fact that the japanese are shipping seats into the u.s. separately, then installing them here to evade both customs laws and the (voluntary export restraints),'' he said
we don't like illogical decisions any more than commissioner von raab,'' dingell said in a statement
von raab said customs soon will seek public comment on the creation of additional criteria that would simplify the classification process
last year, customs and commerce department officials said the u.s. government had little interest in helping the japanese government enforce its export limits, particularly since the u.s. government takes in more money when foreign carmakers opt to pay the 25 percent tariff instead of the lower fee
other japanese companies following suzuki's practice include nissan motor corp., isuzu motor corp., mitsubishi motors corp. and toyota motor corp., the companies said last year
the u.s. government has safety and fuel economy standards, among other criteria, used to classify a vehicle as a car or truck for those purposes
for example, trucks are not yet subject to the same roof-crush, side-strength and high-mounted brake-light standards as cars
but those criteria are not used by the customs service, which instead looks at features such as number of seats to determine a vehicle's apparent purpose when it is imported
the japanese government voluntarily limits exports of japanese cars to this country to 2.3 million per year
under a less-publicized quota that was designed to cover station wagons, which are considered trucks in japan but cars in the united states, the japanese government also limits exports of sport-utility vehicles and minivans shipped to this country to 113,000 to 115,000 a year
suzuki, which gives nearly all its car allocation to general motors corp. for the imported chevrolet sprint, built by suzuki in japan, also has no sport-utility vehicle allocation
earlier this year, suzuki told the customs service it would be forced to close its u.s. dealerships if the samurai were classified as a car
but when that information became public, suzuki denied it had any intention of closing dealerships and said it instead was aggressively expanding its u.s. dealer network
in its second foray into the texas oil and gas market this month, pacific enterprises said friday it has agreed to buy sabine corp. of dallas for $24 per share, or $339 million
that is a 20 percent premium over the $20 per share at which sabine's stock closed thursday. in the past year, its stock has traded as high as $20.75 per share and as low as $9.37{
the deal, which is contingent upon 75 percent of the company's shares being tendered, has been approved unanimously by sabine's directors, the companies said
as part of the agreement, pacific enterprises received an option to buy 2.6 million shares, or 18{ percent, for $24 per share
sabine is engaged in exploration, development and acquisition of crude oil and natural gas in the united states
pacific enterprises, which until recently was known as pacific lighting corp., is the parent of southern california gas co. it also has gas and oil exploration and pipeline operations and runs drugstore and sporting goods chains
the deal will give pacific enterprises proved oil and gas reserves equivalent to 32 million barrels of oil, plus $55 million in cash and mineral rights and leaseholds to nearly 4 million acres of land
it will boost pacific enterprises' proved reserves by 36 percent
earlier this month, the company agreed to buy half the oil and gas mineral rights under 70,000 acres in texas for $93 million. that acreage is on the burnett ranch in king county, texas. operators</head>
the federal communications commission voted thursday to rescind the freedom of a small number of cable television systems to set their own rates for basic service
municipal rate regulation was lifted for more than 90 percent of the country's 7,800 cable tv systems in january 1987
the fcc's rules change, approved 3-0, will subject more systems to regulation by municipal officials, but neither the fcc nor the national cable television association could estimate how many. both, however, said the number would be small
the cable communications act deregulated the rates for basic service of cable systems in areas that had ``effective competition.'' cable systems that met this test became free to set their own rates for their basic tier of service, which includes the retransmission of local broadcast tv signals
but a federal appeals court struck down one of the components of the fcc's definition of that term and the agency's vote thursday was intended to address that decision
under the new definition, a cable system will be deemed to have competition if all residents in the franchise area receive at least three over-the-air broadcast signals, not necessarily the same three signals
under the old defective definition, a cable system was found to have competition if any three broadcast signals covered 75 percent of the county where the cable system operated
the ncta said it was disappointed in the decision since there is no evidence that cable systems have abused their freedom to set rates
but there appears little we can do about it'' because ``the courts are unlikely to second guess the commission on this matter,'' the trade association said
we, therefore, look to the record to be established by the large majority of cable systems which will continue to be deregulated to give us the ammunition to go back at some point in the future and ask the commission to revisit this issue.''
the successful rehabilitation of first city bancorporation of texas inc. is hindered by the apparent failure of some debt holders to accept current conditions for tendering their bonds, according to the head of a private group seeking to complete a $1.5 billion restructuring of the company
each day of delay costs money,'' said a. robert abboud, a chicago investor, in a speech to the french-american chamber of commerce on wednesday
as of last week, 51 percent of first city's $225.8 million in bonds had been tendered, but the restructuring deal requires 90 percent participation by the close of business next tuesday
it's not in their best interest to hang onto the bonds if they're going to crater the deal in the process,'' abboud said. caving into demands for better terms could set a negative precedent for similar transactions in the future, he said
senior debt holders have been offered 45 cents on the dollar for their debt, while subordinated debt holders have been offered 35 cents
on a liquidation basis, their investment is worth zero,'' abboud said, referring to the $100 million in subordinated debt. ``once the preconditions are established, we have to stick to them.''
the professionals in the market should understand that (banking) is not a regular industry,'' abboud said. ``the institutions that are so integral to our financial system should know this.''
he did not elaborate
abboud is trying to restructure houston-based first city using $970 million in assistance from the federal deposit insurance corp., $500 million infusion of capital raised privately by an investor group headed by abboud and a spinoff of $1.79 billion in book value of poorly performing assets
first city, the state's fourth-largest bank holding company with 59 banks in texas and one in south dakota, grew quickly during the texas oil boom, but was hammered by energy and real estate losses when oil prices plummeted. for 1987, the company posted a $1.1 billion loss
abboud, who become chairman under the federal bailout plan, said he was optimistic a deal could be closed by march 31. besides a successful tender, first city still needs to renegotiate unfavorable leases. first city shareholders already have voted to support the abboud plan
ford motor co. will divide up $250 million this year in bonuses for salaried employees who contributed to the success of ford and its subsidiaries in 1987, the company said in its annual report thursday
a proxy statement in the second week of april will reveal how many people will be awarded executive bonuses by the board of directors' compensation and option committee, ford spokesman thomas e. foote said
in 1987, the seven-member committee of directors from outside the company awarded $164.3 million in bonuses for 1986 to 5,528 salaried ford employees, foote said
the 1986 bonuses ranged as high as $1.3 million for donald e. petersen, chairman and chief executive officer, and $1.1 million for harold a. poling, then president and now vice-chairman, foote said
the company does not divulge the amounts of executive bonuses or other compensation except to the five highest-paid executives. their compensation will be revealed in the april proxy report, he said
ford had said in february it was distributing $635 million, or about $3,700 each, to hourly employees as their share of the company's record $4.6 billion in 1987 earnings
the compensation and option committee allocated the $250 million for the executive bonuses out of a possible $363.9 million under a formula in ford's stockholder-approved supplemental compensation plan, the annual report said
foote said the $164.3 million awarded last year was out of a possible $241.9 million
the annual report, mailed wednesday to ford's 250,000 shareholders and released publicly on thursday, cited the income of $4.6 billion _ highest annual earnings of any company in automotive history _ despite the year's seven percent drop in u.s. car and truck sales, higher capital spending and increased marketing costs
the report described a ``corporate culture ... based on the understanding that no individual is responsible for designing, engineering, manufacturing, assembling and selling a product.''
the first page of the report was a tribute to henry ford ii, who led the company as president or chairman for nearly 35 years prior to his retirement as chairman in 1979. ford died sept. 29. ``on all he left his imprint,'' petersen said in the memorial tribute
stock prices have dropped sharply as the dollar slumped in world currency markets and u.s. interest rates headed higher
in trading thursday on the new york stock exchange, the dow jones average of 30 industrials fell 43.77 points to close at 2,023.87
the session marked the fourth time the blue-chip average came close to, but did not quite reach, the 50-point plus or minus limit set by the nyse feb. 4. at that level, restrictions go into effect on the use of nyse computer trading facilities for so-called index arbitrage trading
americans' personal incomes rose at the fastest clip in four months during february while consumer spending was propelled upward by a rebound in car sales, the government has reported
the commerce department said thursday that personal incomes advanced 0.9 percent, reflecting strong employment gains in the past few months. spending rose 0.7 percent
economists said the new figures provided further evidence that the economy has suffered no long-run effects from the october stock market crash
the savings and loan industry, drained by insolvent institutions in texas, last year recorded its worst loss since the great depression, the government said
the federal home loan bank board said thursday that a $3.2 billion loss in the last three months of 1987 pushed the industry's annual loss to a record $6.8 billion
that was nearly 50 percent greater than the previous post-depression record of $4.6 billion set in 1981, when the prime lending rate soared above 20 percent
