irving's stock jumped thursday in response to the news, closing $6.62{ higher at $66.25 on the new york stock exchange, while bank of new york rose $1.12{ to $31.37{
irving's announcement comes about a month after bank of new york received regulatory approval for the merger
west point-pepperell inc. has intensified the bidding war for j.p. stevens &amp; co. inc., announcing a $1.1 billion tender offer for the textile maker and indicating it could go even higher if stevens agrees to a friendly deal
west point-pepperell's new $62.50 a share offer announced thursday topped a bid stevens already accepted from a private investment group as well as west point-pepperell's own earlier bid
stevens agreed last week to accept a $61.50-a-share offer from the new york investment group odyssey partners
the battle for federated department stores inc. showed signs of escalating as the retailer and r.h. macy &amp; co. inc. announced they were beginning talks on a possible sweetening of macy's $6.3 billion offer for federated
federated also said thursday its board authorized company representatives to meet with campeau corp. to discuss the canadian developer's competing $6.53 billion tender offer and its proposal for a friendly merger with federated
wall street analysts have expected macy to increase its cash-and-stock offer since campeau boosted its all-cash bid earlier this week. scale</head>
the proposed contract for northwest airlines flight attendants would eliminate a two-tier wage scale, add $75 million to the company's payroll to cover wage and benefit increases and unify work rules, a company official said thursday
terry erskine, northwest's chief negotiator in contract talks with teamsters local 2747, said that if ratified by the rank-and-file the proposed contract would take effect june 1 and expire dec. 31, 1992
jeff musto, a spokesman for local 2747, said the union negotiating committee voted wednesday night to submit the proposal to the rank-and-file. union officials have said they expect it to be approved
the proposed contract was reached tuesday, averting a strike threatened for march 29
the final hurdle to the agreement had been how to treat lower-paid b-scale employees who were to get an $800-a-month pay raise by moving to the higher-paid a-scale after their fifth year of service, erskine and musto said
the union wanted to retain the provision and northwest wanted to delay the pay raise until the eighth year. as a compromise, the proposed contract will phase the 65 percent increase in after an employee's seventh year of service
workers would be paid under a single scale after 12 years with the company, finally unifying scales of northwest attendants with those of their counterparts from the former republic airlines, which was acquired by northwest in 1986
the two-tier wage scale issue had intensified since the merger. about a third of the 2,600 former republic attendants are on the lower pay scale, and the other two-thirds had said they wouldn't get enough out of northwest's previous wage offer
under the proposal submitted for ratification, flight attendants would get a 7.7 percent pay increase in their second year; a 6.4 percent increase in their fourth year, a 13.3 percent increase in their sixth year and a 27 percent increase in their seventh year
under the proposed new wage scale, most senior flight attendants would earn about $35,500 a year in basic pay _ second in the industry behind delta airlines, erskine said. entry-level flight attendants would be paid about $15,000 a year in basic pay, close to the industry average, he said
the contract also provides for pay raises of 2 percent in june 1990 and 3 percent in january 1992 for all current flight attendants, and a variety of one-time bonuses
former republic airlines workers also would be placed under the northwest pension plan, which would have its benefits boosted by 17 percent to make it level with the former republic plan, erskine said
the pension and pay increases will add about $75 million to northwest's payroll over the life of the contract, erskine said. some of the increase will be made up by adopting northwest work rules _ considered less expensive than rules covering the former republic workers _ for all the attendants
checks treated with a chemical that causes them to disintegrate into confetti shortly after being deposited have shown up in at least two states, costing banks nearly $70,000 since the beginning of the year, police said
a check clearinghouse said thursday it has warned 142 banks to be on the lookout for the dissolving checks, which may have an unusual odor and feel oily
the checks have turned up at five or six banks in the chicago area and at one in tennessee. authorities also are looking into a report of a possible dissolving check in indiana
japan has violated international rules of commerce in its implementation of a u.s.-japanese semiconductor trade agreement, according to a preliminary finding
the computer chip finding, made public thursday, was made by a panel of the gatt, the general agreement on tariffs and trade, an international body that oversees the world trading system
the panel report said japanese companies used improper means to prop up the export prices of semiconductors
ford motor co. will divide up $250 million this year in bonuses for salaried employees who contributed to the success of ford and its subsidiaries in 1987, the company said in its annual report
a proxy statement in the second week of april will reveal how many people will be awarded executive bonuses by the board of directors' compensation and option committee, a ford spokesman said thursday
in 1987, the seven-member committee of directors from outside the company awarded $164.3 million in bonuses for 1986 to 5,528 salaried ford employees
the losing side vowed to fight on after a federal bankruptcy judge approved an $11 million settlement in a case involving three zeros accidentally dropped from some financial documents
we have not given up the ship, so to speak,'' sandra mayerson said thursday. mayerson is a lawyer representing a major creditor in the chapter 11 proceedings of united states lines, a defunct shipping company, and its parent mclean industries inc
prudential insurance co. of america agreed this week to pay about $11 million to united states lines to settle legal claims stemming from a clerical error in which a mortgage lien prudential held on eight ships, worth $92,885,000, was recorded as worth $92,885
ms. mayerson's client, general electric capital corp., opposed the settlement
communism suffered its first big mac attack as mcdonald's opened a restaurant in yugoslavia, and police were called in to keep order among customers who lined up for hours under the golden arches
i just wanted to taste genuine american hamburgers,'' high school student milica nikolic said thursday
people curiously examined the renovated restaurant's plush interior and back-lit signs depicting the french fries, milk shakes and other fare more familiar in the west
stock prices dropped sharply thursday as the dollar slumped in foreign exchange and u.s. interest rates headed higher. the dow jones average of 30 industrials fell 43.77 points to 2,023.87
the dollar declined in foreign exchange. gold prices rose
bond prices finished slightly lower
soybean futures prices closed sharply higher while grain futures were mixed
february surges in personal income and consumer spending are being cited by analysts as further evidence that the economy has suffered no long-term effects from the october stock market crash
but the new government reports failed to cheer wall streeters on thursday, as stock prices took a nosedive that sent the dow jones average of 30 industrials down 43.77 points to 2,023.87
separately, the government reported the savings and loan industry lost $6.8 billion last year, its worst loss since the great depression
in its latest eonomic report, the commerce department said personal income of americans rose 0.9 percent in february, reflecting strong employment gains in the past few months. spending rose 0.7 percent, up sharply from a tiny 0.1 percent january increase
five months ago after the market crash, some analysts feared consumer worries about the future would cause spending cutbacks that could push the country into a recession
for people who were worried about a major consumer retrenchment, these numbers are encouraging,'' said sandra shaber, an economist with the futures group. ``as long as income gains hold up, people will continue to spend.''
analysts said the february gain in incomes, which followed a 0.3 percent january rise and was the best showing since a 1.9 percent october increase, reflected good employment news. the jobless rate fell to an 8{-year low of 5.7 percent during the month
in its report on thrift earnings, the federal home loan bank board said the $6.8 billion loss for the year included a $3.2 billion loss in the last three months of 1987
the year's loss was nearly 50 percent greater than the previous post-depression high of a $4.6 billion loss in 1981. the nation's federally insured s&amp;ls had a modest $132 million profit for all of 1986
earlier this month, the federal deposit insurance corp. said the nation's federally insured commercial banks earned $3.7 billion in 1987
in other economic reports thursday:
_business startups declined nationwide in 1987 for the first time since the end of the last recession, but the level remains strong and reflects economic stability, dun &amp; bradstreet corp. said. the 7.7 percent overall decline, from 253,092 startups in 1986 to 233,710 last year, affected all industry sectors and all regions, especially the south and southwest
_the treasury sold $6.5 billion in four-year notes at an average yield of 7.90 percent, down from 8.33 percent at the last such auction in december and the lowest level since four-year notes averaged 7.89 percent last june 24
energy futures have turned mixed amid doubts by traders over whether opec's pricing committee can soothe the turbulent market at its scheduled meeting next month
on the new york mercantile exchange, the may contract for west texas intemediate, the benchmark u.s. crude, settled at $16.96 per barrel thursday, up 10 cents from wednesday's close. the contract had risen 49 cents on wednesday
among refined products traded on the exchange, the april contract for wholesale heating oil slipped 0.33 cent to 47.40 cents per gallon, after rising 1.47 cents wednesday. unleaded gasoline, up 0.93 cent on wednesday, was up 0.08 cent to 47.33 cents a gallon
oil prices have fallen recently amid allegations that organization of petroleum exporting countries member states were cheating on production levels as well as pricing rules
rilwanu lukman, opec's president, announced wednesday that the cartel's five-member pricing committee would meet during the first week of april to discuss how to stabilize prices
peter beutel, an assistant director at elders futures inc., speculated that no substantive action would be taken until opec's regular meeting in june
a lot of people were wondering if anyting will come out of luckman's various pronouncements,'' he said
irving bank corp. is seeking a ``white knight'' friendly bidder and other alternatives to thwart bank of new york's hostile $1.08 billion tender offer, which began earlier this week
but bank of new york says thursday's announcement, made in a securities and exchange commission filing, changes nothing in its six-month effort to acquire the rival bank holding company
in the filing, which was an official response to the hostile bid, irving said it was in the ``preliminary stages of negotiating with third parties'' in connection with a possible merger, reorganization, sale of assets or change in capitalization
irving also said it has begun furnishing information to unidentified parties its management intended to talk with still more groups. irving officials have refused to comment further on the filing
irving's board of directors repeatedly has denounced as inadequate bank of new york's offer to pay $15 in cash and 1.575 shares of its own stock for each of irving's roughly 18.1 common shares outstanding
from the information they've given we have no way of telling if there's something going on or it's a lot of smoke,'' bank of new york spokesman owen brady said of irving's sec filing. ``we see nothing substantative.''
industry analysts also were at a loss over what irving's plans might include, although wall street welcomed its disclosure as a signal the bidding for irving may escalate
in active trading on the new york stock exchange, irving rose $6.62{ to $66.25 a share while bank of new york rose $1.12{ to $31.37{ a share
i have no idea who they might be talking to,'' said brent erensel, senior analyst with donaldson lufkin &amp; jenrette securities corp. ``but it seems to me the priority for irving is to be independent first, seek a white knight second, and last of all to submit to the bank of new york.''
michael starr, an analyst with duff and phelps inc. in chicago, said irving possibly could keep its current managment team intact by merging with a foreign bank with a strong capital structure
it would be difficult for one of the larger u.s. banks to merge with irving because .. (they) have relatively weak capital structures,'' he said
last month, the federal reserve board and the new york state banking board cleared a bank of new york-irving merger, saying it wouldn't hurt competition in the nation's biggest financial center
irving has asked the federal courts to overturn the fed's decision
earlier this week, bank of new york received the sec's go-ahead to begin its tender offer, and the company also has assembled a slate of 16 nominees to irving's board. bank of new york holds a 4.83 percent stake in irving
irving has stressed its desire to remain independent and has taken a number of steps to spurn bank of new york's advances, including instituting an anti-takeover ``poison pill'' intended to make any hostile buyout prohibitively expensive
in another effort to bolster its takeover defenses and place stock in friendly hands, irving recently issued $100.1 million worth of cumulative convertible preferred stock to 15 investors. the stock expands voting rights and offers other entitlements that could foil a hostile bid
bank of new york sued irving in new york state court to void the preferred issue
bank of new york began its takeover efforts in september with a bid of $1.4 billion, or $80 in cash and securities. it revised the offer to $68 in cash and securities following october's stock market crash, and lowered the offer a second time in late january
hostile takeover efforts are rare in the banking industry. a merger between new york bank and irving would create one of the nation's 15 largest bank holding companies with combined assets of more than $40 billion
yields on four-year treasury notes have declined in the government's latest auction to the lowest level in nine months
the average yield in thursday's auction was 7.90 percent, down from 8.33 percent at the last auction on dec. 23
it was the lowest rate since four-year notes averaged 7.89 percent last june 24. the notes will carry a coupon interest rate of 7~ percent, with each $10,000 in face value selling for $9,991.60
a total of $6.5 billion in notes were sold out of bids totaling $17.2 billion
a preliminary finding that japan has violated international rules of commerce in its implementation of a u.s.-japanese semiconductor trade agreement does not necessarily void the pact, officials say
the preliminary finding disclosed thursday was made by a panel of the gatt, the general agreement on tariffs and trade, an international body based in geneva that oversees the world trading system
the panel report said japanese companies used improper means to prop up the export prices of semiconductors, including production controls and industrywide pricing rules
the panel's finding requires the approval of the gatt council, which meets may 4. it was made public thursday by willy de clercq, chief negotiator of the european economic community, and later confirmed by the office of u.s. trade representative clayton yeutter
the gatt itself declined to comment on the panel's finding, saying it remained confidential
the gatt panel made the ruling three weeks ago, with copies given to the united states, japan and the european economic community. it was kept confidential in hopes that the parties could work out their differences in private
the ruling was distributed thursday to other gatt member nations, even though exact terms of the finding have not been publicly disclosed
the 1986 chip agreement was intended to stop japan from ``dumping'' chips at unfairly low prices in the united states and other markets and to open up the japanese chip market to foreign producers, including americans
in washington, yeutter issued a statement saying the united states was satisfied with the finding
the gatt panel has determined that the objectives of the agreement are consistent with gatt rules but that some of the japanese implementation methods are not. that is what we have been saying since the agreement went into effect,'' yeutter stated
some of these methods of implementation, such as production controls, will need to be changed but the need to make these changes does not relieve japan of its obligation under the semiconductor agreement,'' yeutter said
japan's alleged failure to abide by the pact triggered $300 million in u.s. retaliatory tariffs last year against selected japanese electronics imports. of those sanctions, some $165 million remain in place
gary holmes, a spokesman for yeutter in washington, said the united states never intended that japan cease third-country dumping by market manipulation
however, he said the japanese government had sought to comply with the pact through ``production controls and quantitative restrictions, things we in the united states never agreed to in the first place. we never thought they were legal (under gatt guidelines).''
the u.s.-based semiconductor industry association said the gatt findings ``did not challenge the fundamental legitimacy of the agreement between the united states and japan.''
trade officials in the japanese embassy in washington were away from their offices near the end of their business hours thursday and could not be reached for comment
competition from low-priced japanese chips knocked most u.s. producers out of the business of selling the memory chips known as dynamic random access memories, or d-rams
in addition to complaining to gatt, the eec has launched a probe of its own into possible japanese dumping of several types of computer memory chips
the eec probe involves chips known as eproms, which is short for erasable programmable read-only memories
if the japanese memory chip manufacturers were found to charge unfairly low prices, their exports to europe could be subjected to punitive levies
francoise le bail, the commission's spokeswoman, said the community's dumping investigation will continue despite the gatt finding. plan</head>
santa fe southern pacific corp.'s planned sale of its black mesa pipeline inc. subsidiary would complete a nearly nine-month-old corporate restructuring to pare the railroad and energy conglomerate's holdings
santa fe announced thursday it had agreed to sell black mesa to williams technologies inc. of tulsa, okla., at undisclosed terms
the santa fe restructuring announced june 30 was aimed at reducing the company's holdings to five core businesses in transportation, real estate and natural resources, said spokesman richard hall
chicago-based santa fe has sold or agreed to sell two other pipeline companies, a building contractor company, a timber company, a leasing business and the southern pacific transportation co., one of its two railroads
the company expects to reap $1.7 billion after taxes from the sale of the businesses
the restructuring plan included a $30-a-share payout to stockholders totaling $4.7 billion
hall said in a telephone interview that the restructuring was intended to help pay down debt incurred in paying the special dividend and to improve the company's long-term growth and earning potential
parts of the plan were bitterly opposed by two of santa fe's largest shareholders, the henley group inc. of la jolla, calif., and toronto-based olympia &amp; york developments ltd. both companies failed in attempts to take control of santa fe and have apparently abandoned the efforts
the 273-mile black mesa pipeline carries coal slurry from a mine in northeastern arizona to a power plant in southern nevada
completion of the restructuring will leave santa fe with its chicago-based santa fe railway, san francisco-based santa fe pacific realty corp., houston-based santa fe energy co., albuquerque, n.m.-based santa fe pacific minerals corp. and los angeles-based santa fe pipelines inc
charles h. pistor jr., chairman of troubled first republicbank corp.'s flagship bank will retire early, but not because of the bank's financial problems
pistor, who has been with the banking company since 1956, will retire april 15, he announced thursday
the 57-year-old pistor, chairman of first republicbank dallas, also is president of the american bankers association, the banking industry's main trade group
pistor's announcement comes a week after first republicbank, the state's largest bank holding company with $33.2 billion in assets, announced it would seek federal assistance because of mounting loan problems and deteriorating customer confidence
the fdic gave first republic a $1 billion capital loan last week to stem a serious outflow of deposits
bank officials are expected to recommend that gerald w. fronterhouse, the corporation's chairman and chief executive officer, assume pistor's position
with the fdic's stabilizing assistance and assurance that all depositors are fully protected, the permanent solutions and restructuring of first republicbank are beginning, and i have asked jerry (fronterhouse) not to consider me for responsibilities in the ongoing institution,'' pistor stated
the company also announced thursday that joseph r. musolino, vice chairman of first republicbank, was elected company president. fronterhouse will continue serving as chairman
although senior first republicbank executives had agreed to resign if asked by the fdic, as a condition of the $1 billion loan, fdic spokesman alan whitney said pistor's resignation had not been sought
pistor joined the republicbank organization in 1956 and became president and a director of republicbank dallas, then called republic national bank of dallas, in 1974. he was elected chairman of the dallas bank and a director of the holding company in 1980
general motors corp. officials are shrugging off a new book by a former employee who portrays gm chairman roger smith as a man with a high-tech vision who lacked the people skills to implement it
in his book, ``call me roger, albert lee calls smith's stewardship at gm since 1981 a ``tragedy in leadership.''
lee, a gm speech writer from 1984 to 1987, cites plant closings, gm's decreasing share of the auto market, ford motor co.'s ascendance as industry profit leader and smith's public rift with former gm board member h. ross perot, founder of electronic data systems, in making his conclusions
gm, which acquired eds in 1984, agreed last year to pay perot _ a harsh critic of gm management _ $700 million in return for his gm holdings and resignation from the board of directors
lee wrote of smith that, following the perot departure, ``by almost every measure of management achievement...his leadership had failed.''
lee's former boss, gm public relations vice president jack mcnulty, questioned lee's conclusions
(he's) just one guy who worked here two or three years, and he was in roger's office maybe six times. i don't think he's qualified to talk about gm,'' mcnulty said
the book is due in bookstores next month and will be excerpted in playboy's may issue
roger is aware of the book,'' said gm spokesman jim crellin, asked smith's reaction. ``i don't know if he's read any of it, but all we're saying is that we don't think the book's worth commenting on.''
lee said smith advanced via a fast-track executive development program that left him unschooled in the art of motivating employees. he said smith failed to realize that to make full use of its new technology, gm would require the support of workers from its design labs to its shop floor
mcnulty, who helped arrange interviews for lee and read an early draft of the book, disputed that contention
we've got the most modern plant structure in the industry,'' he said. ``we think we've got the best product line. roger has often said, `we've crossed the river and others have yet to cross it.'''
